<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">NEW POLITICAL, SOCIAL AND ECONOMIC
ENVIRONMENT FOR DIPLOMATIC ACTIVITIES</FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The development of IT has made the modern
world increasingly interdependent and interconnected. Today's
trends and characteristics, which are likely to endure, will bring
about deep changes of economic, political and social structures
in nation states as well as in international relations. The impact
of these changes on diplomacy is in the focus of this part of
the Course.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT AND CHANGES IN MODERN SOCIETY
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question:<I><B> How will IT
affect the way people live, work and learn?<BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Diplomats should have an understanding
of the profound changes in the production processes, and social
structure. They should also be aware of conceptual frameworks
and tools for the analysis of the modern world. These issues are
analyzed in proper economic, political, philosophical and sociological
perspectives. The main schools of thought explaining these phenomenon
is presented and reviewed.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT AND SOVEREIGNTY<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>To what extent
will the development of IT affect the ability of states to assert
their sovereignty in the international arena and over their national
destiny? <BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Diplomacy is directly affected by the
changes in the concept of sovereignty. One of the main function
of traditional diplomacy has been to protect the sovereignty of
states. Is this going to remain the main function of diplomacy?
Given that sovereignty, the key element of state, has been seriously
challenged by modern processes, it is necessary to provide diplomats
with a general understanding of these processes as well as of
the future of diplomacy in new constellation of power.</FONT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT AND INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (CONCEPT
OF POWER</FONT></I><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">)<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>Is it likely
that &quot;provinces&quot; and &quot;backwaters&quot; in the forthcoming
period will not be countries with geographical disadvantages,
but countries without access to the networks, or, for instance,
with IT-illiterate elites?</B></I> <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Professional education of diplomats
and foreign-policy decision makers has been based on the traditional
approaches to international relations (e.g. realist and idealist).
The main purpose of this module of the Course is to provide some
alternative approaches and to bring the diplomats' attention to
new perspectives of analyzing international relations. Special
emphasis is paid to the importance of geographical elements in
international relations. It is likely that the predominant determinant
of a country's economic and overall success is, among others,
the skills in managing information and data instead of controlling
territory or important geographical locations like it used to
be during the history of mankind.<B> <BR>
<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT AND CULTURAL DIVERSITY<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>How will the
growing movement of information in digital form across national
borders affect cultural, religious and other values. Is Huntington's
clash of civilization going to happen in cyber-space? What should
be the function of diplomacy in this respect?<BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Artifacts in digital form imposes a
new form of communication between individuals within the society
as well as between societies. IT will endanger traditional means
for protection and promotion of national culture and, at the same
time, create new ones. The special importance to this question
is in multi-cultural societies and regions (the Mediterranean),
where the issue of the protection of national cultures has a high
political importance.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT AND INTERNATIONAL ECONOMY<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">:
<I><B>How will the transition from a commerce/industry economy
towards an &quot;information economy&quot; influence the diplomats'
task to promote the economic interests of their countries?<BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Classical economic theory and practice
was build upon commerce/industry economy. &quot;Information economy&quot;
will require a new theoretical and practical framework The features
of this new framework are in the focus of this part of our Course.
<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>

</HTML>
