<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">NEW TOPICS ON DIPLOMATIC AGENDAS
</FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The growing centrality of IT-issues
in international relations has raised new and complex topics for
diplomats and foreign policymakers. Information Technology, which
already takes a huge share of economic transactions, requires
proper international legal and political framework. Creating this
framework, both on bilateral and multilateral level, is one of
the major tasks of diplomats. In order to perform this important
function, diplomats should have a broad knowledge of the various
aspects of IT-related issues from a technological, economic and
legal point of view.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">IT COMMODITIES AND SERVICES<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>What are the
most important IT commodities and services? What are their major
characteristics?<BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">The major aim of this part of the Course
is to provide the basic knowledge of IT commodities and services
with special emphasize on those that have or will have high importance
in international trade. The brief survey of major IT commodities
and services is provided, with special consideration of the protection
of software. As far as software is concerned the special attention
is paid on various components of the protection of software such
as: source code, operation systems, compilers, executable elements
of software, etc.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS, FORUMS
AND CHANNELS FOR REGULATION IT-RELATED ISSUES<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>What are the
major international organizations, forums and channels for discussing
and regulating IT-related issues?<BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">This part focuses on international institutional
framework for regulating IT-issues. The survey will start with
the established international organizations and forums such as
International Telecommunication UNION (ITU), The World Telecommunication
Forum, International Standard Organization (ISO), American National
Standards Institute (ANSI), European Computer Manufacturers' Association
(ECMA), etc. It will also consider existence of the number of
important NGOs, such as Electronic Frontier Foundation.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">TRANSFER OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question<B>:</B><I> What are
the various channels for the transfer of IT from developed to
developing countries?<BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Transfer of technology, including IT,
is one of the core topics of the modern international economy.
It has special importance for north-south relations, development,
etc. The major task of this part of Course is to make a survey
on the current policy of transfer of technology and to identify
all those aspect which have a special importance for diplomacy
and international relations. Special emphasize is given to GATT
activities and the newly-established WTO (World Trade Organization).
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">PROTECTION OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY
IN BILATERAL RELATIONS (SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON SOFTWARE) <BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>What are the
methods used for the protection of software in bilateral relations
between states? <BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Analysis of the current practice of
the United States and other developed countries in this respect
is provided. Special emphasis is placed on the position of developing
countries in their attempts with developed countries to enable
bilateral protection of software. The problem of linking bilateral
protection of software to the transfer of technology is also addressed
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">PROTECTION OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY
IN MULTILATERAL </FONT></I>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CONTEXT (SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON SOFTWARE)
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The key question: <I><B>What are the
safeguards used for the protection of software in the available
multilateral mechanisms (e.g. GATT, World Intellectual Property
Organization, EU, etc.). <BR>
</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">The Uruguay Round of GATT and the formation
of the World Trade Organization is taken as a case study on multilateral
protection of software. Positions of developed and developing
countries with regards to the protection of intellectual property
is tackled with special considerations on the pros and cons for
certain forms of protection of intellectual property.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">OTHER INTERNATIONAL LEGAL AND POLITICAL
TOPICS RAISED BY THE DEVELOPMENT OF IT<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Besides the above mentioned topics the
development of IT will bring a number of a new issues that should
be tackled on the international level (e.g. transboundary disputes
related to IT, protection of privacy, limiting of free communication
in the interest of international public order, </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>etc.
)<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>

</HTML>
