<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">NEW TOOLS FOR DIPLOMATIC ACTIVITIES
</FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Today, computers are more widely available
to a large community of users due to its lower cost. In diplomatic
circles, the use of computers was the privilege of the most developed
countries. Now, the use of computers in diplomacy can be afforded
by any country. Moreover, small States and other countries with
limited economic means for running their foreign affairs will
find computers a real necessity.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">This part of the Course considers the
practical use of computers in conducting diplomatic activities.
It focuses on the use of computer technology for:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI>the automation of traditional methods of performing diplomatic
functions; and
<LI>re-engineering of diplomatic procedures.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">INTRODUCTION<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Introduction into the computer science
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">history of computers, basic operations,
major components, distinction between hardware and software, etc.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of the operating system</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">brief survey of existing operating systems;
special emphasise on MS-DOS and Windows;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of word-processor</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI>typewriter vs. word processor; 
<LI>use of word processor for typing texts;
<LI>advanced options related to text-management, such as: language
and linguistic assistance, desktop-publishing, group editing;
tagging languages and compound document architecture (e.g. SMGL,
ODA, etc.). 
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Practical work</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">:
texts typed by students in the framework of other courses is analyzed
with regard to form, graphical presentation, utilisation of fonts
(serif - san serif, etc.)<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of spreadsheet applications</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI>accounting software, statistical operations, quantitative
analysis;
</UL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial"></FONT></I>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Practical work</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">:
students are asked to make small application that will cover part
of one diplomatic mission.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of database</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI>filing cabinet vs. databases
<LI>fast and punctual access to information as a key element of
diplomatic activity; 
<LI>various types of databases; internally-housed and remote databases;
other systems for modern management of data - hypertext and knowledge-based
software;
</UL>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Practical work</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">:
students are asked to build small database that should contain
information of academicians interested in their particular countries
searchable through the name of person, country and topic of interest.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of graphics software</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI>utilisation of graphics software for PR and country promotion.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">COMPUTER APPLICATIONS IN DIPLOMACY
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Model of the computerisation of diplomatic
activities</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">The model of computerisation of diplomatic
activities developed at the Academy is analysed with special emphasise
on: the flow of information, interaction and interchange among
various departments, interaction between the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and the other ministries and governmental departments,
etc.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Creating specialized databases for
international law, international relations, diplomacy, etc.;</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Interdisciplinary study provides students
with knowledge about tools available by IT in handling data related
to international law, international relations and diplomacy.</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Practical presentation</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">
and use of the Database of international legal materials developed
at the Academy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Creating knowledge-based systems
for international law, international relations, diplomacy, etc.;</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Interdisciplinary study of implementation
of artificial intelligence in areas of interest.</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Practical presentation</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">
of the Project related to Expert System for Responsibility Under
International Environmental Law.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of other type of software (simulation
of negotiations, political and economical analysis, etc.);</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Students are instructed how to use the
software for simulation of negotiations as well as for various
political and economic analysis.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Use of computers in preparation and
conducting international conferences (GATT and UNCED)</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Study of experience from GATT and UNCED
related to use of computers in preparing and conducting international
conferences.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">USE OF COMPUTERISED DATA SOURCES
FOR INFORMATION GATHERING RELATED TO DIPLOMATIC ACTIVITIES <BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Concept of International Information
Systems (types, technical requirements, etc.)</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Access remote databases - necessary
technical requirements;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Internet<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Introduction</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Issues:</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1> history and concept
of Internet; basic terminology; way of connecting to Internet.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>E-mail</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Issues</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1>: function of E-mail;
basic terminology; technical requirements; confidentiality and
protection of E-mail; use of E-mail in diplomatic communication;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Telenet and FTP</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Issues: functions of these two services; technical
requirements.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Gopher, Archie, World Wide Web</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Issues</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1>: concepts and functions
of the above mentioned services; future of World Wide Web as a
innovative method for handling information.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Electronic conferences</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Issues</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=1>: concepts and functions
of electronic conferences; electronic conference as a means for
the exchange of information and promotion of national interests;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Internet resources for diplomats</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1>Issues: Internet services of special interest for
diplomats and specialists for international relations available
in international organizations (UN, UNDP, NATO, EU, etc.), educational
institutions, governments, etc. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>

