<DOCHDR>
http://ns.medac.comnet.mt:80/lectures/kappeler/select/gumboot1.htm 194.223.143.33 19970216030010 text/html 1770
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 16 Feb 1997 03:03:18 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
Last-Modified: Tue, 28 May 1996 09:25:22 GMT
Content-Length: 1570
</DOCHDR>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Paper.gif"><TITLE>Query Results</TITLE><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.medac.comnet.mt:81/V/D/1870.html">Gumboot Diplomacy, A New Task for Diplomats by Professor Dietrich Kappeler</A><BR></UL><P><HR>Total: 1

<BR>
<BR>
Quote from Prof. Kappeler's paper:
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="4">
<B>"Gumboot diplomacy may well become a hallmark of the ending 20th and the 
beginning 21st centuries, just as Gunboat Diplomacy characterised the behaviour 
of imperialistic powers in the late 19th and early 20th centuries."</B>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="4">
<BR>

<IMG src="post-it.gif" align=left>The first association with "gumboots", that comes to mind, is<A HREF="debono.htm"> Edward de Bono's</A>
(Maltese philosopher and creative thinking praxeologist) work: Six Action 
Shoes.<P>

Just as a food for thought - it would be interesting to explore differencies 
and similarities in using "gumboots" by two authors as the metaphor for acting.<P>

<IMG src="post-it.gif" align=left>An occasional user of Web probabbly perceives using the Web as an endless 
jumping from one place to another, from one piece of information to another. 
However, the chain of links (providing they are consistent with subject 
matter) should be seen more in the sense of <A HREF="http://www.isg.sfu.ca/~duchier/misc/vbush/vbush7.shtml">
Vannevar Bush's trails</A>. The 
associative pathway, one takes, reflects that person's individual view to a 
certain subject and thus reveils the knowledge of that person that can be 
acquired or considered by others.
<HR>







