<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>A CAREER IN THE DIPLOMATIC SERVICE OF 
THE GOVERNMENT OF MALTA</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!--<Body bgcolor="#fbfbFF"  TEXT="#0000FF" link="#880000">-->
<Body bgcolor="#f8e4f8"  TEXT="#0000FF" link="#880000">


<CENTER>
<table border=5>
<tr><td width=600>
<B><font size=4 color="#880000"><center>A CAREER IN THE DIPLOMATIC SERVICE OF<BR>
 THE GOVERNMENT OF MALTA</CENTER></FONT></B>
</TD>
</tr>
</table>
</CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="mcoa1.gif" align=middle hsize=10>
<B>Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta</B>
</CENTER>
<br><BR><BR>

<hr>

<UL>
<A href="#historical"><img src="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Historical Background</a><BR>
<A href="#public"><img src="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>The Public Competition Process</a><BR>
<A href="#conditions"><img src="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Conditions of Employment</a><BR>
<A href="stairc.htm"><img src="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Career Progression</a>
</ul>


<p><br><hr noshade size=5>
<a name="historical"></a>
<center>
<table border = 5>
<tr>
<td width=600>
<B><font size=4 color="#880000">
<center>A DIPLOMATIC CAREER IN THE <br>
MALTESE FOREIGN SERVICE
</center></Font></b>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>


<P align=center><tt>
<I>&quot;What does independence consist of?  It consists fundamentally
and basically of foreign relations.  That is the test of independence.&quot;</I>

<P align=right>
Pandit NEHRU, 1949
</tt>
<P>
<B>Historical Background</B>

<P>
Efforts to organize and establish a Ministry of Foreign Affairs
in Malta started very soon after Independence in 1964.  At that
time, staff drawn mainly from the General Service of the Public
Service were selected to form the pioneer complement of the Ministry
of Commonwealth and Foreign Affairs.  It was soon agreed, however,
that an External Affairs Service had to be established on a professional
basis, and that the Service therefore required to have within
its ranks individuals with specific qualifications and aptitudes.

<P>
By mid-1965, the organization of the Ministry of Commonwealth
and Foreign Affairs was already taking shape.  The work of the
Ministry was divided into two main blocks: one dealt with administrative,
protocol, information and consular matters, while the other dealt
with political and commercial matters.

<P>

<blockquote><TT> <I>&quot;... the first steps were taken to start
forming an External Affairs Service.  The aim was set to have
a small diplomatic corps of trained and highly efficient officers
who, with experience, would be able to do their job with credit.
 What we were looking for were young men and women endowed with
the requisite intellectual capacity who had a genuine interest
in and dedication for the job, with strength of character and
an agreeable personality thrown in with physical and mental health.&quot;</I>
</TT></blockquote>

<TT>
<P align =right>
F.E. Amato GAUCI <br>
'The Birth of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs'<br>
<I>The Times, Thursday 21st September, 1969</I>
</TT>
<P>
The External Affairs Service may be said to have been formally
set up in 1965.  Initially, it comprised the grades of Counsellor,
 First Secretary and Second Secretary.  In 1973, the higher grade 
of First Counsellor was created.  The Ambassador was generally 
a political appointee.  The rank of Envoy, at a slightly lower 
grade than Ambassador, also existed for a time.
<P>
About 90 candidates competed for vacancies in the first examination 
run to recruit officers in the External Affairs Service.  Between 
1965 and 1968, the Service's diplomatic complement rose to two 
Counsellors, three First Secretaries and thirteen Second Secretaries.
 In 1974, the External Affairs Service was abolished, and recruitment 
of Foreign Service staff did not continue, although a few diplomatic 
officers were appointed.
<P>
With the change of Government in 1987, interest in a Foreign Affairs
Service was revived.  After an internal process, some Counsellors
were appointed and an examination for First Secretaries was held
in April 1992.  The <U><B>Maltese Diplomatic Service</B></U> was
set up on a formal, sound and professional basis in October 1994.
 The maximum point of entry in the Foreign Service is now at the
level of Second Secretary, and public examinations have been run
for this purpose in March 1995 and in April 1996.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><img src="divid049.jpg"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>

<a name="public"></a>
<center>
<table border = 5>
<tr>
<td width=600>
<B><font size=4 color="#880000">
<center>A DIPLOMATIC CAREER IN THE <br>
MALTESE FOREIGN SERVICE
</center></Font></b>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>


<P><font size="4">
<B>The Public Competition Process</B>
<P><font size="3">
<B>Entry into the grade of Second Secretary</B>
<UL>
<LI><B><font size="2">Announcements</font></B>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The call for applications is announced in the Government
Gazette of Malta and advertised in the local press.
<UL>
<LI><B><font size="2">Applications</font></b>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Applications are made on an official form which is obtained
from the Department of Examinations both in Malta and in Gozo.
<UL>
<LI><B><font size = "2">Eligibility</font></b>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Recruitment is open to graduates holding a first degree,
in any discipline, from a recognized University.
<P>
 The competition also requires a working knowledge of two foreign
languages other than Maltese and English.
<UL>
<LI><B><font size ="2">Written Examination</font></B>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The written examination is held in two stages:
<P>
- <I><B>Paper I</B></I> consists of a test in pr&eacute;cis writing
and current affairs.  The current affairs section normally involves
a series of short and multiple choice styled questions.
<P>
- <I><B>Paper II</B></I> consists of a test in international affairs
set in the form of essay type questions.  The topics tackled range
from Malta's foreign policy to socio/economic and political issues.
<P>
 Candidates who achieve at least 60% of the marks in each of the
two written papers move on to the second part of the examination,
the interview.
<UL>
<LI><B><font size ="2">The Interview</font></B>
</UL>


<P>
The interview session normally lasts a full day.  It assesses
candidates on their personality, deportment and quickness of comprehension.
 The methods utilized to carry out this assessment include writing
a short brief on a set news item of the day, a group discussion,
individual interviews and testing a candidate's knowledge of a
foreign language (the candidate will normally be expected to write
a summary in English of a short text in the foreign language).
<P>
 The interview's pass mark is 60% of the marks allotted.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><img src="divid049.jpg"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>

<a name="conditions"></a>
<center>
<table border = 5>
<tr>
<td width=600>
<B><font size=4 color="#880000">
<center>A DIPLOMATIC CAREER IN THE <br>
MALTESE FOREIGN SERVICE
</center></Font></b>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>

<P>
<B><font size ="4">Conditions Of Employment</font></B>
<UL>
<LI><B><font size = "2">Job description</font></B>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Appointees will essentially be representing the interests
of Malta in its relations with other countries.  Furthermore,
diplomatic officers will be offered an interesting and varied
career with possibilities for travel, learning and prospects for
promotion on the basis of performance.  
<P>
 A Second Secretary would carry out the activities pertaining
to the Directorate concerned whilst in Malta.  These duties would
normally include:
<P>
- monitoring relations between Malta and countries with which
diplomatic relations have been established;
<P>
- initiation and possibly renewal of agreements made between Malta
and the countries in question;
<P>
- preparation of briefs analyzing the socio/political and bilateral
history of the countries with which diplomatic relations have
been established;
<P>
- communication with other Ministries clarifying pending matters;
<P>
- following up and updating Malta's interactions with international
organizations.
<UL>
<LI><B><font size = "2">Conditions of Employment</font></B>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Appointment to the grade of Second Secretary entails a
preliminary probationary period of two years.  The employment
contract involves a binding commitment to serve the Ministry in
Malta or overseas when considered necessary and in accordance
with the rules and conditions of the Ministry.
<P>
 The period of training which all Second Secretary appointees
are required to undergo within the probationary term may be carried
out either at Head Office, in Maltese Missions overseas or in
appropriate Institutes of learning in Malta or abroad.  The training
period alternates between expansive academical instruction and
practical hands-on experience working in real life situations.
</BODY>


