<BODY BGCOLOR="#a8c4c0">

<P>
<CENTER><B><I><font size=+3>Art and Architecture of Palazzo Parisio</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<BR>
<HR>
<A HREF="agrech.htm"><IMG SRC="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Mural Paintings</A>
<P>
<A HREF="gallery/gal1.htm"><IMG SRC="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Collection of Paintings</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#architecture"><IMG SRC="abluedot.gif" border=0 hspace=10>Architecture</A>
<HR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="architecture"></A>
<CENTER><B><font size=+2>The Architecture of Palazzo Parisio</font></B></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="murals/paris53.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
The Parisio palace, which is higher up Merchants' Street, at the
corner of Melita Street, consists of three blocks built around
a courtyard. Its main fa&ccedil;ade is symetrical but the plan
is not. The facade is sober and with little emphasis on the centre,
save for an 
<!--<A HREF="mural/capital4.jpg">--><B>elaborate doorway</B></A>
and a broken segmental-headed window above, but the front is not
long, with only six windows in its length, so that the expedients
adopted in the other palaces need not be resorted to here. The
windows have beeen spaced so that a semblance of order was obtained
on the elevation and more or less regular spacing occurred inside
the main room (Sala Giorgio Borg Olivier nowadays - See the upper
right picture of the <A HREF="#FourInteriors"><B>four interiors </B></A>
pictures below). The corner has large superimposed pilasters,
the lower one being heavily rusticated. It is strange to notice
that the joints of the rustications bear no relationship to the
courses of the masonry. Also, the resemblance should be noticed
between the top-floor windows and those on the Selmun palace by
Cachia.
<P>
(After Quentin Hughes, The Building of Malta 1530 - 1798)
<P>
A reader can find a  few <A HREF="../history/famous.htm#2ndfloor"><B>more</B></A>
elements in the V. Denaro's article.
<P>
<!--<A HREF="avi/revol4.avi">--><CENTER><IMG SRC="murals/arch1.jpg"></CENTER></A>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="FourInteriors"></A>
The interiors of the Palazzo Parisio are shown in the following
pictures. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="murals/coridor1.jpg" hspace=10><IMG SRC="murals/gorgroom.jpg"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="murals/shell211.jpg" hspace=10><IMG SRC="murals/coridor2.jpg"></CENTER>
<P>
