<!--<BODY BGCOLOR="#FE9E58" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF8000" VLINK="#A0A0A0" ALINK="#C00000"
 BACKGROUND="tickleaf.jpg" >-->
<BODY Bgcolor="#faebd7" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF8000" VLINK="#A0A0A0" BACKGROUND="tickleaf.jpg" >

<b><h1>The Institute of International Relations of the University of the West Indies (IIRT)</h1></b>
<i><b>St. Augustine, Trinidad & Tobago </b></i>
<hr>


<h2>History</h2>

This Institute is based on an agreement between the governments of Barbados, Guyana, Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago, under whose provisions the said governments share among themselves the financing of the Institute. In 1972 the Institute received a new charter, which was incorporated in 1973 into a revised agreement between the sponsoring countries. 


<h2>Status</h2>

The Institute enjoys financial and academic autonomy but is affiliated to the University of the West Indies which awards its degrees. It is governed by a Board chaired by the Vice-Chancellor of the University of the West Indies. Members are representatives of the University, CARICOM, the OECS, the IUHEI, UNITAR and the funding countries.


<h2>Courses</h2>

The Institute offers a one year course for a Diploma in International Relations for diplomats, non-diplomats and ordinary students alike. Holders of the Diploma who also have a first degree may register for a M.Sc. in International Relations. The Institute also offers a course for a M.A. in International Relations by research and thesis alone, which may be followed by a Ph.D. in International Relations. The first such doctorate has been recently awarded. The teaching and working language is English.  From its inception, the Institute has also organised short training programmes in neighbouring countries, either as crash courses in diplomacy or concentrating on specific issues such as international negotiations.


<h2>Conferences</h2>

The Institute has hosted a number of conferences and seminars of which the one on Regional Integration held in 1987 and another on Narco-Trafficking in the Caribbean held in 1995 deserve special mention.

</BODY>
</HTML>


</DOC>
