<h1><b>The International Relations Institute of Cameroon (IRIC)</b></h1>
<i><b>Yaounde, Cameroon</b></i>
<hr>

<h2>History</h2>

This Institute was set up in 1971 as a result of the decision of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace to discontinue its diplomatic training programme in Geneva. 

<h2>Status</h2>

It is an autonomous institute affiliated to the University of Yaounde II, which awards the degrees for its courses. Its main organ is a Governing Board chaired by the Minister of
Foreign Affairs and on which also sit the Minister of Education, the Chancellor and other representatives of the University and a representative of the IUHEI. The Institute has obtained consultative status with the Organization for African Unity.

<h2>Courses</h2>

The IRIC offers a course for a Master in International Relations for holders of a first degree. Holders of the Master's degree may enrol for doctoral studies. The IRIC also offers a Diplomatic Training Course for junior diplomats from African countries, which lasts one academic year. Teaching and working languages are French and English.

<h2>Conferences</h2>

The IRIC has over the years convened a number of colloquia and conferences, including the one which, in 1972, designed the African concept of an Exclusive Economic Zone which was later submitted as a common African position to the United Nations Conference on the law of the Sea. It has hosted several times an African Seminar on Humanitarian Law, in association with the International Committee of the Red Cross. In 1993, it hosted a Colloquium on the Challenges of African Diplomacy
on the Eve of the 21st Century.


</DOC>
