<h1><b>The Institute of Diplomacy and International Studies of the University
of Nairobi (IDIS)</b></h1>
<b><i>Nairobi, Kenya</i></b>
<hr>


<h2>History</h2>

In 1973 an agreement was signed by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, the Kenyan Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the University of Nairobi for the creation at that University of a Diplomacy Training Programme (DTP). The IUHEI was asked to step in as a sponsor in 1976, under an agreement between Switzerland and Kenya. In 1989 the DTP was transformed into an Institute of Diplomacy and International Studies
with the assistance of the UNDP.


<h2>Status</h2>

The IDIS is an autonomous institution within the framework of the University of Nairobi, which awards the degrees for its courses. Its main organ is a Governing Board, on which the University and some of its faculties and departments are represented, as well as the Office of the President, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Ministry of Finances,
UNDP and the Directorate of Development Cooperation and Humanitarian Aid of Switzerland. The Institute has a long- standing cooperation with the Commowealth Fund for Technical Cooperation (CFTC). It is in the process of obtaining consultative status with the Organization of African Unity, the UN Economic Commission for Africa and the African Development Bank.


<h2>Courses</h2>

The Institute offers a one year course for a Postgraduate Diploma in International Relations, taken over from its predecessor, the Diplomacy Training Programme. This course is specially designed and reserved for African diplomats. The Institute also offers a two year course for a Master of Arts in Diplomatic Studies accessible to any candidate fullfilling the academic admission requirements. For the moment, no doctoral studies are envisaged. Although the Institute is officially bilingual English/French, the main teaching and working language remains English.


<h2>Conferences</h2>

The Institute has organised a number of colloquia and seminars over the years, including one on the Training of Third World Diplomats in 1988 and another on Thirty Years of African Diplomacy in 1991.


</DOC>
