<HEAD>

<TITLE>INAUGURAL SPEECH BY THE HON</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>OPENING STATEMENT<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>The Hon. Prof. Guido DE MARCO</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>,
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs, Malta </FONT>
<HR>

<P>
Mr. President, Ladies and Gentlemen <BR>

<P>
I thank you for giving me the opportunity to address another seminar
organised by the Mediterranean Academy for Diplomatic Studies.
I have strong affinity in the work of this Academy and I have
a great interest in its expansion and further success. Coming
here to discuss topics of world affairs is an exercise in international
relations. The fact that Prof. Bin is holding the Italy Chair
at this academy as being the mover of this conference on Co-operation
and Security in the Mediterranean after the Barcelona Conference,
I think has to be commended because it reflects more aspects than
one. It reflects this Mediterranean approach. It reflects Italy's
involvement in Euro-Mediterranean Affairs. In fact, as Prof. Tanner
has quite rightly pointed out, the fact that this is being held
in Malta reflects the role which Malta envisages, namely that
which aims at regularising relations in our regions. This is a
region which requires stability. This is a region which is in
turmoil. In Barcelona, we tried to create the basis for dialogue,
which in essence is what we are going to discuss today; What Co-operation:
what security in the Mediterranean following Barcelona? <BR>

<P>
Western civilisation knows its origins to the Mediterranean region.
It was here, in one country or other bordering the Mediterranean
littoral, that the development of western civilisation was unfolded
over many centuries. This momentum, however, was not sustained.
Our region regrettably lost the initiative and allowed other countries,
whether it be in other parts of Europe and elsewhere, to take
over what it had painstakingly developed in the first place. It
was no longer the principal actor in the drama of the history
of mankind. Instead, the region sank into an era of ideological
differences and internecine wars which undermined and held back
political, economic and social development. <BR>

<P>
Although the Mediterranean offers all the potential advantages
of a place of convergence, it has more often been an arena of
conflict than a forum for promoting complementarity and unity.
Despite a common patrimony in civilisation and many linkages,
the Mediterranean region remains today separated by contentions
and rifts. <BR>

<P>
We face, in our region, a multitude of complex challenges and
problems, ranging from economic deprivation, environmental degradation,
population explosion and migration to ethnic friction, intolerant
fundamentalism and the escalation of nationalism, the arms trade
and the disregard for international law. <BR>

<P>
There are, in my view, four challenges which are undermining peace
and stability. The first, is the huge economic discrepancy between
the northern and southern countries of the region which is intensifying
the root problems. These include weak economic structures, state
indebtedness, high demographic growth, and an alarming level of
unemployment. I will return and elaborate on this point later
on. <BR>

<P>
The second is the emergence on the southern shores of the Mediterranean
of extremism characterised by terrorism. Socio-economic crises
tend to form a fertile ground for extremist ideologies. The movement
negates universal values and offers no democratic alternatives.
If allowed to spread, it will turn back the clock to dark ages.
<BR>

<P>
Third is a prosperous arms trade, which is growing to the detriment
of economic and social development. The concentration of military
arsenals in the Mediterranean basin remains at alarming levels
because of a preoccupation with declared or potential conflicts.
<BR>

<P>
Fourth is the ecological factor. The pollution of the Mediterranean
Sea is reaching proportions which are alarming. Instead of being
treated in line with its ecological value and as an important
economic resource, the Mediterranean is being considered as everybody
else's domain. Unless together, we do not devise and implement
good-management-of-the-sea measures, the ecological factors will
constitute more instability in region. <BR>

<P>
Added to these challenges is the difficulty of putting into practice
a standard of international law. The lack of standard legality
is hampering the function of the Middle East peace process and
holding up further progress in the resolution of other pending
conflicts, such as those in Cyprus, the Western Sahara, Lebanon,
the former Yugoslavia and the Balkans among others. <BR>

<P>
The result of these and other challenges is insecurity and instability
not only on the southern shores of the Mediterranean region, but
for the entire region. The complexities of the problems that face
us today are such that it is becoming increasingly difficult to
confront them individually and in isolation at the level of separate
states. They necessitate an active participation and genuine solidarity
between all member states of the region. <BR>

<P>
The concept of security is constantly being re-examined and re-evaluated.
In the aftermath of the Second World War, it was thought the security
questions could be resolved by concluding military pacts. Later,
security was associated with arsenals of nuclear weapons and naval
fleets. This political-military strategy which dominated East-West
relations and influenced the North's relations with the South,
led to frustrations, bitter arguments and stalemates. <BR>

<P>
The failure of the political-military strategy led political thinkers
to seek other options to collective security. They developed the
concept of co-operative security. Whereas collective security
is an arrangement for deterring aggression through military preparations
and defeating it when it occurs, co-operative security is designed
to ensure that organised aggression cannot start or be prosecuted
on any large scale. <BR>

<P>
The strategic principle of co-operative security is to enhance
peace and security through institutionalised consent rather than
physical coercion. It seeks collaborative rather than confrontational
relationships among national military establishments. The emphasis
is less on preparation to counter threats than on the prevention
of threats in the first place. Thus, the significance of confidence-building
is obvious. <BR>

<P>
Co-operative security gave rise to the policy of d&eacute;tente
advocated so strongly by the then US Secretary of State and National
Security Advisor, Dr Henry Kissinger and their inviolability and
a commitment not to interfere in the internal affairs of signatory
members. <BR>

<P>
From our perspective, the Helsinki Final Act will always be remembered
in that it was for the fist time that on Malta's initiative security
and co-operation in Europe became linked to security and co-operation
in the Mediterranean region the so called Mediterranean Basket.
More than twenty year ago, in a world still dominated by the Cold
War the Conference for Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE)
recognised the need to promote the development of good neighbourly
relations with non-participating Mediterranean states. This nomenclature
of non-participating Mediterranean States within the OSCE created
a negative environment. It was through Malta' initiative that
in the OSCE Permanent Council December 1995 meeting in Budapest
the nomenclature was turned into Mediterranean Partners for co-operation.
This change in nomenclature is not just of cosmetic value. This
change, in so far as Malta is concerned, was made for explicit
purposes. One cannot participate for non-participation purposes.
One can only participate with partners. This is why Malta was
behind this change in nomenclature. <BR>

<P>
It is on this basis that the European Union has taken the initiative
to found the Renewed Mediterranean Policy. In 1989, it declared
its New Mediterranean Policy in view of the changes in the international
political situation, the globalisation of the economy, the widening
imbalances between North and South, and the completion of the
EU single market. The European Union, in order to be in a position
to withstand competition from the two main strategic areas of
America and Asia, has extended its partnership areas such as:
EFTA, Central and Eastern Europe and the Mediterranean countries.
<BR>

<P>
As a result of the Euro-Mediterranean Conference which took place
in Barcelona in November 1995, the 15 member states of the European
Union and the 12 countries bordering the Mediterranean Sea established
the basis for a lasting framework of collaboration. I am using
the word with a measure of optimism. The Declaration of the Barcelona
Conference gave three reasons for its desire to give a new dimension
to the future Euro-Mediterranean relations based on solidarity
and co-operation. These were: <BR>

<P>
* the strategic importance of the Mediterranean; 
<P>
* the necessity to guarantee peace and prosperity in the region;
and <BR>

<P>
* the co-ordinated answer which was required by new common economic,
political and social challenges. <BR>

<P>
For these reasons, the countries which met in Barcelona &quot;resolved
to establish a multilateral and lasting framework of relations
based on a spirit of partnership, with due regard for he characteristics,
values and distinguishing features peculiar to each of the participants&quot;.
<BR>

<P>
The three aspects of the Euro-Mediterranean partnership are: 
<BR>

<P>
* strengthened political dialogue; <BR>

<P>
* the development of economic and financial co-operation; and
<BR>

<P>
* greater emphasis on the social, cultural and human dimension.
<BR>

<P>
I would like now to dwell for some time on each one of these aspects,
in order to bring into perspective the ultimate objective of the
Barcelona Declaration: the creation of a zone of peace, stability,
prosperity and co-operation based on dialogue and solidarity.
<BR>

<P>
<B>Strengthened Political Dialogue<BR>
</B>
<P>
The objective of this partnership is to consolidate peace, stability
and security in the Mediterranean region. They agreed to establish
a number of common principles and interests, acceptable to all,
which the partners would undertake to promote together. <BR>

<P>
As a starting point, they agreed to act according to the principles
of international law and of different international declarations,
such as the United Nations Charter and the Universal Declaration
of Human Rights, respecting fundamental freedoms and guaranteeing
their free exercise. <BR>

<P>
In internal affairs, Ministers of Foreign Affairs agreed to develop
the rule of law and democracy, recognising the right to choose
and develop freely their own political, legal, social and cultural
systems, guaranteeing the respect of diversity and fighting against
intolerance and racism. They declared their readiness to abstain
from whatever direct or indirect intervention in internal affairs,
respecting the territorial integrity of all partners and using
pacific means to solve conflicts. <BR>

<P>
We agreed to act in favour of chemical, biological and nuclear
arms non- proliferation by complying with the different international
and regional non-proliferation agreements. They also concurred
on the need to organise activities to combat terrorism, organised
crime and drugs. <BR>

<P>
In order to implement the principles of the Barcelona Declaration,
a work programme is scheduled whereby senior officials will meet
periodically to conduct a political dialogue, to decide the most
adequate methods and to submit proposals for the meetings of Foreign
Ministers. <BR>

<P>
<B>The Development of Economic and Financial Co-operation: An
Economic and Financial Partnership <BR>
</B>
<P>
The objective is to build a Euro-Mediterranean zone of shared
prosperity by accelerating the pace of sustained socio-economic
development, improving the living conditions of the population,
increasing the level of employment, reducing the development gap,
and promoting regional co-operation and integration. 
<P>
To this end, an economic and financial partnership is set to be
established based on the following guidelines: <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. The gradual establishment of a free trade area
by the year 2010<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
This is an ambitious approach. An action plan is put forward,
setting out the framework, priorities and arrangements for partnership
in order to establish a Euro-Mediterranean economic area based
on free trade in accordance with the obligations arising under
the World Trade Organisation. A calendar will be negotiated in
order to eliminate tariff and non-tariff barriers on manufactured
and agricultural products, even though the latter will be progressively
liberalised through reciprocal preferential access. To facilitate
the process, it will be necessary to adopt measures concerning
rules of origin, certification, protection of intellectual and
industrial property rights, and to develop policies based on the
principle of free market economy and integration, and on an adequate
legal and institutional framework. The modernisation of the economy
and the social effect on the needy population are also important
factors in the establishment of a free trade zone. <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. Economic co-operation and concerted action
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
It is considered necessary to help internal savings, direct foreign
investment and voluntary regional co-operation, eliminating possible
obstacles. It is also important to achieve agreements between
companies, establishing an adequate legal frame for it, and to
offer to the Small and Medium-sized Enterprises technical support
programmes. The environment is considered as an important issue
tied with economic development, and therefore a short and medium
term programme will be established, which will be granted with
technical and financial assistance, giving priority to combatting
desertification. The Declaration also enhances the key role of
women in economic and social development. Finally, it is necessary
to co-operate in specific areas, such as energy and agricultural
policy and to improve infrastructures, to promote co-operation
in regional planning and in Research and Development to harmonise
statistical techniques. <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. Financial co-operation<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The success of the Euro-Mediterranean partnership requires an
improvement in financial assistance, that should be managed by
local agents to achieve an indigenous and sustainable development.
The European Union has promised 4,685 million Ecu for the period
1995-99 through MEDA programme, in addition to loans from the
European Development Bank and bilateral financial loans from member
states. This co-operation will be managed on the basis of a multi-annual
programme that will be promoted through dialogue, and should take
into consideration the importance of sound macroeconomic management.
<BR>

<P>
<B>Greater Emphasis on the Social, Cultural and Human Dimension:
A Partnership in Social, Cultural and Human Affairs. <BR>
</B>
<P>
The objective is to develop human resources, promote understanding
between cultures and exchanges within civil society. In this context
of decentralised co-operation, the emphasis is placed on education,
training and young people, culture and the media, migrant population
groups and health. Greater co-operation in the field of justice
and home affairs is also envisaged, with action in particular
directed against drug trafficking, terrorism and international
crime. We have to evolve in the Mediterranean a 'people to people'
approach. I think this is of the essence of things. May I give
you Malta's specific approach about the issues I've been explaining
in so far as Barcelona is concerned. The concept of these three
pillars, the making of Barcelona as an ongoing process is the
essence for its success. We cannot speak about the spirit of Barcelona
if we refer to Barcelona in the past tense. It only has a meaning
if it is poised in an ongoing process future concept. We know
and we realise that in order to promote the social pillar and
the economic pillar, basic to all this is the first pillar, namely
the political and security pillar. 
<P>
It is with this in mind that when twenty years ago Malta launched
the concept of the linkage between the security in Europe and
security in the Mediterranean, we realised from our location in
the centre of the Mediterranean, that one cannot speak for security
in Europe if one disregards Mediterranean issues.<BR>

<P>
The fall of the Berlin Wall will have lasting effects on the future
of Europe and the Mediterranean States as far lasting as the fall
of the Bastille because it is not simply the fall of a wall; a
great divide has been broken too. It is not only a unification
of Germany which has taken place; it is a breakdown of an artificial,
ecological and military barrier. <BR>

<P>
The effects of the fall of the Berlin Wall and the effects of
the end of the Cold War, through historical coincidence happened
here in Malta with the Bush/Gorbachev Meeting. In the words of
Eduard Shevardnadze in his book. The Future is for Freedom, we
read,
<P>
&quot;in the tempestuous seas in Malta we buried the Cold War&quot;.
<BR>

<P>
Which Mediterranean therefore, do we see emerging from the end
of the Cold War? Which problems still persist from the Cold War?
The absence of having the Mediterranean poised in a confrontational
issue between the two blocs and the effects of a non-polar world
on the Mediterranean region. We are still confronted with a Mediterranean
region, having its northern shores belonging in the main to the
NATO alliance, and its southern shores fragmented in search of
an identity, troubled by an economic situation which is the main
reason for present disruptive effects. The Middle East Peace is
a process which we think is fundamental for the future of the
Mediterranean. Unless the Middle East Peace Process continues,
the Mediterranean region will find no peace. It will be the greatest
of tragedies if terrorism wins over the peace of the brave as
it was defined. And it will be one of the tragedies of history
when terrorism prevails over dialogue. I think both Chairman Arafat
and Shimon Peres were very clear when they stated in no uncertain
terms that it was easier to wage war than to wage peace. Peace
can only be brought about through dialogue and it is through dialogue,
where the present problems can be discussed and eventually solved,
that Malta believes that there is no alternative to the Peace
Process. <BR>

<P>
It will be the tragedy of us all to succumb to terrorism and stop
a process which can be the only way to guarantee a future for
the people of the Mediterranean region and beyond. We think again
that for the Mediterranean region to discover itself, it needs,
above all stability. On the 20th March 1995, I had the privilege
to attend the Final Conference of the Pact on Stability in Europe,
the so called Balladur Plan. And there for the first time Malta
launched its proposal for a Stability Pact for the Mediterranean,
a Stability Pact which has to be not inspired by the same reasons
and by the same situation which exist in Europe, particularly
in Central and Eastern Europe, nor necessarily by the same round
table approach which was evolved, particularly, for minority issues
in Central and Eastern Europe. The concept of stability for our
region has to be clearly seen by identifying the sources, and
the elements destabilising the Mediterranean, be they terrorism,
or fundamentalism. In this context, I will never use the phrase
Islamic fundamentalism. This is one of the misnomers which is
creating a lot of harm and a lot of misunderstandings. Islam is
one to the great religions, one of the peace factors in global
affairs. And identifying a retrograde approach with a religion
which has permanent values is one of the mistakes which sometimes,
we in politics and some also in diplomacy, manage to commit. 
<BR>

<P>
Fundamentalism is one of the sources creating the destabilising
factors in our region. The same applies also to massive unemployment
which exists in so many regions. There are areas with 50/60% unemployment.
There are areas where we have not only the classical proletariat,
but where an intellectual proletariat, has been created, with
ambitions of power, using the emotive forces created by poverty
in order to ensure a situation where there is a revoking of power
games. Are these the factors that destabilise the Mediterranean
region? <BR>

<P>
May I also say that in this region of ours there are two Curtains.
One creating a stronger barrier than the other. These are the
Poverty Curtain and the Prejudice Curtain. These two curtains
that are creating a great divide in the Mediterranean region.
That is why Malta has proposed the Stability Pact for the Mediterranean.
We appreciate the fact that the French Foreign Minister De Charrette
in Barcelona has also advanced the concept of a Stability Pact
for the Mediterranean. I think it will be certainly a major contribution
to preventive diplomacy having this Stability Pact in place. May
I also add that we have always tended to look at the Mediterranean
in a vertical approach. We suggest that to this vertical approach
should be added the horizontal approach. That is why we have suggested
time and time again, a Council for the Mediterranean; an Association
of Mediterranean States; a Partnership between Mediterranean states;
which does not amount only to the economic partnership envisaged
in the second pillar of Barcelona. Through this horizontal approach
towards the Mediterranean one can evolve a different framework
where the Mediterranean can dialogue. A dialogue taking place
both at governmental level and at parliamentary level. <BR>

<P>
The oldest European institution is the Council of Europe, a Council
where we used to have committees for non-member states, when at
the time, we used to look at the Council of Europe as a beacon
directed towards the Central and Eastern European countries and
also towards the Iberian Peninsula. And this beacon lit. Today
the Council of Europe, which some describe as a club, has created
a European democratic space from the Atlantic further into the
Urals. We in the Mediterranean, without imitating but merely by
adapting ideas, which were proven right, can adapt to our own
region. And this is why we believe that starting from a Council
of the Mediterranean, an Association of Mediterranean States,
we can build this concept of dialogue in this explosive region.
<BR>

<P>
This is something which we have to realise. We have no time to
spare. I have always repeated that the Mediterranean is a time
bomb with an ever shortening fuse. It is difficult to speak about
a Mediterranean identity. We take this Mediterranean region with
all components: whether Europeans, whether Arabs, or whether belonging
to the Middle East. But when we speak about a Mediterranean identity,
it is difficult and on the other hand, understandable, that we
have common interests, common concerns and that we have a common
heritage. <BR>

<P>
So without losing our own identity, I believe we can and will
ensure a process in the Mediterranean region which will create
stability. We need stability. If we face this challenge, the Mediterranean
challenge, much will be achieved both for us belonging to the
region, and for those beyond. This is why the Mediterranean which
resulted from the Barcelona Conference, has to be an on-going
process, a dynamic process, a peace process. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
