<HEAD>

<TITLE>After Madrid and Barcelona</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>AFTER MADRID AND BARCELONA: PROSPECTS FOR MEDITERRANEAN SECURITY
<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Nabil FAHMY, Political Advisor to H.E. Mr. Amre Moussa,
Minister of Foreign Affairs, Egypt</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
The Mediterranean is a region which has not acquired recognition
as a distinct security zone in its own right. This has been due
to a combination of factors, most important of which have been
that the exigencies of superpower rivalry and the Arab-Israeli
conflict have been superimposed on the security considerations
of Mediterranean states. The region has always been perceived
as an extension of other security zones, namely Europe within
the context of the east-west confrontation, and the Middle East
with both the Arab-Israeli conflict and superpower involvement.
<BR>

<P>
Throughout the cold war, European threat perceptions were frozen
around the east-west divide. Because of the military standoff
along the inter-German border, the states of Europe faced an acute
security environment that periodically deteriorated to the point
of crisis depending on the vicissitudes of US-Soviet rivalry.
This daunting threat perception fixated the national security
policies of Europe eastward, thus subordinating the security concerns
of other areas contiguous to Europe, namely the Mediterranean.
With the possible exception of France, that insisted on maintaining
a high security profile in Africa and the Pacific, Europe looked
to `out-of-area' security issues only through the prism of the
cold war. <BR>

<P>
Similarly, the perennial Arab-Israeli conflict ensured that the
priorities of Middle East states remained fixated on regional
concerns especially in times of crisis, or in the course of the
various peace initiatives floated during the 1980s, and later
on the priorities of Gulf security. Any attempt to look towards
the Mediterranean would inevitably have become entangled in the
complexities of Arab-Israeli relations, superpower involvement
in the region, and more recently, issues relating to the military
balance in the Gulf. <BR>

<P>
In recent years, a fundamental transformation in the security
environment of both regions has generated a host of security concerns
that have impacted strongly on both shores of the Mediterranean.
As a result, growing recognition now exists that these problems,
or at least some of them, must be tackled within a regional Mediterranean
context, distinct from, but not independently of, Europe and the
Middle East. <BR>

<P>
The retreat of the Soviet threat from the east altered the political
consensus regarding the security architecture on the continent.
On the other hand, the perceived threats which surfaced in the
Mediterranean prompted the southern European states to consider
multilateral schemes capable of dealing with a complex array of
new security issues. The interlocking complexity of the military,
demographic, socio-economic, religious, and political problems
which were brought to the fore, and the intensification of global
economic integration, compelled analysts to look towards the construction
of a security architecture founded upon a multi-dimensional approach,
which recognises the intricate linkages between these issues,
as opposed to the strict preoccupation with military security
that had previously characterised the European security agenda.
<BR>

<P>
This trend towards a Mediterranean approach was complemented by
the profound developments in the Middle East, in parallel with
the end of the cold war. The peace process initiated at Madrid
in October 1991 by no means brought an end to the preoccupation
of the region with the Palestine problem. However, the region
was on a course of irreversible change prompting Middle Eastern
states to reassess their foreign policy orientation. The Mediterranean
began to take on greater salience in the priorities of the North
African states, and again there was a recognition of the interlocking
nature of the security issues which must be dealt with. <BR>

<P>
The basic premise of this paper is that the dissipation of a central
threat and the recognition of the multi-dimensional complexity
of the security issues facing the states of the Mediterranean
and the Middle East, provided the auspicious environment and impetus
for the commencement of the dialogue initiated at Barcelona, which
can serve as a framework within which a more effective Mediterranean
security relationship can develop. The nature of the issues which
this dialogue will address are by no means exclusive to the region.
The specific socio-cultural and geographic context, however, will
manifest itself on both shores of the Mediterranean, requiring
both a regional, and intraregional approach to the issues. The
specificity and complexity of the emerging security environment
in the Mediterranean, therefore, will give the region, if not
a distinct homogeneous security identity, a uniquely complex identity
where nonmilitary dimensions of security carry at least as much
weight as traditional military concerns. <BR>

<P>
<B>The Emergence of a Mediterranean Approach<BR>
</B>
<P>
Since the end of the second world war, and the emergence of the
bipolar international structure, security in the Mediterranean
region was always perceived as an extension of the east-west standoff
that divided the European continent. This region was seen as a
perimeter where NATO was to ward off Soviet encroachment to the
alliance's southern flank, or as a platform from which the United
States could project its power into the Middle East by way of
its naval presence in the form of the US Sixth Fleet. The Mediterranean
was thus a pawn on the global chess board where regional security
concerns were subordinated to the strategic policies of the superpowers
and their allies. <BR>

<P>
The subordination of regional security concerns was clearly reflected
in the benign neglect which characterised the European approach
to the Mediterranean within Europe's security institutions. The
CSCE, as well as its contemporary permutations, has always embodied
a Mediterranean component. However, this was addressed with diplomatic
formality where form prevailed over substance more than was the
case with any other subsystem. As this developed, specialised
meetings with non-European Mediterranean states were held. At
a later stage, Mediterranean states were given a status below
that of observer, participating instead in their capacity as &quot;Non-Participating
Mediterranean States&quot; (NPMS). These meetings took place in
Valletta (1978), Venice (1984), Palma de Majorca (1990) and in
Valletta again in 1993. Mediterranean issues, however, were never
elevated to anything above the peripheral status within the CSCE's
agenda. Notwithstanding the decisions reached at the Budapest
summit in late 1994 to establish a contact group at the level
of experts within the framework of the OSCE Permanent Council
in Vienna, the Mediterranean remained little more than a marginal
area of concern for all members except the southern European states.
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. Euro-Arab Relations<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Attempts at co-operation between Europe and the Arab world predate
even the early initiatives relating to Mediterranean security.
In 1965, Lebanon was the first state to conclude a three-year
trade agreement with the EC, followed by Egypt in 1972. In the
same year, the then nine member states of the EC responded to
a request made in 1971 by the European Parliament and started
to look into an overall Mediterranean policy that opened up prospects
for co-operation in several areas, an initiative that was referred
to as the &quot;Revised Mediterranean Policy&quot;. Consequently,
discussions with the three Maghreb countries (Algeria, Morocco,
Tunisia) began on that basis in 1973 leading to the conclusion
of agreements between the Community and each of the three states
in 1973. Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, and Jordan followed in 1976. The
co-operative agreements between the EC and the seven Arab Mediterranean
countries were almost identical in nature, focusing on trade preferences
and economic stabilisation, as well as financial and technical
co-operation embodied in a series of protocols of renewable five
year time periods.<BR>

<P>
These initiatives, however, were pursued and developed more within
a bilateral framework between the EC and each Arab Mediterranean
state. There was no serious effort to deal with the Mediterranean
countries together within a multilateral framework. Because of
the preoccupation of both the Arab and southern European states
with the Middle East and the east-west conflict respectively,
the notion of Mediterranean multilateralism never got off the
water. This was clearly reflected in the fate of the &quot;Euro-Arab
Dialogue&quot;. <BR>

<P>
Initiated in 1976, the dialogue was not meant to deal specifically
with Mediterranean issues but rather co-operation between European
and Arab states. However, if it had continued, it would inevitably
have come to embody a pronounced Mediterranean component given
the fact that the region constitutes the main area of geographical
contiguity between Europe and the Arab world. In addition to the
divergent security and political agendas of the parties involved,
the reasons behind the failure of the Euro-Arab dialogue were
also closely linked to the inter-regional divisions which emerged
in the Middle East following the signing of the Camp David Accords
and the outbreak of the Iran Iraq war, as well as differences
within the Atlantic Alliance over the approach which should be
adopted towards the region. The schism that emerged between Egypt
and the Arab states precluded a common Arab stand <I>vis-a-vis</I>
co-operation with Europe, and the lack of receptivity on the part
of the United States to an independent European security policy
in the Middle East diluted the enthusiasm with which the EC approached
the dialogue. The Euro-Arab dialogue thus remained frozen for
most of the 1980s, and after France attempted to revive the process
in December 1989, it was again stalled by the outbreak of the
Gulf crisis. <BR>

<P>
The main conclusion to be drawn from this phase is that the security
concerns of the Middle East and Europe - areas contiguous to but
not a part of the Mediterranean - impinged upon attempts to initiate
a security dialogue across the shores of the Mediterranean. In
essence, prospects for developing a distinct security identity
for the region remained captive to, even submerged by, strategic
developments emanating essentially from areas outside the Mediterranean
itself. <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. Europe's Security Evolution<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
By the end of the 1980s, however, several regional and global
developments combined to gradually loosen the bonds between the
Mediterranean and Europe's security architecture to which it had
previously been so tightly bound, and from the Middle East to
which it was linked through the nexus of the Arab-Israeli conflict
and Persian Gulf oil. Divorcing Mediterranean security from strategic
developments in Europe and the Middle East would be inconceivable.
However, a host of security issues began to emerge, the impact
of which was felt most strongly in the regional Mediterranean
context. <BR>

<P>
The disintegration of the Soviet empire in Eastern Europe finally
brought an end to the standoff that had divided the continent
along the cease-fire lines of World War II. The breakup of the
communist bloc focused European attention mostly on the power
vacuum that emerged in the east, and profoundly altered the security
equation on the European continent as a whole. Inevitably therefore,
the European approach to Mediterranean security issues found a
niche in their concerns. The overarching but coherent Soviet threat
to western Europe was replaced by a host of more limited but equally
demanding security issues affecting different members of the western
alliance asymmetrically. The perceived threat of refugees and
economic dislocation in the east affected Germany much more than
the rest of the continent; the threat of migration from the southern
shores of the Mediterranean affected France and Spain much more
than it did, say, Britain or Germany; and the instability in the
Balkans triggered by the breakup of the Yugoslav Federation threatened
to spark a regional crisis that could suck in such countries as
Italy, Greece and Turkey. <BR>

<P>
The collective security institutions which had previously guaranteed
security on the continent against the Soviet threat failed to
deal decisively with this diverse array of security threats. Although
NATO finally stepped in to enforce the tenuous peace put together
in the Balkans, this was essentially a manifestation of American
leadership. It also remains to be seen whether the commitment
of the alliance will stand if the conflict flares up once again.

<P>
Similarly, it is difficult to conceive of either NATO or the WEU
intervening to stem the tide of refugees that threaten the states
of southern Europe. Unsettling question marks still hang over
NATO's nuclear umbrella now that the fragmentation of the Soviet
Union's nuclear arsenal impacts differently upon each country's
deterrent posture. Finally, the uncertainty surrounding such questions
is reinforced as growing isolationist sentiment in the United
States casts serious doubts on the sustainability of the American
commitment to Europe's defense.
<P>
The combined result of these factors is what several security
analysts have described as the 'renationalisation' of Europe's
security policy, meaning that security threats now impact more
forcefully on alliance members individually rather than on the
alliance as a whole. How this will impact on the overall security
structure in Europe, and thus the Mediterranean, still remains
to be seen. It is unlikely that this trend will lead to the demise
of either the NATO alliance or the European pillar embodied in
the WEU. However, the changing nature of the emerging security
threats on the continent, and the reassessment of Europe's security
institutions, has created an extremely fluid environment that
has opened up a greater margin of maneuver for European states.
This can be discerned in several significant developments with
regards to the security policies of individual alliance members:
Germany's unilateral recognition of Croatia and Slovenia immediately
following the dissolution of the Yugoslav Federation; the independent
stand taken by Greece on the issue of Macedonia; the important
steps taken so far with regards to closer Franco-German security
co-operation; and the initiative taken by Italy and Spain, followed
by France, towards closer Mediterranean co-operation beginning
in 1990.<BR>

<P>
The Spanish-Italian initiative proposed the creation of a CSCE-type
framework for the Mediterranean - hence its formal title, `The
Conference on Co-operation and Security in the Mediterranean'
(CSCM). The Non-Aligned Mediterranean states had already expressed
their support for such a proposal in June 1990 thus paving the
way for Spain and Italy to present a joint non-paper on a CSCM
to the Palma de Majorca CSCE meeting on 24 September 1990. The
non-paper recognised the serious demographic and economic imbalances
existing in the area and their adverse social and cultural consequences.
The CSCM was conceptualised as constituting a joint instrument
the purpose of which was to ward off a potential collision between
the southern and northern shores of the Mediterranean in what
was becoming a new frontier of Europe. <BR>

<P>
The CSCM proposal, however, met with little support by the CSCE
participants, especially France, which criticised the initiative
on the basis of its inapplicability to such a vast and diverse
area as the Mediterranean. The French argument - later developed
into the 5+5 process - stressed that a CSCM like framework must
start with a `core' group of states comprised of the five Maghreb
states (Algeria, Morocco, Tunisia, Libya and Mauritania) and the
five European Mediterranean countries (Spain, France, Italy, Portugal
and Malta). A meeting at the level of Foreign Ministers was held
in Rome on December 10, 1990, in which Malta was granted the status
of an &quot;associate participant&quot; but was soon given the
status of full participant the following year during the second
Ministerial meeting held in Algiers in October 1991. <BR>

<P>
Thus, by the turn of the decade, the fundamental changes in Europe's
security environment combined to prompt the first stirrings of
a southern European approach towards the Mediterranean within
a multilateral framework. The fragmentation of the Soviet empire
brought with it a reassessment of threat perceptions of Europe's
major actors that consequently generated a state of flux with
regards to the overall security architecture on the continent.
This prompted the states of southern Europe to embark on a number
of initiatives that sought to focus attention on the Mediterranean
basin within some sort of grouping bringing together the states
of the region. 
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. The Middle East Security Evolution<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
A similar trend can be discerned with regards to developments
in the Middle East. The significant steps taken towards resolving
the Arab-Israeli conflict, and especially the Palestinian issue,
have led to a profound reassessment on the part of Middle Eastern
states with regards to their regional policies. This development
has diluted the exclusive preoccupation of Middle Eastern states
with the Arab-Israeli conflict, and the nuances of their position
towards Israel. As progress was witnessed in the peace talks,
Arab states began to look beyond the confines of the region for
outlets of manoeuver in order to augment their regional position.
<BR>

<P>
Egypt in particular looked to the Mediterranean area and Europe
in order to secure markets for its exports and ensure an alternative
supply of high technology. Egypt's motives in this regard were
also influenced by a profound recognition that a dangerous north-south
schism was developing across the Mediterranean basin due to the
economic and demographic imbalances between the North African
and southern European states. These imbalances have also taken
on religious overtones that are threatening to transform this
schism into a cultural antagonism dividing both shores of the
Mediterranean. Egypt's Mediterranean Forum proposal presented
in April 1991 at the European Parliament in Strasbourg was based
on the necessity of instituting some sort of political and cultural
dialogue to ameliorate what could potentially develop into a volatile
security situation. <BR>

<P>
In short, the regional transformations witnessed by both Europe
and the Middle East after the end of the cold war profoundly altered
the security situation of the Mediterranean countries and permitted
the development of a nascent security approach towards the area.
The problems that began to emerge in the Mediterranean area could
no longer be thought of as simply an appendage of the security
concerns of the NATO alliance. Similarly, the North African states
saw that these problems were not all predominantly linked to the
Arab-Israeli conflict. <BR>

<P>
Again it is important to emphasise that this does not imply that
Mediterranean issues can be decoupled from the wider security
zones of either Europe or the Middle East. Alliance concerns and
conflicts in Europe and the Middle East will continue to impinge
on Mediterranean security, and will inevitably influence the ultimate
security architecture which prevails in the area. However, the
diverse cultural and religious context in which the security issues
of the area are unfolding, makes it inconceivable to perceive
them as simply an extension of NATO's southern defense perimeter,
or in attempting to view them through the prism of the Arab-Israeli
conflict. <BR>

<P>
If not addressed appropriately, this new breed of security threats
faced by the Mediterranean will become daunting. The threat of
massive migration from the south to the north; the danger of economic
dislocation leading to social disruptions and consequently to
ethnic strife and religious xenophobia; the growing economic rift
between north and south as the process of European integration
deepens; and the threat of weapons proliferation along the southern
Mediterranean rim, have all become familiar themes in the security
literature dealing with the area, and there is consequently little
need to elaborate upon them here. <BR>

<P>
What is perhaps less well known, but no less important in explaining
the current changes in the region, is the impact of global economic
and technological forces in intensifying these dislocations. I
refer specifically to the advent of the information revolution,
the impact of which on the current global economic, cultural,
and social order will be nothing less than profound. The social
and political consequences of the current technological revolution
are daunting in their complexity and, consequently, are not yet
fully understood.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. The Social Consequences of the Technological
Revolution<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
In a strictly technical sense, the information revolution refers
to the merger between communications and computer technology thereby
greatly augmenting the ability to process, store, and disseminate
information. However, the significance of this revolution lies
not so much in the technology but in its remarkable ability to
compress time and space, thereby fundamentally altering the nature
of social activity once it is transferred to the information network.
When the forces of the market merge with the information revolution
through the ever expanding network, business organisations will
expand their reach to a degree unprecedented in magnitude or scope,
allowing business operations to be conducted on a global scale.
<BR>

<P>
This remarkable ability to transcend the traditional confines
of time and space is what gives information technology its incredible
power. This power, in turn, gives it the ability to erode the
barriers that obstruct the free flow of information, including
the nation state itself. <BR>

<P>
Wealth and competitive advantage in information economies lie
in sophisticated information handling rather than in the ownership
or management of capital. This has led to the rise of a nascent
class that US Secretary of Labor Robert Reich termed 'symbols
analysts' - a class of professionals who thrive on the network
by manipulating digital information. Because the network has no
physical location, and because the global reach of business reduces
the dependence of the economy on the nation state, this class
becomes disembodied of its national loyalties. The nation state
itself becomes less and less capable of regulating the economy,
and therefore sustaining the extensive welfare system that underpinned
the social order and guaranteed loyalty to the state. Since work
in the information economy depends on the requisite education
and training, an ever larger sector of the population becomes
economically marginalised. <BR>

<P>
The trend which emerges from this development is one of an ever
greater concentration of wealth in the hands of those who no longer
depend on the state to sustain their economic activity, leaving
behind an impoverished underclass which cannot hope to compete
in such a demanding environment. Caught in between is the middle
class of managers and high income workers. Those who manage to
acquire the requisite skills will be elevated to the ranks of
the symbols analysts that run the economy, those that do not will
join the ranks of the underemployed facing the persistent threat
of job insecurity. <BR>

<P>
The middle class has always constituted the bulwark of loyalty
for the nation state. As its position is undermined, however,
other loyalties begin to supersede the ideology of secular nationalism.
Primordial loyalties based on ethnicity, race or communal affiliation
take its place for that strata of society which has been marginalised
by the fast-paced economy, while a kind of cosmopolitan `supranationalism'
captivates those who live and work on the network. The nation
state thus becomes undermined by the dual pressures of the rise
of subnational loyalties from below, and the secession of the
economic elite from above. <BR>

<P>
This trend is reinforced by the social and cultural consequences
that accompany the spread of information technologies. One of
the hallmarks of the information revolution is its incredible
ability to propagate and disseminate images. This power is now
being harnessed by business organisations so that market advantage
is now dependent on packaging and repackaging products in images
and icons with a distinctly American quality. What is actually
marketed, therefore, is not the product itself, but images reflecting
the rise of `soft' industries based on entertainment, advertising,
media and information services that are woven together to create
a kind of global theme park reflecting cosmopolitan American life
style and values. This development, however, constitutes an incredibly
powerful cultural force that often assaults the indigenous value
systems that it hopes to integrate into the global market. <BR>

<P>
This, in turn, inevitably generates a cultural backlash that seeks
to emphasise religious and cultural identity as a form of psychological
reassurance against the cultural assault of - in this case - western
materialism. This backlash is by no means exclusive to Arab or
Third World cultures as is evidenced by the rise of conservative
sentiment that has shifted the political spectrum rightwards in
such countries as the United States, Germany, France and Great
Britain that has been accompanied with a strong nationalistic
and xenophobic flavor. What serves to exacerbate this trend towards
cultural and religious xenophobia is the transparency that comes
with the communications revolution. Because of its remarkable
ability to compress time and space, the information revolution
significantly contracts the socio-cultural space that previously
insulated separate social groups.<BR>

<P>
How these powerful trends will affect the political and security
situation in the Mediterranean cannot yet be discerned with any.
However, one can attempt to establish a tentative link between
these developments and the general socio-cultural trends witnessed
by communities on both shores of the Mediterranean. One only has
to look at the recent election results in such countries as Italy,
France, Greece, and Turkey to notice a gradual shift of the political
spectrum towards the right. Similarly, the creeping tide of cultural
and religious conservatism in North Africa threatens to open up
a north-south cultural rift across the Mediterranean. The economic
imbalances caused by the intensification of market forces inevitably
reinforce this trend. The disparities in wealth both within Mediterranean
countries, and between the European and North African flanks of
the region, are undermining the social pillars of support that
sustained the secular national order. What this inevitably generates
is a creeping cultural radicalism that leads to the rejection
of the `other' however defined. Not only does this xenophobic
trend serve to solidify the cultural divide emerging across the
Mediterranean, but also threatens to spill over onto both shores
with every incident of communal violence against foreigners or
immigrant workers. <BR>

<P>
Security, in this sense, therefore tends to take on an abstract
quality intertwined with the complexities of social and political
interaction in the information age. No longer can security be
gauged in strictly military terms. Security must be based on a
multidimensional approach in order to be able to cope with this
new breed of threats which are specific, although not exclusive
to, the Mediterranean area. It is this recognition on the part
of Mediterranean states in the particularity of the security threats
they face that is giving rise to the notion of a distinctly `Mediterranean'
security regime based on dialogue and a multidimensional security
approach, regardless of the fact that this regime is still in
its preliminary stages. <BR>

<P>
How these issues will be tackled, however, will depend on the
ultimate security framework that emerges for the area as a whole.
Recognition of the complex multi-faceted nature of the security
threats facing Mediterranean states, in and of itself, will not
be sufficient to ensure that they will be successfully addressed.
This will depend to a large extent on how the multiple security
interests in the region are reconciled making the process of institution
building in the Mediterranean a complex exercise in balancing
the competing frameworks put forward for the security of the region,
including the influence of extra-regional parties.<BR>

<P>
<B>Reconciling the Overlapping Interests in the Mediterranean
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. Managing the European-Mediterranean Linkage
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
As was mentioned in the introduction to this paper, the state
of flux that characterised Europe's security architecture after
the cold war opened the door for the recognition of Mediterranean
security concerns as one among several competing areas of priority
that must be addressed. What this signifies is not the detachment
of the area from Europe, but that the current security debate
on the continent now must encompass security concerns that directly
relate to the Mediterranean. <BR>

<P>
Europe's ultimate security structure will be decided according
to how it manages to reconcile the competing Atlantic, European,
and inter-European visions for European security. It would be
a misperception to think that this linkage with European security
will subjugate the Mediterranean to purely European and American
concerns. The nature of the security threats in the region, and
the recognition of the need for a multilateral approach to address
them, precludes this possibility. However, it would be impossible
to formulate a viable security framework for the area unless the
interests of the various actors in Europe, and even the United
States, are taken into account and loosely or informally integrated
into an institutional framework in which they can complement,
rather than compete with, each other.
<P>
Managing this linkage, however, will be a difficult task even
if we restrict ourselves to the traditional military dimension
of security. The latent tension between the national security
interests of NATO members and the collective security commitments
of the alliance has always been most pronounced in the Mediterranean.
This explains why NATO was never able to incorporate the area
within its integrated defence structure, and instead relied on
the US naval presence to ward off Soviet encroachment on the southern
defence perimeter of the alliance. The region thus remained as
a `gray zone' within the alliance's defence structure in which
the question of whether the US naval force served purely American
or alliance interests was never quite defined. <BR>

<P>
This ambiguity that has characterised the position of the Mediterranean
within alliance politics will have a profound impact on the ultimate
security approach adopted for the region. Also important will
be the issue of the competing `European' and `Atlantic' visions
for European security. The current emphasis on greater burden-sharing
within NATO by strengthening the alliance's European pillar is
only one facet of the issue. Equally important is whether the
WEU will be integrated into NATO's defence structure, or whether
it will constitute the military arm of a strengthened EU once
the differences on formulating agreement on a common foreign and
security policy are resolved. <BR>

<P>
If Europe fails to resolve the Atlantic-European tension in its
security policy, then the present arrangement within NATO guaranteeing
American preeminence within alliance affairs will likely prevail.
In that event, if European security policy towards the Mediterranean
continues to be formulated within the NATO framework, the resulting
approach is not likely to constitute a viable multilateral formula
for the area. 
<P>
Like other institutions of the cold war, NATO has always regarded
the region with little more than marginal concern, a fact evidenced
by the initiatives taken by the alliance towards the area following
the end of the cold war. As was the case with the CSCE, NATO undertook
several declaratory steps towards closer co-operation with Mediterranean
countries. In their declaration issued in Brussels on January
11, 1994, the Heads of State and Government of NATO reiterated
their &quot;conviction that security in Europe is greatly affected
by security in the Mediterranean&quot;. They strongly welcomed
the agreements concluded within the framework of the Middle East
peace process and regarded this &quot;much awaited&quot; breakthrough
as having a positive impact on the situation in the Mediterranean.
They subsequently directed the North Atlantic Co-operation Council
(NACC) to continue to review the overall situation in the region,
and encouraged all efforts conducive to strengthening regional
stability. <BR>

<P>
This was followed, in December 1994, by the initiative of the
NATO Foreign Ministers to open a dialogue between the alliance
and the non-NATO Mediterranean states. Within this framework,
NATO invited Egypt, Israel, Morocco, Tunisia, and Mauritania to
study their views concerning stability in the Mediterranean and
prospects for possible co-operation with the alliance. NATO's
initiatives, however, did not seek to establish any institutional
linkages between the alliance and these states, nor did they envisage
what type of linkage would exist between the Mediterranean and
Europe as a whole. <BR>

<P>
More serious perhaps than the absence of any institutional framework
for the NATO initiatives are the possibly adverse consequences
resulting from the maintenance of the US naval deployment in the
Mediterranean without a multilateral framework governing its presence.
As Roberto Aliboni has perceptively pointed out, &quot;the national
dimension of the US naval presence in the Mediterranean could
prevail over its multilateral dimension.&quot; European naval
deployment in the area could also have a similar effect. The fact
that a predominantly American - European military presence in
the area operates without a multilateral cover could heighten
concerns on the part of some southern Mediterranean states regarding
US and European intentions. Security issues in the region, therefore,
would be regarded in terms of deterrable events that can be addressed
through military force without recognition of their cultural and
socio-economic root causes. The current north-south divide would
thus become militarised, cementing the division of the region
into two antagonistic blocs that would accentuate the trend towards
cultural xenophobia that is emerging on both sides of the Mediterranean.
<BR>

<P>
If, however, the European pillar of the alliance is strengthened
and integrated into NATO's defence structure, one can expect a
more pronounced European role in Mediterranean security. This
would also be the case if the WEU were to emerge as the military
arm of an EU that would gradually assume more responsibility for
the continent's defence, although this scenario remains problematic
given the difficulties that plague such matters as formulating
a collective nuclear umbrella and an integrated command structure.
In both cases, however, the strength of Europe's commitment to
a Mediterranean outlook would depend on how the foreign policy
priorities of the major European states are reconciled; in particular
between Germany's eastward focus on the countries of the former
Soviet bloc, and France's southern foreign policy orientation.
<BR>

<P>
However these competing priorities are reconciled, this would
still leave the issue of the American role and military presence
in the region undefined. A more prominent European security profile
does not automatically mean an end to the US military presence
in the area, nor even its reduction. What it will imply, however,
is the dominance of US national security concerns over whatever
collective commitments it may have considered within the NATO
alliance. Any Mediterranean multilateral framework, therefore,
must somehow accommodate American interests in order to ward off
what could develop into a serious competition for influence that
could have destabilising consequences in the form of a regional
arms race.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. The Madrid Process and Mediterranean Security
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The process begu at Madrid has set in motion a loose but comprehensive
framework for Middle East dialogue and co-operation that has the
potential to extend to the Mediterranean. As was demonstrated
during the 1980s, developments in the Middle East region cast
a powerful shadow on wider Mediterranean concerns which become
entangled in such issues as relations with Israel, the regional
arms race, and the latent competition between the United States
and Europe for influence in the region. 
<P>
The Madrid process seeks to disentangle such issues in order to
enhance co-operation between the states of the region. This does
not mean that the multilateral tracks can proceed in isolation
of progress on the bilateral negotiations. The 'Multilateral track'
has been divided into five working groups that are separate but
with an implicit linkage between them as well as between this
track and the bilateral - conflict resolution - tracks of the
peace process.<BR>

<P>
Provided that this issue of linkage is handled carefully, together
with other sensitive issues such as the current military imbalance
between Israel and the Arab states, and Israel's nuclear posture,
the multilateral track can constitute a framework around which
co-operation can emerge and spin off with a positive southern
Mediterranean contribution to the Mediterranean security debate.
<BR>

<P>
This is particularly true for the ACRS track. The Arms Control
and Regional Working Group (ACRS) has, in many ways, informally
emulated the cooperative security model applied in Europe in developing
its work. During the first phase of ACRS, regional parties were
introduced to the modalities and procedures that guided the CSCE
and the US-Soviet arms control experience. In the third ACRS plenary
meeting held in Washington in May 1993, it was agreed that the
parties would consider a number of CSCE-like CBMs. Such CBMs included
the exchange of military information, risk reduction measures,
and agreements on measures to prevent incidents at sea (INCSEA)
and to cooperate in search and rescue maritime missions (SAR).
<BR>

<P>
It was also agreed in Washington that parties would hold intersessional
activities, each entrusted with a specific assignment. Mentor
states were nominated from outside the Middle East to assist regional
states in four main domains; <BR>

<P>
- The United States and the Russian Federation were to guide efforts
to define the ultimate objectives of ACRS and to help parties
on a set of declaratory CBMs and the principles of the security
process;<BR>

<P>
- Canada was to assist efforts on maritime CBMs and means of preventing
incidents at sea;<BR>

<P>
- Turkey was to assist efforts to explore alternative means of
exchanging military information and prenotification of military
exercises and large-scale movements;<BR>

<P>
- The Netherlands was to assist in efforts to establish a regional
crisis communications network in the Middle East. Again following
the European experience, agreement was reached in Moscow to divide
the future intersessional activities of ACRS into two main baskets.
The Conceptual Basket was to include all conceptual aspects of
the process while the Operational Basket mainly dealt with practical
mechanisms to increase military transparency and reduce dangers
of unintended military escalation. Particularly noteworthy in
this regard is that the conceptual basket - albeit without success
so far - has attempted to develop a Regional Security and Arms
Control Declaration for the Middle East, encompassing principles,
parameters and objectives. 
<P>
ACRS has continued for over three years to deal with an extensive
agenda aiming at the creation of a new Middle East security environment.
However, after the April 1995 Review/ Extension Conference of
the NPT, with Arab-Israeli differences resulting from Israel's
refusal to accede to the treaty or to negotiate a Nuclear Weapons
Free Zone in the Middle East, ACRS activities have subsided. The
ACRS process thus became hostage to Israel agreeing to deal constructively
and structurally with the nuclear issue. The failure of the ACRS
members to adopt the Declaration on Regional Security and Arms
Control came as a direct result of Israel's failing to agree to
commit to adhere to the Non-Proliferation Treaty even in the future.
<BR>

<P>
This was clearly evidenced after the sixth ACRS plenary held in
Tunis, which made several recommendations including the possible
working out of a mandate for a Regional Security Center (RSC)
in the Middle East. In Jordan, Tunis and Qatar pursuant to that
meeting no agreement was reached concerning the RSC document due
to Egypt's insistence on the creation of some type of linkage
between the functions of the RSC and the establishment of a NWFZ
in the region, rather than being limited in its activity to the
classical conflict prevention domain.<BR>

<P>
Two things are important to note in the work of the ACRS working
group. First, the activities of the working group are only one
dimension of a matrix of five covered by the multilateral working
groups on Water, Environment, Refugees, Economic Co-operation
and Arms Control, which together exemplify the multidimensional
approach that could form the basis for wider security co-operation
encompassing the Mediterranean area. This, however, will depend
on the delicate link which exists between the process of institutionalising
CBMs in the Middle East and the issue of Israel's nuclear position.
The question of Israel's nuclear posture, and the issue of the
linkage between the multilateral and bilateral tracks, point to
the second, and perhaps more important aspect. The involvement
of several European actors in the activities of ACRS means that
the sensitivity of the issues discussed will clearly have an impact
on any Mediterranean multilateral framework combining Europe and
the non-European Mediterranean states, a fact which was clearly
emphasised at Barcelona.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. Barcelona and the Prospects for a Multilateral
Framework<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The historic meeting which took place in Barcelona in November
of last year reflected the change in perceptions regarding the
security of the Mediterranean region. The issue of whether regional
security would be addressed within a strictly Mediterranean context
envisioned in the '5+5' initiative, the CSCM, or the Mediterranean
Forum, a wider framework encompassing European security concerns,
was finally resolved in the form of a Euro-Mediterranean conference.
Whether such a framework will survive to constitute a viable security
regime for the area is not yet clear, and will ultimately depend
on both the final security architecture which emerges in Europe,
and the course of the Madrid peace process in the Middle East.
The Declaration adopted at Barcelona exemplified the multidimensional
approach to security that recognises the deep-rooted linkages
between security and economic and social development, as was evidenced
in the references throughout the text to the common' challenges
necessitating a common security approach. Also apparent was the
recognition of the non-military dimension of security in the form
of demographic dislocation causing current migration flows. Although
not mentioned within the security chapter, there was implicit
recognition that such an issue has obvious security implications.
<BR>

<P>
This does not mean, however, that differences do not exist. In
particular potential differences may emerge in the various conceptions
regarding such basic principles as democracy and human rights.
The only way that such differences will be resolved is through
a cultural dialogue to reconcile the contending interpretations
surrounding these concepts. Another divisive issue could emerge
with regards to the treatment of migrant workers, and especially
the policy of the European states which admit the possibility
of the return of illegal migrant workers to their countries of
origin. What needs to be recognised is that whatever policy is
adopted in this regard will carry with it profound social consequences
that will inevitably have ramifications on other areas of European-Mediterranean
co-operation. In addition to this heightened cultural dimension
of Euro-Mediterranean relations, there will also be the problem
of politicising such thorny issues such as `self-determination'.
This will inevitably cause differences when applied to issues
such as the Cypriot question, the Balkans, and above all the Middle
East with regards to Palestine. <BR>

<P>
This last point avidly portrays the overlap between the Middle
East and the Mediterranean, an overlap that and which was most
apparent in the security chapter of the Barcelona Declaration
which highlighted a host of security issues that have a special
relevance to the Middle East. These included such issues as arms
control and the regional arms race, especially the reference to
the creation of a `Middle East' zone free of weapons of mass destruction
and their delivery systems, and the reference to the possibility
of `regional and sub-regional security co-operation'. What clearly
demonstrated the overlap between the two regions, however, was
the exchange at the Barcelona conference between the Syrian and
Israeli Foreign Ministers that dominated a substantial portion
of the meeting. That a Middle Eastern issue could impinge so forcefully
on a forum designed to discuss Mediterranean co-operation is testimony
to the strength of the linkage between both regions. <BR>

<P>
It is therefore these linkages that will decide how the multidimensional
security approach on which a tentative consensus was reached at
Barcelona will be addressed. What Barcelona managed to achieve
was the formulation of a broad proposal for co-operation grounded
in a firm recognition of the non-military aspects of security.
What was thus envisaged was a functional approach encompassing
such areas as investment, the environment, tourism, information
technology and telecommunications, fisheries, and transport to
name only a few. This broad framework is supposed to take concrete
form in the follow up meetings. <BR>

<P>
However, this will depend on whether the Euro-Mediterranean framework
envisaged in Barcelona can be transformed into a viable security
regime for the region. As was already mentioned, the fate of this
broad cooperative framework will be intimately linked to the course
of the Euro-Mediterranean process as a whole. If the Barcelona
framework manages to reconcile the contending visions within the
EU for European security, and is complemented by a stable peace
process in the Middle East, then the prospects for the development
of a cooperative security regime are positive. If, however, the
Barcelona process fails to develop into a viable framework capable
of filling the institutional vacuum in the Mediterranean, then
the cooperative schemes envisaged for the region will suffer the
fate of the previous Mediterranean initiatives that failed to
reconcile the competing interests of the multiplicity of actors
involved.<BR>

<P>
<B>Conclusion: Towards a Flexible Institutional Framework<BR>
</B>
<P>
By a historical coincidence that is rare in modern history, the
countries of Europe and the Middle East have found themselves
looking towards each other across the Mediterranean, both cognisant
of the pressing need to institute some sort of cultural and security
dialogue in order to prevent the emergence of a cultural rift
between them. 
<P>
The true significance of the end of the bipolar international
order lies in the fact that the intersecting geopolitical and
cultural zones that were hitherto sucked into the vortex of superpower
rivalry are now open to the emergence of new power centers and
cooperative interaction. This phenomenon of greater regionalisation
of international relations is clearly exhibited in such areas
as eastern Europe that is now open to the spread of German influence,
Southeast Asia that is gradually emerging as an economic zone
tied to the powerful Japanese economy, a North American zone under
the hegemony of the United States, and the Mediterranean area
between Europe and the Middle East. <BR>

<P>
The rise of regionalism is being fuelled by the confluence of
several factors, only one of which is the waning of superpower
dominance. More important perhaps is the emergence of a new breed
of security threat that defies the traditional approach to security
as defined in military terms. The illusory semblance of stability
maintained by both superpowers in their respective spheres of
influence ensured that latent geopolitical and socio-cultural
tensions remained hidden from the view of policy makers, waiting
to resurface once the power structures constructed by Washington
and Moscow began to erode. The predominant characteristic of this
new type of threat is the intricate complexity of the issues it
poses, a complexity which will increase as the awesome power of
the technological revolution breaks down the traditional barriers
that had limited the scope of communal, social and political interaction.
<BR>

<P>
Complex security threats cannot be segmented into separate military
and non-military solutions. Rather, they must be faced by a sophisticated
approach that recognises this deep-seated complexity. The states
bordering on the Mediterranean have clearly recognised the need
of adopting such an approach within a multilateral regional framework.
Both sides have had prior experience in this regard: Europe within
the context of the OSCE, and the Middle East with the fragile
experiment at multilateral co-operation now being undertaken.

<P>
Consequently, both sides accept the reality that the security
challenges they now face are making themselves felt most strongly
in the regional Mediterranean context, and therefore require an
approach tailored to the specific cultural and political context
of the region. One can therefore expect that the strategic and
cultural changes that have lead to the renewal of interest in
the Mediterranean, will prompt a more intensified form of cultural
dialogue between both sides. This does not mean that military
security will be unimportant. However, military manifestations
of conflict are symptoms of much deeper causes not all of which
are under the purview of governments. <BR>

<P>
Cultural dialogue must therefore be complemented by a multilateral
security framework, within which it must be conducted. Such a
framework is essential if the various strategic interests of the
regional and extra-regional actors are to be reconciled. This
does not necessitate the creation of an all-inclusive forum in
which the security structure of the region is defined in detail.
This type of framework would be too rigid and cumbersome to deal
with the fluid security situation that is emerging in the Mediterranean.
<BR>

<P>
What can be considered instead, at least for the meantime, is
a complementary arrangement that may even include several frameworks
operating in tandem. In this sense, the various fora put forward
for the region do not have to be seen as mutually exclusive. Depending
on the nature of the issue being discussed, different frameworks
can operate, thus including different combinations of actors according
to the situation. For example, issues such as migration and the
environment can be handled within the context of The Mediterranean
Forum; cultural exchange and religious dialogue can be included
within the Euro-Mediterranean framework initiated at Barcelona;
and wider security concerns can be somehow linked to either NATO
or the Trans-Atlantic Charter so as to bring in the United States.
<BR>

<P>
Until such a flexible framework is developed, the efforts of the
Mediterranean states should focus on two possible areas of action.
The first is the need to continue to work on developing a consensus
on the issues put forward at Barcelona. Consensus on such sensitive
issues as human rights, democracy, self-determination, religious
tolerance, together with the initiation of economic and financial
co-operation between the Mediterranean states, can constitute
a first step towards generating agreement on a wider multilateral
framework. What is essential to keep in mind is the necessity
of developing some sort of political framework that will fill
the institutional void in the Mediterranean. This point is crucial.
If no such framework is developed, informal approaches can quickly
become politicised and exacerbate contentious issues rather than
fostering co-operation. <BR>

<P>
This leads to the second area of priority. Consensus building
on the ultimate security framework for the region will be a difficult
and time consuming process. In the meantime, incremental steps
must be taken to avoid potentially contentious areas such as migration,
arms proliferation - especially the issue of nuclear possession
- and terrorism, from hindering the process of consensus building.
Measures on a case-by-case basis that would attempt to prevent
the escalation of differences into conflicts cannot stand by themselves
and could end up legitimising the unacceptable status quo for
a temporary period. On the other hand, measures meant to prevent
the exacerbation of thorny issues by taking concrete if modest
steps towards an ultimate objective should be pursued and could
be useful. As was graphically demonstrated by the recent events
in the Middle East, minor events can spiral out of control and
seriously undermine the painstakingly constructed peace process
despite the political commitment of all the parties involved to
its continuation.<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
