<HEAD>

<TITLE>International and internal security in the European, the Transatlantic and the Mediterranean Region
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>INTERNATIONAL AND INTERNAL SECURITY IN THE EUROPEAN, THE TRANSATLANTIC
AND THE MEDITERRANEAN REGION<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Fulvio ATTINA</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>, Director,
Department of Political Studies, University of Catania</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
There was a time the Europeans considered their security and also
their identity as being dependent on the formation of their own
foreign and security policy independently of the United States.
At present times, this is no longer true. Current relations between
the governments of the European Union and the United States are
hardly the same as they were a decade ago. It is not easy to define
such relations, but it is clear that today European identity and
security are not linked to dissociating European foreign and security
policies from the foreign and security policy of the United States.
The renewed European endorsement of the United States as the provider
of last resort of international security in the Bosnian war is
proof of such a change. In the Balkans, Wahington has again been
put in the role of security provider of last resort of the international
system, with the consent and support of European governments.

<P>
In line with such a re-orientation of European attitudes, hurrying
to formulate a foreign and security common policy (FSCP) and its
institutionalisation is turning out to be of little importance
to the Europeans. 
<P>
At the same time, it is widely admitted that more co-operation
and even a new common policy is needed in another security area:
the internal one. Such a new security co-operation has a strong
international dimension and no state can present itself as the
provider of last resort in such a field. The international dimension
of internal security is not a worry only for the Europeans, but
for all the states of the world. It is also a problem to be solved
by international co-operation. Two solemn documents recently signed
by European Union and its special partners (the traditional major
ally, the United States, and the Mediterranean neighbours) make
important declarations about this problem. The documents are the
New Transatlantic Agenda, signed in Madrid on December 1996, and
the Barcelona Declaration on the Euro-Mediterranean Partnership,
signed in the Catalan town just a few weeks before the other document.
<BR>

<P>
&quot;New dimensions of security&quot; is a frequently used term
in the current vocabulary of international relations. In past
years, researchers and professionals have repeatedly called attention
to the multiple dimension of security in today's world. Concepts
like societal security, cultural security and environmental security
are increasingly used. This paper focuses on one of the &quot;new
dimensions&quot; and the reason why internal security has approached
foreign security as an important object of intergovernmental co-operation
and as an issue of the global system.<BR>

<P>
Firstly, the paper deals with the addition of internal security
to external security in the agenda of the European Union. It deals
with the development of co-operation in justice and home affairs
(JHA) and wih the difficult (or failed) development of FSCP. 
<P>
The second subject of the paper is the nature of EU-US relations
and the presence of co-operation on international security in
the New Transatlantic Agenda. Thirdly, the paper examines the
Barcelona Declaration and the presence of co-operation on internal
security in this document. The argument of the paper is that a
single group of causes is at the origin of the presence of this
security dimension in all the most important documents of contemporary
diplomacy.<BR>

<H1>From EPC to FSCP: re-conceptualising foreign policy and security
from the European experience<BR>
</H1>

<P>
In the first fifteen years of its existence, co-operation in foreign
policy achieved better results in the organisational, institutional
and political domain than it from Maastricht up to the present.
Institutional and political results obtained in the initial period,
from the 1969 Summit in The Hague to the signature of the Single
European Act in 1985, have all not been exciting, but some of
them have been important.<BR>

<P>
If to carry out the communitarisation of foreign policy means
to progressing from 0 to 100, in the earliest fifteen years communitarisation
progressed from 0 to 10; in the following period -though moving
forward- it covered less distance. In the first period of co-operation,
committees and working groups were brought into existence; important
declarations, such as the famous Declaration on European Identity,
were issued; co-operation was set out on at the United Nations.
Finally, in 1986 the Secretariat for Political Co-operation was
created, but in 1992 the Maastricht Treaty canceled it out (See:
Allen, Rummel and Wessels, 1982; Longo, 1995; Schouteete, 1980).
<BR>

<P>
Dates are important. At the time of the signing of the Single
European Act, in 1985, the short Gorbachev era was just starting
and the Soviet Union was in trouble, though Europeans did not
realise they had left behind the so-called Second cold war (See:
Kaldor, 1990). By the time of Maastricht, in 1992, the Gorbachev
era was over, as was the Soviet Union.<BR>

<P>
What of importance for Europe and the common foreign policy took
place in the world at that time? The answer is that the world
went through two changes and, because of these, Community co-operation
in foreign policy lost its former nature and principal raison
d'etre, at least till now. However, not only EU common foreign
policy but all national foreign policies are currently in a condition
of crisis,. The term 'foreign policy' may even sound obsolete
today. To say the least, foreign policy is something very different
today from what it was yesterday.<BR>

<P>
As we have said, the world changed twice in the last few years.
The first change was that the Soviet Union disappeared and, with
it, like cold war, bipolar international politics, and so on (See,
for instance: Haftendorn and Tuschoff, 1993; Lellouche, 1992).
In addition a given Atlantic politics and typical American foreign
policy disappeared, i.e. Atlantic politics as the politics of
opposition of the Western capitalist world to the Communist bloc.
The American foreign policy of forwarding American hegemony in
the international system in rivalry to the Soviet government also
broke up.<BR>

<P>
What is there instead of Atlantic politics? The answer is &quot;trans-Atlantic
politics&quot;, in process of definition since the first Transatlantic
Declaration signed in November 1990. What is there instead of
the old American foreign policy of &quot;hegemony with rivalry&quot;
with the Soviet Union? The answear is &quot;the new American policy
of hegemony with shared responsabilities&quot; with Japan and
the European allies, which also is in process of definition.<BR>

<P>
Does this change mean something to the foreign policy of the European
Union? Obviously, yes. It means a lot. However, it is better to
clearing from the outset an ambiguity. Western European integration
has been put in relation with the Est-West divide of the international
system. Integration used to be considered chiefly as something
formented on the two sides of the Atlantic to reinvigorate Europe
and rescue it from falling into communism and under the control
of the Soviet Union. Such an interpretation is to be rejected
as a reductive theory of the causes and evolution of the European
integration process. It is not in this sense that the demise of
the Soviet Union has changed the process of foreign policy communitarisation.
<P>
The point is that the anti-American motive to common foreign policy
has been much stronger than the anti-Soviet one. The anti-Americanism
of the European integration process has been commonly interpreted
as being of an economic nature. This is a partial vision of reality.
Customs union, economic and, nowadays, monetary integration is
and always has been strongly motivated in Europe by the need to
counter American strength in the world economy. Integration is
for the Europeans the condition for prevailing in industrial and
monetary competition with the Americans and, obviously, also with
the Japanese (See: Bourrinet, 1987; Khaler, 1995; Schwok, 1991).
Since the <I>defi americain</I> of the early 1960s, nobody has
disputed this. But such an argument fits also in with co-operation
in the field of foreign and security policy. Indeed, in the 1970s
and early 1980s, European co-operation in foreign policy got a
decisive push from the anti-American claims of many social, political
and even governmental actors in Europe. It is enough to recall
the Declaration on European Identity, issued in 1973 by EC foreign
affairs ministries, and the Kissinger's anger at it. This early
- some would say premature - result of the anti-American looming
of EPC is a good proof of the fact that EPC was fuelled mostly
by the aspiration of European governments to dissociate themselvesfrom
important aspects of the American foreign policy of the time.
As examples of this &quot;aspiration to dissociate&quot; the following
cases may be recorded:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the war in Vietnam ( then reculing its end)
by opposing it with such declarations as the Declaration on European
identity; 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the Middle-East and oil policies followed
by the American government in the late 1960s and early 1970s,
by presenting the Euro-Arab dialogue as an alternative to the
Washington diplomacy of confrontation with the oil producing and
exporting countries; 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the European security policy as outlined
by the Pentagon by opposing it with Ostpolitik and the Helsinki
process; 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the invasion of Grenada, the embargo on
Nicaragua, and the Latin-American policy of the Reagan Administration
by opposing it with initiatives like the San Jos&egrave; conference
explicitly aimed at creating ties between Europe and the Central
American countries, in spite of the fact that such ties had never
existed before; 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the boycott of the Siberian pipeline and
the Moscow Olympic Games proclaimed by Washington; (by mere disobedience);

</UL>

<UL>
<LI>dissociation from the hard anti-Soviet stance wanted by the
United States in the CSCE follow-up conferences by showing fair
co-ordination among diplomats of the EC countries in all the meetings
of the Helsinki process. 
</UL>

<P>
It may be ojected that the list of anti-American declarations
and actions of EC countries may be countered by a similar list
of anti-Soviet positions. But this objection is not decisive.
The fact is that, when the EPC venture started, the European governments
already had appropriate diplomatic and strategic institutions
- namely, the Atlantic Pact and NATO - to neutralise the Soviet
threat. They did not enter into the EPC process either to substitute
those institutions as inefficient instruments of defence against
the Soviet enemy or to supplement them with other instruments.
At that time, the anti-Soviet stance of the European governments
was almost the same as the anti-Soviet stance of the American
government. In other words, the &quot;value added&quot; by the
EPC to the foreign policies of the European countries was not
anti-Sovietism; rather, it was dissociation from important aspects
of American foreign policy.
<P>
Briefly, in the 1970s and 1980s, European governments considered
it advantageous to themselves to loosen and reduce ties with their
American ally, which had turned uneasy. In the 1990s, instead,
that ally is turning to be an easy ally again (See: Peterson and
Ward, 1995). At the same time, co-operation in foreign and security
policy is becoming more difficult. Such co-operation, always inherently
difficult, appears today to be more difficult than ever because
it is largely purposeless - at least in the international security
area - until a re-conceptualisation of its nature is appropriately
made.<BR>

<P>
In 1991 foreign policy co-operation lost its raison d'&egrave;tre
because the end of the Soviet Union removed almost all the reasons
for dissociating European diplomacy from important aspects of
American diplomacy and strategy. Even during the Gorbachev era
- when the EU states invented the common defence policy with the
Single European Act, and later, when they invented the common
security policy with the Treaty of European Union - effective
progress toward the reorganisation of the Western European Union
(WEU) had been small.<BR>

<P>
The dissolution of the Warsaw Pact caused anxiety and fear amongthe
Europeans and rushed them to find to remedies and make plans for
what they had never been able to accomplish, i.e. the creation
of common defence structures. It forced them to consider it feasible
to take upon themselves the burden of greater military expenses,
with the blessing sight of the Washington government. However,
because the American economy was overheated at that time, to slim
NATO down by reducing the number and size of the American military
bases in Europe was a decision also in the interest of United
States (See: Attin&agrave;, 1993 b; Hyde-Price, 1991; Mcardle
Kelleher, 1993; Smith, 1993). After a short time, however, the
problem of security in Central and Eastern Europe was revealed
to be not so big as to push for the immediate creation of new
structures for common defence. After all, Central and East European
states as well as the post-Soviet states (C.I.S.) had enough domestic
problems to deal with, and no time to ignite international violence.
This could be expected unless the domestic problems of those nations
turned into violence, and domestic violence turned into international
war (See: Barb&egrave;, 1995; Braillard, 1995). The Balkans fitted
this condition, but before turning to this case we have to come
back to the second great change undergone by the world. <BR>

<P>
If the fall of the Soviet Union and its consequence for the political
organisation of the international system - i.e., the end of the
rivalry between the hegemon of the system (the United States)
and its poorer (therefore, improbable) challenger (the Soviet
Union) - may be considered a sudden change, the second one is
not a sudden change but has been creeping up on us gradually,
even if it has only been defined recently.<BR>

<P>
In a few words, the world of today is the world of globalisation
and not only of interdependence. It is the world of easy and intense
mobility and communication; the world of imperious demands for
individual and collective human rights; the world of the third
and the widest wave of democratisation; the world of fast imitation
and, at least to a certain extent, unavoidable homogenisation
of societies and cultures (See, for instance, Kennedy, 1993).
It is also the opposite of all these aspects: it is the world
of fragmentation, discontinuouity and individuation; and the world
of strenuous and even violent reaction of individuals (single
persons, groups and cultures) against the risk of being overwhelmed
by the rest of the world in a situation in which individuals realise
they cannot &quot;shut the door&quot; separating them from the
aliens (See, for instance: Friedman, 1994; Mlinar, 1992; Robertson,
1992).
<P>
In such a world, the state has lost the ability to control its
borders. It is wonder that it lacks the same ability to make foreign
and security policy as it had before such a change took effect
(See, for example: Attin&agrave;, 1993 a; Camilleri and Falk,
1992; McGrew and Lewis, 1992). In spite of this change, the state
is safe in the present international system as it has never been
before.
<P>
Everything will blow up in the air if someone decides to use nuclear
weapons, but - apart from this circumstance - no state has a reasonable
chance of being destroyed by arms used by other states. From 1945
up to the present, no state has been destroyed by military invasion.
When a state risked destruction by military invasion, someone
intervened to rescue it. Some states have died in violence in
the contemporary international system, but this was by &quot;suicide&quot;,
that is by disintegrating themselves. There are - in my knowledge
- only four divergent cases, which may be easily explained. Two
cases - South Vietnam and East Germany - were the halves of divided
states and wanted to be somehow integrated to the other half (the
same is expected to occur to the two Koreas). The two remaining
cases - East Timor and Western Sahara - were in a nascent state
and were killed almost on the verge of becoming states. Incidentally,
it may be noted also that violent disintegration is not the only
form of state disappearance. Disintegration may be &quot;smooth&quot;
- as in the case of the Soviet Union - and peaceful - as in the
Czechslovak case. State disappearance may also occur by voluntary
bilateral or multilateral integration, but no real case is known
in the contemporary international system, apart from the building
of the European Union.<BR>

<P>
The present condition of international security of states may
be explained only by making reference to a fundamental value change
in the international system. The value change is that international
security (i.e. security of states as territorial entities) is
today a collective good, not simply an individual one. This is
new and peculiar to the contemporary international system. It
was not so in past international systems. In the past the persistence
of the international system, as opposed to the persistence of
any single state was a collective good; the plurality of states
was to be assured and the formation of world empires avoided,
but the existence of single states - especially small or middle
powers - was not to be necessarily preserved. The division and
the annexation of the whole territory of a state by other states
was not excluded as contrary to the basic principles of the international
system of the time as it is excluded in the contemporary international
system.<BR>

<P>
An individual good is something that individuals secure for themselves
mainly by their own means. A collective good, instead, is something
individuals benefit from mainly because an authority makes it
available to all; individuals have only to comply with a few obligations
to avoid &quot;wasting&quot; the good. In national political systems,
the authority that supplies public goods is an institution (the
executive or a state agency). In the international political system,
instead, the authority is the hegemonic (or global) power and/or
an institution. Authors of the hegemonic theory of international
politics like Gilpin (1981), Modelski (1978) and - espcially on
collective goods - Kindleberger (1970 and 1988), have focused
on certain public goods provided by the leading power to the system
such as currency for international exchange and freedom of circulation
for international trade. In the contemporary international system,
there are at least two important changes regarding collective
goods: one is the inclusion of territorial security among the
collective goods of the system; the other one is the legitimation
role of the United Nations in the field of international security,
i.e. the U.N. role of legitimating the actions of the hegemonic
state (the United States), no matter what the content of the U.N.
Charter and what may be best for the world.<BR>

<P>
In the past, state security was acquired through national military
power and/or military alliances with the strongest state(s). In
the contemporary international system, national security is mainly
and in the last resort defended by the &quot;governmental institutions&quot;
of the system, i.e. by the United States and the United Nations.
For that reason, in current international politics making military
alliances is becoming an obsolate instrument of foreign policy.
Indeed, the number of military alliances created in the last ten
years is near to zero. The last big wave of military alliance
creation took place at the time of the so-called Second cold war
with the military pacts signed by Brezhnev's Soviet Union and
certain so-called communist states in Africa and the Arab Peninsula.
The only important exception to this decaying importance of military
alliances is Nato. It is not difficult to explain why this is
so. In the contemporary international system, only four cases
can be counted as cases of real threat to the existence of a &quot;formed&quot;
(as opposed to &quot;nascent&quot;) state by invading its territory:
they are the invasion of South Korea by North Korea, the invasion
of South Vietnam by North Vietnam, the invasion of Kuwait by Iraq,
and the invasion of Bosnia by Croatia in 1995. Other cases of
military occupation - for example, in the Middle East - can be
counted; but in those cases territorial offence was neither deliberately
intended to produce the death of the offended state nor produced
such a result unintentionally. The rescue of three attacked and
threatened states (South Korea, Kuwait and Bosnia) was carried
out by the United States under the legitimating flag of the United
Nations. In the fourth case (South Vietnam), the United States
failed as much in military intervention as in obtaining United
Nations legitimation certainly because Soviet Union had understood
the error of its conduct in the Korean affair.<BR>

<P>
It is now clear why NATO is alive and in good health. Indeed,
it grows toward the East with the Partnership for Peace and even
considers it possible to extend to the South (see the proposal
made to certain Maghreb countries in 1995). The fact is that NATO
is not a traditional military alliance. It has gradually assumed
the nature of the major military instrument of Pax Americana in
the enlarged European region. However, it is not an all-purpose
military instrument in the hand of the United States. European
allies may at any time &quot;dissociate&quot;themselves, and also
resort to the reinvigoration of the Western European Union.<BR>

<P>
The principle of territorial integrity (that is: no state be invaded
and &quot;killed&quot; by another state) goes together with the
principle of non-intervention. Taken together, such principles
imply that a state may disintegrate into many fragments without
actions by other states. The two principles are so strong today
as to be valid also for each of the fragments fallen out of a
disintegrated state, whatever the &quot;living conditions&quot;
of the fragments. 
<P>
One example is near to us. No state has been ready to intervene
to stop mass killings in Bosnia, a fragment state fallen out of
the disintegration of Jugoslavia, always itself on the verge of
exploding and subdividing in fragments. 
<P>
This is because in our international system disintegration is
allowed and no state is legitimised to impede the disintegration
process of another state by direct military intervention. But
when the Croatian army entered Bosnia to annex a piece of land
and risked producing the death of Bosnia by &quot;inviting&quot;
others (i.e. Serbia) to annex other pieces of Bosnian land, at
that time the political organisation of the international system
mobilised and reacted as, four years before, it had reacted to
the Iraq's invasion of Kuwait though Bosnia has no oil!<BR>

<P>
Mobilisation of the political organisation of the international
system means that the &quot;constitutional&quot; rules and institutions
(See: Attin&agrave;, 1989 and 1991) and the leading state(s) of
the system enter in action. In this case, the United States intervened
in Bosnia - as they had done in Kuwait and also in Korea - with
the legitimation of the United Nations, without giving to the
United Nations the control of the operations.
<P>
Also in the present international system of &quot;hegemony without
rivalry&quot;, the United States are taking on themselves the
role of security provider of last resort and they do so without
involving European allies in operations and alignments they dislike.
In such circumstances, the low interest of EU countries in deepening
the FSCP is hardly surprising.<BR>

<H1>International crime and police co-operation in the European
Union<BR>
</H1>

<P>
So far we have seen how the first and second change of world conditions
add toghether in negatively affecting the evolution of FSCP. At
the same time, the two changes affect the internal security of
states, forward the &quot;international dimension&quot; of internal
security and favour the emergence and development of the Third
Pillar in EU co-operation. Whoever accepts the claim of re-conceptualising
foreign policy, may find valuable hints in the Maastrich process.
<BR>

<P>
Since globalisation and interdependence are important characters
of the present world, especially in the economic and social fields,
foreign policy is made by the European governments, above all,
through measures for building monetary union, restructuring economic
relations with neighboring countries (the Central and Eastern
European Countries and the Mediterranean countries) and policing
state borders. It may be said that foreign and security policy
is made also with the First and the Third Pillar, and - in specific
matters - even better than with the Second one: the first to handle
the problems of economic co-operation and competition, the third
to deal with issues like international migrations (See: Collinson,
1993; Waever et al., 1993) and international crime (See: Ahnfelt
and From, 1993).<BR>

<P>
The world has problems which in their origin, growth and, solution
exceed national borders and capacities. More exactly, they cannot
be controlled and solved by state legislation and national authoritative
decisions. Their solution depends on international and supranational
regulation. This is true in such different fields as environment
(pollution), demography (migrations), health (epidemics) and public
security (organised crime, illegal business, trade in persons).
Because of the effects of interconnection that the process of
globalisation has on the politics of almost all contemporary states,
governments are able to exert the old and new functions of public
security, economic growth, health protection, social security,
etc., only if they resort to international co-operation and co-ordination.

<P>
Certain issues, affected by the globalisation process, are more
efficiently controlled by governments when they agree to co-ordinate
national policies with multilateral international policies and
regulations. Other issues - either produced or heavily conditioned
by the globalisation process - can be solved only if they enter
the agenda of co-operation at the level of the global system or,
at least, at the level of regional systems. The inclusion of a
problem in the international agenda means that the problem is
the object of the formulation of international legal norms, the
creation of competent international institutions or the attribution
of competence to already existing international institutions (See
Livingston, 1992): in other words, their solution may only be
made by issuing a world public policy.<BR>

<P>
In such a perspective, the effects of the accomplishment of the
four freedoms, scheduled in the Treaty of Rome, and of the single
market, scheduled in the Treatry of Maastricht, are not the only
reason for police co-operation in the European Union. Indeed,
they add to the effects of globalisation in causing the common
problem of protection from illegal and criminal actions in the
territory of the Union and across its borders. Co-operation in
public security is not only an instrument to protect public and
social order from the effects of opening internal borders; it
is an instrument to defend from one of the unwanted effects of
globalisation, that is international crime.<BR>

<P>
The most important form of international crime today is organised
crime, i.e. groups of people equipped with a stable, mostly hierarchical
organisation, which perpetrate illegal actions, usually using
violent means, in order to enrich themselves without consideration
for international frontiers. Important international organised
crime groups are the Mafias (Sicilian, American and Russian Mafia),
the Japanese Yakuza, the Colombian drug cartels of Medellin and
Cali, the Chinese Triads. But the phenomenon is only partially
known, and in continuous evolution. Certainly, these groups are
not unitary organisations but networks of homogeneous, loosely
subordinated groups.<BR>

<P>
An organisation may prefer to exploit a particular sector more
than others, but no orgnised crime body neglects drug trafficking,
arms trade, prostitution, people trade and international money
laundrering - the last being the natural complement of all kinds
of criminal activity, including traditional ones behind state
borders (extortion, usury, etc.).<BR>

<P>
In to the fight against international crime, whether organised
or not, there is no alternative than to collaborate and co-ordinate
national police and judiciary action. To improve such co-ordination,
agencies like Interpol and the new Europol have been constituted.
But the constitution and the operation of these agencies face
great obstacles and problems, because states have peculiar penal
law codes and institutes; they regulate police operations (like,
for instance, telephone controls, collection of information and
preventive incarceration) in very different ways.<BR>

<P>
International police co-operation has a long tradition. When crime
assumed the character of an international phenomenon, the police
responded with cross-border co-operation. During the first half
of the present century such co-operation was of an informal nature
and not based on formal agreements and conventions. The situation
changed significantly in the 1950s. Since 1956, Interpol has been
the key organisation for international police collaboration. Towards
the end of the 1950s, two important criminal law conventions -
one on Extradition (1957), the other on Legal Aid (1959) - were
formulated under the auspices of the Council of Europe (See: Gianaris,
1992-1993).<BR>

<P>
Almost all the states of the world are members of Interpol. About
eighty police agents of different countries work at the headquarters
of the organisation in the French city of Lyon while in the national
capitals of the member countries the CNOs (Central National Offices)
operate with local police officers. These offices communicate
directly for information exchange. The central data bank in Lyon
receives and gives information and data. This is what Interpol
mainly does (See: Bresler,1993; Valleix, 1984).<BR>

<P>
So, police co-operation is not new but its growth in recent times
has been very great and, obviously, related to the escalation
of international crime. Regarding EU countries, judiciary and
police co-operation started in the 1970s to fight terrorism. Recent
acceleration of co-operation, by contrast, is linked to the upsurge
of drug-related crimes as well as to the control of immigration
and prevention of illegal immigration (Ahnfelt and From, 1993;
Benyon, 1994; Fijnaut, 1994).<BR>

<P>
On German initiative, the need for police co-operation in the
EU has been discussed since the beginning of the 197Os. (See:
Benyon, 1992; de Boer and Walker, 1992). The extent of political
terrorism experienced by several member states led to the creation
of TREVI Group. This intergovemmental forum of EC Ministries of
Justice and Home Affairs was established by the European Council
in 1975 to co-ordinate anti-terrorism measures. TREVI's organisational
structure had three co-ordinated levels: ministerial, top civil
servant and the working group level. The Presidency of TREVI followed
the Presidency of the EC. 
<P>
The working groups, composed of civil servants and police officers,
were responsible for preparatory work on matters to be discussed
at higher level meetings, as well as for carrying out research
and planning at the request of the politicians. In 1991 the Commission
and the Secretariat of the Council of Ministers were permitted
to participate as observers in the working group responsible for
preparatory work on the removal of border controls within the
Community. With the construction of the Third Pillar, TREVI structures
have been progressively converted into structures of the Pillar
(See: Adam, 1994).<BR>

<P>
Since November 1993 and the coming into force of the Maastricht
Treaty, the EU's Council of Interior and Justice Ministers has
co-ordinated a number of actions on the basis of Article K (Title
VI on &quot;Co-operation in the Fiuds of Justice and Home Affairs&quot;)
of the Maastricht Treaty (See: den Boer, 1995; Vilarino Pintos,
1994). Article K l. identifies nine areas as &quot;matters of
common interest&quot;: (1) asylum policy; (2) rules governing
the crossing by persons of the external borders of the Member
States and the exercise of controls thereon; (3) immigration policy
and policy regarding nationals of third countries; (4) combating
drug addiction in so far as this is not covered by (7) to (9);
(5) combating fraud on an international scale in so far as this
is not covered by (7) to (9); (6) judicial co-operation in civil
matters; (7) judicial co-operation in criminal matters; (8) customs
co-operation; (9) police co-operation for the purposes of preventing
and combating terrorism, unlawful drug trafficking and other serious
forms of international crime, including if necessary certain aspects
of customs co-operation, in connection with the organisation of
a Union-wide system for exchanging information within a European
Police Office (Europol). Like foreign and defence affairs, justice
and home affairs are sensitive matters of state sovereignty. They
involve the use of coercion, the restriction of liberties, and
the conditions of public and social order. The execution of Title
VI provisions hence is a particularly difficult task. The desired
harmonisation of different penal laws will be a slow and painstaking
task. In spite of this, the opinion of the experts is that results
have already been achieved in the first two years of existence
of the Third Pillar (Willy Bruggeman, 1996).
<P>
Article K.l.9. of the Maastricht Treaty provides for the establishment
of Europol. In June 1991 Germany put a formal proposal to the
delegates negotiating on the reform of the treaties. The proposal
was to establish a unit for combating terrorism and organised
crime through the exchange of information and also with an operational
mandate.<BR>

<P>
Europol is &quot;to improve the effectiveness and co-operation
of the competent authorities in the Member States in preventing
and combating terrorism, unlawful drug trafficking and other serious
forms of international crime where there are factual indications
that an organised criminal structure is involved and two or more
Member Stares are affected... &quot; (article K.1.). 
<P>
The supplementary Declaration appended to the Treaty also refers
to other instruments like support, analysis of national prevention
programmes, training and research and development. Finally, the
Europol Convention (signed in Brussels on July 26th) describes
Europol's tasks as: exchange of information; analysis; facilitating
the co-ordination of ongoing investigations; increasing expertise;
training.<BR>

<P>
Europol's tasks will be performed by Europol officials and analysts
on the one hand and by liaison officers from the Member States
on the other. Every country is obliged to set up a national intelligence
service (Europol National Unit).
<P>
However, Europol is not a completely new agency. On June 2, 1993,
a Ministerial Agreement set up the Europol Drugs Unit (EDU), which
started operation on January 1st, 1994. Its mandate has been extended
by the Joint Action of the Justice and Interior Ministers of March
10, 1995 from drugs-related crime only to illicit trafficking
in radioactive and nuclear substances, illicit vehicle trafficking,
clandestine immigration networks and all associated money-laundering
activities. EDU does not take charge of cases but provides assistance
and support. Each team of liaison officers remains under the exclusive
control of the national authorities and the management of EDU
co-ordinates the team, not the cases. According to Bruggeman (1996),
this provisional model will probably be one of the cornerstones
of Europol: &quot;nothing else is possible given that the Member
States' criminal justice and law enforcernent systems are based
entirely on the principle of sovereignty&quot;.<BR>

<H1>EU and US transatlantic partnership and internal security
<BR>
</H1>

<P>
Since the end of World War II, relations between Western Europe
and the United States have been the object of continuous debate
among politicians, diplomats, academics and concerned people.
The conflict of interests and the similarity/identity of the fundamental
values of the two parts have been repeatedly assessed during the
last fifty years. 
<P>
The importance, for the whole international system, of co-operative
relations between the two sides of the Atlantic and the aknowledged
reason for differentiation and even for conflict on certain issues
have always encouraged concern for studying the alliance and devising
a stable and enduring framework to overcome recurrent tensions.
Academics defined the nature of the relation using concepts like
hegemony and asymmetrical interdependence. Politicians, instead,
preferred to soften asperities by not sparing in the use of words
like partnership and friendship. Contrary to past attention and
concern and in spite of the convulsive state of change of the
present international system, debate is mostly &quot;soft&quot;
today. A larger opportunity for change goes with less debate on
steering the change of Atlantic co-operation. It is as if academics
and politicians feel themselves inadequately informed as to how
to interpret the evolution of affairs, and, above all, uncertain
on how to take good decisions to update and/or upgrade Atlantic
co-operation. But, not every thing is immobile.<BR>

<P>
In November 1990, in Paris the United States and the European
Community signed the Transatlantic Declaration and opened a new
set of diplomatic negotiations. The Declaration was not consonant
with the traditional nature of US-Europe relations, either in
terms of the nature of the signatory parts or of the content of
the document. One of two signatories was the government of the
United States but the other one was an uncommon diplomatic actor,
the tandem composed of the EC Presidency and the President of
the Commission. As for the content of the Declaration, it was
concerned with low political matters as much as with high and
sensitive issues, like trade and GATT. However, the public's attention
(even that of concerned people) rapidly fell off. The same lack
of public attention marked the annual summits of the signatory
which followed the Paris summit. Two years ago, one of the few
researchers attentive to the Declaration and the following transatlantic
negotiatons made this remark: &quot;politicians and academics
alike have apparently forgotten the so-called Transatlantic Declaration,
the major attempt to redefine the common relations and to build
up something like a stable network of relations&quot; (Wessels,
1993).<BR>

<P>
The reason for the constitution of the transatlantic network can
be found in the need to prevent the blossoming of reciprocal worries.
On the American side, the worry is that once EU governments reach
a common position, this is declared as final and not open to negotiation
with the United States. On the European side, the worry is that
the United States wants to it at the EU negotiation table and
dominate the debate. Indeed, in a situation of no conflict among
EU governements, these may confront the US government with a non-
negotiable position; in a situation of conflict among EU governments,
instead, the US government may easily interfere by its direct
relations with the single European governments. 
<P>
Therefore, the transatlantic network of negotiations may be the
way to avoid such a double negative situation and make more equal
- perhaps, in the future also deeper - links between EU and the
United States.<BR>

<P>
The annual transatlantic summits between the Presidents of the
European Council and Commission and the President of the United
States have been considered as a major step to establish a <I>communaut&eacute;
de vue</I> as a base for common activities. At the same time,
the frequent meetings of working groups have been considered valuable
instruments of &quot;confidence building&quot; among administrations
not used to work toghether. 
<P>
But, critics say, the annual meetings are too infrequent to create
the projected <I>communaut&eacute; de vue</I> and the working
groups are inconclusive experiences for administrators used to
work with very different practices and styles. As a matter of
fact, the US side has to get accustomed to EU practices, like,
for instance the rotation of the Presidency. EU diplomats, in
their turn, have to work hard to get at effective co-ordination
of national positions and, when this is impossibile, to reduce
the effect of failed co-ordination in order to appropriately confront
their American counterpart.<BR>

<P>
In spite of complaints, the transatlantic network has not been
dismantled. On the contrary, by agreeing on the New Transatlantic
Agenda (signed in Madrid on December 15-16, 1995), the two parts
considered the present structure of co-operation as fitting well
to the state of EU-US relations. The Agenda presents four major
goals of co-operation (promoting peace, stability, democracy and
development around the world; responding to global challenges;
contributing to the expansion of world trade and closer economic
relations; building bridges across the Atlantic) and issues a
Joint EU/US Action Plan. It is difficult to say whether the Agenda
is a real incremental step, a simple updated version or a mere
repetition of the 1990 Declaration. Undoubtedly, the implementation
of the Action Plan will be the litmus test of the importance of
the Agenda and viability of the transatlantic network. The actions
to be taken are not easy, but the seriousness of the issues linked
to the first and second world change is certainly a strong incentive
to move in the direction devised in the Agenda.<BR>

<P>
Co-operation in the field of internal security is a major topic
of the Action Plan. It extensively defines the problem of international
crime prevention and containment, differentiates many aspects
of crime at the global level, and openly considers the case for
police co-operation.<BR>

<P>
The new dimensions of security - explicitly reported as products
of the globalisation process - are the very object of the Joint
EU/US Action Plan. The concluding part of the Agenda merits full
quotation. Governments confess their <TT>concern to address in
an effective manner new global challenges which, without respect
for national boundaries, present a serious threat to the quality
of life and which no one state can overcome alone. They list the
following global issues: international crime, terrorism and drug
trafficking, mass migration, degradation of the environment, nuclear
safety and disease. <BR>
</TT>
<P>
<TT>A series of bilateral co-operation and institutional contacts
are envisaged to fight against illegal drug trafficking, money
laundering, terrorism, organised crime and illicit trade in nuclear
materials. They are the enhancement of the capabilities of criminal
justice and investigative systems, the promotion of the rule of
law through international training programmes at regional institutions,
the establishment of an information exchange mechanism on co-operation
between the U.S. and the EU and member states in the law enforcement
and criminal justice fields, the exchange of law enforcement and
criminal justice. The possibility of establishing interim co-operative
measures between competent U.S. authorities and the European Drugs
Unit, the execution of the measures contemplated in the convention
on EUROPOL to facilitate relations between EUROPOL and the U.S.
Government are proposed, as well as co-operation in the framework
of the UN Drug Control Programme. To counter drug production,
the establishment of co-operative links between EU institutions
such as the European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction
and the Commission Interamericana para el Control del Abuso de
Drogas are also proposed. <BR>
</TT>
<P>
<TT>Illegal immigration, traffic in illegal immigrants and the
traffic in women are further areas of public security co-operation
signalled in the Action Plan. Legal and judicial international
co-operation is also pledged as the dena for future common action.
<BR>
</TT>
<H1>The Barcelona Declaration and the Mediterranean theatre of
internal security<BR>
</H1>

<P>
At the very time the two world changes matured and the Atlantic
countries started the transatlantic network, the EU and its member
governments began to reconsider the state of another sector of
their international relations. The political and economic instability
of East European countries after the dissolution of communism
was not more serious than the condition of the neghbouring countries
in the Mediterranean region. It took some years to pass from the
awareness of the problem to the formulation of a policy, from
realising the unproductiveness of past programmes and actions
towards the Mediterranean countries, to putting on the ground
a new strategy aimed at substituting the traditional sectorial
and bilateral approach with the Euro-Meditarrean Partnership (See:
Joffe 1994; Pace 1995). The Barcelona conference - where the Partnership
has been solemnly launched - may be the opening of a new chapter
in the history of relations between the European Union and the
countries of the Mediterranean.<BR>

<P>
The United States has not been admitted as a full participant
state but assisted to the official parts of the conference. The
European Union and its member governments, with different positions,
excluded them for formal reasons. The United States is not a Mediterranean
country. However, invitation has been discussed and the exclusion
may be taken as an indication of the persistence of the &quot;dissociation
syndrome&quot;.
<P>
To take the United States as much as possible out of the restructuring
of the Mediterranean region while the restructuring of international
politics is in progress, was a delicatetask. However, the European
Union and its governments talked with the rest of the Mediterranean
governments on important political, security and economic matters
without the presence of the Washington government and made future
plans in all those matters.<BR>

<P>
The Declaration targets a free trade area among the 27 participants
by the year 2010 and pledges to start co-operation in a broad
range of political, social and economic fields. It comprises four
chapters (Political and Security Partnership; Economic and Financial
Partnership; Partnership in Social, Cultural and Human Affairs;
Follow-Up) and a work programme.<BR>

<P>
In the chapter on Political and Security Partnership the participants
stress their conviction that peace, stability and security in
the Mediterranean region are common assets which they pledge to
promote and strengthen &quot;by all means at their disposal&quot;.
It is in this chapter that they undertake to, among other things,
<BR>

<UL>
<LI>strengthen their co-operation in preventing and combating
terrorism, in particular by ratifying and applying the international
instruments they have signed, by acceding to such instruments
and by taking any other appropriate measure; 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>fight together against the expansion and diversification of
organised crime and combat the drugs problem in all its aspects.

</UL>

<P>
In the chapter on Economic and Financial Partnership, the participating
countries fixed three long term objectives to their partnership:
to speed up the pace of lasting social and economic development;
to improve living conditions by increasing employment and closing
the development gap in the Euro-Mediterranean region; to promote
co-operation and regional integration.<BR>

<P>
In the chapter on Partnership in Social, Cultural and Human Affairs,
governments recognise that mutual understanding can be greatly
enhanced by human exchanges and dialogue between cultures. 
<P>
The conference agreed to establish a wide range of co-operation
between peoples, not only in politics but also in culture, religion,
education, the media, as well as between trade unions and public
and private companies. The Declaration also recognises the challenges
posed by current population trends in the Med12 (non-EU countries)
and says that they must be counterbalanced by &quot;appropriate
policies to accelerate economic take-off&quot;. Participants agreed
to strengthen their co-operation to reduce migratory pressures
and illegal immigration. They also acknowledged the principle
that source countries had &quot;a responsibility for readmission&quot;
of illegal immigrants to Europe. In this chapter again they pledge
to act against crime:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>they agree to strengthen co-operation by means of various
measures to prevent terrorism and fight it more effectively together;

</UL>

<UL>
<LI>by the same token they consider it necessary to fight jointly
and effectively against drug trafficking, international crime
and corruption. 
</UL>

<P>
Like the Helsinki Conference, the Barcelona Conference provides
for Follow-Up. Foreign Ministers from the 27 nations will meet
periodically to review progress in implementing the Declaration
and to agree on actions which will achieve its objectives. Their
first meeting will be in the first half of 1997 in a Mediterranean
member state of the Union. Sectorial meetings at ministerial level
will be organised together with <I>ad hoc</I> conferences.<BR>

<P>
To translate the Barcelona Declaration into concrete action, the
Conference approved a Work ProgrammeThis Programme encourages
initiatives to discuss migratory flows and co-operation between
law and order authorities as part of the fight against terrorism,
drug trafficking, organised crime and illegal immigration.<BR>

<H1>Conclusion<BR>
</H1>

<P>
The European Union is at the cross-roads of the Transatlantic
and the Mediterranean co-operation and is, at the same time, attempting
to formulate its own joint actions and common policies. The United
States is committed to reshaping its hegemonic foreign policy
but has to take into account contradictory trends: on the one
hand, the continuing need for the presence of an actor as the
provider of last resort of important collective goods of the system;
on the other hand, the challenges put to it by the aspirations
to greater autonomy of old and new actors of the global system.
The Med12 are both anxious to prevent the explosion of many crisis
factors in their societies and conscious, almost unanimously,
of the need for international co-operation to approach the condition
of take off. <BR>

<P>
In such a contingency, the fact that the objects of co-operation
in the European Union, Transatlatinc relations and the Euro-Meditarranean
region are the same, though not particularly astonishing to professional
observers of international politics, is a fact that merits attentive
consideration. The longer the governments go on with the implementation
of the Action Plan and Work Programme of such co-operation, the
stronger will be the change of the international system in the
direction of improving security in different dimensions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

