<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>TOULONMADS</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>A EURO-MEDITERRANEAN PARTNERSHIP: WHOSE SECURITY</B>? <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Dominic FENECH</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>, Co-ordinator,
Contemporary Mediterranean Studies Programme, University of Malta</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
Until recently not many were willing to concede that there exists
a specific Mediterranean regionality. That is to say, considering
the great diversity and disparity that exist among its component
parts, does the Mediterranean possess the characteristics that
qualify it to be approached as a single region? No other geographical
area of comparable size incorporates such widely diverse characteristics
and problems and, inevitably, conflict situations and potential.
This concentration of diversity and disparity, with its conflict
potential,in part accounts for the failure on the part of many
riparian states themselves to seek, recognise and promote a common
Mediterranean identity. Yet paradoxically, security in its widest
definition is probably the single most important factor that qualifies
and requires the Mediterranean to be approached as a single region.
Partly as a result of the end of the East-West confrontation,
partly as a side product of Europe&iacute;s own integration process,
the subject of security in the Mediterranean has, quite suddenly,
become a focus of international attention. Mediterranean regionality
is now treated as axiomatic. <BR>

<P>
It is symptomatic of the modern history of the Mediterranean that
the international actors most prepared to regard it as a single
region have been those possessing global interests, viewing it
as a function of those interests. The west&iacute;s post-World
War II definition of the Mediterranean as &euml;Europe&iacute;s
southern flank&iacute; accorded to it such astrategic regionality
- as a function of European security. The Soviet Union likewise
came to regard the Mediterranean as a strategic unit, engaging
in a maritime competition with the predominant United States.
Of course this view of regionality, the corollary of bringing
the Cold War down to the Mediterranean, had nothing to do with
fostering the coherence of the region. Neither did it have as
its primary aim the solution of the problems that afflicted the
Mediterranean people themselves.<BR>

<P>
In a different way and on a different plane, the consolidation
of the European Economic Community in time led to another major
international actor addressing the region as a single entity,
through its comprehensive Mediterranean policies, acknowledging
the importance of striking an economic relationship with its immediate
neighbourhood. Despite many shortcomings, this Mediterranean policy
did seek a relationship of interdependence with Mediterranean
non-member states, revealing a clear sensitivity to the political
dividends of such a relationship. By the 1970s, the European Community
was overtaking the United States as the mainstay of economic and
political, though not of course military, support to many Mediterranean
countries. Especially after the worst of the first Cold War phase
was over, Euro-American disagreement - or at least failure to
co-ordinate policy and action - surfaced over security matters
outside the strict framework of the east-west confrontation. And
this failure to see eye to eye is chiefly noticeable with regards
to Mediterranean affairs. <BR>

<P>
If the USA regarded local problems from the perspective of a world
power with world views, the Mediterranean and its parts were no
exception. The global problem being security in relation to the
USSR, its Mediterranean policy aimed to contain USSR influence.
If US national security interests - as opposed to the broader
western world&iacute;s security interests - were not directly
affected by specific problems of the Mediterranean, the same cannot
be said of western Europe, itself in part Mediterranean. Unlike
the USA, the Europeans could not afford the end-justifies-the-means
approach. Thus for example, where the USA could live with the
contradiction that several south European allies were governed
by right wing antidemocratic regimes, as this was in itself a
guarantee of anti-communism, the Europeans were less comfortable
condoning such regimes on their doorstep. European support for
democratic transition in Portugal, Spain, Greece and Turkey has
been on the whole consistent and concrete.<BR>

<P>
One feature of Euro-American disagreement has been the limits
of NATO&iacute;s scope, with the Americans urging NATO to broaden
its scope to include objectives not related to the Soviet threat
in Europe and the Europeans keen to reserve NATO for the defence
of Europe and its members. In the circumstances, the most likely
candidate areas for so-called out-of-area operations were in the
Mediterranean and its environs, notably the Middle East. Nonetheless,
whereas the United States failed to address NATO to areas adjacent
to, but outside, Europe, in the Mediterranean it unilaterally
pursued security policies that were neither related to any threat
to Europe or to defence from the USSR. This it could do thanks
to its heavy naval presence and its network of military bases
in the Mediterranean. This ability to act in Europe&iacute;s neighbourhood
independently, combined with Europe&iacute;s resistance to the
Alliance&iacute;s operating outside its original brief, resulted
in the Euro-American allies sometimes pursuing different or even
competing policies in the Mediterranean.<BR>

<P>
Other than the defence of Europe&iacute;s southern flank from
the Soviet threat, US policy in the Mediterranean increasingly
came to focus on Middle Eastern oil, especially following the
1973 oil shock. By the late 1970s, this objective had become prominent
enough for the United States to institute the Rapid Deployment
Force, and for constant American surveillance of the Persian Gulf.
It happenedalso that the late 1970s and early 1980s saw a scrambling
of regional alignments in the Middle East, through a series of
events including the change of regime in Iran, the Soviet invasion
of Afghanistan, and the beginning of the Iran-Iraq war. The late
1970s therefore intensified American sensitivity to the issue
of Middle Eastern oil, just as the &euml;second Cold War&iacute;
was beginning. <BR>

<P>
In summary, for almost half a century security in the Mediterranean
has been defined by powers and forces that were either external
or peripheral to the Mediterranean. Whether in terms of Europe&iacute;s
southern flank, or the western world&iacute;s supplies of oil,
or simply as an arena of superpower naval competition, the matter
of broader Mediterranean security was not in the charge of the
Mediterranean riparian states. <BR>

<P>
The contradiction was that while the Mediterranean was regarded
as a area where Europe and the west in general had vital security
interests, the non-European Mediterranean was not and could not
be involved in European security concerns. The contradiction surfaced
more than once in the councils of the Conference on Security and
Co-operation in Europe (CSCE). Whereas the purpose of the CSCE
was to foster security through co-operation in Europe, the main
theatre of the East-West conflict, it proved difficult to persuade
member states, most especially the superpowers, to extend the
scope of the conference to include the whole Mediterranean. As
a result, whatever achievements were made with regards to European
security were not reflected with regards to Mediterranean security.
<BR>

<P>
No sooner was the mantle of the Cold War lifted from international
relations than the extent of the problems of the Mediterranean
became highlighted. If anything, the security problems of the
Mediterranean appear bigger today than they did before 1989. The
only area of progress registered has been the Middle East peace
process, and even that required a major international war in the
Middle East to set it afoot. In compensation, warfare reminiscent
of the nineteenth century erupted in the Balkans, south-north
emigration has accelerated, and fundamentalism has spread in numbers
and militancy in different parts of the Mediterranean.
<P>
The two movements of emigration and fundamentalism are indeed
a barometer of the degree of distance that has been allowed to
develop between the two opposing shores of the Mediterranean,
with the former denoting despair and flight, and the latter resignation
and rejection of the western model of the state with its broken
promises.<BR>

<P>
The question of the future for Mediterranean security in the post-Cold
War era cannot ignore the experience of the past decades, even
if the international situation today is substantively different
from what it was a few years ago. During the past half-century,
the Mediterranean has not only been a theatre of east-west confrontation,
chosen by the non-Mediterranean protagonists of that contest for
its strategic relevance to the main theatre. 
<P>
Less spectacularly but equally importantly and certainly more
durably, the Mediterranean is a political equator between the
two hemispheres of north and south. The healing of one divide
(the east-west) has little or no relevance to the surviving one.
If anything, the north-south divide here is the more glaring for
that reason.<BR>

<P>
For better or worse, the future of Mediterranean security will
continue to be intimately bound with European security. The question
of which security structure will prevail in Europe would seem
to be central to the future of Mediterranean security. Equally
relevant is the nature of the relationship that will evolve between
Europe and the United States - and perhaps also Russia. <BR>

<P>
The question comes down to a simple one: will Europe formulate
its security in collaboration with its southern neighbours, or
will it formulate it in confrontation with them? This is a good
time to posit such questions, not only because security concerns
in the Mediterranean are serious and immediate, but also because
Europe&iacute;s security architecture is in a state of flux. In
part, this is also because identifying the direction from where
European security might be threatened is less easy today than
it was in the later 1940s. On the eastern front, the Soviet threat
has disappeared, but the long tradition of distrust and fear of
Russia have not. On the southern front, meanwhile, the threat
to European security is not a military one - and therefore there
is no simple way of dealing with it. Indeed, the only way to deal
with it appears to be the long and laborious process of healing
the causes. If that is the solution - and certainly from a Mediterranean
point of view it is the best solution - a lot will depend on which
security structure ultimately prevails in Europe, how such a structure
will define European security interests, and what the true targets
of its protagonists are. <BR>

<P>
Until now, of the different European security organisations, NATO
is the clear front-runner. Quickly shedding its Cold War function
it redefined itself as a long term security through co-operation
organisation with a rapid trouble-shooting capability. In so doing
it assumed functions and objectives that collectively subsume
the functions and objectives of its potential competitors, while
proclaiming itself ready to co-ordinate its activities with them.
<BR>

<P>
Furthermore, through the Partnership for Peace it has extended
its field of operations to include practically all of Europe.
By placing itself at the disposal of the CSCE, NATO has circumvented
the problem of replicating the functions of that organisation,
without however giving up its freedom to act on its own initiative.
The future of other, competing, security set-ups which have resurfaced
or come into being after the fall of the Berlin Wall is uncertain,
and the degree of overlap between the different set-ups and initiatives
is bewildering. CSCE, NATO, The Western European Union, the Pact
for Stability in Europe and the embryonic Common Foreign and Security
Policy of the EU may be similar but different. But it will take
time, for some coherence to emerge between all these set-ups if
it ever does. Some are independently making moves and soundings
to address the Mediterranean. What is not clear is whether these
are motivated by the notion of a common Euro-Mediterranean destiny
or by their perception of the southern Mediterranean as a potential
foe.
<P>
In theory, NATO might have disbanded as soon as the Soviet Union
gave up the fight. In theory too, the obvious set-up for the future
security of Europe was the CSCE, for if the concept of achieving
security through co-operation could be valid in a confrontational
situation, it would be even more valid in a peaceful one. Indeed
it is the mission of the CSCE that NATO has claimed to adopt as
an alternative to its Cold War mission. And it is over the entire
territory of the CSCE that NATO has been aiming to spread by inviting
all CSCE members to join its Partnership for Peace programme.
The offer by NATO to place itself as an operational body at the
disposal of the CSCE followed logically. <BR>

<P>
The ascendancy of NATO over all other security set-ups with pan-European
objectives, and the corollary of NATO fitting into the CSCE glove
is not necessarily the best security forecast for the Mediterranean.
Reinforcing the Euro-Atlantic security link, it implicitly competes
with the concept of a Euro-Mediterranean security partnership,
by seeming to perpetrate the Cold War-inspired notion that NATO&iacute;s
primary interest in the Mediterranean is the defence of the West&iacute;s
security. It may be argued, if one can ignore the comments of
NATO&iacute;s former Secretary General, that NATO does not harbour
aggressive feelings towards the Arab neighbourhood in the Mediterranean
and the Middle East. It can also be argued that NATO has transformed
its mission and is not solely or primarily an alliance with a
specific adversary, as it used to be <I>vis-a- vis</I>. the Soviet
Union. Nevertheless, when all is said and done, it remains an
alliance concerned with the security interests of its members
only. That being so, every neighbourhood is a potential adversary.
Most importantly, NATO&iacute;s willingness to serve as the instrument
of the CSCE in no way limits its freedom to act independently
of it. For the same reason that Russia does not welcome the expansion
of NATO&iacute;s towards its borders, it must not be assumed that
the Mediterranean neighbours welcome the entrenchment of NATO
as the European security structure par excellence. Under its American
leadership, and with its potential for assuming even out-of-area
missions on behalf of the UN and/or the OSCE, it appears too much
like an instrument of a first-world dominated New World Order.
That is the more so since it does not come under the control of
either the UN or the OSCE. On top of that, then, the United States
itself retains the freedom to act independently, even of its NATO
allies, in this region.<BR>

<P>
A Pax Americana, whether real or perceived, cannot be the ideal
setting for confidence-building. The drawback of having the United
States concerting Euro-Mediterranean security is that, unlike
Europe, which has a neighbour&iacute;s interest in achieving stability
for its own sake, the US is prone to define Mediterranean security
in terms of extra-Mediterranean issues and targets, such as the
oil of the Gulf. The continued definition of Mediterranean security
in terms of extra-Mediterranean objectives can foster further
division by competing with the real concerns of Mediterranean
security as defined by Mediterranean countries themselves. Thus
for example, for all the support that Arab governments gave to
the US-led coalition against Iraq in 1991 in the first test case
of the projected &euml;New World Order&iacute;, it is clear that
the hearts and minds of the Arab populations resented the role
of the United States as guardian of international order inside
the Arab world. <BR>

<P>
Which is also to say that the support of such Arab governments
was dependent on their being undemocratic. The question of democracy
indeed is crucial to the future of any working Euro-Mediterranean
relationship, especially in terms of achieving enduring security.
In terms of experience in supporting democratic transition in
the Mediterranean the European Union has a sound record. 
<P>
In the past, Europe&iacute;s approach of encouraging the combination
of democratic transition and economic development in southern
Europe proved to be more far-sighted than that of condoning authoritarian
regimes on the grounds that their anti-communism made Europe&iacute;s
southern flank safer from Soviet penetration. That experience
ought to serve as the basis for dealing with the Arab Mediterranean
countries, which suggests that fearing democracy because it gives
space to Islamic fundamentalists or because it might produce governments
that do not share western values and objectives is short-sighted.
There is no reason why the maxim that democratic countries make
peaceful neighbours should not apply to the Mediterranean also.
<BR>

<P>
Nor should Europe be pusillanimous about pushing for the required
changes in the internal system of government in its neighbours
across the water. For just as Western Europe could not integrate
parts of itself before those parts became democracies, so it cannot
integrate an entire region which denies democracy to its people.
<P>
It would certainly be against the best of European tradition to
try fostering its own security by shoring up regimes that do not
speak for their own people. It is the surest way, not only of
delaying democratic transition in these societies, but of securing
the enduring distrust of such societies. <BR>

<P>
Conversely, while Arab societies can be expected to be suspicious
of a security system concerted by the United States, these same
quarters seek - and indeed, expect - Europe to be more forthcoming
towards them. If any criticism is levelled towards Europe frontier
quarter, it is that the Europeans have not done enough to assist
them, not that the Europeans must keep to their side of the sea.
After all, it is with Europe, even more than with each other,
that they conduct most of their economic business.<BR>

<P>
It would seem therefore that for Euro-Mediterranean security to
achieve a concrete level of co-ordination, the divide that exists
between north and south has to be acknowledged for what it is,
and the causes addressed squarely, in a context of partnership.
In this light, the best model for a Euro-Mediterranean security
structure and framework appears to be the OSCE. From its inception,
this organisation (as the CSCE) addressed a situation of division,acknowledging
that co-operation amongst adversaries generated confidence and
produced security. It was to be expected - though it has not resulted
in practice - that the termination of the Cold War would crown
the CSCE as the ideal pan-European security framework and structure
to help consolidate the peace in the same way as it had earlier
contributed to defuse tensions. Thus, Russia&iacute;s support
for this line of thought stems from the fact that its position
in the CSCE is one of parity with that of its former adversaries,
a logical expectation in a new order to replace the Cold War division
of Europe. The same logic applies to the Euro-Mediterranean situation.
<BR>

<P>
At the time of the East-West divide, it proved impossible, beyond
declarations, to persuade the CSCE to include the non-European
Mediterranean in its scope and thus acknowledge the inseparability
of European and Mediterranean security interests. Proponents of
that line of action argued that security in Europe achieved to
the exclusion of security in the Mediterranean was tantamount
to the former being achieved at the expense of the latter. If
the protagonists of the CSCE then objected to extend the scope
of the Conference because their chief concern was to bridge the
east-west division of Europe, the same reason cannot apply today.
Today, there are clear signs that Europe is taking very seriously
the implications to its own security of problems that could emanate
from the Mediterranean. <BR>

<P>
Replicating the OSCE on a minor scale through regional arrangements,
such as a Conference on Security and Co-operation in the Mediterranean
(CSCM) and similar initiatives, may be a good start as intermediary
measures leading to a more comprehensive approach. But such initiatives
can become meaningless or worse if they are seen as Europe&iacute;s
way of keeping the problems of the Mediterranean at arm&iacute;s
length. Similarly, to be beneficial, initiatives by NATO or the
WEU to involve themselves in Mediterranean problems cannot aim
to compete with the prospects of a more comprehensive partnership.
What the Mediterranean does not need is a myriad of organisations
trying to upstage each other as its security guardians. On the
other hand, adoption of the principle that Euro-Mediterranean
security is one and indivisible on the basis of a full Euro-Mediterranean
partnership would be a confidence-building measure in itself,
given that a relationship of parity has never existed between
the northern and southern shores of the Mediterranean. In short,
a Euro-Mediterranean partnership should be just that. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
