<BODY>

<H3>Tuesday, November 21, 1995</H3>

<P>
<B>IT and <A HREF="4day.htm">New Political, Economic and Social environment </A>for
diplomatic activities</B>
<P>
<B>Presenter:</B>
<P>
 Mr. Jovan Kurbalija,
<P>
 Head of Unit for IT and Diplomacy,
<P>
 Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies
<P>
<B>Introduction :</B>
<P>
IT has led to a new political, economic and social environment
for international relations which is characterised by interdependence,
interconnectivity and profound change. The impact of these changes
are both positive and negative.
<P>
<B>IT and changes in modern society</B> 
<P>
  - IT has fueled the transition from the industrial towards the
information society.
<P>
<B> IT and sovereignty</B> 
<P>
- IT has not superseded but eroded sovereignty. The national legal
system, for example, can be by-passed by network 
<P>
  piracy and the accessing of pornography where prohibited.
<P>
<A HREF="#Joe_Woods">IT and international relations (concept of power)</A>

<P>
- IT has produced not only a change in the concept of power but
also in the source of power. As a consequence of
<P>
  IT, for example, the economic clout of the Republic of China
has been recognised despite the political standing of the
<P>
  People's Republic of China, inter alia, as a permanent Member
of the United Nations.
<P>
- Fibre optics, has, additionally, changed geopolitics in that
Marseilles, France, is now the new geopolitical centre, a
<P>
   position formerly held by Gibralta, Malta and Cyprus.
<P>
<B>IT and cultural diversity</B> 
<P>
- Through IT all States have the means to promote and exploit
their own cultures and interests.
<P>
<B>IT and international economy</B> 
<P>
- IT has facilitated the economic growth of the &quot;Asian Tigers&quot;.
<P>
<B>Evaluation:</B>
<P>
- IT is to modern society what rail was initially to industry.

<P>
- Information has always been power, but it is now no longer the
monopoly of big and /or rich countries.
<P>
- Are the resultant implications being applied in national policy
and personal lifestyle goals?
<H5><B>IT and National Comparative Advantages - National IT Strategy</B>
-</H5>

<P>
Presente<A NAME="Joe_Woods">r:</A> 
<P>
Joe Woods, Malta Council for Science and Technology, Malta
<P>
Introduction:
<P>
Thesis: IT should not be for its own sake( titillation, bemusement)
but rather for <A HREF="#Commonwealth">empowerment.</A> 
<P>
Main points:
<P>
The ability to produce a value -added component is now a resource
in itself. The possession of natural resources is therefore no
longer obligatory for economic growth.
<P>
Interdependence and interconnectivity producing globalisation
now means that &quot; the world's problems are now yours&quot;,
that is , the national context is now affected.
<P>
This new environment produces opportunities and threats. The response
can either be reactionary or proactive and visionary. The former
results in despair and fear. Embracing the latter can lead to
a quantum leap.For example, the appreciation of the concept of
interconnectivity emphasised by Mediterranean litoral States has
caused a policy shift in the political and economic relation between
the European Union and the Mediterranean.[Hyperlink : Maltese
intiative on stability to Eureo-Mediterranean Conference.] IT
and globalisation constitue the motto of Malta's Vision 2000 strategy
by which it is hoped to make Malta a leader in international business
and restore her as the hub of the Mediterranean.
<P>
A further consequence is the potential for a shift in the global
balance of power in international relations between small and
third States. It was stressed that the Commonwealth could take
the lead in this regard.
<P>
Size is therefore no longera disadvantage but an asset, given
the generally greater adaptability and homogenity of small States.
<P>
Small States can now participate competetively in new strategic
alliances with big States. For example, Malta is now being considered
as a hub by the United States to access North African market.
<P>
Maximisation of IT requires an attitude shift for sustainable
development.
<P>
<A NAME="Commonwealth">Evaluation</A> 
<P>
-Are the implications of IT in the new global environment being
applied in national policy? From Mr. Wood's presentation, the
answer is a resounding 'yes' in the case of Malta.
<P>
- Mr. Wood's concept of 'quanatum leap' and attitude shift' though
reminiscent of former United States President Ronald Reagan's
&quot;Star Wars', is intriguing with historical precedent in the
development of technology in general. It should therefore be tested
in the very context he proposes: a new attitude and strategy for
small states in the commonwealth. For example, the Commonwealth
should adopt a pilot project whereby its small states not only
network in an agreed area of strength/advantage, but also establishing
an area of strategic alliance with bigger sister commonwealth
states.
<P>
<B>IT INITIATIVES IN THE COMMONWEALTH</B>
<P>
Presenter: Dr. Sajda Qureshi, Commonwealth Seceretariat, London
<P>
Introduction
<P>
Analysis of national development of countries have shown that
the locus of growth of national economic development cannot merely
be explained in terms of labour and capital. There is a third
factor and it is the technological factor. On a world scale, the
evolution of completed strategic planning as a field of practice,
which began during the 1960s decade, views the 1990s decade as
the decade during which human resources development and utilisation
and technology and development are, and progressively become,
the centre-piece for national development plans of developing
countries countries. For the 1990s and beyond, technology and
human resource development can be described to be inseparable
elements of sustainalble development.
<P>
Main points:
<P>
- IT is disseminated throughout the Commonwealth by
<P>
: products, example: equipment, assembly plants and production
tools
<P>
: human resources; training (individual, group, exchanges, attachnments,
expert and technical assistance, skills upgrading (industrial,
technical, vocational)
<P>
: technology transfer (institutional development, settimg up computer
and data communications networks, rehabilitation of small industrial
enterprises, advisory services, research and development and information
exchange)
<P>
- The source for data on Commonwealth IT initiatives is the Commonwealth
Debt Recording and Managing System (CS - DRMS)
<P>
Evaluation
<P>
Secretariat IT initiatives which have particular significance
for the development and attainment of Commonwealth Secretariat
and member state prioroties are, respectively the Informal Consultative
Group of Information Technology for Development (ICGITD) via a
computer and telecommunications network among identified officials
only from a rangr of international agencies, and the Commonwealth
Secretaarit Debt Recording and Management System and the concept
behind GOVERNET.
<P>
<B>ELECTRONIC EMBASSY: OPENING SYSTEMS _ HOW TO CHOOSE THE PROPER
OS FOR MINISTRY OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS AND DIPLOMATIC NETWORK?</B>
<P>
Presenter: Zoram Ivanovic, Manager, RS/2 International
<P>
Introduction- Why we need OS? Bookmark: Summary notes, third page
<P>
of presenter Zorem Ivanovic
<P>
- Expectations of OS [Bookmark: Summary Notes, fourth page of
presenter Zoran Ivanovic]
<P>
- Business Planning [Hyperlink: Summary Notes, third page of presenter
Helga Pizzuto on 'Business and IT Plans for the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, Malta and, presentation slides by Dr. gaetan Naudi on
'The Effects of the Introduction of Informatiom Technology in
the mlatese Ministry of Foreign Affairs'
<P>
Main Points:
<P>
How to Choose the right OS?
<P>
:Hardware - combining the old with new equipment will be more
costly in the long run, than investing in all new equipment
<P>
: Users - internal, national, external
<P>
- key players [Hyperlink: summary notes, sxth page, Helga Pizzuto]
<P>
: networking - application of both local area network (LAN); wide
area network (WAN)
<P>
: Internet connection - most direct, easily available node should
be used
<P>
: security - protection should be a joint decision that is, based
on wide consultation [Bookmark: eighth page, Ivanovic]
<P>
: Available software - [Bookmark: ninth page, Ivanovic]
<P>
- [ Hyperlink: Tucker presentation]
<P>
: Budget - The larger ones budget, the more one can satisfy all
aspects of the highest expectations of OS
<P>
[Bookm,ark: sixth and final (future of OS) presentation by Ivanovic]
<P>
Evaluation
<P>
- A trained, updated human resource user and support system whichn
includes human alertness and accountability as the best basis
for security and protection, are the ideal prerequisites for sustainable
MFA OS
<P>
- Networking (LAN and WAN) is the best mechanism for an effective
MFA OS. In this context the Maltese Legal Materials Database has
the potential to be an invaluable resource tool not only for MFAs
globally, but also for relevant regional and international organisations
[Hyperlink: Maltese Legal Materials Database Homepage]. 
</BODY>

