<P>
Wednesday, November 22, 1995<HR>

<H5><A HREF="#Integrated">Integrated Resource Management</A> and
Networking: Innovative Tools for the 21st Century Diplomat </H5>

<P>
<I><B>Mrs. Jennifer Cassingena, Malta Council for Science and
Technology</B></I> 
<H5><A HREF="#Transfer">New topics on diplomatic agendas: Transfer of Technology </A>
</H5>

<H6><EM><B>Mr. Martin Spiteri, Principal, Department of Trade,
Malta</B></EM> </H6>

<H5><A HREF="#Intellectual">New topics at Diplomatic Agendas: Protection of intellectual property</A>
</H5>

<P>
<I><B>Dr. Emilie Camilleri</B></I> 
<H5><A HREF="#Embassy">Electronic Embassy: Introduction to the Internet</A>
</H5>

<P>
<I><B>Mr. Jovan Kurbalija</B></I><HR>

<H6> <B><A NAME="Integrated">Integrated</A> Resource Management
and Networking: Innovative Tools for the 21st Century Diplomat
</B></H6>

<P>
<I><B>Mrs. Jennifer Cassingena, Malta Council for Science and
Technology</B></I> 
<P>
This presentation focused on the sharing of information resources
among and between the various groups and organizations within
the State. Mrs Cassingena's argument was that the rapidity of
the changes being wrought by IT required an holistic and coordinated
approach towards the management of one's information resources.
She essentially advocated the sharing of the information resource
through an information network across sectors.
<H6><B>New topics on diplomatic agendas: <A NAME="Transfer">Transfer</A>
of Technology </B></H6>

<P>
<I><B>Mr. Martin Spiteri, Principal, Department of Trade, Malta</B></I>

<P>
The speaker was concerned with the developments in the field of
technology transfer. He covered basic concepts, looked at some
issues of concern to developing countries and the role of public
policy. His main concern was the sharing of information resources
among EU countries.
<H6><B>New topics at Diplomatic Agendas: Protection of <A NAME="Intellectual">Intellectual
</A>property</B></H6>

<P>
<I><B>Dr. Emilie Camilleri</B></I> 
<P>
The speaker dwelt on the essence of Intellectual Property Rights(IPR).
These are basically aimed at protecting inventors, creators of
literary and artistic works, whilst at the same time giving access
to the users to prevent monopoly by the former. Works and inventions
used to be protected by the Patent, Trademark or Copyright of
the producer. As protection laws and legislations became increasingly
challenged, legislators decided to come up with more methods of
protection such as Protection against Unfair Competition/Antitrust
Law, Trade Secret Law and Contractual. Dr. Camilleri reiterated
on the different national and international legislations which
govern the protection of intellectual property. These legislations
date as far back as 1952 with the Universal Copyright Convention
which was revised in 1971. She looked at the protection of software
within the existing legislative framework illustrating her argument
by the recent United States-China dispute over the production
of US copyrighted software in China.
<H6>Electronic <A NAME="Embassy">Embassy</A>: Introduction to
the Internet</H6>

<P>
<I><B>Mr. Jovan Kurbalija</B></I> 
<P>
Mr Kurbilija, the programme coordinator/organiser, introduced
participants to the use of the Internet. 
