<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jovan Kurbalija">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>Thursday, November 23, 1995</B><HR>

<P>
<B>Electronic Messaging</B> 
<P>
<B>Dr. Spackman, Management Systems Unit Ltd.</B> 
<P>
<U>CHANGING PARADIGMS</U> 
<P>
This presentation focused on the significance of electronic messaging
for Governments. The role and function of conducting government
business is changing as a result of the introduction of Information
Technology (IT) which now facilitates interaction while engendering
productivity and at the same time breaking down the barriers of
time and space.
<P>
<U>THE TECHNOLOGY OF PARADIGM SHIFT</U> 
<P>
The general acceptance of all technology follows the same curve.
There is first of all a resistance phase, evidenced by a slow
curve at the introduction of new technology followed by a slow
induction phase and then a rapid acceptance phase. The growth
begins to fall off at the point of general acceptance of the technology
as a normal way of doing things. At some point in the period of
general accepance a new technology emerges.
<P>
The question that then arises is to recognise the point at which
one should shift from the old to the new technology. This is the
paradigm shift.
<P>
<U>NEW PARADIGMS</U> 
<P>
The effects of the new paradigms have dictated new roles on governments
from one of exerting control to one of service. Governments gave
been forced to become increasingly outward looking and open to
national and public scrutiny as well as global sharing of information.
Governments now see their roles as that of facilitators and supporters
of private enterprises through the provision of appropriate environment
and infrastructures for growth.
<P>
As a result of this new role, governments have had to adopt new
managerial methods which include decentralisation of operations,
networking, sharing of organisation resources, and cooperating
with industries and business enterprises. They have equally realised
that immediacy and sharing of information through IT are necessary
tools for both survival and existence today. This has resulted
in the utilization of certain Key Technologies and their resultant
applications.
<P>
Governments have accepted the need to be part of the global electronic
network society. The use of electronic communication and information
exchange systems such as internet, with its reservations, trans-european
telematic network and the Commonwealth network for Information
Technology for Development are all part of the global network
communication.
<P>
<U>CONCLUSION</U> 
<P>
Electronic messaging has come of age because we are a networked
society . Governments worldwide must IT to the top of their political
agendas. <HR>

<P>
<B>Presentation <U>of</U> the Model of Computerisation of Ministry
of Foreign Affairs</B> 
<P>
<B>Mr. Jovan Kurbalija, Head of Unit for IT and Diplomacy.</B>

<P>
<U>MODELS FOR THE COMPUTERISATION OF THE MINISTRY OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS</U>

<P>
This presentation positioned diplomacy and the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs (MFA) within the overall scheme of international interaction
among states using the Malta experience in the application of
IT. The resultant role of the MFA therefore is that of coordinating
interaction rather than imposing actions in the implementation
of foreign policy. This necessicitated a reliance, to some extent,
on the development by and experience of the business community
in strategising and planning the computerisation of the MFA.
<P>
The strategy adopted by Malta was an initial methodology of internal
network through the linkage of desk officers by Personal Computers
connected to those of Directors while the latter were linked with
that of the Permanent Secretary. This phase resulted in the introduction
of new tools in the automation of the manual tasks of the Ministry
some of which include routine and repetitive activities , information
gathering and thinking intensive activities which have been earlier
been identified.
<P>
The experience indicates that data bases are best developed in-house
for the use of the ministry or missions and that it was important
to decide what databases should be developed in-house. These should
be based on the needs and resources of the ministry. There should
be a clear identification of the procedures, levels of access,
security, applications and software and hardware required. Sources
of other databases should be identified so as to prevent duplication
of efforts.
<P>
<U>THE ELECTRONIC POST MASTER UNIT</U> 
<P>
In furtherance of the establishment of a wider network, the role
of the MFA is further enhanced as a coordinating point of information
based on interactions between other MALTESE missions, other government
ministries, the Business Community, the Academia and other economic
operators.
<P>
In the final analysis, computerisation of the foreign ministry
should have as its objective, the ease of formulation, facilitation,
and implementation of foreign policies.<HR>

<P>
<B>Public Service Reform and IT Polciy</B> 
<P>
<B>Mr. Philip Micallef, Manager, Strategy &amp; Planning Department,</B>

<P>
<B>Management Systems Unit Ltd</B>.
<P>
The major thrust of this presentation was that any reform process
should be approached from an integrated basis. This approach however,
has to balance the strategies for short, medium and long term
planning needs.
<P>
In putting forward his proposal for an integrated approach, Micallef
using the Maltese experience, recalled certain milestone events
and stressed the need for a review of the operations of government
and the role of the Public Service Reform Commission. He underscored
the need for an Information Systems Strategic Plan (ISSP) and
the key issues that should be addressed as well as the principal
factors that were critical for the success of any reform process.
<P>
In the case of Malta, the establishment of the Management Systems
Unit ( MSU) is one of the positive by-products of a successful
ISSP serving as an agent of reform in the civil service of Malta.
In pursuing its objectives and its role in the reforn process
of the public sector, the MSU undertakes strategic planning, consultancy
services, delivery and support services.
<P>
As with all reform processes, there is in Malta, a concern about
value for money as well as opportunity cost in view of the enormity
of investment by government in the process. However, the process
continues. 
</BODY>

