<P>
GOVERNMENT FRAMEWORK FOR THE COMPUTERISATION OF DIPLOMACY: DEPLOYMENT
OF STANDARD INFRASTRUCTURES. by Ernest Stater
<P>
Mr Stater discussed the importance of architecture, which deals
with the blueprint of the infrastructure required. He emphasized
the importance of adhering to standard infrastructure in implementing
IT. He introduced the concept of Management Architecture and Models
available (scan slide 7, 8,9, 10). Inorder to make the
<P>
<U>COMNET.IT</U> by Mr. Henry Alamango
<P>
Mr Alamango provided a comprehensive talk on COMNET.IT its concept
and objective, processes and organisations and the Maltese Experience.
<P>
<U>Concept and Objective</U> 
<P>
COMNET.IT is to facilitate the Use &amp; Development of Computer
Networks for Exchange of Information &amp; Expertise. It was achieved
through networking of individuals, groups and institutions with
the purpose of accelerating social and economic development through
the <U>use of Computer networks.</U> 
<P>
<U>Processes and Organisations</U> 
<P>
Networking was accomplished through exchange of informations in
all levels; through workshops, discussion groups, publications,
training, provide skills and expertise. Networking also involves
commissioning of R&amp;D on the use of Computer Networks and other
IT, promotion of technical cooperation between various levels
of networks and institutions, eg strategic partnerships and alliances
of relevant organisations; access to information on various topics
available in the Internet.
<P>
COMNET.IT are in two levels: the Strategic and policy making bodies
- Board of Directors and its supporting Secretariat. The second
level is the Tactical and Operational level which links individuals,
task forces in administrative, management reforms, researches,
publication and education. It further links institutions and Operation
Centres, such as NCST, and MSU
<P>
COMNET provides services in five major areas; (I). Network start-up
help which includes advice and training packages and e-mail setup;
(ii). Research and publication which promotes networking in research
projects and receiving feedback from other networks, such as ICA;
(iii). Information Access which provides WAN such as to WWW, CAPAM,
and COMSEC; (iv). It also connects to other development programmes
with IT projects, such as through IDRC and UNDP etc.; (v) COMNET
also provides training activities for networking, communications
and IT applications.
<P>
<U>Governet/ MSU/Malta</U> 
<P>
The Maltese Government had adopted Governet as an administrative
service reform network which provides: E-mail connectivity, end-user
workshop, training, civil service reform dbase, thematic development
through operational centres and task forces, produce newsletters,
connet to internet and www etc.
<H2>Email Services for the Government of Malta (EGM)</H2>

<P>
Presenter:
<P>
Mr. Chris Sammut,
<P>
Technical Consultant,
<P>
Management Systems Unit Ltd.
<H5>The Email Services for the Government of Malta (EGM) is the
an ambitious 3-year project currently underway and being implemented
by MSU. This project aims to improve communications between government
departments thereby decreasing loss of time in information handling.
This project will enable the following:</H5>

<P>
*the establishment of a robust Email service for the Government,
meeting defined service levels and performance standards
<P>
*the establishment of an Email service that congforms to all Customer
needs whilst meeting change, control, security and quality management
standards
<P>
*the ability to issue &quot;Email&quot; accounts to users immeadiatly
as they become members of the Malta Government Network
<P>
*the ability to integrate to all other applications currently
running in Government
<P>
*the establishment of a national and international connectivity
service
<P>
*the ability to exploit the application and network environment
through the use of electronic messaging
<P>
*the integration of Email w ith othe electronic messaging initiatives
(e.g. EDI)
<H4>The EGM Project:</H4>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >Pilot Project  </A>(Mar.
95 - Nov 95)
<LI><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >Top Structure Project </A>(
1995/1996)
<LI><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >Project 3000 </A> (1997/1998)
<LI><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >Project Status </A> 
</UL>

<H4>Ancilliary Services:</H4>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >X.400 and Internat Mail 
</A>
<LI><A HREF="#fax_messages" >Fax Messaging </A> 
<LI><A NAME="remote_access"></A><A HREF="#remote_access" >Remote Access 
</A>
</UL>

<H4><A HREF="#general_EGM_benefits" >General Benefits of EGM 
</A><A NAME="pilot_project"></A></H4>

<P>
<B>Pilot Project (Mar. 95 - Nov. 95):</B> 
<P>
The establishment of the Email service for Government. Sites included
in the Pilot are:
<UL>
<LI>MSU ( Gattard House, Villa Protelli, Swatar Centre, Project
House)
<LI>Office of the Prime Minister (Castille)
<LI>Ministry of Foreign Affairs
<LI>Ministry of Education and Human Resources
<LI>Ministry of Gozo
</UL>

<P>
<B><A NAME="Top_structure_project">Top Structure Project</A> (1995/1996):
</B>
<UL>
<LI>Initiate Email services at the top levels accross Government
<LI>All Permanent Secretaries in all Ministries
<LI>Any Director residing on the same network
<LI>Direct support staff (Secretaries)
</UL>

<P>
<B><A NAME="project_3000">Project 3000</A> (1997/1998):</B> 
<P>
This will be the project for the establishment of an Email service
accross Government as a standard for all users formaing a part
of the Maltese Government Network (MAGNET).
<P>
<B><A NAME="project_status">Project Status</A>:</B> 
<P>
As of mid-November 1995 approximately 400 users spread over 9
sites in Malta, Gozo and even Brussels were connected to the
<P>
EGM network, having a facility to send electronic messages. Other
services introduced include the ability to send and receive fax
<P>
messages as well as Internet mail from the same user interface.
<P>
<B><A NAME="internet">X.400 and Internet Mail</A>:</B> 
<P>
The system chosen is based on industry standards and allows users
to send and receive X.400 and Internet mail from within the same
front end.
<P>
<B><A NAME="fax_messages">Fax Messages</A></B>:
<P>
Sending an electronic message to a fax machine allows communication
with anyone not having Email themselves. All messages sent to
fax machines will automatically be sent on letterheads which vary
according to the Ministry from which they originated.
<P>
<B>Remote Access:</B> 
<P>
The facility to access mail and internet services remotely via
modem is also being given to various users. This enables anyone
having a laptop/notebook or a PC at home to send and receive mail
and also use all internet services.<A NAME="general_EGM_benefits">
</A>
<P>
<B>General EGM Benefits:</B> 
<P>
EGM will bring about a number of benefits for the users in the
Ministries and Departments, not least of which will be a
<P>
consistent interface for communication, with one set of commands
for faxes, memos, file transfers, and so on. This will add value
to the Government network and enable better communication between
government departments which in turn decreases loss of time in
information handling. The impact of these benefits will ultimately
be felt even by the public in general who will receive more timely
and accurate information.
</BODY>

