<H2>Wednesday, November 29, 1995</H2>
<HR>

<H4>Programme of the day.</H4>

<H4>1.Internet</H4>

<P>
- Introduction
<P>
- E-mail
<P>
- Telnet and FTP
<P>
- Gopher, Archie, World Wide Web
<P>
- Electronic conferences
<P>
- Future tendencies in the development of the Internet
<P>
        Jovan Kurbalija
<P>
<B> 2. Administration of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs with
special emphasise on the Financial packages.</B>
<P>
         Mr. Gaetan Nauci, Director-Corporate Services, Ministry
of Foreign Affairs, Malta
<P>
<B> 3. Multimedia Use in Diplomatic activities.</B>
<P>
         Mr Dalibor Milenkovic
<P>
<B>  4. Electronic Embassy Topic: Databases</B>
<P>
         <A HREF="http://www.unige.ch/mads/">Jovan Kubalija </A>
<HR>

<P>
1. Internet
<P>
The 10th day of the workshop started with a general introduction
to Internet, E-mail, Telnet and FTP, Gopher, Archie, Electronic
Conferences and World Wide Web (WWW) by Jovan Kurbalija. The purpose
of this session was to give the participants the conceptual background
of all these IT tools.
<UL>
<LI>Internet is global network.
<LI>Node is a point of location in home country
<LI>HTTP is indicative for home page
<LI>FTP is for file transfer protocol
<LI>Gopher is file a manager allowing the reorganisation of files.
Instead of going through all the files, you go through Gopher
to get the information guideline e.g. put in GOPHER//UN ORG
<LI>Upload means sending a file or files to pre-specified destination.
<LI>Download means receiving a file or files from other location
<LI>Caveat! With Gopher you cannot bring the full text.
<LI>To find specific information on the Net, one can use search
engines such as Yahoo. This engine is based in Princeton University.
Such other engines include Lycos, CityNet, etc.
<LI>UNIX is an operating system based on a command line. It is
similar to MS-DOS, but it offers many more possibilities. This
is why it is used by most universities.
<LI>Microsoft Windows NT is a 32 bit operating system with graphic
interface.
</UL>

<P>
Moving from concepts to practice, Mr. Kurbalija informed the participants
that he had decided to create a web-site containing all the informations
about the workshop: Programme, list of participants, documents
of the workshop. The structure of this Web site was drafted. Participants
were to create homepages containing the report of each day. For
this purpose participants were divided in groups and given specific
assignments. <HR>

<P>
2. Administration of Foreign Affairs
<P>
Mr. Gaetan Nauci, Director of Cooperate Services in the Maltese
Ministry of Foreign Affairs presented his country's experience
in the introduction of IT in diplomacy. He introduced his speech
by warning the audience that the use of IT was not a panacea.
 Introducing some humour, Mr Nauci said that for some pessimists
the organisation of tomorrow will have two main actors : a dog
and a man. The dog's function will be to prevent man from using
machine and man's function will be to feed the dog. For the optimists
on the other side, machine will do everything and man will just
have to dance  and make love. 
<P>
IT is only a tool to assist in arriving at given objectives. Before
investing in IT , the Government has to address certain key questions
: Is there any need for IT ? What are the advantages of IT compared
to other means of communication ? How should IT be acquired ?
What are the costs of introducing IT and maintaining it ? What
quality is required ? Will IT bring any constraints ? All these
questions imply that a sound feasibility study should carried
out before any commitment is made. This study should give a guarantee
that the equipements are maintainable , adjustable to accommodate
the technology required, up-to-date and competitive with the latest
on the market. 
<P>
Talking from his own experience, he advised that when purchasing
equipments, one should look for the best value for money and not
necessarily the cheapest on the market.
<P>
The introduction of IT in the Maltese Ministry of Foreign Affairs
raised some fears. People were usually afraid of change and many
examples of  inconveniences of IT such as being time consuming
, insecurity, impersonal management, more paperwork, lack of visible
management..
<P>
Nevertheless, the introduction of IT has improved the financial
management of the Ministry. With the Department Accounting System(DAS)
, the Ministry now has a proper budgeting and  a timelier and
better financial management; debtors and creditors are now well
known and convenient reports can easily be obtained.
<P>
He stated finally that if IT is not hurting, then it is not working.
In this business one has to be neither over pessimist nor over
optimist but simply realist.
<P>
During the discussion Mr. Nauci explained that for security reasons,
the use of IT would not replace the traditional mailing systems(diplomatic
bag, diplomatic cargo, and courier services). On the security
of the accounting system, Mr. Nauci said that those actually giving
needed authorisations at various levels will continue to do the
same job but would use a system of passwords whereby each officer
would access only  information relevant to his or her hierarchical
position. An incription system has already been elaborated on,
in order to ensure the security and confidentiality of IT messages.
<HR>

<P>
3. Multimedia - Use in Diplomatic activities. Case Study : Hypermedia
Presentation of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta.
<P>
On behalf of the Multimedia Team of the Mediterranean Academy
of Diplomatic Studies, Mr. Milenkovic presented a hypermedia application
built in MS Viewer authoring software. It consisted of the following
main topic groups :
<P>
 A.Ministry of Foreign Affairs
<UL>
<LI>Policy-Foreign of Malta
<LI>- Organization of Maltese Ministry of Foreign Affairs
<LI>-Our Home : Palazzo Parisio Building
</UL>

<P>
This allowed the participants to have an unexpected overview of
the Maltese History.
<P>
  B. Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies.
<UL>
<LI>- Profile of the Academy
<LI>- Research and Meetings
<LI>-Degree Programmes
</UL>

<P>
   C. IT Projects
<UL>
<LI>-Course in Diplomacy
<LI>-Diplomacy and Information Technology
<LI>-Database of International Legal Documents
</UL>

<P>
Being hypermedia means that the materials consist not only of
a text and images, but also of video clips and sound pieces, organised
in an ordered fashion and connected with hyperlinks, very much
like www pages.
<P>
Hypertext concept has been explained and true hypertext features
(jump another piece of information, insertion of embedded paragraphs
, pop-up windows, graphical navigation map) were discussed in
comparison with www hypertext features.
<P>
The technical methods of acquiring graphical , video and sound
material were explained and advice for acquiring them were given
.<HR>

<P>
4. Electronic Embassy : How to create home pages.
<P>
Mr. Kurbalija informed the participants that he wanted to engage
the creation of home pages for the workshop. It was suggested
that the group as a whole would create a great website for the
workshop. Each two participants were assigned to write on deliberations
on a specific day. Methods and procedures of creating homepages,
hyperlinks, bookmarks etc. were explained . 
<P>
The participants then started creating homepages and some remained
in the computer room over midnight.
</BODY>

