<BODY>

<H2><B>THURSDAY, MAY 21st</B></H2>

<H3><B>FIRST MORNING SESSION</B></H3>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#intro1" >Paper of Professor Dietrich Kappeler: "Which are the spaces beyond national jurisdiction"  
</A>
<LI><A HREF="#discus1" >Discussion  </A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Professor Attard
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: Spaces Beyond National Jurisdiction
<P>
Professor Kappeler presents the following paper:<A NAME="intro1">
</A><HR>

<H3><B>WHICH ARE THE SPACES BEYOND NATIONAL JURISDICTION?</B>
</H3>

<H4><B>Introduction</B></H4>

<P>
The expression &quot;spaces beyond the limits of State jurisdiction&quot;
appears to imply that there is a clear limit to spaces under State
jurisdiction. This, increasingly, is no longer the case. States
exercise residual jurisdiction beyond the limits of spaces traditionally
attributed to them, and they continue to exercise jurisdiction
over objects and human beings in spaces beyond their jurisdiction
as a result of which their responsibility may be engaged by incidents
caused by such objects or human beings. Conversely, their jurisdiction
over spaces traditionally attributed to them is increasingly restricted
by rules of international law. Moreover, the physical limits of
the spaces under State jurisdiction are often in doubt, or there
are different limits for different aspects of State jurisdiction.
<P>
Before considering the spaces which essentially escape State jurisdiction,
we would thus like to briefly consider the limits of spaces traditionally
under the jurisdiction of individual States.
<H4><B>The physical limits of State jurisdiction</B></H4>

<P>
States exercise their jurisdiction over their territory which
comprises land, inland waters and, in most cases, a stretch of
territorial sea, as well as over the air space covering this land
and waters. On land and inland waters, borders delimit the jurisdiction
of one State with regard to that of others. This may also be true
on sea, as regards the jurisdiction over territorial waters of
geographically adjacent States as well as where the sea space
separating two States is so narrow as not to exceed the width
of their combined territorial waters.
<P>
Where a State faces a wider sea space the limits of its jurisdiction
are gradual. Full jurisdiction ends at the outer limit of territorial
waters<A HREF="#footnotes" >(1) </A><B>.</B> Residual jurisdiction
ends for the most part at the outer limit of the contiguous zone
<A HREF="#footnotes" >(2) </A>. However a few elements of jurisdiction
remain up to the outer limits of the exclusive economic zone<A HREF="#footnotes" >(3)  
</A>. Finally, where the continental shelf<A HREF="#footnotes" >(4)  
</A>extends beyond the limits of the exclusive economic zone of
the waters covering it, the coastal State retains jurisdiction
over that shelf in spite of the fact that the waters covering
this part are definitely beyond such jurisdiction.
<P>
The limits of the air space over a State's territory and territorial
waters with respect to outer space are in dispute<A HREF="#footnotes" >(5)  
</A>. Several theories have been advanced in this regard and,
for the purposes of codification of law, arbitrary limits have
been proposed by some but rejected by others. This means that
for different purposes the upper limit of a given State's air
space may be set at different altitudes. As regards air space
over seas beyond the outer limits of the territorial waters, it
is no longer under the jurisdiction of the coastal State<A HREF="#footnotes" >(6)  
</A>.
<H4><B>The Antarctic Continent<A HREF="#footnotes" >(7) </A></B>
</H4>

<P>
Over time many States have claimed slices of Antarctica. Such
claims are however frozen as long as the Antarctica Treaty of
1959 remains in force. As a result the legal regime of the Antarctic
Continent is determined by international law and State jurisdiction,
as far as it is allowed to exist, is determined and limited by
that law.
<P>
Most legal norms governing Antarctica are found in the Treaty
itself and in the growing number of secondary texts adopted pursuant
to it. The current list of legal texts governing Antarctica is
as follows:
<P>
- Antarctic Treaty or 1959
<P>
- Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Seals, 1972
<P>
- Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources,
1980
<P>
- Convention on the Regulation of Antarctic Mineral Resource Activities,
1988
<P>
- Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty,
1991, with annexes<A HREF="#footnotes" >(8) </A>
<P>
As can be seen from the above, the legal regime of Antarctica
extends beyond its land mass and covers a sizeable expanse of
the waters surrounding it, at least as far as protection of living
resources and the environment is concerned.
<H4><B>The Arctic Ocean<A HREF="#footnotes" >(9) </A></B></H4>

<P>
Not so long ago, this region was governed only by the international
law of the sea. However, the fact that large parts are covered
with more or less permanent ice and the discovery that, like the
Antarctic Continent, this maritime region plays a fundamental
role in the ecological equilibrium of the world, have led to the
adoption of special rules by coastal States surrounding the Arctic
Ocean and joint endeavours to further develop the nascent specific
legal regime. Besides a number of bilateral treaties dealing with
specific parts of the Ocean such as the Barents Sea and the and
the Spitsbergen (Svalbard) Archipelago<A HREF="#footnotes" >(10)  
</A><B>,</B> representatives of Arctic countries have met since
1989 to review the problems of the region and the possibilities
and means of dealing with them. In June 1991 they adopted a lengthy
document known as Arctic Environmental Protection Strategy<A HREF="#footnotes" >(11)  
</A>.
<H4><B>The High Seas<A HREF="#footnotes" >(12) </A></B></H4>

<P>
Until the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea becomes legally
binding on most maritime nations as a result of its entering into
force with regard to them, or until such time as its essential
provisions have become universal customary law, both the delimitation
and the regime of the high seas are in a state of confusion and
controversy. For the moment, only the four conventions
<P>
adopted in Geneva provide rules accepted by a seizable number
of maritime countries:
<P>
- Convention on the Territorial Sea and Contiguous Zone
<P>
- Convention on the High Seas
<P>
- Convention on Fishing and Conservation of the Living Resources
of the High Seas
<P>
- Convention on the Continental Shelf
<P>
Otherwise the only rules that are generally applicable are those
of traditional customary international law, and these mainly provide
for more or less unlimited freedom. There are of course conventions
on fishing and the protection of certain species as well as regarding
marine pollution which have been widely accepted by maritime nations
and thus provide a more acceptable legal regime in the fields
they cover:
<P>
- International Convention on the Regulation of Whaling, 1946
<P>
- International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution of
the Sea by Oil, 1954
<P>
- Treaty Banning Nuclear Weapons Tests in the Atmosphere, in Outer
Space and under Water, 1963
<P>
- International Convention Relating to Intervention on the High
Seas in Case of Oil Pollution Casualties, 1969
<P>
- International Convention on Civil Liability for Oil Pollution
Damage, 1969
<P>
- Treaty on the Prohibition of the Emplacement of Nuclear Weapons
and Other Weapons of Mass Destruction on the Seabed and Ocean
Floor and in the Subsoil Thereof, 1971
<P>
- Convention on the Prevention of Marine Pollution by Dumping
of Wastes and Other Matter, 1972
<P>
- International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from
Ships, 1973, amended in 1978
<P>
As for the air space covering the seas beyond the territorial
waters of coastal States<A HREF="#footnotes" >(13) </A>, the main
concern of legal regimes adopted so far is aviation. Only recently
have efforts been initiated to deal with the protection of this
part of the globe's air space against pollution and other undesirable
immissions. In particular, efforts to protect the ozone layer
and to prevent global warming and other forms of climate change
affect air space over the seas as much as national air spaces.
<H4><B>Outer Space<A HREF="#footnotes" >(14) </A></B></H4>

<P>
This part of the universe became relevant in legal terms only
since humanity developed the means of entering it with technical
devices and even vessels carrying human beings. As far as the
Earth's environment is concerned, only a tiny segment of outer
space can be affected by human technology. But that part, because
it interacts with the atmosphere and the Earth's surface itself,
is of course of greatest importance for the future of our globe
and its inhabitants.
<P>
Legal norms governing outer space seek to remove it and the natural
objects it contains from any attempts at accaparation by individual
States or groups of States while at the same time preventing States
from using those regions for military purposes or polluting them
with man-made objects sent into it. In both these latter regards,
international efforts so far have only been partly successful.
The main legal texts are:
<P>
- Declaration of Legal Principles Governing the Activities of
States in the Exploration and Use of Outer Space, 1962
<P>
- Treaty on Principles Governing the Activities of States in the
Exploration and Use of Outer Space, Including the Moon and Other
Celestial Bodies, 1967
<P>
- Convention on International Liability for Damage Caused by Space
Objects, 1976
<P>
- Agreement Governing the Activities of States on the Moon and
Other Celestial Bodies, 1979
<H4><B>The relevance of regimes as regards environmental protection
</B></H4>

<P>
In the case of the arctic and antarctic regions, regimes already
set up or in the making will probably allow for comprehensive
systems to regulate the protection of the local environment. However,
because these regions are very much affected by what happens elsewhere,
in particular in the seas, in the air and in outer space, the
effectiveness of such overall regulatory systems is dependent
on how environmental problems are handled in other parts of the
world.
<P>
As regards these other parts, the absence of generally applicable
legal norms seems to militate in favour of the punctual approach
followed so far. Specific aspects of environmental protection
and rehabilitation must be tackled in such a manner that rules
adopted also apply to terrestrial and celestial spaces beyond
State jurisdiction or regarding which the existence and extent
of State jurisdiction is in doubt or a subject of controversy.
Another approach which has proved useful in the past and merits
to be pursued in the future is the regional approach<A HREF="#footnotes" >(15)  
</A>. The Mediterranean is a good example in this regard<A HREF="#footnotes" >(16)  
</A>.
<P>
Its coastal States have come to realise that survival of the Sea
itself as a living entity is only possible if they act in concert,
irrespective of political, economic and military conflicts which
otherwise may divide them. One must hope that this Colloquium
will help to add new impetus to efforts currently under way to
further strengthen and develop measures to safeguard and even
rehabilitate the Mediterranean Sea. Success achieved in a geographically
limited area may also become a stimulant for similar efforts elsewhere
and even at the global level.<A NAME="discus1"></A><HR>

<H3><B>DISCUSSION</B></H3>

<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef</B> noted that scholars, lawyers and diplomats
can not work credibly if they are ignorant of how their national
government and administration function.
<P>
<B>Professor Serracino Inglott</B> asked Professor Attard whether
it would not be better to adopt a general regime of the atmosphere
as in the case of the Law of the Sea rather than a convention
on climate change alone.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard </B>agreed that a general regime should be
the objective. In Ottawa there was however a lot of hostility
to such a venture, whereas there existed some feeling of urgency
with regard to the need to protect the climate worldwide. What
was unusual in the proceedings was that the UN imposed a deadline
for the completion of a draft as a reflection of the urgency of
the situation. Existing sectorial regimes however already contain
some elements for an overall regime to be adopted later. One should
also note that the draft convention on climate change mostly contains
principles which will have to be implemented by more detailed
rules to figure in protocols.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> wondered whether one should be talking
about boundaries at all. She suggested discussion of regimes rather
than areas. She disagreed with Prof. Kappeler's statement that
boundaries are not properly defined in law as there is a lot of
solid customary law in this field.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes</B> agreed that one should not concentrate on the
definitions of boundaries but more on the regulating activities.
Even the Mediterranean Action Plan found it impossible to define
the limits of its spatial scope.
<P>
<B>Dr. Raftopoulos</B> felt that this is not a question of technicality
but responsibility. In environmental matters one should stress
the functional aspects of international law.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> also disagreed with the idea that only
pollution matters in extraterritorial spaces. Due attention must
be given to living resources.
<P>
<B>Dr. Simone Borg</B> noted that international law is still too
immature not to consider boundaries in diplomacy. We have to deal
with sovereign States and boundaries are needed to delimit areas
of jurisdiction.
<P>
<B>Professor Serracino Inglott</B> reminded the participants that
the sovereignty concept is not part of the essence of international
law. In medieval times it hardly played a role.
<P>
<B>Dr. Mifsud</B> pointed out that there are other impacts on
extra-territorial and faraway areas than pollution of air and
water. Certain technologies can unleash hurricanes over great
distances and also cause floods.
<P>
<B>Dr. Raftopoulos</B> agreed with Professor Serracino Inglott
that the concept of sovereignty was unknown to the founders of
international law.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> said that he could sympathise with the
diplomat's dilemma of having to respect sovereignty while dealing
with problems transgressing this concept. This is why he had suggested
to consider the climate a common concern of mankind, as a means
to overcome the sovereignty impasse. This was largely accepted.
<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler </B>concluded that whereas problems, concern
and solutions to be sought as regards the preservation of the
environment are universal, yet those who have to deal with them
are States still attached to their sovereignty. As their responsibility
may be engaged for areas under their control, the delimitation
of the latter remains necessary.<A NAME="footnotes"></A><HR>

<H3><B>Footnotes</B></H3>

<OL>
<LI><B>Cf. Sharma, S.P.</B> in Encyclopedia of Public International
Law 11, p. 328., <B>Churchill, R.R. &amp; Lowe, A.V</B>., The
Law of the Sea, 2nd ed., pp. 77-84.
<LI>Cf. the article of <B>Wooldridge, F</B>. in Encyclopedia,
loc.cit., vol. 11, p.78., <B>Churchill &amp; Lowe</B>, op.cit.,
pp. 116-118.
<LI>Cf. <B>Oda, S</B>., in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol. 11, p.
102,<B> Churchill &amp; Lowe</B>, op.cit., pp. 137-140,<B> Attard,
D.W.</B>: The Exclusive Economic Zone, 1987.
<LI><B>Rozakis, C.L</B>. in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol. 11, p.
88, <B>Churchill &amp; Lowe</B>, op.cit., pp. 121-123.
<LI>Cf. the article on Space Law of <B>Mateescu-Matte, N</B>.
in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol. 11, p. 303 on p. 307. Physical
criteria have mainly been used, e.g. the point where aircraft
is no longer carried by the too rarefied air or the point where
orbiting satellites are slowed down by the resistance of air particles.
Modern space technology which has produced spacecraft that can
also be used as aircraft (like the space shuttle) makes such criteria
difficult to apply. Arbitrary limits of 100 and 300 km have also
been postulated. Matters are further complicated by the claim
of equatorial countries to the space segment in which geostationary
satellites can be stationed.
<LI>Cf. <B>Hailbronner, K.</B> in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol.
11, p. 27, who notes however that the 1982 Convention on the Law
of the Sea provides for limited jurisdiction over airspace above
the contiguous zone.
<LI>Cf.<B> Wolfrum, R. &amp; Klemm, U.D</B>. in Encyclopedia,
op.cit., vol 12, p. 10, and for more comprehensive studies <B>Wolfrum,
R.</B> (Ed.), Antarctic Challenge I (1984), II (1986) and III
(1988).
<LI>International Legal Materials XXX, 1991, pp. 1455-86
<LI>Cf. <B>Kunig, P</B>. in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol. 12, p.
24, and for a recent survey of issues and policies<B> Osherenko,
G. &amp; Young, O.R</B>.: The Age of the Arctic, 1989.
<LI>Cf. the articles in Encyclopedia, loc.cit., vol. 12, by <B>Schweisfurth,
T</B>. (p. 49) and Hofman, R. (p. 352).
<LI>International Legal Materials XXX, 1991 pp. 1627-67
<LI>Cf. <B>Treves, T.,</B> in Encyclopedia, op.cit., vol. 11,
p. 136, <B>Churchill &amp; Lowe</B>, op.cit., p.
<LI>Cf.<B> Hailbronner</B>, loc.cit.
<LI>Cf. <B>Mateesco-Matte</B>, loc.cit.
<LI>Here are some examples of regional arrangements:
</OL>

<P>
1967 Convention on the Conduct of Fishing Operations in the North
Atlantic
<P>
1974 Convention on the Protection of the Marine Environment of
the Baltic Area
<P>
1979 Convention on Future Multilateral Cooperation in the Northwest
Atlantic Fisheries
<P>
1979 Convention on Future Multilateral Cooperation in the Northeast
Atlantic Fisheries
<P>
1981 Convention for Cooperation in the Protection and Development
of the Marine and Coastal Environment of the West and Central
African Region
<P>
1981 Convention for the Protection of the Marine Environment and
Coastal Area of the South-East Pacific
<P>
1981 Agreement on Regional Cooperation in Combating Pollution
of the South
<P>
East Pacific by Hydrocarbons and Other Harmful Substances in Case
of
<P>
Emergency, with 2 Protocols of 1983
<P>
1982 Regional Convention for the Conservation of the Red Sea and
Gulf of Aden Environment, with Protocol
<P>
1982 Convention on the Conservation of Salmon in the North Atlantic
Ocean
<P>
1983 Eastern Pacific Ocean Tuna Fishing Agreement
<P>
1983 Convention on the Protection and Development of Marine Environment
in the Wider Caribbean Region
<P>
A number of more recent regional conventions and arrangements
are not yet in force.
<OL>
<LI>The basic conventional texts were adopted by the Barcelona
Conference of 1976.
</OL>

<P>
They are:
<P>
Convention for the Protection of the Mediterranean Sea Against
Pollution
<P>
Protocol for the Prevention of Pollution of the Mediterranean
Sea by Dumping from Ships and Aircraft
<P>
Protocol Concerning Cooperation in Combating Pollution of the
Mediterranean Sea by Oil and Other Harmful Substances in Cases
of Emergency
<P>
The following protocols were added later:
<P>
1980 Protocol for the Protection of the Mediterranean Sea Against
Pollution from Land-Based Sources
<P>
1982 Protocol Concerning Mediterranean Specially Protected Areas.

