<H2><B>THURSDAY, 21st MAY</B></H2>

<H2><B>SECOND MORNING SESSION</B></H2>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#intro2" >Degradation and Remedies to it  </A>:-
Paper of John C. Pernetta: &quot;Environmental degradation of
spaces beyond the limits of national jurisdiction: scientific
and management considerations&quot;
<LI><A HREF="#disco2" >Discussion  </A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Dr. Boldirev
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: Scientific Aspects of Environmental Degradation
and Remedies to it
<P>
The chairman singled out the following key points to be considered
from a scientific perspective:
<OL>
<LI>What is degradation? How should one define it? For example
there are some views that climate changes do not necessarily cause
a degradation of the environment.
<LI>How do we learn about changes likely to produce a degradation
of the environment?
<LI>How can degradation be measured?
</OL>

<P>
The attempt to answer these questions raises the problem of certainty
in science that has important implications on legal administrative
and political fields.
<P>
Dr. Pernetta at the request of the Chair, made some preliminary
remarks which he later consolidated in the following study:<A NAME="intro2">
</A><HR>

<H3><B>ENVIRONMENTAL DEGRADATION OF SPACES BEYOND THE LIMITS OF
NATIONAL JURISDICTION: SCIENTIFIC AND MANAGEMENT CONSIDERATIONS
</B></H3>

<H4><B>Introduction<A HREF="#endnotes" >(1) </A></B></H4>

<P>
This paper considers only the scientific and managerial aspects
of environmental degradation of the oceans and atmosphere (including
the troposphere). Issues relating to inner and outer space beyond
the limits of the atmosphere, and space &quot;litter&quot; are
not discussed. The particular environmental problems of the Antarctic
Continent which is subject to special
<P>
treaty arrangements and where territorial claims are currently
suspended under the present Antarctic Treaty, are also excluded
from this brief overview.
<P>
At the outset it is worth noting that from a scientific or environmental
perspective the limits of national jurisdiction are artificial
boundaries which in most cases have no environmental reality.
Regulation of human activities and environmental management actions
therefore take place within a framework based on social, legal
and cultural systems which have been generally developed for purposes
other than protection of the environment and maintenance of natural
productivity.
<P>
The failure of management units to follow natural system boundaries
leads to difficulties of sustainable use and maintenance of environmental
quality. In addition legal boundaries are normally static, derived
from some spatially fixed point or recognisable, agreed baseline,
whereas environmental boundaries are generally dynamic, changing
on diurnal, seasonal, annual and longer term bases. Anthropogenic
activities in one compartment of the biosphere can and do have
impacts and consequences at considerable distance from their sources;
due in part at least to natural cycles, such as the hydrological
cycle; and processes, both physical, such as basin scale ocean
currents, and biological, such as long distance migration.
<P>
It is important to recognise in the first instance that all living
organisms affect their physical surroundings, and indeed that
the first photosynthetic organisms to appear on earth had a major
effect both on the composition of the atmosphere and the chemistry
of the oceans (Siever, 1975). Pre-life atmosphere was dominated
by water, methane and ammonia; both oxygen and tropospheric ozone
were absent. The emergence of simple photosynthetic organisms
around a billion years ago, resulted in production of atmospheric
oxygen which, by the beginning of the palaeozoic era 600 million
years ago, was at sufficiently high concentrations to permit the
evolution of consumer organisms, which fed upon the autotrophic
photosynthesing organisms. On much shorter time scales the actions
of animals affect the rate and direction of plant succession and
hence the characteristic vegetation of an area.
<P>
Changes to the vegetation in turn affect the cycling of water
and nutrients and the rate of soil formation and loss through
erosion and transport to the marine environment.
<P>
It should come as no surprise therefore that a species as abundant
and widespread as humanity impacts the environment resulting in
physical and biological changes to the world's ecosystems and
global processes. A priori one should have anticipated this. Whilst
the scale of human impacts may now appear obvious, particularly
in the light of present ideas concerning global climate change
and ozone depletion, such a possibility received little attention
in the last century when Arrhenius first postulated the idea that
man might have an effect on global climate. The relatively recent
acceptance of this idea that the scale of human-induced changes
could affect global processes and systems, reflects the rapid
improvement in scientific knowledge and the recent development
of tools and technologies which enable us to measure different
kinds of environmental change.
<H4><B>Environmental Degradation: Causes and Effects</B></H4>

<P>
In general the sources of environmental degradation of spaces
beyond the limits of national jurisdiction result from:
<P>
- Landbased activities occurring within national jurisdiction;
<P>
- Maritime and aerial transport activities;
<P>
- Living marine resource exploitation;
<P>
- Offshore mineral exploration and exploitation;
<P>
- Marine dumping and incineration.
<P>
These result in:
<P>
- Contamination and pollution;
<P>
- Changes in atmospheric composition and chemistry;
<P>
- Changes in ocean chemistry;
<P>
- Marine resource depletion;
<P>
- Global climate change and sea level rise.
<H4><B>The Atmosphere</B></H4>

<P>
Sources of change
<P>
Changes in atmospheric composition result from a variety of human,
landbased activities. Agriculture increases atmospheric methane
concentrations both from paddy rice and stock production. Global
estimates of the rate of increase in atmospheric methane demonstrate
a clear relationship with increasing human populations (UNEP,
1987). Forest clearance for alternate land use reduces the biomass
sink of carbon dioxide and if accompanied by burning results in
increased flux of carbon dioxide to the atmosphere.
<P>
Agrochemicals including both pesticides and fertilisers, applied
in intensive agriculture may enter the atmosphere and be transported
over considerable distances prior to subsequent degradation and/or
deposition on land or in the ocean. Through the processes of leaching
and runoff such chemicals may also enter the coastal ocean, ultimately
finding their way into water masses beyond the exclusive economic
zones of the originating State.
<P>
Industrial development results in an increased rate of consumption
of fossil fuels and hence an increased rate of carbon dioxide
production into the atmosphere. In addition industries create
a wide variety of atmospheric pollutant gases such as sulphur
dioxide, carbon monoxide, nitrous oxide and xenobiotic gases such
as chlorofluorocarbons together with fine particulate matter and
aerosols of varying chemical composition and toxicity.
<P>
Pathways
<P>
Whilst many of the gaseous contaminants and pollutants entering
the atmosphere have a short lifespan, being quickly dissolved
in water droplets and subsequently deposited on land or ocean,
others may have long residence times in the atmosphere, causing
changes to its overall gaseous composition and chemistry. In general
shortlived contaminants have greater impacts
<P>
within the areas of national jurisdiction, whilst longerlived
contaminants can and do impact environmental spaces beyond the
limits of national jurisdiction.
<P>
Contaminants can travel in the atmosphere either as gases or as
aerosol particles; phosphorus and all trace metals except mercury
travel in association with aerosol particles while fixed organic
nitrogen can travel as gases or as aerosols. Generally contaminant
substances are injected into the atmosphere at or near the surface
of the earth, are mixed vertically and transported hundreds to
thousands of kilometres from the site of emission. Because most
sources are generally in northern midlatitudes, most transport
is from west to east with North America contributing to the north
Atlantic and the Asian areas contributing to the North Pacific.
In the trade wind zones however transport may be from East to
West, resulting in for example transport of contaminants from
Latin America across the Pacific towards Hawaii.
<P>
The state of the atmosphere
<P>
There can be no dispute that the gaseous composition of the atmosphere
is changing, with measurable increases in radiatively active gases
such as carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide and chlorofluorocarbons
(Siegenthaler &amp; Sanhueza, 1991). Tropospheric ozone is continuing
to decrease in concentration, and these changes are observable
throughout the atmosphere. The concentration of shortlived atmospheric
contaminants and pollutants is highly variable from region to
region.
<P>
The issues of transboundary air pollution are addressed within
the context of a number of regional conventions and international
declarations. The issues of widespread changes to atmospheric
quality in terms of ozone depletion and greenhouse gas buildup
are addressed through the Vienna Convention, the Montreal Protocol
and the Climate Convention. By and large the wording of these
conventions is related solely to controlling the effects of one
State's actions or omissions on the areas under the jurisdiction
of another State.
<P>
The protection of the environmental quality of spaces outside
national jurisdiction is by and large not directly addressed in
the context of international legal agreements. Where the state
of extranational environments is addressed in the context of international
agreements, consideration is limited to human use and enjoyment
of such space and the possible consequences of human-induced changes
to such use and enjoyment.
<H4><B>The Ocean</B></H4>

<P>
Contaminants and pollutants enter the ocean via leaching, runoff
and discharge from land, via dumping and incineration, maritime
transport and offshore production and via the atmosphere (44%;
10%; 12%; 1%; &amp; 33% respectively; GESAMP, 1990).
<P>
Not all landbased sources of change in the ocean fit a strict
definition of contamination or pollution, since human activities
may merely increase the rate of natural processes such as erosion.
It is interesting to note in this regard that human landbased
activities such as forest clearance, overgrazing, mining and construction
have dramatically increased the flux of sediments to the ocean.
It has been estimated that human induced changes have resulted
in a doubling of sediment inputs into the coastal ocean since
the industrial revolution. Such a change is measurable in geological
terms. More recently widespread dam construction for hydropower
and freshwater management has had the reverse effect, reducing
sediment and nutrient inputs to coastal waters and resulting in
the collapse of fisheries such as the sardine fishery off the
Nile Delta in the Mediterranean.
<P>
Landbased sources of marine pollution
<P>
The most recent GESAMP report on the State of the Marine Environment
(GESAMP, 1990) states that dissolved nutrient fluxes in rivers
resulting from human activities are at least comparable to and
probably significantly larger than the natural fluxes (15, 1,
&amp; 100 Mt yr1 for nitrogen, phosphorus and silicon respectively).
The bulk of these are removed or retained within
<P>
estuarine and continental shelf areas under national jurisdiction
and in the case of nitrogen and phosphorus only an estimated 0.44
and 0.3 Mt yr are thought to enter the open ocean. Estimates of
trace metal contaminants entering the open ocean are variable,
depending upon the database and the method of estimation employed,
while global estimates of synthetic organic compounds are not
possible due to the complex chemistry of the substances involved
and their heterogeneous distribution.
<P>
Atmospheric pathways of marine pollution
<P>
Sources of atmospheric trace metals include natural and manmade
inputs and both global and regional estimates of emissions are
available (Pacnya, 1986). Atmospheric fluxes of trace metals to
the ocean vary regionally, depending on proximity to continental
sources, with the North Sea and Mediterranean generally displaying
the highest values and the tropical South Pacific the lowest.
In the case of mercury there is little regional variation since
mercury is transported in the gaseous phase as opposed to aerosol
particles. Organic substances of concern include pesticides and
Polychlorinated Biphenols (PCB's) and polyaromatic hydrocarbons
(PAH's). In the latter case no reliable global estimates are available.
<P>
Comparison of atmospheric and riverine inputs of pollutants
<P>
The relative importance of the two possible routes for contaminant
and pollutants entering the marine environment varies considerably
from region to region, and for many regions data are not available.
However available information suggests that river inputs are generally
more important in areas of the ocean under national jurisdiction
whilst atmospheric inputs are more important in open ocean areas.
In the case of the North Atlantic and North Sea however it would
appear that atmospheric inputs of lead, zinc and cadmium substantially
exceed those of rivers. In the case of nutrients such as nitrogen
most of the river based inputs are trapped within the coastal
zone resulting in atmospheric inputs of nitrogen to the open ocean
dominating. In contrast riverine inputs of phosphorous are more
important than atmospheric sources.
<P>
Marine based sources of pollution
<P>
Marine based sources of pollution associated with international
shipping, maritime transport and offshore mineral production have
generally declined over the last two decades although accidents
involving oil well blowouts and tanker spillages may have major
impacts locally. In general marine based sources of pollution
have their greatest impacts in coastal waters under national jurisdiction,
although oil slicks and plastic litter are found in all major
sea lanes and ocean incineration and dumping continue in some
areas.
<P>
Exploitation of marine resources
<P>
Changes to the marine environment have resulted from the use of
marine species largely for human and animal feedstuff. It has
been estimated by FAO (1985) that around 75% of all marine resources
are taken from within 9 Kilometres of the shore, and that the
present yield of around 100 million metric tonnes per annum represents
the maximum sustainable yield from presently exploited global
fisheries resources. It is further estimated that by the year
2000 the total increase in demand for fisheries products will
equal around an additional 20 Million metric tonnes annually.
To-date the impacts of harvesting marine resources have therefore
been felt in areas under national jurisdiction, and include overexploitation,
habitat degradation and changes to species composition.
<P>
Although the existence of unexploited stocks is probably limited,
the possibility that technologies will be developed for exploiting
bathypelagic fish stocks and mesopelagic stocks of squid must
be considered. In addition stocks of nontraditional species such
as krill, may be exploited at much higher levels in the future
for animal feed. Such stocks are by and large found in areas of
the open ocean outside national jurisdiction. Current open ocean
fisheries involve exploiting shallow swimming transboundary and
migratory species such as the pelagic tunas. The use of environmentally
damaging technologies, such as the massive drift nets employed
by Asian longdistance fishing fleets in the Pacific, is a cause
of particular concern to small coastal and archipelagic States
for whom such resources represent one of the major if not the
sole source of development income.
<P>
State of the open ocean
<P>
The 1989 GESAMP report on the State of the Marine Environment
states:
<P>
1. In 1989 man's fingerprint is found everywhere in the Oceans.
Chemical contamination and litter can be observed from the poles
to the tropics and from beaches to abyssal depths. But conditions
in the marine environment vary widely.
<P>
2. The open sea is still relatively clean. Low levels of lead,
synthetic organic compounds and artificial radionuclides, though
widely detectable, are biologically insignificant. Oil slicks
and litter are common along sea-lanes, but are, at present, of
minor consequence to communities of organisms living in openocean
waters.&quot; (Executive summary, GESAMP, 1990).
<P>
It further suggests that no area or resource has yet been irrevocably
damaged or destroyed and that in the immediate future increasing
rates of environmental degradation might be expected to occur
primarily within the coastal zones; that is areas within national
jurisdiction. It might be inferred from the above discussion,
however that degradation of the environmental quality of ocean
areas beyond national jurisdiction will follow as a logical consequence
of dispersal and movement of contaminants and pollutants from
coastal to off shore waters; and as a consequence of rapid industrialisation
and development increasing the flux of airborne contaminants.
<P>
Threats posed by climate change and ozone depletion
<P>
In terms of general marine productivity open ocean areas are the
watery equivalent of deserts and most marine productivity is centred
in zones of upwelling where cold nutrient rich water is brought
to the surface and in coastal zones where nutrient inputs from
landbased sources are high. The overall impact of reduction in
the marine primary productivity of open ocean areas as a consequence
of increased UV radiation is likely to be small and of greater
concern are potential impacts in the more productive coastal areas,
at high latitudes.
<P>
The relationship between changes in major ocean circulation and
current patterns and the distribution and productivity of many
stocks of marine resources is well known and demonstrated as in
the case of the Japanese sardine fishery associated with the Kyushu
current and the Peruvian anchovetta fishery associated with the
Humboldt current (Kawasaki, 1991). In the latter case the pelagic
fishery collapses during El Nino years when warm surface water
from the western Pacific dominates the offshore areas (Escobar,
et al., 1988). Quite apart from the impacts that changes to global
air temperature may have on weather and climate, changes to ocean
surface water temperatures are likely to have major consequences
for the distribution and abundance of marine organisms including
planktonic species. Changes in species composition are likely
to occur at all levels of the food chain; the magnitude and duration
of primary production in temperate and higher latitude ocean areas
can be expected to change; and, spring peaks of production may
occur earlier in the year.
<P>
Such examples suggest the changes to major ocean currents and
oceanic primary productivity, which might arise as a consequence
of global warming and could affect the distribution and abundance
of marine resources in the open ocean. It is virtually impossible
to predict with any certainty, the scale and magnitude of such
impacts at the present time.
<P>
Scientific uncertainty
<P>
Although it is now possible to identify many of the point sources
of emission or discharge and the nature of pollutants and contaminants
entering the oceans and atmosphere considerable scientific uncertainty
continues to surround the fate and flux of such materials. In
addition the identification of diffuse sources of contaminants
and pollutants, or those which disperse widely through the atmosphere
or ocean is difficult and often such sources cannot be positively
pinpointed. Although the impacts, both potential and actual of
certain contaminants can be predicted with some accuracy, in the
case of others risk assessments and potential impacts are less
certain. The impacts of global climate change and ozone depletion
on environmental quality and the productivity of natural environments
outside national jurisdiction are as yet unclear.
<P>
In part this uncertainty reflects inadequate knowledge and understanding
of the foodwebs and natural productivity of marine systems, particularly
those occurring at depth, and in part uncertainties surrounding
the actual magnitude and extent of predicted changes in physical
variables such as water temperatures and ocean current patterns.
In addition recruitment rates of currently exploited stocks of
pelagic fish, their standing stocks, turnover-times and present
harvest rates are not sufficiently well quantified to permit accurate
modelling and prediction of sustainable yields.
<P>
For planning and management purposes science is expected to produce
accurate, precise and detailed statements in answer to questions
of what if ... ? Such an expectation on the part of decision-makers
is unrealistic at the present time and would require considerable
investment in data collection, modelling and analysis. It is imperative
therefore that any management regime, whether national, regional
or international take adequate account of existing scientific
uncertainties.
<P>
In the early days of the application of Environmental Impact Assessments
for example, the stance of the developer was often based on the
attitude &quot;the environmental scientist must prove that impacts
will occur before we concede the need for action&quot;. In general
the position of environmental science confronted with the need
to make predictions is well summarised by Jackson (1982) in writing
about the impacts of a major copper mine development in New Guinea
who states:
<P>
But the facts available are very few, casting perhaps as much
light as might a crescent moon on a man searching a medicine cabinet
full of poison for an aspirin to relieve a worrisome headache
....... the experts, if they are honest, will be keeping their
fingers crossed and their environmental monitoning systems under
constant scrutiny.
<P>
Increasing recognition of scientific uncertainties not only surrounding
global issues such as climate change impacts, but single development
activities involving resource exploitation has lead increasingly
to the adoption of a
<P>
precautionary approach. This approach assumes that where impacts
are likely to occur mitigatory measures should be adopted. This
approach differs significantly from the initial approach of industry
to EIAs outlined above; the onus is now on the developer or potential
polluter to prove that impacts will not occur.
<H4><B>Scientifically based management systems</B></H4>

<P>
Modern environmental science has its roots in the scientific discipline
of ecology whose most prominent founding exponent, Charles Elton,
recognised the vital imperative of understanding the linkages
between physical, and biological processes in shaping the environment
(Elton, 1927). The approaches of the science of ecology are essentially
holistic, a recognition that the sum of natural systems is greater
than the sum of their component parts. In concentrating on what
one might call human ecology, environmental science has lost this
holistic view, the environment is seen as the product of human
interaction with natural systems, and yet humanity is not seen
as being both dependent on, and an integral part of, the system
itself. Indeed the very concepts of sustainable use, wise management,
and integrated environmental management imply that humanity &quot;controls&quot;
what happens to environments rather than recognising that human
actions &quot;affect&quot; environments and vice versa.
<P>
The inability of science to accurately model and predict future
changes to natural and manmade systems with any degree of certainty
means that in reality we can neither, manage nor control environments
as environments, but only manage and control human actions which
we know will result in some impact on the physical and biological
surroundings. The limits to these effects both in spatial and
temporal terms are thus vitally important components of any management
system.
<P>
It is possible within the biosphere to recognise boundaries and
edges between different systems. Within the boundaries of any
one system energy and matter flow and circulate, whilst considerably
less energy and matter are exchanged across the boundaries of
such ecosystems. Human actions inside such a
<P>
system, whether these involve producing pollutants, changing habitats
or exploiting a natural resource will therefore have greater impacts
within the system than on neighbouring systems.
<P>
Ideally therefore scientifically based environmental management
systems must adopt two basic philosophical approaches:
<P>
a) Holistic (sometimes inaccurately referred to as integrated)
approaches to managing, controlling and regulating all human activities
simultaneously;
<P>
b) Recognition of environmental limits and boundaries in time
and space; and consequent adoption of management units which correspond
as closely as possible to &quot;real&quot; environmental units.
<P>
Implications for future management of areas beyond the limits
of national jurisdiction
<P>
It is important to recognise that existing national and internationally
agreed boundaries generally do not correspond to the boundaries
of environmental units (see p 190 In Elder &amp; Pernetta, 1991).
Thus the areas of the open ocean beyond the 200 mile exclusive
economic zones have no real integrity as functioning environmental
systems. Migratory stocks of important fish routinely move between
areas of the high seas and areas under national jurisdiction,
whilst pollutants and contaminants are transported and mixed by
atmospheric and ocean processes which are determined by factors
such as physical topography and climate.
<P>
Most boundaries adopted for legal purposes at all levels are the
result of historical, social, cultural and other human factors,
and the consequences for environmental protection and management
are frequently disastrous. The failure of countries in the GangesBrahmaputra
catchment to jointly regulate and manage their use of the watershed
and freshwater resources has profound consequences for downstream
neighbours and illustrates the problems of
<P>
reconciling environmental management with existing legal regimes
and national interests even within small regional and subregional
areas.
<P>
Often transboundary and migratory stocks are subject to exploitation
not only within a number of EEZ's but by distant water fishing
fleets. Whilst regional fisheries bodies attempt to advise governments
on the rates of sustainable harvest they have no power to enforce
exploitation rates and not all States involved in a fishery are
necessarily part of the regional fisheries body. Sustainable management
of such stocks is only possible when all parties involved in the
exploitation of such stocks cooperate in pooling data relating
to the stock itself and in determining total harvest limits and
their allocation between users.
<P>
It is salutary to realise that most individual States are incapable
at the present time of integrating their management and use of
environments and resources over which they have sole jurisdiction.
Many of the current widespread environmental problems of coastal
zones result directly from the sectoral approaches to development
and use which have been applied in the past. As noted elsewhere
(Pernetta, &amp; Elder, in press) such approaches work, only when
one use does not conflict with another. As human populations grow,
and resource consumption increases the potential and actual conflicts
between competing sectoral interests within States result in accelerating
rates of degradation. Although the need for integrated coastal
zone management is widely recognised internationally, no country
has successfully implemented such a programme to date. This does
not augur well for international management of spaces outside
national jurisdiction.
<P>
Whilst some international agreements and declarations attempt
to control the actions and omissions of one State which affect
neighbouring States, their effectiveness is limited. Legal mechanisms
including laws, conventions, protocols and other tools for regulating
actions can only function when the parties to the instrument agree
on the principles which form the basis for the agreement. This
viewpoint contrasts sharply with that of science. The view of
science is that facts are facts and that predictions can only
be made with a certain level of probability. The level of scientific
certainty depending on the nature of the available data and the
models, it is normal for scientists to
<P>
disagree on the consequences of particular courses of action.
Indeed agreement is rare and at least in environmental science
is normally based on the absence of evidence to refute a view
or theory rather than on the existence of absolute proof that
the theory is indeed correct.
<P>
Despite assertions to the contrary, there is not an &quot;international
scientific consensus&quot; that global warming will actually occur.
There are significant dissenters from this view and it is perhaps
salutary to remember that following the cooling which occurred
in the sixties scientific attention was directed towards the possibilities
of the next ice age rather than towards the prospects of a warmer
world. What currently exists is a majority opinion that warming
will occur and although the differences between these two expressions
might appear slight and semantic they are nevertheless significant
in terms of planning and management. Consensus implies the absence
of any possible alternative future whilst majority opinion implies
that real alternatives exist which must also be taken into account.
<H4><B>Conclusions</B></H4>

<P>
Despite the various scientific uncertainties action must be taken
in the face of global changes which are to some extent predictable:
including growing human populations; industrialisation and development;
and increasing consumption of the limited resource base of the
world. All too often the scientific uncertainties are used as
a basis for not agreeing to the principles, or as a basis for
failing to take action. Regrettable as it is, science does not
operate on the basis of consensus, hence there exists a need to
integrate the development of consensus based international legal
regimes with the probabilistic approaches of environmental science.
<P>
In the case of ocean and atmospheric spaces beyond national jurisdiction
it is possible to clearly and definitively state that changes
will occur in these areas as a consequence of growing human populations
and increasing consumption of natural resources. An ultimate precautionary
approach would be to take action designed to limit both the magnitude
and the direction of such changes despite our inability to predict
the impacts and consequences which such
<P>
changes might have on the environmental quality and productivity
of such areas.
<P>
Such actions should include:
<P>
a) The minimisation of waste emissions and discharge;
<P>
b) Storage and retention of waste emissions and discharges within
the environmental compartment or system in which they are produced;
<P>
c) Restriction of human activities which increase the natural
flux of materials and energy between environmental units (e.g.
land to sea);
<P>
d) Development of appropriate management systems and regimes for
resources currently or potentially exploited in extranational
spaces; and,
<P>
e) Integrated planning of sectoral use of environments and resources.
<HR>

<H3><B><A NAME="disco2"></A>DISCUSSION</B></H3>

<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> opened the discussion saying that scientists
should give initial signals for legal action which should result
in international regulations. He emphasised the problem of adequacy
of information and knowledge for successful actions. As regards
the relations between scientific and policy spheres, he mentioned
the additional difficulty that politicians demand to have precise
options, among which they can make a choice. From the scientific
point of view this is difficult to achieve.
<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler</B> stressed the problem of clear definition
of degradation. He said that it will be necessary to distinguish
evolution and normal processes from degradation. There is also
an interaction between the problems and attempts at remedying
them. Sometimes the solution adopted produces worse effects than
the problem itself. There is an need for constant dialogue between
science and law if one is to avoid shortcomings based on lack
of coordination.
<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef </B>said that the quality of legal rules is a
necessary but not sufficient condition for effective action. Bottlenecks
delaying environmental action are very often found at the administrative
level in States. Without effective administrative implementation
at national level many valid ideas and international legal instruments
become ineffectual. For example, although the Mediterranean Action
Plan (MAP) is considered a model of regional action by UNEP, there
are a lot of difficulties as regards its implementation due to
a lack of efficient action within member States. This is often
due to the absence of means for enforcement at both national and
regional levels.
<P>
<B>Dr. Spiteri </B>noted the usefulness of environmental auditing,
especially if done jointly by lawyers and scientists.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes</B> said that the problem of implementation is real.
The Barcelona Convention for example does not provide for effective
mechanisms of control and implementation. Mostly it relies on
voluntary implementation. To some extent this is due to the fact
that sovereignty-conscious States were pushed by
<P>
popular pressure to adopt regimes that do not reflect political
and economic realities. Moreover poor countries were sometimes
persuaded to accept a regime by the promise of financial assistance,
which then failed to materialise.
<P>
<B>Dr. Raftopoulos</B> confirmed that the Barcelona Convention
only requires reporting. Contributions to the trust fund might
be a means of enforcement, but this is prevented by the permissive
language used. Nevertheless the Convention anticipates the holistic
approach now favoured by stressing the mobility of boundaries.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> noted tendencies in the regional treaties
not to use enforcement mechanisms provided for by international
law. Parties are invited to &quot;take necessary measures&quot;.
Such tendencies reflect the need to accommodate many divergent
interests. On the other hand, newer regimes provide scientific
criteria for measuring their implementation and for serving as
basis for national rules to be enacted. The Convention on the
Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) unfortunately does not provide for mutual
inspection by the parties as do earlier more specific regimes.
More prominence should be given to the cautionary principle which
aims at preventing damage rather than providing remedies when
it already has happened.
<P>
<B>Dr. Mallia </B>deplored the absence of commonly agreed definitions
of what constitutes pollution and degradation and of minimum standards
for environmental protection at national level. Degradation of
the environment should be seen as a threat rather than an impediment
to development, although this is sometimes disputed. International
agencies often compete with one another rather than cooperating
in search of a joint approach.
<P>
<B>Ms. Spiteri</B> noted that the situation has improved thanks
to the availability of new technological tools such as computers
and observation satellites. This particularly applies to extra-territorial
spaces. Computer technology can improve the exchange of information.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes </B>said that lack of information is no longer a
problem. What is often missing is the political will at State
level to take appropriate action. Lack of cooperation and competition
between international agencies and institutions is mostly due
to competition among State agencies which send out conflicting
signals.
<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef </B>also agreed that there is no lack of knowledge.
What is missing is coordinated action at national levels, based
on cooperation of all concerned agencies.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> said that there is indeed a proliferation
of treaties without effective implementation. Partly this is the
result of a lack of follow-up processes, including monitoring
systems at national and international levels. There is an important
role for science in creating such systems. Diplomats make treaties,
scientists should monitor their implementation. On the other hand,
the accumulation of declarations and resolutions constitutes a
type of international pressure that may produce action. Diplomats
should be backed by adequate environmental knowledge. UNITAR is
currently considering means of training diplomats in environmental
negotiations.
<P>
<B>Dr. Raftopoulos</B> said that vagueness of treaty provisions
reflects the need to accommodate divergent interests. It is necessary
to use a step-by-step approach, beginning with the establishment
of a global framework based on consensus. Thereafter concrete
measures of implementation, entailing strict legal obligations
can be adopted by way of protocols. Such an approach was adopted
in the case of the Barcelona Convention.
<P>
<B>Dr. Pernetta</B> noted that there area often misunderstandings
as regards scientific data. There is not a lack of information
but often the impossibility of any valid prediction that could
be derived from it. The concept of degradation implies a value
judgement which makes a scientific definition impossible.
<P>
Summing up the discussion, <B>Dr.Boldirev</B> noted the following:
<P>
1. Changes in extra-territorial spaces have occurred and can be
measured. Thus a monitoring system that would estimate what has
happened and what might happen is possible;
<P>
2. In dealing with environmental matters, a holistic approach
is needed, involving all disciplines;
<P>
3. Recommendations for national and international actions should
be worked out with those who will have to implement them;
<P>
4. Science cannot always identify who is responsible for a given
development. More reliance should therefore be put on damage prevention
and limitation through properly planned action (cautionary principle).
<A NAME="endnotes"></A><HR>

