<BODY>

<H2><B>THURSDAY, 21st MAY</B></H2>

<H2><B>FIRST AFTERNOON SESSION</B></H2>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#intro3" >Degradation and remedies to it :- Consideration of specific issues  
</A>
<LI><A HREF="#disco3" >Discussion  </A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair:</B> Dr. Boldirev
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: Scientific aspects of environmental degradation
and remedies to it: consideration of specific issues<A NAME="intro3">
</A><HR>

<P>
The Chairman opened the discussions by identifying four issues
for consideration:
<P>
1. The Open Sea
<P>
2. The Mediterranean
<P>
3. Climate as a global concern
<P>
4. Biodiversity
<P>
How much do we know about environmental state? What kind of recommendations
could be made for governments to establish international policies?
<A NAME="disco3"></A><HR>

<H3><B>DISCUSSION</B></H3>

<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler</B> asked whether the scarcity of fish on
the high seas as described by Dr. Pernetta in the morning also
applies in the Mediterranean.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> wanted to know which are the primary sources
of pollution of the high seas from the atmosphere.
<P>
<B>Dr. Pernetta </B>answered that 33% of the pollution of the
high seas comes from the atmosphere, which acts as vehicle of
pollutants produced on land. Pollutants carried by the atmosphere
are aerosols and gases. Aerosols are dropped close to coastal
areas whereas gases can be transported over vast distances. Aerosols
consitute the bulk of pollutants which means that coastal
<P>
waters are more affected than high seas. As regards fishing, the
high seas can be considered the equivalent of deserts on land.
Lack of proper nutrients does not allow important fish populations
to exist.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes </B>added that the fisheries situation in the Mediterranean
is the same as worldwide. In addition there is a great difference
between northern and southern shores of that sea. The latter are
nearly devoid of prosperous fishing grounds. Most of the species
are currently overfished, so that depletion is a distinct menace.
<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef</B> noted that as far as pollution with heavy
metals is concerned, studies show that in the Mediterranean these
are carried mostly through the atmosphere. Land-based sources
of such pollutants have been identified.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes </B>explained that present models do not allow for
proper identification of the sources of pollutants carried by
air. A great part is likely to originate from distant hinterlands,
especially from northern Europe.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> wondered whether, in view of the modest living
resources of the high seas and of the fact that most airborne
pollutants do not reach them, there is much urgency in adopting
a legal regime for them.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> pointed out that, as no country in the
Mediterranean has yet declared an exclusive economic zone, national
jurisdiction effectively ends at the limit of their contiguous
zone. This leaves a much larger proportion of high seas than on
the oceans.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> concluded from what had just been said that
the Mediterranean is more polluted than the oceans and that a
large proportion of its fishing areas are still beyond national
jurisdiction.
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes </B>explained that the Mediterranean could be considered
as a small model for the oceans. Most fish caught are migratory
species whose spawning grounds are far removed from where it is
caught and lie mostly within areas of national jurisdiction (fishing
zones). Those spawning grounds therefore need international protection.
<P>
<B>Dr. Mallia</B> wondered whether the Black Sea should be considered
as part of the Mediterranean. She also drew attention to proposals
to tax tourists in order to raise funds for protecting the marine
environment.
<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef</B> reminded participants that the Mediterranean
represents less than 1% of the global maritime surface. As there
is very little exchange of waters with the Atlantic, anything
that happens within the Mediterranean remains there for a long
time. Sometimes phenomena do occur that attract the attention
of all Mediterranean States like the 1983/4 jellyfish invasion,
whose origin was never fully determined. It is however likely
that it lies in areas beyond national jurisdiction.
<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler</B> asked for information regarding the
importance of absorption of carbon gas by the oceans.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev </B>replied that absorption capacity increases
with lower temperatures. It is estimated that about 50% of man-made
CO2 emitted into the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans. This
might change with higher temperatures. The impact and final fate
of absorbed CO2 in the oceans is not yet known. This whole issue
underlines the importance of a holistic approach to environmental
phenomena and their consequences.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> said that the IOC draft did not consider
CO2 absorption by the oceans because of the complexity of the
issue but instead only considered the impact of deforestation
on atmospheric CO2 content.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> noted that a warming of ocean temperature
could modify currents along the South American coasts to the detriment
of the hinterland. This should draw the attention of Amazonian
countries to the interest of stopping deforestation.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> as Chairman summed up the discussion by noting
that data gathered often create a need for more studies, observations
and research. It is important that responding to this need be
done in common by all concerned.<HR>

</BODY>

