<BODY>

<H2><B>FRIDAY, 22nd MAY</B></H2>

<H2><B>SECOND MORNING SESSION</B></H2>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#mark1" >Paper of Mr. Saviour Borg  </A>: &quot;The
Trusteeship Council as a keeper of the global commons for future
generations and the role of diplomacy in implementing effective
environmental protection&quot;
<LI><A HREF="#mark2" >Paper of Dr. Simone Borg  </A>: &quot;The
evolution of an International Regime on environmental protection
in the areas beyond national jurisdiction&quot;
<LI><A HREF="#reference" >References </A>
<LI><A HREF="#mark3" >Discussion  </A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Professor Birnie
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: Strategies for the Future<A NAME="mark1"></A>
<HR>

<H3><B>1. Presentation of his Paper of Mr. Saviour Borg</B></H3>

<H3><B>THE TRUSTEESHIP COUNCIL AS A KEEPER OF THE GLOBAL COMMONS
FOR FUTURE GENERATIONS AND THE ROLE OF DIPLOMACY IN IMPLEMENTING
EFFECTIVE ENVIRONMENT PROTECTION</B></H3>

<H4><B>Introduction<A HREF="#endnotes" >(1) </A></B></H4>

<P>
In a few days time, the international community will be gathering
in Rio de Janeiro to take crucial decisions on two important area
relating to the wellbeing of our planet Earth and to our societies.
The United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED),
to be held in Brazil from the 3rd to 15th June 1992, will be the
climax of a process which began in December 1989 by the adoptive
of resolution 44/228 by the Session of the United Nations General
Assembly. The main objective of the conference is to take steps
to reverse trends and establish the basis for a sustainable way
of life on the planet as we move into the 21st century.
<P>
It will be an exercise in international diplomacy to review the
overall situation of the environment and its interrelationship
with development already recognized twenty years ago at the United
Nations Conference on the Human Environment, heId in Stockholm,
Sweden, in 1972. Fifteen years later in 1987, in its report &quot;Our
Common Future&quot;, the World Commission in Environment and Development
concluded that &quot;environment&quot; and &quot;development&quot;
must be integrated to achieve &quot;sustainable development&quot;
which &quot;meets the needs of the present without compromising
the ability of future generations to meet their own needs&quot;.
<P>
UNCED, or the Earth Summit as it is now called, will hopefuIIy
bring to a conclusion a threeyear exercise on a number of issues,
mapping out a strategy with builtin mechanisms to address the
degradation of and threats to the environment and create a more
balanced and equitable sustainable development.
<P>
Among the issues which the Earth Summit will address are:
<P>
protection of the atmosphere (climate change, depletion of the
ozone layer, transboundary air pollution);
<P>
protection of land resources (combating deforestation, soil loss,
desertification and drought);
<P>
protection of freshwater resources;
<P>
protection of oceans, seas and coastal areas, and the rational
use and development of their living resources;
<P>
environmentally sound management of biotechnology and hazardous
wastes (including toxic chemicals);
<P>
prevention of illegal traffic in toxic products and wastes;
<P>
improvement in the quality of life and human health; and
<P>
improvement in living and working conditions of the poor by eradicating
poverty and stopping environmental degradation.
<P>
The Rio Conference will also consider the underling patterns which
cause stress to the environment, addressing issues like poverty
in developing countries, levels of economic growth, unsustainable
patterns of consumption, demographic pressures and the impact
of the international economy.
<P>
The Conference is expected to adopt:
<P>
the Rio Declaration that will embody basic principles that must
govern the economic and environmental behaviour of peoples and
nations to ensure &quot;our common future&quot;;
<P>
Agenda 21, a blueprint for action in all major areas affecting
the relationship between the environment and the economy, focusing
on the period up to the year 2000 and extending into the 21st
century;
<P>
the means to carry out the Agenda by making available to developing
countries the additional financial resources and environmentally
sound technologies they require to participate fully in global
environmental cooperation and to integrate environmental considerations
into development policies and practices;
<P>
agreement on strengthening institutions in order to implement
these measures; and
<P>
a Framework Convention on Climate Change. a Convention on Biological
Diversity and a Convention on Forestry
<P>
But you may ask, why have I introduced my intervention by giving
prominence to the forthcoming Rio Conference. The answer is simple.
For Malta, the agenda of the Conference presents a challenge,
a vision for the future, a compliment to the initiatives taken
by Malta at the United Nations in the protection and conservation
of the environment, that which represents today the fundamental
concept of the &quot;common good&quot;, which in the words of
the Maltese Prime Minister &quot;was traditionally considered
the object of political activity for the individual State, (and)
should now be seen to be and become the good of all human kind.&quot;
<P>
It was precisely on this concept that already twentyfive wears
ago, Malta introduced the concept of the Common Heritage of Mankind
to the international seabed and ocean floor and the subsoil thereof,
underlying the high seas beyond the limits of national jurisdiction,
and that this area would be used exclusively for peaceful purposes
and its resources would be used for the common benefit of all
mankind. The adoption of the U.N. Convention on
<P>
the Law of the See in 1982, heralded the first allencompassing
international legal regime that brought together, in an unprecedented
achievement, ideals for the conservation of the environment with
those of &quot;equitable and economic development.&quot;
<P>
In 1988, another concept was launched by Malta and accepted by
the community of nations in the UN General Assembly resolution
43/53. I am referring to the Common Concern of Mankind attributed
to Climate Change. This in turn started a process that will reach
its climax at the Rio Conference by the adoption of a Framework
Convention on Climate Change that will serve to protect global
climate for present and future generations of humankind.
<P>
A year later, Malta submitted for the consideration of the 44th
Session of the United Nations General Assembly yet another environmental
issue on the &quot;Protection of ExtraTerritorial Spaces for Present
and Future Generations&quot;. Malta's request to establish a Group
of Eminent Persons to prepare a study on this problem did not
attract sufficient attention and it was decided to adjourn the
debate on this issue. However, I am glad to point out that the
International Law Commission has taken up the matter in its consideration
of the topic &quot;International liability for injurious consequences
arising out of acts not prohibited by international law&quot;.
<P>
Professor Guido de Marco, in his capacity as the President of
the 45th Session of the General Assembly, put forward a proposal
whereby the United Nations Trusteeship Council would be given
an additional function under the United Nations Charter to hold
in trust for humanity its common heritage and its common concerns:
the environment, the protection of the extraterritorial zones,
the resources of the sea and of the seabed, the climate and the
rights of future generations.
<P>
The proposal to give additional functions to the UN Trusteeship
Council would create a complementing mechanism that would strengthen
and manage those parts of the planet that fall outside notional
jurisdiction &quot;through international cooperation and agreed
regimes for surveiIIance, development and management in the common
interest.&quot;
<P>
The ongoing discussions on environment and development should
make us pause and take a closer look at the two initiatives launched
by Malta on the protection of extraterritorial zones and the UN
Trusteeship Council which in my view merit further consideration,
perhaps even suggesting what action con be taken to promote them
further.
<H4><B>Extraterritorial spaces </B></H4>

<P>
On 24 July 1989, following a Cabinet decision to accept a proposal
put foreword by Professor David Attard, Malta, through its Permanent
Representative to the United Nations, on 11th August 1989, addressed
a letter to the SecretaryGeneral of the United Nations requesting
the inclusion in the provisional agenda of the 44th Session of
the General Assembly under item 83, entitled &quot;Development
and international economic cooperation&quot;, of a supplementary
subitem entitled &quot;Environmental protection of extraterritorial
spaces for present and future generations&quot; in the agenda
of the 44th session of the General Assembly.
<P>
In an explanatory memorandum annexed to the proposal, Doc. A/44/193
dated 17th August 1989, Malta spelled out the rationale for the
effective and comprehensive environmental protection of extraterritorial
spaces, such as the high seas, which Malta viewed as vital to
safeguard the global environment. The memorandum went on to explain
that &quot;the human urge to improve, coupled with increased population
growth, and the remarkable developments in technology may cause
substantial, irreparable environmental harm to an increasing number
of 'extraterritorial spaces'. This harm, to a greater or lesser
extent, would adversely affect all States and would prejudice
the interests which the international community as a whole may
have in the said spaces.&quot;
<P>
In view of the magnitude and complexity of the issue, the Government
of Malta, proposed that the 44th Session of the General Assembly
&quot;should request the SecretaryGeneral to establish, through
the Executive Director of UNEP, a group of eminent persons to
prepare or study, which would,
<P>
interalia, make recommendations with respect to the identification
and extent of 'extraterritorial spaces,' the state of the environment
in such spaces, the rights and duties of States and the international
community therein, and possible strengthening of relevant existing
legal instruments, and which would make proposals on how the effective
and comprehensive environmental protection of such space can be
best achieved&quot;.
<P>
On 14th September 1989, the Prime Minister of Malta wrote a letter
to a number of eminent persons requesting their personal support
in order to ensure the smooth passage of this proposal. On his
letter, the Prime Minister highlighted the fact that &quot;it
is pointless to protect the environment in areas that fall within
notional jurisdiction, but, at the same time, neglect the environmental
integrity of the ExtraTerritorial Spaces. The current state of
the High Seas, for example, demonstrates that this ExtraTerritorial
Space con no longer continue to safely accommodate all human needs
and uses. There is also the question of interdependence between
the various ExtraTerritorial Spaces.
<P>
Letters were sent. among others to, President Mugabe of Zimbabwe.
Prime Minister Lubbers of the Netherlands, Prime Minister Brundtland
of Norway, Prime Minister Rocard of France, Prime Minister Gandhi
of India. President Mubarak of Egypt and Prime Minister Mulroney
of Canada.
<P>
The Executive Director of UNEP, Dr. Mostafa Tolba, characterized
the proposal as &quot;'timely and necessary&quot; and encouraged
the Government of Malta to put forward its proposal.
<P>
The former United Nations SecretaryGeneral, Javier Perez de Cuellar,
in a letter to the Prime Minister of Malta, stated that the proposal
clearly indicated that &quot;this is an area which deserves serious
attention.&quot; He also paid tribute to the Government of Malta
for the forwardlooking approaches which it continued to take with
regard to environmental issues that are of such major concern
to the international community as a whole.
<P>
On 20th September 1989, the General Committee of the General Assembly
approved the inclusion of the item 43 part of the Agenda of the
Assembly, allocating the discussion and consideration of the issue
to its Second (Economic) Committee.
<P>
Immediately afterwards, intensive informal consultations began
on a draft text of a resolution based primarily on the points
contained in the Explanatory Memorandum presented previously.
<P>
The initial reactions to the draft were not encouraging, and as
had happened on many other instances at the United Nations, questions
were raised as to how much the proposal was valid or whether such
an initiative cost money or whether it infringed on the sovereignty
of a State. It was therefore of no surprise that Malta's proposal
did not receive that enthusiastic support which it merited even
though many others recognized that the problem did exist. After
all one still remembers the air of initial scepticism and uncertainties
that surrounded the initiatives introduced by Malta on the Law
of the Sea and on Climate Change.
<P>
During the informal consultations concerns were expressed on the
definition of the phrase 'extraterritorial spaces' as according
to certain delegations this was a completely new terminology and
because it was used in reference to a concept that was not fully
understood. Others questioned the appropriateness for the setting
up of an Eminent Persons Group, the difficulty in defining its
terms of reference and the fact that such a Group would have entered
into uncharted or sensitive and controversial waters (such as
Antarctica). The point was also made that already too many activities
and initiatives relating to the environment were being undertaken
and therefore some questioned whether the time was opportune to
open up in a new direction.
<P>
The Maltese Delegation, taking into account most of the points
raised, formally submitted to the Secretariat on 15 November 1989,
a revised draft resolution which was circulated under the reference
A/C.2/44/L.41. The Maldives, Mali, Vanuatu, Paraguay and Togo,
joined as cosponsors of the draft resolution.
<P>
The draft resolution was formally introduced in the Second Committee
of the General Assembly on 20 November 1989, after which it was
examined in informal consultations in one of the Working Groups
of the Committee chaired by one of its ViceChairmen.
<P>
Very extensive and elaborous consultations were held which could
not be concluded because of the limited time available and when
it seemed thus some form of a consensus could be reached, the
process was suspended.
<P>
The reactions following the decision not to press for action highlighted
the complexity of this topic. The consultations held helped delegations
to be enlightened in their thinking on this topic which deserved
all that attention. France, on behalf of the European Community,
stated that although the time was not ripe, the initiative was
useful and could be raised later.
<P>
In its decision 44/51, the General Assembly on the recommendation
of the Second Committee, decided to take no action on the draft
resolution &quot;at the present time&quot; thus leaving the door
open for further consideration of the Maltese initiative.
<P>
In retrospect, one can realize the difficulties faced by a number
of delegations to come to grips with the portent of the Maltese
proposal. Precisely because of the concerns raised and the questions
made that the proposal could have been addressed if the draft
text of the resolution had been successfully negotiated and adopted
giving the mandate to an eminent person group to study the matter.
<P>
The failure of the General Assembly to adapt a text on this important
subject, was fortunately enough mitigated by an important development
in the International Low Commission and in the Preparatory Committee
for UNCED.
<P>
The International Law Commission, for some time now, has been
exploring the possibility of extending the topic of liability
for acts not prohibited by international law to harm caused to
the socalled &quot;global commons&quot;. The
<P>
Special Rapporteur, Prof. Julio Barboza, in his sixth report contained
in document A/CN.4/428/Add.1, deals extensively and in detail
on the liability for harm to the environment in areas beyond national
jurisdiction that which Malta has described in its proposal to
the United Nations cis &quot;extraterritorial spaces&quot;.
<P>
Prof. Barboza's report unequivocally ascertains that &quot;we
have now reached the point where cumulative effects, on the one
hand, and major accidents, on the other, are causing harm to the
environment which is having and appreciable (significant) impact
on States, their nationals and their property&quot;. The report
continues that &quot;'the effects usually are not concentrated
in one place: they are dispersed by water or aircurrent and disappear
into the vastness of the seas or the atmosphere. The harm is intangible
for now potentially threatening, and no longer just for the environment
but also for mankind itself.
<P>
It is of great satisfaction to note that the International Law
Commission's recommendation that this question be put on its agenda
has been endorsed by the 46th Session of the General Assembly.
<P>
Yet another development which has to be recorded here, is the
text that is being considered for discussion at UNCED relating
to the sustainable use and conservation of the high seas living
resources. This proposal, if adopted, would promote rules for
management and conservation of the marine living resources on
the high seas so as not to cause damage to the living resources
within the 200mile limit of national jurisdiction of coastal States.
<H4><B>The U.N. Trusteeship Council</B></H4>

<P>
The evolvement of the environmental protection of our planet and
the fact that &quot;the atmosphere and the oceans are not the
property of any particular State or group of States, but are a
common property of all nations on the globe&quot;, should create
a new conscience to control the contamination of these environmental
resources that effect the present and future generations of mankind.
<P>
It is a well known fact that the creation of new mechanisms or
institutions within the United Nations system has always raised
eyebrows and objections particularly when it relates to their
organizational and financial structures. These in fact are the
two major stumbling blocks which have caused divisiveness among
and between participants of the preparatory process for UNCED
where agreement has still to be reached particularly on how to
finance Agenda 21 and what institutional arrangement should be
established to monitor the implementation of Agenda 21.
<P>
One therefore appreciates the timely and valid proposal put forward
by Prof. de Marco during the Fortyfifth Session of the United
Nations General Assembly and later expounded in a number of lectures
he delivered in Genoa, Moscow, Beijing, Turin and Prague, on giving
an additional role to the UN Trusteeship Council, transforming
it into a guardian and supervisor of matters &quot;affecting the
Common Heritage and Common Concerns of an everlasting humanity.&quot;
<P>
During his Presidency, Prof. de Marco emphasized the need to revitalize
the United Nations General Assembly and through it the United
Nations. In mapping out a twelve point proposal on the future
role of a Second Generation United Nations, he spoke on the Trusteeship
Council, one of the the five major organs of the United Nations
System, as follows:
<P>
&quot;I feel that with a slight correction this body can be made
to function for the common wealth of man. I suggest that from
an administrator of territories, this Trusteeship Council be converted
into a guardian and supervisor of the common heritage of mankind.
The resources of the sea and of the seabad, the climate, the environment
particularly the protection of the extraterritorial zones and
the rights of future generations, all these priceless possessions
of humanity, invoke the creation of such a Council if they are
to be handed down to future generations&quot;.
<P>
It is a known fact that the role of the Trusteeship Council has
been reduced as a result of the attainment of independence by
those NonSelfGoverning Territories administered by a number of
Member States. It will also be
<P>
recalled that the Trusteeship Council was established under Chapter
XIII of the United Nations Charter to supervise the administration
of Trust Territories and to ensure that Governments responsible
for their administration took adequate steps to prepare them for
the achievement of the Charter goals. In the early years of the
United Nations, 11 Territories were placed under the Trusteeship
System. By 1975, all except the Trust Territory of the Pacific
Islands had either attained independence or were united with neighbouring
State to form an independent country.
<P>
Furthermore, the Trusteeship Agreements of three entities of the
Pacific Islands the Federated States if Micronesia, the Marshall
Islands and the Northern Mariana Islands were terminated by Security
Council resolution 683 on 22 December 1990. While the Northern
Marianas opted for Commonwealth status in 1975, the Federated
States of Micronesia and the Marshall Islands became full Members
of the United Nations Organization. Palau the lost remaining entity
of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands has yet to determine
its future status. Until then, the United States remains the Administering
Authority of Palau reporting periodicaIIy to the Trusteeship Council.
<P>
Now that the major goals of the Council have been achieved, consideration
could be given to the adaptation of the International Trusteeship
System under Article 75 to 91 of the UN Charter to guard and supervise
'the global commons' for the benefit of all nations. The Council
could align its present procedure of considering and examining
reports on matters affecting the Common Heritage and Common Concerns
thus ensuring cooperation on those critical and uncontrolled areas
described as the global commons.
<P>
In a 1977 report prepared for UNEP/IOC, Dr. Michael Waldichuk,
a leading Canadian marine scientist, stated that:
<P>
<I>Because the atmosphere and the oceans are not the property
of any particular State or group of States, but are a common property
of all the notions on the globe, there must be some control of
contamination of these environmental resources.</I>
<P>
While it must be recognized that since Dr.Waldichuk's report national
legislation as well as international multilateral conventions
and protocols have been adopted and mechanisms established for
safeguarding what man has, since his creation, considered as his
common property, there remains a need for a central authority
or organ that can truly assess the state of these global commons,
give guidance and examine how the norms of international cooperation
in the protection and preservation of the &quot;possessions of
humanity&quot; can be advanced and promoted further.
<P>
The relevance of such an &quot;authority&quot; is further accentuated
by the fact that no agreement was reached during the preparatory
phase of UNCED on the institutional arrangements concerning the
body that will be in charge of the detailed implementation of
Agenda 21.
<P>
In the light of this impasse, Malta intends to pursue its proposal
made at the last Fourth Preparatory Committee on giving an additional
assignment to the United Nations Trusteeship Council, by promoting
this initiative at the forthcoming session of UHCED in Rio next
month. This would give a broader institutional framework which
would ensure in the longer term the political momentum envisaged
to be generated in Rio.
<H4><B>A Proposal</B></H4>

<P>
As a complementary measure to the steps envisaged to be taken
at UNCED, it is my view that further enhancement of this initiative
could be achieved if a parallel process of momentum building is
undertaken at the earliest. In this regard, I wish to propose
a three stage plan that would sensitize and amplify the proposal
on the Trusteeship Council.
<P>
The first stage would be for this Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic
Studies to prepare an indepth study on how the United Nations
Trusteeship Council could involve itself as a guardian for specific
environmental concerns. In the preparation of this study, the
assistance should be sought of UN bodies and programmes such as
UNEP, WMO, IMO, IOC and ILC
<P>
which could provide inputs at the experts and technical level.Once
this study is completed, an international expert meeting could
be organized where this report could be presented to a wider audience,
preferably composed of Government representatives. NonGovernmental
Organizations could also be involved in this review.
<P>
The third stage would be to submit the findings of the study plus
the views of Government representatives and NGO's, to a meeting
to be convened under the auspices of the United Nations and its
relevant Specialized Agencies that would prepare a final report
to the United Nations General Assembly for a decision.
<P>
This process should be seen as a translation into practical terms
of the discussions being held to revitalize and restructure the
work of the General Assembly, to reform and improve the efficiency
and effectiveness of the United Nations, particularly of its principal
organs.
<H4><B>Conclusion</B></H4>

<P>
The former Commonwealth SecretaryGeneral, Sir Shridath Ramphal,
in his address made at St. John's College in 1989, during the
inauguration of the Cambridge Lectures on Environment and Development:
Our Common Future, stated:
<P>
<I>Some international problems those concerned with the global
commons, the oceans and the ocean bed, the atmosphere, Antarctica,
which no one owns present particular problems. Unless access is
regulated in some way, rising demand will result in overuse. For
the global commons this means internationally agreed controls.
</I>
<P>
He further underlined the Brundtland Commission's message of a
&quot;common future&quot; in that the &quot;unspoken premise that
we must think of our planet not only as a world of many States
but also as the state of our one world; thus we
<P>
must be ready to nurture tomorrow's concepts of global governance,
not have them stifled at birth by yesterday's notions of national
sovereignty; that our common future may not be secured save by
the reach of enforceable law across environmentally invisible
frontiers.&quot;
<P>
The strengthened awareness and utility of the United Nations in
solving international political issues has increased the commitment
of all Member States to abide more scrupulously with the provisions
of the Charter of the Organization. While serious problems will
always exist, there is recognition that with determination and
will, collectively we can find durable solutions to these problems.
The problems faced by humanity in the protection and preservation
of our environment are many. A revitalized and restructured United
Nations can contribute towards this end. Some of its bodies may
no longer reflect the needs of present day commitments and could
be improved, if not reformed.
<P>
This is the case of the Trusteeship Council. Its effectiveness
has diminished if not disappeared. It can still play a role as
a Keeper of the Global Commons for Future Generations. Are we
ready to assist in bringing this idea to fruition?<A NAME="mark2">
</A><HR>

<H3><B>2. Presentation of her paper by Dr. Simone Borg</B></H3>

<H3><B>THE EVOLUTION OF AN INTERNATIONAL REGIME OF ENVIRONMENTAL
PROTECTION IN THE AREAS BEYOND NATIONAL JURISDICTION</B></H3>

<P>
Statehood implies absolute sovereignty over a particular territory.
Matters within the competence of states under international law
are said to belong to the &quot;reserved domain&quot; and therefore
falling under the national jurisdiction of States. During these
last three decades a number of issues were internationalised and
politicised to become part of the international agenda. In this
context the environment has become a matter of international concern
rather than pertaining solely to the domestic jurisdiction of
States. The reasons for this are mainly twofold: first the degradation
of the environment knows no national boundaries and secondly the
effects of such degradation are not only transgressing boundaries
but also evident in areas lying beyond the limits of national
jurisdiction. The international legal framework relating to the
environment has evolved rapidly since the 1972 Stockholm Conference
on the Human Environment. However conflicts of interests between
States have often been the cause of sporadic efforts and ineffectual
results.
<P>
International Environmental Law attempts to achieve an equilibrium
between the protection of the environment and the sovereign right
of States to development. This entails the creation of a system
of rights and obligations in order to strike a proper balance
of interests and, where this equilibrium is disturbed, in order
to provide an adequate remedy. Efforts to protect the environment
mainly deal with activities which have a negative effect on areas
within State jurisdiction. This is understandable due to the fact
that a large number of environmentally harmful activities are
carried out within the territories of sovereign States, effective
enforcement
<P>
jurisdiction has traditionally belonged to States and the absence
of an effective international institutional authority, have further
encouraged this tendency. This approach, however, has proved to
be highly inadequate, because environmental harm is not only transnational
in scope but has also negative effects on areas beyond the limits
of national jurisdiction.
<P>
In this context, the international community has not yet succeeded
in developing an effective international regime which recognizes
the importance of regulating anthropogenic activities that have
an adverse effect on areas beyond the limits of national jurisdiction,
whether these activities occur <U>within</U> or <U>outsidenational
borders</U>. Various treaties regulating these areas such as the
Outer Space Treaties and the Antarctica Treaties do exist; the
approach however is rather haphazard and piecemeal, despite the
interdependence which exists between these extraterritorial spaces.
<P>
Having participated in the various negotiating sessions for a
framework convention on climate change I have chosen to concentrate
particularly on this part of the environment which falls beyond
the limits of national jurisdiction but it can be said that the
legal regime established to protect climate from change can be
viewed as an example which may be adopted to safeguard other areas
lying outside territorial jurisdiction. It is therefore pertinent
to examine emerging issues during the sessions of negotiations,
to analyse whether the regime has met with expectations and where
it has failed, and what are the international regimes and mechanisms
needed for the future.
<H4><B>Sovereignty</B></H4>

<P>
Sovereignty has been the main stumbling block in achieving appropriate
commitments. Sovereignty has been defined as the State's absolute
and exclusive authority and control over its territory. The main
rule of this sovereign equality of States is the duty of each
State within the international community to refrain from intervention
in the external and internal affairs of
<P>
other States. Sovereignty is therefore an obstacle to provide
a solution to problems which are transnational in scope.
<P>
To qualify as an issue pertaining to the domestic jurisdiction
the matter has to be beyond the cognizance of International Law.
It is debatable whether a matter which falls essentially within
the domestic jurisdiction of States can be removed from the reserved
domain by becoming subject to a treaty obligation. In real fact
with respect to certain issues considered to be of international
concern by the United Nations General Assembly, the international
community has witnessed the erosion of the notion of the reserved
domain, i.e the domain of State activities where the jurisdiction
of the State is not limited by International Law. The notion of
reserved domain is relative because a State cannot plead provisions
of its Law or its deficiencies as a defence, whilst international
obligations may refer to national law as a means of describing
a status to be created and protected.
<P>
The traditional concept of sovereignty is often interpreted in
such a way as to be the root cause of marginality and residuality
of International Law as if a State owes duty to its citizens and
neighbouring States but not to the International Society as a
whole.
<P>
Sovereignty is used as a term to describe the legal personality
of a State and incidences of that personality in International
Law. In the <U>Island of Palmas Case</U>, it was held that concomitant
to the right of territorial sovereignty, a State has the duty
to protect within its territory the rights of other States. The
<U>Trail Smelter Arbitration</U><B> </B>case lays down that a
State has an obligation not to use its rights to the extent of
injuring the rights of others and the <U>Corfu Channel Case </U>confirms
this by acknowledging that the principle of sovereignty embodies
the obligation of every State not to allow its territory to be
used for acts contrary to the rights of others.
<P>
A proper balance between external competence and international
responsibility has not yet been attained. Sovereignty continues
to be abused of and used as a guise by States to avoid commitments
of an international nature. It has to be finetuned by States and
restructured to
<P>
meet with the needs of the formulation of a global strategy to
protect the International Commons.
<P>
In the preamble to the Climate Convention the parties agreed that:
<P>
States have in accordance with the Charter of the United Nations
and the principles of International law the sovereign right to
exploit their own resources, pursuant to their own environmental
policies and the responsibility to ensure that activities within
their jurisdiction or control do not cause damage to the environment
of other States or of areas beyond the limits of national jurisdiction.
<P>
This first paragraph recalls Principle 21 and 22 of the Stockholm
Declaration. These two principles were the first attempt in International
Law to regulate environmental protection on a global scale. It
took these two principles, formerly considered as &quot;soft law&quot;,
twenty years to be embodied in a multilateral convention even
if they are only preambular rather than substantive in nature:
<P>
The parties reaffirm the principle of sovereignty of States
<P>
in international cooperation to address climate change.
<P>
This second paragraph is a blanket provision which was embodied
into the preamble after considerable debate. A number of States
insisted that nothing contained in the Convention could impinge
on the notion of sovereignty and therefore it was fallacious to
consider the need to reaffirm the principle of sovereignty of
States in the convention. But most of the developing States misinterpreted
this stand as a threat to this fundamental principle, a loophole
for the richer OECD States to stultify the development of the
poorer States.
<P>
As international concern for the environment increases, States
should move away from the primacy of the community of nations
and the primacy of government in stressing the paramount duty
of the heads of all States throughout the world to guarantee the
right to live in an environment fit to
<P>
sustain life. The negotiations for a Framework Convention on Climate
Change proved that the traditional concept of sovereignty remains
a formidable obstacle when tackling problems of an international
nature. These negotiations also brought to light an even greater
challenge to the traditional concept of State sovereignty which
is likely to cause a tremendous upheaval in the evolution of modern
International Law, as certain areas, although lying within the
territorial jurisdiction of a State, were identified to be of
international environmental concern the Amazon forest for instance
is an excellent example.
<H4><B>The sources of international environmental law</B></H4>

<P>
Although International Environmental Law, is still in an embryonic
stage, there exist various rules, standards and guidelines which
regulate to some extent the protection of areas beyond national
jurisdiction. The innovative nature of these rules is that they
are also preventive and precautionary besides being responsive.
<P>
In the <U>Antarctica Treaty</U> and the <U>Treaty on Principles
Governing the Activities of States in the Exploration and Use
of Outer Space</U> the parties attempted in some way to regulate
the environment on a universal level and acknowledged that effective
results in protecting the international commons can only be achieved
through coordination between governments and other policy makers.
<P>
Two fundamental legal principles emerge from the Convention on
Marine Pollution from Land-Based Sources: first, the obligation
of States to protect the environment and their corresponding strict
liability and secondly the requirement to study alternative measures
for attaining environmental objectives.
<P>
<U>UNCLOS III</U> builds upon the principles found in the Stockholm
Declaration. It proposes a balance of interests by recognizing
that countries shall take all necessary measures &quot;to ensure
that activities under
<P>
their jurisdiction or control are so conducted as not to cause
damage by pollution to other States and that pollution arising
from incidents or activities under their jurisdiction or control
do not spread beyond the areas where they exercise sovereign rights
in accordance with the convention&quot;. The convention requires
environmental impact assessments of the potential effects, when
countries believe that their planned activities may cause substantial
pollution or harmful changes to the marine environment. It also
states that countries shall cooperate in studies, research, exchange
of information and data and in establishing appropriate scientific
criteria. It grants preferential treatment to developing countries
in the allocation of funds, technical assistance and specialized
services.
<P>
The &quot;<U>Convention on LongRange Transboundary Air Pollution
</U>&quot; defines 'air pollution' and 'long range transboundary
air pollution' for the purposes of the convention in its very
first article. These definitions are of fundamental importance
as they determine what falls within the ambit of international
law for the purposes of the convention. This definition takes
into consideration that pollution is transboundary if it has adverse
effects in other areas beyond the jurisdiction of the polluter
and:
<P>
it is not generally possible to distinguish the contribution of
individual
<P>
emission sources or groups of sources.
<P>
The Parties to the Convention based their considerations upon
the Declaration of the <U>UN Conference on the Human Environment
</U>particularly <U>Art.21</U>, namely, that States have the sovereign
right to exploit their natural resources according to their own
environmental policies and the responsibility not to cause damage
to the environment of other States or of areas beyond the limits
of national jurisdiction by activities carried out within their
jurisdiction or control. Although this ECE Convention dutifully
invokes <U>Principle 21</U> of the <U>Stockholm Declaration</U>in
its preamble, during the negotiations the Government of the Federal
Republic of Germany reportedly stipulated that preambles have
no force of law and that in any case it does not hold itself to
be legally bound by <U>Principle 21</U>. Another weakness in the
convention is the fact that it does not contain any rules on State
liability, but with regard to settlement of disputes, <U>Art.13
</U>states that:
<P>
If a dispute arises between two or more contracting parties to
the present convention as to the interpretation or application
of the convention, they shall seek a solution by negotiation or
by any other method of dispute settlement acceptable to the parties
to the dispute.
<P>
The Convention is the first international accord on air pollution,
its Chairman Johnson, hailed it as &quot;a breakthrough in the
development of International Environmental Law&quot; but not all
consider it so. It has been critizised because it includes no
mechanism for the enforcement of its terms, nor does it delineate
the responsibility of member States to abate pollution causing
damage in another State or to award compensation for such damage.
<P>
The <U>Vienna Convention on the Protection of the Ozone Layer
</U>sets down general principles and a series of specific protocols
including the <U>Montreal Protocol</U>. The Convention shows that
the international community is able to deal effectively on a multilateral
level with the serious problem of ozone depletion. in its preamble,
the <U>Vienna Convention</U> recalls <U>Principle 21</U> of the
<U>Stockholm Declaration</U>. It lays down a number of legal principles
which have come to be considered as the basics of International
Environmental Law.
<P>
Under the general obligations, the convention lays down that the
parties should cooperate in the scientific, technical and legislative
fields and requires the use of measures of a predetermined standard
to combat pollution, in particular the adoption of administrative
and legal measures. The Convention obliges countries to cooperate
in the formulation of agreed measures, standards and procedures
and with the competent international bodies. The Convention states
that developing nations are to receive information on alternative
technologies, necessary equipment, facilities for research and
training of scientific personnel. Perhaps this is one of the reasons
which made the <U>Vienna Convention</U> a success, because often
developing countries cannot afford to adopt new technical measures
due to financial problems. Receiving assistance from industrialised
countries would help them to overcome such difficulties.
<P>
The <U>Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone
Layer</U> (1987) has been described by US President Reagan as
a &quot;<U>monumental achievement</U>&quot; and by UNEP's director
Mostafa Tolba as &quot;<U>the beginning of a new era of environmental
statesmanship</U>&quot;. It is an agreement reached by representatives
of countries from every region of the world, an achievement which
has always been deemed to be impossible in the diplomatic sphere.
But it is remarkable mostly because of its preventive nature,
rather than its being simply a response to an environmental disaster
on a global scale, because the Protocol establishes international
controls on certain chemicals that destroy the stratospheric ozone
and aggravate the greenhouse effect. The parties not only established
controls with the full knowledge that these might have serious
repercussions on the chemical industry but also agreed upon target
dates for emissions reduction, even though technology has not
yet offered alternative solutions to be able to accomplish these
goals.
<P>
Amongst the emerging legal principles we find once again the recognition
of the transboundary nature of pollution. The protocol emphasizes
that States have the responsibility to prevent, minimise and eliminate
pollution from land based sources and it establishes joint programmes
of scientific and technical research to determine the best methods
of reducing pollution. As in the case of the Vienna Convention,
special attention was given to developing States. The Protocol
in fact entitles developing States to delay compliance with control
methods for ozone depletion, whilst promising them assistance.
<P>
Although at first negotiating parties were far apart in their
positions, political consensus was achieved as a result of the
development of a commonly accepted body of data and analysis.
The initial framework agreement in the <U>Vienna Convention on
the Protection of the Ozone Layer</U> provided a useful model.
It has helped governments to launch coordinated scientific research
which served as a guide to the formulation of a common policy.
The Protocol is a dynamic and flexible instrument with many innovative
features. There are provisions which represent creative resolutions
that can lead the way for the future protocols or resolutions,
<P>
such as the trigger mechanism for entry into force, fixed target
dates for reductions, twostage voting to reflect the large shareholders
interests and transitional provisions for developing countries.
The Protocol is not a static solution but an ongoing process.
The parties to the Protocol considered the risks of waiting for
more complete evidence to be too great. Consensus was achieved
irrespective of uncertainty which seems to be omnipresent in international
environmental relations. This global threat has demonstrated that
the international community is capable of accepting the common
responsibility to safeguard present and future generations and
of undertaking complex cooperative actions despite the ambiguity
of the situation. The <U>Montreal Protocol</U> serves as a prototype
for the development of new diplomatic approaches to emerging global
issues such as climate change. The problem of climate change is
even more complex than the protection of the ozone layer, because
there are more contributing factors, more wide ranging and uncertain
consequences and above all more economically painful choices.
The framework Convention on Climate Change provides for various
protocols which are likely to be negotiated in the near future.
It is through these protocols that adequate measures to protect
the climate would be formulated.
<P>
Besides these multilateral conventions there are also a number
of bilateral treaties or treaties between small groups of States.
These treaties are usually 'contractual' in nature, as opposed
to 'lawmaking treaties' which lay down rules of universal and
general application. Contractual treaties deal with special matters
concerning the parties exclusively but although not a direct source
of International law they may still have a lawmaking effect. Contractual
treaties in fact, may constitute 'particular rules' between the
parties, or contribute to the formation of international law by
establishing norms which may later crystallize into custom. Examples
of contractual treaties on pollution are: the <U>Nordic Convention
</U>signed by Scandinavian countries which provides a framework
for abatement and for compensatory relief for persons injured
by transboundary air or water pollution and the <U>Tripartite
Agreement</U> between the US, France and the UK.
<P>
Treaties concerning air pollution may be split into two groups.
There are treaties imposing obligations on a contracting party
to inform and consult with other States when activities within
the jurisdiction of the former cause harmful affects to the environment
of the latter or to the global commons. Such treaties lay down
coordinated research programs and data exchanges. An example would
be the <U>Convention on Long Range Transboundary Air Pollution
</U>(1979). Other treaties go one step further and include provisions
for settlement of disputes, such as the right of access to administrative
bodies or municipal courts. In other cases an impartial commission
is set up. This is mostly the case with bilateral agreements such
as the USCanadian Joint Commission. The <U>Vienna Convention of
the Protection of the Ozone Layer </U>(1985), belongs to the latter
category. There are two main queries regarding the position of
treaties in Public International Law. The first is whether treaties
are of legal significance only as between the parties and the
second is whether they play a role in the evolution of customary
law or whether they are declaratory of it.
<P>
It is always a problem to confirm whether a customary rule exists
or not in International Law, particularly when it comes to environmental
issues. The existence of a customary rule which regulates protection
of the environment, whether damage is transboundary or extraterritorial,
has always been traditionally based on the maxim &quot;sic utero
tuo ut alienum non laedas&quot;. However the legal nature of this
principle has at times been challenged by States as not being
legally binding. The <U>Trail Smelter Arbitration</U> case however
acknowledges this principle on the part of the sovereign State
not to use its territory to cause damage to another sovereign
State whilst the <U>Stockholm Declaration</U> adopted and elaborated
this obligation to include also these areas beyond national jurisdiction.
A useful antecedent for the formation of legal principles concerning
the protection of the environment on a global scale emerges from
the International Court of Justice (ICJ) in the <U>Corfu Channel
Case</U>, when it recognized that every State has the obligation
not to allow knowingly its territory to be used for acts contrary
to the rights of other States. In this context extra-territorial
spaces are also covered because these areas, although beyond national
jurisdiction, are the patrimony of the whole
<P>
international community. This is also the case with another emerging
legal principle, this time from the <U>Lake Lanoux Arbitration
</U>. The Tribunal in this case strived to achieve a balance between
rights and duties in international law, and established that a
State has a right to make use of its resources but not to the
extent of ignoring the rights of others.
<P>
Although in International Law the decisions of the ICJ and its
predecessor the PCIJ, are not considered as binding legal precedents
they are considered by international lawyers to be the expression
of what the most authoritative international judicial body holds
to be the position in International Law under those particular
circumstances. Even international arbitral tribunals commonly
act according to judicial principles rather than basing their
arbitral adjudications on a compromise. Besides all this, the
ICJ may play another role in the formation of International Law
through an advisory opinion sought by other UN organs. This would
prove to be very valuable particularly in the face of all the
uncertainty which surrounds the international legal principles
regulating the protection of those areas beyond national jurisdiction.
<P>
It is not my intention to enter into the merits of whether soft
law should be considered as a source of International Law or not.
Its importance however should not be undermined, particularly
during the negotiations for the drafting of multilateral treaty.
Principles embodied in UNGA resolutions or other declarations
emanating from international meetings have undisputable weight,
particularly when adopted unanimously. The notion of &quot;common
concern&quot; for example was at times attacked and a few delegations
sought its deletion from the draft text during the negotiating
sessions for a framework Convention on Climate Change. The very
fact that the climate had been unanimously acknowledged as a &quot;Common
Concern of Humankind&quot; in four consecutive UNGA resolutions
(43/53; 44/207; 45/212; 46/169), gave this new concept a special
status and, although not acknowledged as a substantive principle
of International Law, it was established as the first preambular
paragraph of the Convention on Climate Change. The Climate Convention
promotes
<P>
cooperation between States in taking measures to implement the
convention providing financial and technological assistance to
developing countries.
<P>
It has as its objective &quot;the stabilisation of greenhouse
gas concentrations in the atmosphere at a level that would prevent
dangerous anthropogenic interference with the climate system.&quot;
<P>
The convention acknowledges the need that the parties &quot;should
take precautionary measures to anticipate, prevent or minimise
the causes of climate change and mitigate its adverse effects&quot;.
<P>
It is sad to note however that one of the basic rules and standards
in International Environmental Law, namely Principle 21 and 22
of the Stockholm Declaration have been embodied only in the preamble.
The Convention does not in fact account for liability elsewhere
except in this preambular paragraph:
<P>
Recalling that States have, in accordance with the Charter of
the United Nations and <U>The Principles of International Law
</U>, the sovereign right to exploit their own resources pursuant
to their own environmental and development policies, and the responsibility
to ensure that activities within their jurisdiction or control
do not cause damage to the environment of other States or of areas
beyond the limits of national jurisdiction.
<P>
The wording of the paragraph recognizes this right and duty to
be a principle of International Law. The parties however were
reluctant to include it in Article 3 as one of the principles
to the Convention.
<H4><B>State responsibility</B></H4>

<P>
The question of liability brings us to examine the notion of State
responsibility under International Environmental Law. The responsibility
of States for internationally wrongful acts arises out of the
nature of the international legal system.
<P>
The existing sources of International Environmental Law do imply
that there is an obligation upon States to protect the environment
of other States and also of the International Commons. Even if
there is no specific positive rule forbidding environmentally
harmful activities under International law, liability results
from the nonapplication of principles of a preventive character
and the obligation of international cooperation among States for
the protection of the environment. As International Environmental
Law evolved from various sources and State practice over these
last decades, it has begun to generate subsidiary principles of
behaviour in the environmental field that tend to have substantive
implications or effects. The main subsidiary norms can be grouped
thus:
<P>
(a) The duty to conduct environmental impact studies before launching
on a project that may adversely effect the environment.
<P>
(b) The duty to inform and consult other States which may have
an interest in the effects of a particular project or activity.
<P>
(c) The duty to warn other States in the event of an accident
with environmental implications.
<P>
(d) The duty to deal on the basis of nondiscrimination and equality,
with persons, whether, they are nationals or foreigners because
they may have an interest in some environmental question either
as victims after the event, or as individuals providing suggestions
on the prevention of environmental damage.
<P>
(e) The obligation to avoid harmful environmental damage has been
said to include also the obligation to take all the necessary
measures to ensure that activities within the jurisdiction or
control of a State conform to international rules and standards
for the protection of the environment of other States or areas
beyond national jurisdiction, as they arise from various treaties
dealing with the common waters, marine areas, outer space and
Antarctica.
<P>
However, it has never been put to test as to whether these norms
are considered to be binding among States. The Chernobyl Nuclear
Accident brought to light the inadequacy of International Law
on the subject. The existence of an international obligation upon
sovereign States to refrain from carrying out activities within
and outside their jurisdiction which might have an impact on extra
territorial spaces is likely to prove rather difficult to assert.
<H4><B>The Common Concern Concept</B></H4>

<P>
It is clear that the classical issues of State to State liability
and the traditional notion of legal standing under the present
system of International Law are inadequate to deal with the devastating
damage which State activities are causing in areas beyond national
jurisdiction. Such an issue, which concerns the very existence
of mankind and life as we know it on our planet, cannot remain
part of the &quot;reserved domain&quot; of States. It is on this
basis that the UNGA Resolution 43/53 recognises specifically that
Climate Change is a &quot;Common Concern of Mankind, since climate
is an essential condition which sustains life on earth.&quot;
<P>
The Maltese initiative to request the inclusion of the item entitled
&quot;<U>Conservation of Climate as part of the Common Heritage
of Mankind</U>&quot; in the provisional agenda of the 43rd Session
of the General Assembly, attracted widespread support both at
the General Assembly plenary meeting and at the 2nd Committee,
where Malta formally presented its draft resolution.
<P>
Malta's draft resolution was adopted in the 2nd Committee, following
some amendments which were acceptable to Malta. In fact, due to
the unhappy history of the 'Common Heritage' concept a number
of States objected to the idea of classifying climate as part
of the &quot;Common Heritage of Mankind&quot;. Malta's intentions
however were not to speak in terms of appropriation of any part
of the climate but in terms of protecting it. Its ultimate aim
was to ensure that by addressing the problem of climate change
on a multilateral basis, it would lead the international community
towards the formulation of an effective and comprehensive strategy
to protect the global climate from change as a result of State
activities. The Assembly's General Committee accepted Malta's
request and on the 6th December 1988, Resolution 43/53 entitled
&quot;<U>Protection of the Global Climate for Present and Future
Generations</U>&quot; was adopted unanimously in the plenary.
<P>
The international community sustained this innovative concept
and unanimously classified climate change as a Common Concern
of Mankind in the Resolution adopted by the General Assembly.
This concept of &quot;Common Concern&quot; is closely related
to other international concepts, such as the &quot;common interest&quot;,
the &quot;international commons&quot;, the concept of &quot;intergenerational
rights&quot; and to the concept of the &quot;Common Heritage of
Mankind&quot;. The latter concept has been incorporated in a 1979
agreement governing the <U>Activities of States on the Moon and
other Celestial Bodies </U>with respect to the moon and its natural
resources and in the 1982 <U>Convention on the Law of The Sea
</U>(UNCLOSIII) with respect to certain areas of the seabed, ocean
floor and subsoil. It has been applied to areas and resources
found outside the national jurisdiction of States, as it proposes
the common management of the earth's resources. But in the political
sphere it has always caused much debate and has also been defined
as &quot;a rush consent by the hungry, to gobble down sundry goods,
spread out on somebody's else's table.&quot;
<P>
Areas beyond national jurisdiction are certainly an integral part
of mankind's heritage. Such areas are a natural resource to be
utilised by all States but which cannot be abused or tampered
with to the detriment of
<P>
present and future generations. Consequently, it cannot be left
to individual States to unilaterally decide whether, and which,
conservation measures should be taken to protect them. The concept
of &quot;Common Heritage&quot; refers to &quot;patrimony&quot;,
whilst the term &quot;concern&quot; is more general. It speaks
of concerted action rather than benefit sharing: it is closer
to &quot;interest&quot; implying a series of rights and obligations.
<P>
The Common Concern concept is traceable in various Resolutions
and Declarations of the General Assembly. The debates of the UN
Charter speak of matters considered to be of &quot;international
jurisdiction because they are of an international concern.&quot;
In 1972, the <U>Stockholm Declaration on the Human Environment
</U>expressly referred to the &quot;common good of mankind.&quot;
Two years later the UN Charter on Economic Rights and Duties stressed
that &quot;the duty of protection and preservation of the environment
for present and future generations was the responsibility of all
States.&quot; In 1980, the General Assembly adopted a resolution
on the historic responsibility of States to protect the environment
for the benefit of present and future generations. In 1989, UNGA
Resolution 44/228 convened a UN Conference on Environment and
Development and the General Assembly pointed out that environmental
problems in their global dimension required action at all levels
involving the commitment and participation of all countries.
<P>
To understand the legal implications of the Common Concern concept,
it is necessary to analyse its two component elements. The first
element of &quot;common concern&quot; could be interpreted as
an analogous to the term &quot;common interest&quot;, which means
that the issue is a matter which concerns all States and all the
members of the world community. In the <U>Barcelona Traction Case
</U>, the ICJ held that there are two types of obligations under
International law those obligations arising between a number of
States because of some agreement considered to be binding, under
international law and <I>erga omnes</I> obligations. Defining
extra-territorial spaces as a &quot;Common Concern of Mankind&quot;
(as already is the case with Climate Change) implies that, any
obligations in this respect run <B>erga omnes</B>. The International
Law Commission itself, in its draft articles on State
<P>
Responsibility recognized the superiority of fundamental interests
of the international community, stating that the breach of an
international obligation, so essential for the protection of such
interests, constitutes an international crime. In <U>Art 19</U>of
the same draft, it stated that &quot;an international crime may
result inter alia from .....a serious breach of an international
obligation of essential importance for the safeguarding and preservation
of the human environment, such as prohibiting massive pollution
of the atmosphere or of the seas.&quot; Consequently, any State
should have a standing to make representations to any other State
concerning the latter's activities and policies which are harmful
to the human environment without having to allege that it is directly
affected.
<P>
This is in fact the position with respect to legal standing in
the case of pollution of the marine environment in the convention
on Marine Pollution from Land Based sources.
<P>
Any significant pollution of the marine environment is of concern
to all States. Any State may complain to the offending State or
to an appropriate international agency, against the violation
of generally accepted international rules and standards for the
protection of the marine environment by another State or its nationals
or ships.
<P>
The possibility of development of customary rules, that with respect
to the natural resources there exists a collective interest which
may be vindicated by any State, was mentioned by the International
Law Commission in its Draft on State Responsibility. This approach
links the whole issue of environmental protection with the protection
of human rights, also classified as an <I>erga omnes</I> obligation.
States have a legal standing in such cases even if events happening
within the jurisdiction of other States do not directly involve
or jeopardise their interests.
<P>
Defining areas beyond national jurisdiction as &quot;A Common
Concern of Mankind&quot; may also be interpreted as extending
the fundamental human right to life to include the right to a
healthy and safe environment. If this
<P>
aspect of the Common Concern concept is developed, it would also
be possible to say that there is a standing to complain about
prospective harm to extra territorial spaces anywhere in the world
by means of an <I>Actio Popularis<B>,</B></I> which under International
Law is only possible under <U>Art 24</U> of the <U>European Convention
on the Protection of Human Rights</U>. Although this would create
new problems with the possibility of over-zealous complaints,
such harm would be legitimised by broadened notions of standing
which is likely to create less harm than that which results from
activities which cannot effectively be challenged unless particularised
effects on individual States are apparent.
<P>
The second element &quot;Humankind&quot;, is more controversial
as it does not only refer to vindication for a collective interest
but also to the temporal aspect of the whole concept. The term
&quot;Humankind&quot; includes all those who influence international
decision-making: that is, not only governments but also NGOs,
citizen groups, the scientific community and public opinion.
<P>
The Common Concern concept has three facets. The spatial facet
implies that there must be co-operation between all States on
matters being similarly important to all nations and to the whole
international community. Another facet is the social aspect of
the concept. All structures of society are involved in the process
of combating global environmental threats, but legal guarantees
are also required to support it. The third facet is the temporal
aspect which is two-fold. Protection of the international environment
therefore, may be classified as an inter-generation right, described
as : &quot;the right of every human being and of all human beings
taken collectively&quot;. This aspect of the Common Concern concept
evokes the idea of &quot;public trust&quot; extending protection
to the beneficiaries of future generations in terms of International
Law, but the scope of this concept comprises the protection of
the well-being and viability of future generations.
<P>
These facets of the Common Concern concept can be traced in positive
International Environmental Law. The <U>World Heritage Convention
</U>of 1972, in its preamble, refers to &quot;the heritage of
all nations of the world.&quot; The <U>Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Flora and</U>
<P>
<U>Fauna</U>, 1973 recognizes in the preamble that &quot;wild
fauna and flora... are an irreplaceable part of the natural system
of the earth which must be protected for this and the generations
to come.&quot;
<P>
The Commonwealth countries which represent one fourth of the world's
population in the <U>Langkawi Summit</U> of October 1989, expressed
their deep concern &quot;at the serious deterioration of the environment
and the threat this poses to the well-being of the present and
future generations&quot;, and also that the &quot;current threat
to the environment which is a common concern of all mankind, stems
essentially from past neglect in managing the natural environment
and resources.&quot;
<P>
The wide application of this new notion in International Law by
the world community reflects a consensus which in the long run
may reach an <B>opinio iuris</B> on the applicability of the concept
to a wide range of global environmental issues. The <U>Declaration
of the UNGA Special Session on Development and Co-operation</U>states:
<P>
The current threat to the environment is the common concern of
all. All countries should take effective measures for the protection
and enhancement of the environment, in accordance with their respective
capacities and responsibilities and taking into account the specific
needs of developing countries.
<P>
The provisions of this declaration might serve as a description
of the common concern concept as it includes important aspects
essential to the concept itself. These are:
<P>
1. Sustainable Development
<P>
2. Subsequent Rights and Obligations
<P>
3. Inter-relations between developed and developing States.
<P>
Also when one analyses all these international documents which
have referred to the concept, it is evident that the notion of
&quot;common concern of mankind&quot; serves as a consolidating
factor between all the countries of the world despite the geographical,
economic and political differences existing between them. This
obligation to co-operate should involve all countries and all
levels of concerted actions; the concept of ecological interdependence
has obtained not only spatial but also temporal parameters. The
concept of common concern should develop into a principle which
allows the international community to act on matters which are
of common interest. The principle of domestic jurisdiction can
no longer be allowed to be used as a defence when the global well-being
is at stake. The joint efforts of governments, the scientific
community, legal experts and the public opinion are of crucial
importance for the concept of &quot;Common Concern of Humankind&quot;,
such that it does not remain a vague political formula but should
be interpreted in terms of legal rights and duties, to become,
for the international community, a source of action-oriented,
binding obligations.
<P>
The object of International Environmental Law is to regulate inter-State
relations or the activities of International Organizations, which
involve environmental issues. As we have seen, the current situation
however, does not adequately regulate State activities which have
a harmful effect on the international commons. The magnitude of
the problem requires the development of innovative, legal and
conventional proposals to meet this threat facing humankind. Despite
the widespread recognition of the catastrophic effects on these
areas, this is far from an easy task, particularly because of
the very nature of International Law.
<P>
The methodology adopted to implement these goals must be framed
in such a way as to gain the adherence of a large number and a
balanced range of States. It might include the adoption of uniform
standards or choosing flexible approaches to accommodate developing
States, such as transferable allowances and incentives.
<P>
Environmental damage to areas beyond national jurisdiction would
affect directly or indirectly all strata of society. The international
community therefore should continue to strive towards a broader
understanding of the issue, so as to facilitate the adoption and
the implementation of an effective and comprehensive legal strategy
intended to protect the very existence of life on earth.
<P>
&quot;No species has ever had such wholesale control over everything
on earth, living or dead as we now have. That lays upon us, whether
we like it or not an awesome responsibility. In our hands now
lies not only our own future, but that of all other living creatures
with whom we share the earth.&quot;<A NAME="reference"></A><HR>

