<BODY>

<H2><B>FRIDAY, 22nd MAY</B></H2>

<H2><B>FIRST AFTERNOON SESSION</B></H2>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#mark1" >Beyond the National Jurisdiction  </A>:-
<I>Paper of Professor Dietrich Kappele</I>r
<LI><A HREF="#mark3" >Discussion  </A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Dr. Raftopoulos
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: The Diplomacy of protecting the Environment beyond
National Jurisdiction<A NAME="mark1"></A><HR>

<H3><B>Professor Kappeler presents his paper on the subject:</B>
</H3>

<H3><B>Introduction</B></H3>

<P>
 Spaces beyond the limits of national jurisdiction are land, sea
and air spaces as well as outer space<A HREF="#endnotes" >(1)  
</A>. The only land space within this category is the Antarctic
continent, removed from national jurisdiction by the Antarctica
Treaty. Sea spaces are the maritime surfaces beyond territorial
seas and the seabed beyond the limits of the continental shelves.
Air space beyond national jurisdiction is the air space covering
land and sea spaces which are themselves beyond national jurisdiction.
The delimitation of outer space with regard to air space is controversial.
<P>
Antarctica has no territorial neighbours, so that protection of
its land surfaces, territorial waters and continental shelf is
obviously a common concern, not only of the parties to the Antarctica
Treaty but of humanity in general, as shown by the impact of the
yearly ozone hole that appears over the continent. Favourable
and unfavourable impacts on the maritime and atmospheric environment
tend to circulate freely, being carried onwards by maritime currents
and atmospheric winds. They may produce their effects in places
far removed from their origin.
<P>
In consideration of the above, it is obvious that no single State,
no bilateral arrangement will be able to protect the environment
beyond the limits of national jurisdiction with any effectiveness.
Only multilateral treaties imposing rules on all concerned, which
often means the international community as a whole, can provide
effective protection. This is why the Rio Conference has been
convened. Within the framework of global conventions, regional
and subregional arrangements may be possible and even desirable,
and within both global and regional or subregional frameworks
bilateral arrangements may make sense or even be necessary. One
may mention here the need of environmental clauses in bilateral
agreements on development cooperation.
<P>
The diplomacy of protecting the environment beyond the limits
of national jurisdiction is thus inevitably multilateral. This
means that the possibilities of individual actors, even big and
powerful ones, are limited. Moreover, the subject-matter, i.e.
protection of the environment, means that cooperation of all concerned,
the willing and the unwilling ones, is required to produce the
desired result. It will not suffice to draft nice treaties that
States will be free to ratify or accede to or not. Only treaties
which will be ratified or acceded to by all concerned will be
useful. This will immensly complicate negotiations. There are
of course treaties that anyone will accept to become party to
because they only contain pious recommendations and platitudes,
are so vague that eveyone can interpret provisions to suit his
purposes, and lack any form of sanction. This again will not do
because the desired effect will then not be achieved. One might
as well forgo the costly exercise of convening lengthy international
conferences if the result will only be this.
<P>
This paper considers the preparation of environmental negotiatons,
the required briefs, the actual negotiating process as well as
the drafting of the treaties which should be the outcome of such
negotiations. This is being done with special regard to the issue
at hand: the protection of the environment beyond the limits of
national jurisdiction.
<H4><B>Preparing the negotiators</B></H4>

<P>
Grounding in international law
<P>
Desirable negotiators for our purpose should have a solid background
in international law, both as regards its principles and with
respect to State practice, past and present. This is essential
if treaties negotiated are to be easy to understand, do not offer
loopholes permitting escape from apparently binding obligations,
and provide the kind of sanctions that will ensure their actual
implementation by the parties. Special familiarity will be required
with international environmental law, as this is the branch of
international law which deals with the regulation of often complex
scientific issues in a manner that will ensure that they are properly
handled.
<P>
Grasp of scientific issues
<P>
Understanding of the scientific issues involved is also essential.
This does not only mean some failiarity with terms like global
warming, climate change, ozone layer depletion, maintaining of
biological diversity. It means that the issues and principles
underlying these terms must be grasped, so that even the course
of scientific argumentation can be understood. Of course there
will be scientists available as consultants<A HREF="#endnotes" >(2)  
</A>. But their explanations and advice can only be understood
if the diplomat has a general grasp of the issues discussed. Scientific
knowledge is all the more important as there are constant attempts
at demagogic obfuscation, using isolated bits of evidence to defeat
those who argue for concerted action against such matters as the
use of fluorcarbones or the uncontrolled escape of sulphuric gases.
One should be able to understand for example how the penetration
of volcanic dust from the recent Pinatubo eruption produces a
layer that prevents the effects of global warming from being felt
for several years.
<P>
Understanding of environmental diplomacy
<P>
Just as essential as familiarity with underlying scientific issues
is an understanding of the peculiarities of environmental diplomacy.
There is for instance the economic aspect. Countries are asked
to forgo some types of development because of its negative ecological
implications. Tropical countries are asked to stop overexploiting
and burning down virgin tropical forests and to replant exploited
surfaces in the interest of humanity, much of which lives a lot
better than their own population. Conversely, developed countries
are asked to pay penalties for having spoilt the world environment
during their own industrialisation, including where, at the time
of the damage, the environmental implications were unknown. Proposing
and promoting global solidarity that would lead to a generally
acceptable form of burden sharing must be done in a manner that
carries conviction and does not sound like lofty preaching of
the rich to the poor or the supposedly victimised poor to the
rich.
<P>
Levels and institutions of training
<P>
This raises the question of how environmental diplomats can be
produced and traditional diplomats can be re-trained for the purposes
of environmental diplomacy. The answer varies to some extent according
to the countries concerned. In a country like the USA, Japan or
even China, where a great number of persons should be trained
or re-trained, national programmes can easily be worked out with
the cooperation of a plethora of qualified scientific and ordinary
training institutions. At the other end of the scale, we have
small and often poor countries, mini-States with minuscule diplomatic
services. These must obviously rely on facilities elsewhere to
enhance the preparedness of their diplomats. But would the Maldives
wish to train their diplomats in the USA, when their basic concern
is physical survival of their islands in rising sea-levels, whereas
the US economy is likely to be very adversely affected by most
measures taken to reduce global warming?
<P>
It is in this context that regional training facilities can be
of considerable help. They can produce programmes tailored to
the requirements of different types of countries. At the same
time, by bringing together diplomats from a number of countries
with similar or differing outlooks and aims, they can provide
a forum for sharpening conceptions and approaches or, in the case
of diplomats from countries with different outlooks, they can
help to promote better mutual understanding. With time permitting,
certain types of negotiations could even be simulated, thus providing
participants with better views of the kind of outcome that could
be expected. UNITAR is currently seeking to promote programmes
for the training of environmental negotiators. In so doing it
is considering the differing needs and goals of various types
of countries and attempting to devise different programmes tailored
to their needs. This could be pushed further by deliberately bringing
together diplomats from countries with very antagonistic approaches,
e.g. least developed tropical countries and OECD countries of
some size. In a quasi-academic environment such diplomats could
for once speak freely and, after having done so, seek ways of
solving their differences without having to consider narrow national
interests.
<H4><B>Briefs</B></H4>

<P>
National briefs
<P>
When preparing for any type of environmental negotiation, each
country has of course to prepare a national brief. This brief
will contain as precise as possible an assessment of the country's
ecological situation, of the causes of degradation and damage,
of the type of action required and the forseeable cost of preventing
further damage and remedy existing degradation. It will then consider
how the required action can be exercised. In the case of the environment
beyond the limits State jurisdiction, any action that can be expected
to be effective will have to be multilateral. In closed or nearly
closed regional environments such as the Mediterranean, considerable
useful
<P>
action can be taken by the regional countries. Regarding global
issues, only the combined efforts of the international community
as a whole can bring remedy. This means that national briefs must
assess the manner in which alliances could be forged to promote
common causes and defeat negative policies of others. Sub-briefs
must be prepared for the requisite preliminary bilateral and multilateral
contacts aiming at building up the necessary alliances.
<P>
Let's take the extreme case of the Maldives. Their very physical
survival is menaced by the expected rise of the sea level as a
result of the global warming process. The only remedy available
to the country itself would be the building of dykes to protect
their islands from being flooded into extinction. Such remedial
action is clearly beyond the means of the country. Thus the national
brief would have to stress the need of strong measures to slow
down and possibly reverse global warming with a view to delaying
and possibly even preventing the previsible catastrophe. Allies
would have to be sought among countries with similar plights such
as Bangladesh and the Netherlands. Together such particularly
menaced countries might conceivably persuade a larger group of
others that it would be cheaper for the international community
in the long run to slow down, stop and reverse global warming
than to face the exorbitant costs of remedial action once the
sea level starts to rise significantly.
<P>
Group briefs
<P>
In environmental matters the traditional groups, mainly based
on geography, will often not have a common interest. If we take
Africa, its landlocked countries are not affected by the rising
of the sea level. Only adverse effects of global warming on their
climate would awaken their concern with the phenomenon. Thus new
alliances, cutting accross traditional groupings and whose members
may be spread far apart over the globe are likely to emerge. To
be able to properly influence the outcome of global negotiations,
such groups will have to consider the likely attitude of other
groups and the kind of deals that might induce them to accept
compromises they would otherwise
<P>
reject. Such alliances are already in evidence as the Rio Conference
approaches and preparatory work progresses. But one wonders whether
this evolution is always clearly understood and assessed. Let's
just consider a few likely groups whose common interest is strongly
affected by global issues:
<P>
a. Countries with tropical forests: All of them are over-exploiting
these forests and in many the forests will disappear in the near
future. These countries are asked to cut down or even forgo exploitation
in the interests of humanity, which needs those &quot;global lungs&quot;
to prevent further accumulation of carbon dioxide and possibly
reduce the atmospheric content of this gas in the long run. These
countries feel that they are in a strong position to exact compensation
from the rest of the world and particularly the rich countries.
They tend to overlook the fact that the destruction of their forests
is an ecological desaster for themselves and their own population
as well and represents in many cases the loss of one of the country's
major sources of income.
<P>
b. Archipelagos and continental countries with low coastal
<P>
areas, especially if these are heavily populated, have a vital
<P>
interest in fighting global warming and the consequent rise of
<P>
sea levels. Some such countries are quite rich while others
<P>
are among the poorest of the world. But the group cannot
<P>
produce remedial action on its own. It must persuade all
<P>
other nations that the effects of global warming will be
<P>
generally more detrimental than helpful. In so doing the
<P>
group must realise that certain regions of the globe might
<P>
actually benefit from global warming and that the countries
<P>
situated there may be aware of this or will certainly realise
<P>
the fact in the very near future.
<P>
c. Countries menaced by desertification may or may not derive
some benefit from global warming. In most cases, desertification
is likely to be accelerated and such countries would be natural
allies of group (b). The others are likely to form a separate
group asking for consideration of the economic impact for them
of forgoing possible benefits of global warming.
<P>
d. A number of countries, both among the most developed (USA)
and those embarking on forced development (China) are reticent
to fight global warming. They do not feel that it would affect
them very adversely, wherea the cost of measures to reduce production
of carbon dioxide and sulphurous gases by their often oldfashioned
industrial complexes are staggering. Some of the countries in
this group may be able to make a case for obtaining economic compensation
for undertaking remedial action. Others, especially the USA, clearly
cannot do so.
<P>
So far we have considered alliances that are likely to be stable.
But there will be others that will only form occasionally around
a specific issue like the conservation an protection of fishing
grounds, whereas their members may very much disagree on others.
Developing countries are claiming that much of the emissions which
are causing global warming are the result of early industrialisation
processes in Europe and North America, at a time when they themselves
had no industries whatsoever and were mostly under-populated.
As a result they feel that industrialised countries should first
pay for the damage they did in the past before asking for economic
sacrifices by the developing world. But in matters of conserving
tropical forests or preventing global warming these same developing
countries are often far from united.
<H4><B>The negotiating process</B></H4>

<P>
The overall approach
<P>
Regulating the environmental situation beyond the limits of national
jurisdiction is a job that can only be tackled collectively. Thus
all countries concerned must seek solutions that they can accept
together. This means that only the package approach used initially
at the Law of the Sea Conference can be conducive to positive
results. Consequently, regulations must be adopted as a whole
and by consensus, so that each individual State and each group
of States with a special interest has a stake in their being actually
observed.
<P>
Stages of negotiation
<P>
Experience of the last few years shows that there is much merit
in having environmental issues identified for regulation discussed
at a preliminary meeting of expert scientists. Their findings
help environmental diplomats to identify those points where the
present state of the art allows precise conclusions and projections
and those where a degree of uncertainty or even wide divergence
among opinions still exist. In this last case it may be preferable
to postpone the drafting of rules until more certainty has been
achieved, as negotiators will inevitably exploit divergent scientific
conclusions in order to pick out the ones which favour their country's
or their group of countries' position.
<P>
The preparation of the Rio Conference shows us that a meeting
of plenipotentiaries empowered to sign a convention should be
presented with drafts that enjoy wide consensus achieved in earlier
discussions at expert level. In this context we mean by &quot;experts&quot;
diplomats rather than scientists. These diplomats would be the
ones who have undergone special training and briefing before tackling
their task, whereas the plenipotentiaries at the final conference
may be more inclined to consider national political and economic
<P>
interests rather than the future of humanity as a whole. What
negotiating may have to be left to the final conference would
be the conciliation of powerful group interests that may imply
concessions that diplomatic experts at preparatory meetings were
in no position to make.
<P>
Especially because of the last point mentioned, the final conference
should be composed of delegations enjoying full powers to adopt
decisions with far-reaching effects for their country. This may
mean that senior decision-makers and even heads of State or government
would have to attend. Moreover they should be made aware of the
need of having gone through sufficient consultation and concertation
processes at home to be able to make instant decisions which would
have a good chance of being ratified by the competent organs in
their country.
<H4><B>Drafting of treaties</B></H4>

<P>
Substantive clauses
<P>
Such clauses must be clear and unequivocal. Differences cannot
be allowed to be overcome by adopting wordings that can be interpreted
by each side according to its own views and preferences. Where
&quot;soft law&quot; is stated it must be done in such a manner
as to ensure that States will actually have to do their utmost
to implement its exhortations and cannot get away with claiming
that their economic situation or other circumstances prevent them
from taking any meaningful action.
<P>
Particular care must be given to ensure that versions in different
languages actually say the same thing. Evasive action by relying
on divergent interpretations based on a lack of concordance of
treaty texts must be effectively prevented.
<P>
The texts adopted by the final conference must be definitive and
complete. The practice followed by the Law of the Sea Conference
which gave the drafting committee a mandate to review certain
clauses should not be followed. The issues at hand when dealing
with the global environment are of such momentous importance that
many countries would be only too happy to seize the pretext of
a drafting committee having gone beyond its mandate to go back
on their consent. And this of course would in most cases make
the whole attempt at regulation useless.
<P>
Only reservations discussed and approved by the final conference
should be permitted and participating States should openly undertake
not to seek to dilute their undertaking by means of additional
reservations or so-called interpretative statements. The convention
should clearly state that such reservations and statements will
be without effect.
<P>
Dealing with disputes
<P>
Problems that must be settled may consist of bona-fide difficulties
in interpreting certain clauses inspite of careful drafting, or
they may arise out of conflicts of interests which are not rooted
in the text of the treaty as such. Especially in the last case,
much freedom should be available to parties to the conflict for
attempting to settle it by negotiations and other consensual means.
It is less clear whether allowance should be made for agreements,
where a conflict has been finally decided, to amend the content
of this decision, as this may give rise to new problems and controversies.
<P>
Because rules governing the global environment or the environment
of a specific region can only work when all countries concerned
abide by them, conventions setting up such rules must provide
for a compulsory way of settling disputes if all other attempts
at solving them have failed. Moreover provision must be made for
enforcement should one of the parties concerned refuse to abide
by the compulsory settlement.
<P>
Entry into force
<P>
Countries which are not happy with the final outcome of a negotiation
dealing with the global environment may be tempted to delay ratification
or accession in order not to have to implement clauses they dislike.
Such attitudes are much in evidence as reagrds the Law of the
Sea Convention. It might be useful therefore to attempt to introduce
clauses in treaties dealing with the environment beyond the limits
of State jurisdiction which provide for provisional implementation
pending ratification or accession. In this manner all countries
concerned would have to begin with the implementation of at least
the essential clauses of the treaty, however long they delay the
constitutional steps leading to full expression of consent to
be bound.
<H4><B>Concluding remarks</B></H4>

<P>
More even than when attending meetings of collective organs of
international institutions, State representatives negotiating
rules for the protection of the environment beyond the limits
of national jurisdiction are in fact participants in a community
effort. All national and group interests must be subordinated
to the overall purpose of the negotiation and interpreted in that
light. This, for many diplomats, will constitute a considerable
departure from attitudes they are accustomed to and for which
indeed they may have been specifically trained. But only the full
realisation and conscious adoption of the required attitude will
allow any significant progress in adopting rules that preserve
the global environment for future generations.
<P>
In order to produce the kind of diplomat required for environmental
negotiations curricula for training and re-training diplomats
at national and regional levels must be reviewed. A habit must
be generated to consider the common interest before examining
in what way national interests can be made to fit into it. This,
to some extent, is quite a reversal of traditional attitudes.
But as the world shrinks, multilateral diplomacy will ever more
resemble parliamentary deliberations at the national level.
<P>
Very small and/or poor countries face a special plight when entering
important environmental negotiating processes. They cannot afford
to use the sort of experts that are found in delegations of larger
countries, and indeed such experts may not be available to them
even at home. The only remedy to their plight appears to be a
sharing of resources. Small countries with similar problems, e.g.
small island States, could share the same experts and thus have
access to the kind of knowledge easily available to bigger delegations.
<A NAME="mark3"></A><HR>

<H3><B>DISCUSSION</B></H3>

<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef</B> suggested that in addition to legal and scientific
knowledge the environmental diplomat should also have a sound
knowledge of the workings of his country's administrative processes
in order to be credible. This means that the diplomat should have
had a long exposure to those processes.
<P>
<B>The Chairman</B> wondered if managerial knowledge might help
in this regard.
<P>
<B>Dr. Pernetta</B> pointed out the difficulties of getting sound
scientific advice. In his view even the International Panel on
Climate Change (IPCC) is flawed by the fact that scientists sitting
on it are government appointees and thus not free to voice scientific
views which clash with government policies. Moreover scientists
hardly ever agree fully on the scientific interpretations of a
phenomenon. Their advice should therefore be considered in the
light of these shortcomings. In the case of small countries not
only the diplomats but also the experts must have a broad knowledge
as specialists in a number of fields may not be available. It
is regrettable in this regard that the Alliance of Small Island
States is content to be a pressure group. It should consider setting
up a scientific secretariat able to properly brief its various
members.
<P>
<B>Mr. Mifsud Bonnici</B> noted that environmental diplomacy may
already be an obsolete notion, as current emphasis is on combining
environmental and development issues.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> wondered what the alternative to government-appointed
scientists on the IPCC would be. States will only act on advice
proffered if their governments are involved. Even when acting
only as a pressure group, the Alliance of Small Island States
has managed to exert much more influence than the combined weight
of its members would normally warrant. As regards experts working
for small delegations, one must realise that there are already
firms and other entities which simultaneously advise a considerable
number of delegations, as a result of which they may influence
the outcome of a negotiation more than might be acceptable.
<P>
<B>Mr. Micallef</B> felt that good relations between the administrations
in charge of environmental matters and the foreign service would
be a considerable asset.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> wondered whether instead of concentrating
on the training of diplomats one should not consider more urgently
the provision of diplomatic knowledge to the numerous officials
of technically competent ministries which tend to lead delegations
to international conferences on their own.
<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler</B> noted that this issue has already been
given a lot of consideration by training institutions, some of
which have admitted officials from ministries very active in external
relations to their regular training courses. Another possibility
is the organisation of short ad hoc training courses tailored
to the needs of individual ministries.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> noted that when the moment comes to negotiate
issues of key importance for States, diplomats tend always to
replace experts from other administrations who might previously
have attended discussions.
<P>
<A NAME="endnotes"></A><HR>

<H3><B>Footnotes</B></H3>

<OL>
<LI>For details consult my paper on &quot;Spaces beyond State
Jurisdiction&quot; submitted to he Colloquium.
<LI>Even this may not be true for delegations from very small
and/or very poor countries, so that their negotiators must be
able to fully grasp scientific issues involved and to discuss
them meaningfully with experts of other delegations.
</OL>
<HR>

