<BODY>

<H2><B>TRENDS AND RISKS OF SECURITY IN THE MIDDLE EAST</B></H2>

<P>
<B>Brig.Gen. (Res.) Aryeh SHALEV</B>
<P>
Senior Research Fellow, The Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies
<P>
Tel Aviv University, Israel<HR>

<P>
The subject I will speak about is Security Trends and Risks in
the Middle East in the coming 5-10 years. Being a researcher at
the Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies at Tel Aviv University,
whatever I will say represents only my personal opinion.
<P>
It could be said, in general, that security trends derive from
the following main factors: major opposing interests between countries;
the concept of rival states about legitimate means to be used
to attain objectives, including or excluding the use of force;
the regional and world political ambiance; the internal situation
and the degree of instability in rival states. In this context:
will the Arab countries continue to be ruled by totalitarian regimes
or a change will occur towards democratization? Will fundamentalism
expand and take over the control in Arab states bordering Israel
or be considerably weakened and even curbed?
<P>
Before referring to possible future security trends in the Middle
East and risks to Israel, I would like to present three basic
elements which affect the Israeli concept, and which should be
kept in mind:
<P>
(a) The ratio between the active ground forces of Israel and the
Arab confronting states is quite negative and disadvantageous
for Israel (1:6). This fact is relevant since it could be estimated
that in the case of a war in the Middle East, Arab states will
do their utmost to start it by surprise, when the balance of the
ground active forces is in their great advantage, before Israel
mobilizes its reserve forces (the time necessary to mobilize and
deploy the reserve is 48 hours).
<P>
(b) A second important factor is the topographic one: the West
Bank dominates the coastal plan, which is the essential part of
Israel, the width
<P>
of which is only 13 to 30 kilometers. The Golan Heights dominate
the Hule and the Gordan valleys adjacent to the international
border.
<P>
(c) Potential acts of war against Israel could be initiated and
carried out either by neighbouring or by distant Arab Muslim states,
or by both. The Israeli population was already, during the Golf
War, a target for surface-to-surface missiles launched by Iraq.
Thus, the towns in the depth of Israel turned into a front line,
and this may be the case in the future as well. Distant countries
that posses long range surface-to-surface missiles are Iraq, Iran
and Libya.
<P>
In my opinion, risks of war in the Middle East will continue in
the coming years, until the peace develops to one between the
peoples, to a peace like the one existing between France and Germany;
countries that repeatedly fought but reached the stage of no risk
of war where the border has no more any security significance.
<P>
I am optimistic about the chances of peace between Israel and
the Arab countries but cannot ignore potential security risks.
With respect to security risks, I will refer to risks and not
try to make a forecast of events. I will analyze the risks deriving
from the development or regression of one major variable which
is the Arab-Israel Peace Process. I see three possible scenarios:
<P>
<U>First-</U>The assumption in this scenario is the worst possible
case, i.e. that the parties involved were unable to overcome the
serious difficulties and obstacles they encountered in the negotiations.
Thus no peace agreement was reached, the negotiations failed and
broke, and the status returned to one of tension and possible
struggle. If this scenario takes place, the risks could be:
<P>
(a) Progressive rise of tension and the military option of another
Arab-Israeli war in which the key country will be only Syria but
other neighbouring states will take part as well. The war could
include the
<P>
launching of long range surface-to-surface missiles (by Iraq,
Lybia and Iran) against civilian and probably also military targets
in the depth of Israel.
<P>
(b) Struggle over sensitive issues, like water resources and water
rights.
<P>
(c) Activation of terror against Israel and Israelis.
<P>
(d) Weakening of the Israeli-Egyptian peace structure and even
gradual regression towards a state of no peace and no war.
<P>
<U>Second</U>- Even in the positive case that a peace treaty is
signed between Israel and Syria as well as between Israel and
the P.L.O., a long period will be required to implement the various
difficult articles and phases and to develop the peace to a stage
of peace between the peoples. During this long period serious
difficulties could hamper the execution of the agreement, and
be followed by limited use of force. The risk during this long
period could be :
<P>
(a) Activation of terror against Israel and the Israelis, the
main targets being Jerusalem, Israeli settlements in the West
Bank and Gaza, and terrorism from Lebanon, controlled by Syria,
in the northern part of Israel.
<P>
(b) A military confrontation having a limited or a vast objective.
The purpose being either to gain territory or to get hold of stronger
cards.
<P>
<U>Third</U>- The more optimistic scenario, assuming that peace
treaties were signed with Jordan, Syria and the Palestinian and
the peace developed, after years, into peace between the peoples.
It seems that extremist organizations and states would act to
sabotage the execution of the agreement. The risks could be:
<P>
(a) Launching of long range surface-to-surface missiles by Iraq,
Lybia and Iran.
<P>
(b) Activation of terror against Israel by Palestinian extremists
and Hisballah from Lebanon. 
</BODY>

