<H2><B>ISRAEL'S VISION ON THE GOALS AND PRINCIPLES OF THE REGIONAL
SECURITY AND ARMS CONTROL PROCESS </B></H2>

<P>
<B>Ambassador Eytan BENTSUR</B>
<P>
Senior Deputy Director
<P>
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Israel<HR>

<P>
This paper document presents Israel's vision on the long term
goals for the Regional Security and Arms Control process, as well
as its outlook on the principles that ought to govern the process.
This document was formulated in response to the request contained
in the concluding statement of the Moscow meeting of the RS&amp;AC
Working Group, September 1992. The policy presented in the document
was recently approved by the Israeli Cabinet.
<H4><B>1. The Vision</B></H4>

<P>
Israel's vision of the long-term goals for Middle-East RS&amp;AC
process, as approved by the Israeli Cabinet, states as follows:
<P>
The prophets of Israel gave voice to the message of universal
peace and disarmament to which the Jewish people held fast and
which is Israel's heritage:
<P>
<I>They shall beat their swords into ploughshares, and their spears
into pruninghooks; nation shall not lift up a sword against nation,
nor shall they learn war any more. But they shall sit every man
under his vine and under his fig tree, and none shall makethem
raid</I>. (Micah 4, 3-4)
<P>
The goal Israel constantly aspires to is to live in a region in
which full and lasting relations of peace prevail, based on reconciliation
between peoples, good neighborliness, open borders, and trust
among nations.
<P>
Thus will our region know stability and security; dangers of war
and horrors of mass-destruction will be removed, and all states
and nations of the region will be able to live in peace and dwell
safely.
<P>
Such relations of peace will put an end to arms races, and lead
to reductions, to the minimal levels required for national self-defense,
of standing military forces, defense expenditures and conventional
arms.
<P>
In the spirit of the global pursuit of general and complete disarmament,
Israel will endeavor, upon the establishment of relations of peace,
that the states of this region should jointly establish a mutually
verifiable zone free of ground-to-ground missiles, of chemical
weapons, of biological weapons, and of nuclear weapons.
<P>
From its very inception, the state of Israel appealed to its neighbors
to enter with it into such peace; this is and has been Israel's
aspiration, and will remain its vision for generations to come.
<H4><B>2. Principles</B></H4>

<P>
The RS&amp;AC process is an integral part of the Middle East peace-making
effort commenced in Madrid in October 1991. The goal of the RS&amp;AC
Working Group of the multilateral peace process is to complement
the bilateral talks by seeking multi-lateral cooperative responses
to security problems in the region.
<P>
The Government of Israel believes that the RS&amp;AC process ought
to be guided by the following principles:
<P>
a) RS&amp;AC and Conflict Resolution
<P>
The conflicts that permeate the region have been the root causes
of arms races and wars in the area. RS&amp;AC regimes will, therefore,
prevail only once the causes of conflict are satisfactorily resolved.
Thus, the Middle
<P>
East RS&amp;AC process can only achieve its practical goals if
the process is in step with the peace-making efforts aiming at
ridding the region of the conflicts afflicting it. Accordingly:
<P>
i) The RS&amp;AC process should reflect the common interest of
all the peoples of the region to co-exist in peace, free of threats
of war.
<P>
ii) Progress in RS&amp;AC will be made in parallel with the resolution
of conflicts and commensurately with the evolution of relations
of peace between the states and peoples of the region.
<P>
iii) RS&amp;AC will have to be supportive of the Arab-Israeli
peace-making process and will inevitably be influenced by it.
<P>
b) Security<B> </B>and Stability
<P>
i)<B> </B>The RS&amp;AC process should enhance the security of
each and every one of the states taking part in it, thereby contributing
to the stability and security of the region as a whole.
<P>
ii) All steps and measures to be adopted throughout the RS&amp;AC
process must be designed so as to increase the overall stability
of the region. At no point should they diminish the security of
any state, nor should they allow at any stage of the process any
state or group of states to misuse them in order to acquire a
military advantage over others.
<P>
iii) Each state is entitled to an equally high level of overall
security, defined as freedom from threats to its existence and
well-being. Thus, structural vulnerabilities, should be compensated
for by offsetting capabilities; requirements of self-defense and
deterrence of aggression are the only legitimate needs that should
be taken into consideration in the RS&amp;AC process.
<P>
iv) Every state in the region has the right to define the threats
it considers relevant to its own security. All states of the region
will be called upon to do so with view to having the RS&amp;AC
process provide adequate responses to them.
<P>
v) The RS&amp;AC process and the agreements that may derive from
it should take into account not just threats and capabilities
of individual states (and non-state entities) but also threats
and capabilities deriving from coalitions, treaties, as well as
political and military alliances and accords between states of
the region
<P>
c) Comprehensiveness
<P>
i) The RS&amp;AC process is designed to ensure security and stability
in the region at reduced levels of militarization by:
<P>
* Building mutual confidence between states;
<P>
* Reducing the risk of hostilities;
<P>
* Lowering the incentives and capabilities for surprise attack;
<P>
* Enhancing crisis stability;
<P>
* Curtailing arms races and containing the proliferation of destabilizing
weapons;
<P>
* Assuring compliance with arms control accords.
<P>
ii) In its course the RS&amp;AC process will deal with all types
of threats, capabilities as well as intentions, in all pertinent
areas, specifically:
<P>
* Military and paramilitary, including terrorism;
<P>
* Military and security forces and their deployment;
<P>
* Defense expenditures;
<P>
* Conventional hardware and weapons systems;
<P>
* Ballistic missiles, chemical weapons, biological weapons, and
<P>
nuclear weapons.
<P>
iii) Each of these categories will be addressed on its own merit,
and in accordance with its intrinsic characteristics.
<P>
iv) Progress in the process in any given area will not be conditional
on progress in other areas.
<P>
d) The<B> </B>Regional Framework
<P>
The uniqueness of the present RS&amp;AC process stems from its
regional focus. RS&amp;AC regimes and the process designed to
accomplish them are in the interest of each and every one of the
states of the region as well as of the region as a whole. Thus,
it ought to evolve and be based on mutually agreed measures, arrangements,
and agreements. Towards that end the process must aim:
<P>
i) To arrive at an agreed delineation of the area;
<P>
ii) To ensure that, based upon the agreed delineation, the arms
control accords will include <U>all</U> states of the region
<P>
iii) To ascertain that progress, both on substance and procedure,
will be arrived at through free and direct negotiation, and that
agreements will be concluded by consensus among all the parties
to the process.
<P>
iv) To arrive at agreed upon effective RS&amp;AC implementation
and verification regimes. These should be conducted by the states
of the region through mutual verification mechanisms, mutual inspections
and specialized institutions, leaving no room for discrimination
of any state, in rights or in duties.
<P>
v) To ensure the success of the process, the support of the cosponsors
as well as of other extra-regional states is clearly of importance.
They should lend it and its goals support, assist in its realization,
and respect the accords and agreements that emerge from it.
<P>
e) Practicality
<P>
For progress to be made, the RS&amp;AC process has to be pragmatic.
Progress should be made wherever and whenever possible. Its pace
will obviously be governed by the conditions prevailing in the
region.
<P>
To facilitate progress, lessons ought to be learned and drawn
from successful RS&amp;AC experience of other states and regions,
bearing in mind the unique features of the Middle East and its
RS&amp;AC process.
<P>
i) Progress must be incremental, through a step-by-step approach.
<P>
ii) Considerations of practicality mandate that the first steps
in the process should be:
<P>
* Establishing of Confidence Building Measures; confidence is
essential for the entire RS&amp;AC process. As long as the conditions
of peace and tranquility do not prevail in the area, building
and sustaining mutual confidence between states of the region
is necessary in order to defuse tensions and diminish the threats
of war.
<P>
* An overall effort to contain and arrest the spread of destabilizing
weapon systems in the region.
<P>
iii) Priority in the process ought to be assigned to dealing with
such systems that experience has proven to be de-stabilizing,
which have been used in regional wars and have caused massive
casualties, suffering and destruction.
<P>
f) Reliability
<P>
All Regional Security and Arms Control arrangements arrived at
must be both reliable and dependable. Attaining the necessary
confidence that arms control accords will be scrupulously addressed
to in contingent upon inter-alia, the existence of:
<P>
i) Mutual and effective verification arrangements (mutual visits
and inspections).
<P>
ii) Consultative and coordinating bodies, agreed to by all states
of the region.
<P>
iii) Appropriate enforcement mechanisms.
<H4><B>3. General remarks</B></H4>

<P>
Historically Israel has been the one state in the Middle East
that is not a member of military or political coalitions in the
region. Most states of the area have joined regional alliances
and collective security arrangement, and formed extensive networks
of politico-military cooperation arrangements. This reality has
to be taken into account and should be reflected in future arms
control arrangements.
<P>
Israel believes that economic cooperation between states has benefits
above and beyond economic prosperity. It brings societies closer,
and creates interdependence as well as a common interest in the
existence of a calm and open environment. Thus, economic cooperation
between the states of our region will positively affect progress
in the RS&amp;AC process.
<P>
Israel recognizes the political and cultural diversity of the
region. Yet, as a democratic state and an open pluralistic society,
Israel believes that advancing democracy in the region has an
important role to play in enhancing peace, stability and security.
Democratization will introduce shared values such as openness
and transparency between states. It will contribute to political
stability, diminish bellicosity, and reduce threats of terrorism
and subversion whether by individuals, groups or states. It will
also strengthen a common norm of adherence to the principle of
the rule of law, and respect for treaties and agreements. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
