<BODY>

<H2><B>ARMS CONTROL AND CONFIDENCE BUILDING MEASURES IN THE MIDDLE
EAST</B></H2>

<P>
<B>Dr. Mahmoud A.J. ALI</B>
<P>
Member of the Palestinian Delegation to the Arms Control and Regional
Security Working Group (ACRS), Assistant Professor, Department
of Political Science Applied Science University, Amman, Jordan
<HR>

<H4><B>1. Introduction</B></H4>

<P>
Resolution of international conflicts remains one of the most
significant issues which policy-makers and political analysts
have to grapple. The point in time for this attempt to shed some
lights on one of the most important topics in international relations
is especially important as the end of the Cold War has brought
a major shift in the manner states interact in the search for
finding solutions to international and regional conflicts. This
new perception of international relations in a growingly interdependent
world community also symbolizes what might be considered as a
new era in inter-state behaviour at the end of the twentieth century.
<P>
The examination of approaches to the peace settlements, security
arrangements, and arms control is usually described as a multidisciplinary
study of predominantly bilateral relations, reflecting both the
standard mode of international politics as perceived and studied
for a long time, and the preferred method of imperical studies
including traditional histories of diplomacy.
<P>
The peace process in the Middle East launched in<B> </B>Madrid
in October 1991 constituted a major step when Arab and Israeli
delegations met publicly to try to find ways to put an end to
their long lasting hostilities. This peace process was crowned
by the signing in September 1993 of the Israeli-Palestinian Declaration
of principles (D.O.P). Consequently, Israeli forces
<P>
were redeployed in Gaza Strip and Jericho area as a first step
towards a complete Palestinian Self Rule in the whole of the West
Bank and Gaza.
<P>
In addition, Jordan and Israel signed at the same time their common
agenda by the Washington Declaration in July 1994, which laid
the foundation for a peace treaty between the two sides. The negotations
between Israel and Syria over the Golan Hights, and with Lebanon
regarding the bilateral relations between the two sides are going
on positively, and the chances and possibilities of a real breakthrough
on these two tracks are increasing.
<P>
With the advancement and progress of the peace process which inevitably
will restructure regional relations on a less militaristic basis
so that many new regional and transregional arms control arrangements
are created, and a major change in security perception in turn
will occur, which will automatically lead to a major change in
military deployments in the region. In this process of transforming
relations in the Middle East from hostility and confrontation
to coexistence and cooperation, arms control and confidence-building
measures (CBMs) must play an essential role. In fact, states of
the region have widely acknowledged the urgency of these issues
and agreed to engage in the discussions and deliberations of the
Arms Control and Regional Security Working Group (ACRS). The objective
of this working group is to determine mechanisms by which security
for all parties in the region at a minimum level of armaments
will be achieved, and not the achievement of security for one
party at the expense of others.
<P>
In addition to that, arms control, CBMs and security arrangements
are also being discussed in a bilateral fashion between Israel
and each individual Arab states (Syria, Jordan, Egypt and the
Palestinians). Discussions in (ACRS) in Moscow, Washington and
Doha developed on different related issues focussing mainly on
the needs and means to resolve conflicts in the area, as well
as other security arrangements and security concerns of participants
of this working group.
<P>
It is to be noted that despite the great importance of the issues
and matters contained in the agenda of this working group, so
far, discussions in the formal plenary meetings, as well as in
the intersessional activities can be described as purely academic
and theoretical, ranging from convening training courses to workshops
and seminars on monitoring and related activities.
<P>
It is obvious that arms control and security arrangements in the
Middle East have become a central issue deeply connected with
the peace process in the region. In fact, they constitute an essential
part of the whole peace process. So, while recognizing the importance
of this process, one should not ignore the existing arms race
in the area which negatively affects social and economic development
in the region. In this context, and because regional arms control
and security arrangments mainly and directly concern the interests
of the countries of the Middle East, these countries should play
a leading role in formulating the major components of the peace
process in accordance with their security needs and requirements.
<P>
One of the main objectives of arms control in the Middle East
is to create regional security arrangements that would set the
base for further peaceful relations and peaceful co-existence
between all parties of the region. These security arrangements
should be based on the principle of mutual interests derived from
the fact that security must be insured for all parties of the
region, that it should be in line with the idea of non-use or
threat of use of force in the settlement of conflicts between
states of the region.
<P>
By far, the peace process in the Middle East is the start of a
long and important effort which concentrates on promoting regional
security and regional cooperation. Arms control and confidence-building
can play an important role in the overall effort to promote a
durable and just peace in the region. We think that the time is
ripe to undertake real steps towards the establishment of useful
mechanisms to regulate and reduce arms in the area. Arms control
efforts should not be seen as a substitute for security, but as
a means of an accrued security for all states. It is only acceptable
if it<B> </B>respects the right to each state's security. In this
respect, arms control arrangements must take into account the
geographical, strategic, political
<P>
and economical data of the region itself, some of which is the
high density of weapons in an exceptionally restricted space .
<P>
One must recognize the fact that each party has its special security
needs, and for arms control and confidence-building measures to
succeed, they should address these needs. At this stage, parties
of the region should be looking for kinds of CBMs that could support
and push forward the peace process itself, as well as answering
and satisfying security concerns of all parties of the region.
<P>
It is essential to understand that arms control and CBMs are of
great importance for the region because of the great amount of
military build-up in the area. So, addressing the issue of conventional
as well as chemical and biological weapons in the area will be
an important route of direction that parties of the region should
follow.
<P>
One of our concerns in the area is the proliferation of weapons
of mass-destruction. I believe that Israel has to do a lot in
this regard. I must point out that Israel's nuclear programme
- which in itself is a destabilizing factor - will encourage others
in the area to try to acquire this kind of weapons by all attainable
means.
<H4><B>2. Initiatives for Arms Control in the Middle East</B>
</H4>

<P>
Previous arms control initiatives in the Middle East were merely
of a political nature. These initiatives were not transferred
into a real negotiation because of the continuous conflicts and
confrontations which always created arms race and arms build-up
in the area. Taking this into consideration, one can refer to
certain key initiatives in this regard:
<P>
a) The Tripartite Declaration of 1950
<P>
This was an initiative by the United States, France and Britain
which can be described as the first official attempt by external
powers in this direction. Through this declaration, the three
powers committed themselves to freeze their arms transfer to parties
to the Arab-Israeli conflict at that time in an attempt to maintain
the balance of power in the Middle East after the 1948 war. But
this declaration failed, because of continued confrontation between
Arabs and Israel, and because of conflicting interests of the
Western powers at that time, especially France's shipment of advanced
aircrafts to Israel in 1954.
<P>
b) President Carter's Initiative
<P>
The U.S. administration under President Carter took an ambitious
arms transfer restraint effort in the late 1970 when it declared
that conventional arms sales to the third world countries threatened
world stability. The initiative also encouraged others to take
the first step towards reducing global arms trade. This initiative
was seen at that time as part of U.S. foreign policy which could
be used as a tool for promoting American security interests by
affirming America's leading role. Talks between the U.S. Administration
and the Soviet Union about the<B> </B>matter failed because of
different strategic interests of both parties in the Middle East.
<P>
c) President Bush's Two Initiatives of May 1991 and July 1992
<P>
These two initiatives mainly dealt with weapons of mass destruction,
conventional and chemical weapons, as well as ballistic missiles.
The two initiatives urgently called the Big Powers especially
those of the Security Council to play a major role in this regard.
Moreover, they called upon all states including those of the Middle
East to take major and real steps towards the reduction of their
weapons weapons of mass destruction.
<P>
d) The Egyptian Initiative of 1990
<P>
In this regard, one should recognize the Egyptian initiative of
April 1990 which was supported by most Arab states as a real step
towards creating a peaceful and stable Middle East. This initiative
called for making the Middle East an area free of all kinds of
weapons of mass destruction, as well as creating proper means
of verification to insure the states' compliance with requirements
of arms control and security arrangements.
<P>
e) Paris Declaration of October 1991
<P>
In this declaration, the Big Five of the Security Council tried
to adopt proper regulations to reduce the flow of arms to the
Middle East. At the end of their meeting in Paris, the participants
agreed to follow certain common procedures related to transfer
of conventional arms to the Middle East.
<P>
The importance of this declaration is due to the nature of restraints
adopted by the main suppliers of arms to the Middle East. One
can easily feel this degree of flexibility given to those suppliers
in deciding about these restraints when it - the declaration -
authorized them to decide whether arms transfer to the<B> </B>area
might affect the military balance or whether it might be used
in a defensive or an offensive way.
<P>
It is to be said in this regard, despite all these constructive
initiatives, one can easily notice that states of the region could
easily obtain very advanced military systems. This fact might
be duo to deep differences among the world major arms suppliers
and the recipient states about the size and level of restraints.
For arms control and restraint measures to be effective, productive
and succesfull, they must acquire support and encouragement by
the external powers, especially the Big Five since they are the
major suppliers of most advanced and<B> </B>sophisticated weapons
to the Middle East.
<H4><B>3. Arab and Israeli Perceptions on Arms Control and CBMs
</B></H4>

<P>
Examining the working process of Arms Control and Regional Security
Working Group (ACRS) reveals certain points of differences among
participants on number of issues. These differences might be due
to different priorities and perceptions each party has established.
Arab participants in ACRS wanted to see Israel's nuclear capabilities
put under control. So, they keep insisting on the establishment
of a Nuclear Weapons - Free Zone in the Middle East as well as
on Israel's signing the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT),
and accepting International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) safeguards
at its nuclear facilities.
<P>
Arab participants in ACRS have also insisted on the position that
for arms control and security arrangements to be efficient, Israel
should reduce its nuclear weapons in exchange for Arabs reducing
their conventional, chemical and biological weapons. Not only
that, but they stress the idea that Israel's concessions on the
issue of nuclear weapons might encourage other Arab and other
Middle Eastern states to join the peace process and accept limitations
on their weapons.
<P>
We believe that confidence - building measures (CBMSs) are part
of the whole peace process in the Middle East mainly and directly
designed to complement and support the process itself, especially
the bilateral tracks. ACRS should thus concentrate on different
types of CBMs which can push forward the peace process, as well
as answering and satisfying security needs of the region.
<P>
Israel, on the other hand has a different perception. Many Israeli
policy-makers believe that arms control arrangements will inevitably
weaken Israel's ability to defend itself. They also think that
these arrangements will result in a major reduction of Israel's
deterrent capability. One can notice that through the discussions
and deliberations of ACRS and other meetings and workshops, Israeli
negotiators tend to avoid discussing directly the
<P>
issue of Israel's nuclear capability, proposing instead that participants
in ACRS concentrate and focus on reductions of conventional, biological,
and chemical weapons in the area. Israel emphasizes on CBMs and
considers them as a symbol of cooperation designed to transform
relations between states of the region from a state of confrontation
to a state of cooperation.
<P>
It is to be noted that CBMs - which are essential for any arms
control agreements in the Middle East - will be difficult to achieve
because of the long history of confrontation this area had witnessed.
Preliminary or &quot;Precursor&quot; CBMs might have a positive
impact on the hole peace process by bridging centuries of hostilities
that led to the absence of communications among countries of the
Middle East. These preliminary or &quot;precursor&quot; CBMs such
as communication, and exchange of information, if introduced in
a step-by-step manner building on previous successful efforts
in the area, will automatically increase transparency and mutual
understanding, and consequently reduce the likelihood for war.
<P>
It is widely believed that without proper CBMs, no breakthrough
in arms control in the Middle East will be possible. The importance
of these measures will be great because of mutual mistrust between
Israel and its Arab neighbouring countries.
<P>
Examining CBMs in the Arab-Israeli context, one might refer to
other experiences in this field especially those of Europe. In
this context, one<B> </B>can recall James Goodby's ten-point proposal
for CBMs in the Middle East which includes the following:
<P>
- Establishment of a Conflict Prevention Centre (CPC) for the
Middle East like the one established in Europe.
<P>
- Annual exchange of military data regarding types, quantities
and deployments of major military equipments through the CPC or
third parties.
<P>
- Exchange of visits each year to the territories of each of the
parties involved to confirm the accuracy of the data exchanged.
<P>
- Notification forty five days in advance through the CPC of any
out-of-garrison activities, maneuvers, or concentration of troops
above agreed-on thresholds.
<P>
- Observation by CPC of out-of-garrison activities that are subject
to notification, including short-notice alert and<B> </B>mobilization
exercises lasting more than twenty - four hours.
<P>
- A specified number of on-site inspections of each party's territory
each year by CPC or third-party representatives.
<P>
- An explanation by a participant of unusual military activities
it is undertaking, in lieu of an adequate explanation, inspection
of such activities by the CPC, third parties, or their national
technical means (NTM) of verification.
<P>
- An open skies aerial monitoring system operated by the CPC or
third parties.
<P>
- A hot line for rapid communications among participants, including
- if necessary - a CPC or third parties.
<P>
- Annual meetings of participants' military chiefs of staff with
the CPC or with third parties to review past implementation, future
military activities, and planned acquistion and development of
major weapons systems
<P>
It might be useful also to look at the European example regarding
CBMs adopted by the Conference on Security and Cooperation in
Europe (CSCE), and try to draw some conclusion out of that example.
It would be possible in this context to categorize them as follows
<P>
a) Measures of Information
<P>
These measures are mainly designed to facilitate understanding
of all participating states of routine activities by providing
adequate information
<P>
about routine training activities which are going to take place.
These measures can be divided in to the following types:
<P>
i)<B> </B>Exchange of General Military Information
<P>
This measure aims at keeping all states informed about the structures
of national forces, their command and control arrangements, tactical
grouping at division level and above, and normal peacetime location
of major military units, military installations and permanent
training places on a routine - annual or semiannual updates -
basis.
<P>
ii) Exchange of Annual Forecasts of Major Military Activities
<P>
This measure is designed to provide prior notification about military
activities on the territory of participating states, as well as
providing a broad time-table concerning the size and scope of
major military activities which might take place in the succeeding
calendar year. This kind of measure will make it more easier to
predict about any routine activities by any of the participating
states. This measure will include activities of major units, their
movements and deployments 'Outside their usual location.
<P>
iii)<B> </B>Establishment of Communications
<P>
This measure is intended to provide communications by linking
states concerned through their defence and foreign ministers in
&quot;Hot Line&quot; arrangements. These arrangements will provide
exchanges of information, as well as quick clearing up of any
misunderstanding about information received or activities observed
under normal circumstances.
<P>
iv) Exchange of Information on Military Budgets
<P>
This measure stipulates that participating states announce in
advance the date when their annual defense budgets is submitted
for approval by their national authorities, as well as sending
copies to all other participants when the budget is approved.
Clarifications of any<B> </B>questions by any participants about
any of the items of the budget, and the way it is developed must
be also available.
<P>
b) Measures of Notification
<P>
This measure mainly deals with providing advance warnings about
any major military activity by any party of the region concerning
the size, scope, location and duration of its military activity.
These measures are intended to make transparent all out-of-garrison
activities of major military units and the notification of any
alert of military activities.
<P>
This group of measures includes the following:
<P>
i) Notification of Out-of-Garrison Activities
<P>
This measure stipulates that each party prenotify other parties
about its actual military activities to take place by its major
military units at the level of division or 10,000 men, or their
equivalent in air forces or naval force structures. Out-of-garrision
activities is defined in this respect as the deployment of the
division headquarters and/or the majority of its combat elements
away from their normal peacetime garrison location.
<P>
ii) Notification of Mobilization Activities
<P>
This measure stipulates that each party should notify other parties
about its troops mobilization activities including numbers and
units participating in this activity, their destination, and the
purpose of the activity and its time-
<P>
duration. By doing this, the party involved will provide assurances
that his mobilization activity is not being used as to increase
his offensive power.
<P>
iii) Notification of Alert Activities
<P>
This measure is designed to reduce the perception of threat. States
of the region should make clear and explicit the number, size
and scope of alert exercises to be conducted in the coming year.
These activities should be notified to all states at the time
of their commencement using different communication links.
<P>
c) Measures of Stabilization
<P>
These measures are mainly designed to increase confidence between
parties in the area by removing or reducing major military activities
which might be considered as threatening the security of any party
ill the area.
<P>
These types of measures will include:
<P>
i) Troop ceiling
<P>
This measure stipulates that parties of the region agree to keep
the size of their routine major military activities below the
scale of forces needed to launch a full-scale attack against any
of the participating states of the region. This measure is also
designed to gradually reduce the number of major military activities
which participating states consider essential for the maintenance
of national security.
<P>
ii) Limitation on Major Military Activities in Certain Areas
<P>
This measure gives participating states the chance to designate
a certain area as a limitation zone if they feel that this area
will be a source of threat to their security, especially if it
is used as an assembling or a passing area
<P>
to launch offensive attacks. It will be reasonable to make a balanced
distribution of areas designated as limitation zones so as to
prohibit unreasonable demands by any one state at the expense
of others. Criteria of what constitutes a sensitive security area
will have to be negotiated in advance and then judiciously applied
to areas proposed for such status by the various participating
states.
<P>
iii) Limitation on Number of Major Units Out-of Garrison
<P>
This measure stipulates reducing the total number of major units
which may be out-of-garrison at any one time in order to eliminate
the possibility of building up a threatening force posture by
conducting a series of allegedly unrelated military activities
in the same time frame. It is also designed to dismiss any fears
of a likely opponent gaining an advantage by slipping through
a loophole in the CBM network. Also it might be possible that
this measure includes limitations on the total number of major
military units within a certain distance of specified designated
areas or international borders.
<P>
iv) Limitation on Major Units from Outside Europe
<P>
This measure stipulates that units from outside Europe must be
limited since introducing new units from outside Europe might
have a destabilizing influence. This measure was mainly designed
to prevent both the United States and the Soviet Union to bring
additional troops into Europe, and thus affecting the military
balance and military stability reached at by previously mentioned
measures.
<P>
v) Limitation on Military Budgets
<P>
This measure would necessitate that participating states put limitations
on their military expenditures, and reduce them in subsequent
years to a
<P>
growth not exceeding the rate of inflation prevailing in their
respective national economies.
<P>
d) Measures of Verification
<P>
This kind of measures dictates a mandatory obligation of participating
states to allow observers from other participating states to monitor
and observe major military activities to make sure that thesame
activity notified is exactly taking place. Also, this category
of measures stipulates the establishment of an overall verification
system acceptable to all participants. It will provide a continuous
monitoring of military activities taking place within the area.
Observation and verification system will provide sufficient flexibility
to satisfy the security needs of all parties as well as giving
all states active roles in verification procedures. These measures
of verification might include the following:
<P>
i) Observation of Notifiable Military Activities
<P>
This measure is designed to allow participants to check the nonaggressive
intent of the activity taking place. It also stipulates that obligations
to invite observers from all participating states will be mandatory
rather than voluntary. In this regard, observers can do the following:
<P>
- Monitor preparations and deployments of forces.
<P>
- Report on the standard of troops training.
<P>
- Report on the status of military equipments like tanks and artillery.
<P>
- Check command and control,communications, tactics and morals
of troops.
<P>
- Monitor the return of participating forces to their garrisons.
<P>
ii) Verification of CBMs Implementation
<P>
The main motive for this kind of measure is to verify compliance
with agreements, and to avoid any possible violation to that agreement.
A two level approach is suggested in this regard. The first one
would be non-intrusive containing the following stages:
<P>
- Routine monitoring by national technical means (NTM),
<P>
- Submission of a request for consultation or clarification if
uncertainties arise;
<P>
- A specified time limit for a reply; and
<P>
- Communication of the outcome to all participating states.
<P>
If this non-intrusive level of verification did not achieve satisfactory
results, then the intrusive level would become operational. It
could contain the following stages:
<P>
- Request for an on-site ground and /or aerial inspection of tile
area where violation might had happened;
<P>
- A specified time-limit for a replay;
<P>
- On site inspection;
<P>
- Findings reported to all participating states;
<P>
- Arbitration of disputes;
<P>
As it was stated before, the main goal of arms control and CBMs
in the Middle East is to reduce the likelihood of war. Consequently,
effective arms control arrangements and CBMs should be carefully
designed to strengthen deterrence and foster a stable balance
of power which will make war less likely. These measures should
be also designed to help reduce the scope, destructiveness, or
duration of war.
<P>
Consequently, we believe that the following conditions and requirements
should be fullfilled. The full compliance of all states of the
region to the norms, objectives and purposes of the U.N. Charter
and the principles of mutual respect of sovereignty and territorial
integrity, mutual non-aggression and noninterference in internal
affairs of any state in the region, since it is essential to keeping
weapons at the minimum level required only for defense purposes.
<P>
- It is necessary to define and determine the geography of the
Middle East, the area where measures and objectives of arms control
will be implemented.
<P>
- There should be some declaratory measures by all parties in
the region. These measures might include principles, elements
and guidelines which will help building and enforcing peace and
stability in the region.
<P>
- The signing by all parties of the region of treaties that call
for an area free of weapons of mass-destruction, and the control
of conventional weapons. In<B> </B>this respect, one can recommend
that parties of the region should work on and join in:
<P>
* The Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT);
<P>
* Regional Convention For Chemical and Biological Weapons; and
<P>
* Ballistic Missiles Proliferation Treaty. (MTCR) for the Middle
East including both suppliers and recipients. 
</BODY>

