<BODY>

<H2><B>MARITIME CONFIDENCE-BUILDING MEASURES IN THE MIDDLE EAST
</B></H2>

<P>
<B>Mr. Peter JONES</B>
<P>
Regional Security Officer, Non-Proliferation, Arms Control and
Disarmament Division, Canadian Department of Foreign Affairs and
International Trade<HR>

<P>
The political context of the Middle East Maritime Confidence-Building
Measures(MCBM) discussions arises from the so-called Madrid Formula
of the Middle East Peace Process (MEPP). The Madrid Formula, established
during the ground-breaking Madrid Middle East Peace Conference,
created a two-track MEPP under the over-all sponsorship of the
United States and Russia.
<P>
The first track was devoted to a series of bilateral negotiations
between the participants in the Peace Process. The second called
for the creation of a series of multilateral working groups on
various issues germane to the creation of a Middle East at peace.
It was recognized from the beginning that the bilateral track
was the more important, and that the progress in the multilaterals
would ultimately depend on the progress in the bilaterals.
<P>
These multilateral groups would include all of the Middle East
participants in the MEPP and several states outside the region
which had demonstrated a willingness to become involved in the
search for a settlement to the Middle East dispute and were able
to contribute to the process. The five multilateral groups established
in Moscow in January 1992 were: the Arms Control and Regional
Security Working Group (ACRSWG); Water Resources; Environment;
Regional Economic Development; and Refugees.
<P>
What I have to say relates to the ACRSWG. After initial meetings
of an exploratory nature in both Moscow and Washington, the Middle
East participants were asked to submit views on specific topics
they would be
<P>
willing to discuss. Eventually, six topics were agreed, one of
which was MCBMs.
<P>
MCBMs were seen as a potentially productive topic because, of
all the spheres of military rivalry in the Middle East, the maritime
sphere is generally regarded as the least contentious, <U>initself.
</U> Though naval forces are firmly caught up in the various military
disputes of a purely maritime or naval character. Thus, it was
reasoned that it might be easier for concrete steps to be taken
in the maritime sphere at the beginning of the ACRSWG process.
It was thus agreed at the third ACRSWG Plenary in Washington that
an examination of MCBMs could begin.
<P>
Canada is a firm supporter of the MEPP and a consistent contributor
to peacekeeping forces in the region. We also enjoy good relations
with all countries in the region. Finally, Canada possesses both
a highly professional and respected Navy and Coast Guard with
the requisite expertise to contribute substantively. For all of
these reasons, Canada was asked to serve as Mentor (we prefer
the term Facilitator) of the ACRSWG examination of the applicability
of MCBMs in the Middle East.
<P>
After consultations, Canada proposed that initial considerations
should center on two specific MCBMs; enhanced regional cooperation
in maritime Search and Rescue (SAR); and the elaboration of the
basic framework of a regional Prevention of Incidents at Sea (INCSEA)
Agreement. These two were selected because they represent areas
where work could go forward towards practical and political useful
agreements on relatively uncontentious issues. Search and Rescue
is first and foremost a humanitarian activity and no state wants
to see an unplanned incident escalate into a tense situation.
Also, both areas require naval officers to work cooperatively
towards the establishment and realization of agreed goals.
<P>
With agreement to make SAR and INCSEA the focus of consideration,
the task was to identify ways of getting the regional parties
together to explore these issues. After consulting with the co-sponsors,
Canada proposed a Workshop on these two issues. It was further
proposed that this workshop take place on neutral ground, at the
Canadian Coast Guard College in Sydney, Nova Scotia in September,
1993. It was also decided that the Workshop would not seek to
explore the basic concepts in play in a generic fashion.
<P>
Accordingly, Canada, in cooperation with the two co-sponsors,
developed a program for the Sydney Workshop which emphasized practical,
hands-on examination of both SAR and INCSEA concepts. The participants
were broken into small, mixed nationality groups and each group
was given specific tasks in terms of both SAR and INCSEA. These
tasks concentrated on solving generic problems with the concepts
in play. Though all have SAR capabilities, cooperation in this
field is not yet a common feature in the region. INCSEA, meanwhile,
is entirely new to the navies of the region.
<P>
The INCSEA scenarios were intended to demonstrate that early communication
of intentions between ships is the best means of avoiding misunderstandings,
and that the ready availability of a group of specially tailored
signals can be a factor in preventing a benign misunderstanding
from becoming a potential source of conflict. Discussions at Sydney
amongst the participants, demonstrated the importance of timely
and thorough consultations.
<P>
The SAR discussions focused on the effectiveness of pooling resources
to deal with humanitarian emergencies. In addition, the technical
requirements of such pooling were identified. At the lower end
of the scale of complexity these were seen to be communications
capabilities which would cut across regional and political boundaries.
Moving higher on the scale, participants identified the need to
familiarize each other with their procedures, training and equipment,
and ultimately to standardize these on regional or sub-regional
basis. The SAR discussions also looked at existing
<P>
arrangements for international SAR cooperation and examined their
potential applicability to the Middle East.
<P>
At the end of the Sydney Workshop it was agreed by all that neither
SAR nor INCSEA presented any insurmountable obstacles of a technical
nature. On SAR, it was agreed that a good beginning would be made
if the regional states were to exchange information on their SAR
communications frequencies and their command and control provisions
for SAR. This would enable them to contact each other quickly
in cases of emergency and to have some idea of the capabilities
which others could contribute quickly to a SAR response. On INCSEA,
the essential simplicity of the existing arrangements was endorsed,
as was endorsed, as was their emphasis on professional Navy-to-Navy
contacts.
<P>
Accordingly, the regional participants asked Canada to prepare
two things for the next Workshop. First, they wanted Canada to
prepare a questionnaire on regional SAR practices. The intention
was that the responses to this questionnaire would form the basis
of an initial exchange and discussion of information on basic
SAR capabilities and practices in the region. Second, they asked
Canada to prepare a draft multilateral INCSEA text for the Middle
East. This text would serve as the basis for an examination of
what such an agreement might look like in the Middle East. Interestingly,
this would be the very first multilateral INCSEA ever produced
as all previous Agreements had been bilateral.
<P>
Canada worked on these requests in the hope that another Workshop
would be held in the late autumn of 1993. For various reasons
(some technical, some political) it was not until March of 1994
that the next Workshop could be held in Antalya, Turkey. In the
Meantime, the results of the Sydney Workshop were endorsed by
the ACRSWG Plenary held in Moscow in November, 1993.
<P>
Discussion of SAR at Antalya was uneven. Disappointingly few of
the regional participants actually returned their SAR questionnaires.
This meant that the detailed exchange of information upon which
much of the meeting had been predicated could not take place.
The Canadian facilitators had some success in drawing information
out of the participants in discussion, but not to the extent we
had hoped.
<P>
Nevertheless, the regional participants continued their exploration
of the desirability and mechanics of enhanced regional cooperation
in SAR. They agreed that a regional communications network being
set up initially by the Dutch as another ACRSWG activity should
be used for SAR coordination. Encouragingly, a few regional states
even offered to host an eventual regional Rescue Coordination
Centre.
<P>
It is difficult to discern the exact reason for the less than
expected performance on SAR in Antalya. Much of it stems back
to the fact that very few of the regional participants filled
out the Canadian questionnaire. We do not know why this was so.
It may be that many were unwilling to provide the level of detail
requested on what is, after all, an essentially military function.
It may be something as benign as the fact that the questionnaire
simply fell between the cracks of bureaucratic responsibility
in most countries.
<P>
Whatever the reason, it seems clear that the discussions will
remain at a rather basic level for some time unless the regional
participants decide to be more forthcoming regarding their own
capabilities.
<P>
The INCSEA discussions, by contrast, made considerable progress.
Canada's draft INCSEA text was accepted as a basic framework for
the discussions. In many respects, the draft followed the existing
Canada-Russia INCSEA text. This was especially true with respect
to the obligations to be under taken by parties concerning the
avoidance of harassment. The draft differed in that its consultative
mechanisms had to reflect the need to encompass a multilateral
framework.
<P>
This is a critical change in that a substantial part of the value
of any INCSEA Agreement is the requirement to consult on safety
on a regular basis at the navy-to-navy level. That obligation
is the foundation of the face to face contact between naval professionals
which an INCSEA Agreement seeks to promote. In a multilateral
Agreement, these reviews would have to include both a regular
multilateral meeting at which all parties could discuss the operation
of the Agreement, and a regular set of interlocking bilaterals
at which individual Parties could sit down to discuss matters
of mutual concern.
<P>
The whole question of reviews is also bound up with the membership
question, which raises questions over the formal recognition by
others. Because of this problem, a lengthy discussion was held
over what form an eventual INCSEA Agreement might take. It was
pointed out that a form of document which was not legally binding
would be just as effective operationally. Others responded that
such a fix might lack certain of the political benefits sought
by some, in terms of normalizing relations between states in the
Middle East. Obviously, this is part of a larger political problem,
the solution to which will have to come through the bilateral
process.
<P>
Finally with respect to the provisional title of the draft document,
some pointed out that there is little history of naval ''incidents''
as such in the Middle East. It was also feared that the current
title sounded too provocative in the light of the desire to highlight
the cooperative nature of the proposed under taking. Therefore,
it was suggested that the title should be cast more in terms of
''facilitating the safety of navigation'' in the region.
<P>
In operational terms a number of other questions arose. For example,
language was introduced by some which sought to constrain the
use of certain technology devices when ships were in proximity
to each other. The problem with these ideas was that, in some
cases, the non-use of certain technologies may be impossible to
verify. Furthermore, the very
<P>
idea appears to change the purpose of an INCSEA Agreement, making
it into a much more operationally constraining regime than the
present one.
<P>
The principle behind existing INCSEA Agreements is that participants
will naturally refrain from activities which might endanger their
partners. It is not seen as necessary to spell everything out,
but rather to rely upon the desire of the participants to have
the Agreement succeed. Problems which arise should thus be dealt
with by the review process. Trying to define every possible case
where problems might happen, and come up with firm provisions
to prevent them, is seen as both inconsistent with the spirit
of the exercise and impossibly complex. It might also lead to
a potentially divisive negotiation over what should be restricted
and what should not. Moreover, certain possibilities inevitably
would be omitted in any such discussion and come back to haunt
the Parties later.
<P>
Obviously, this point of view is based on a premise of a certain
level of trust existing between the participants. This approach
recognizes that, even though they may have certain operational
difficulties, the navies of the participating states will recognize
their mutual interest in avoiding incidents. Examination of this
issue continues.
<P>
Another operational difference which arose concerned the question
of what are known as <U>exclusion zones</U> around ships engaged
in maneuvers. When the original INCSEA Agreement was negotiated
the then USSR sought to apply restrictions as to how close US
Navy ships could get to Soviet ships. Accordingly, they proposed
that definite distances, known as range limitations, be incorporated
into the INCSEA Agreement.
<P>
In the initial INCSEA negotiations with the USSR, the US disagreed
vehemently with this approach. It took the view that the normal
exercise of good seamanship would dictate the distance one ship
should maintain from another for safety's sake. The US Navy did
not want any restrictions placed on its freedom to get as close
to Soviet ships for surveillance purposes as circumstances would
permit. They preferred that it be left to the individual captains
concerned, recognizing that responsibility for any mistakes would
also rest with them. After intense discussion the USSR accepted
the US position as part of a final trade-off to achieve an Agreement
in 1972. At the same time, the Russians reserved the right to
raise the question again and did so in succeeding years.
<P>
At Antalya, some naval experts also sought <U>range limitations
</U>. This approach was strongly resisted by others, including
the US Navy observers to the talks. In particular, the US Navy
is concerned that a regional INCSEA Agreement which includes specific
distance requirements could set an unfortunate precedent for future
regional Agreements of this type. This is a clear example of the
needs of an extra-regional, but nevertheless heavily involved
power, having an impact upon a regional discussion.
<P>
Yet another interesting question which has arisen concerns the
eventual applicability of a Middle East INCSEA Agreement. All
current INCSEA Agreements clearly apply ''Beyond the Territorial
Seas'' of the Parties. That phrase is, in fact, in their titles.
This means that in any case of incursion by ships of one Party
into the territorial waters of another, the navy of the transgressed
Party will not be bound by the INCSEA provisions in making its
response. It may choose to exercise these provisions, but does
not have to.
<P>
Because of the geographical complexities of the Middle East, this
provision may cause problems. In the Red Sea, for example, there
is no international water. The Red Sea is so narrow that the territorial
waters of the states around it are directly joined in the Red
Sea. This being the case, actions taken by one Navy in its territorial
waters could be considered provocative to ships of another Navy
in their own territorial waters but within eyesight.
<P>
Unless the Middle East INCSEA Agreement is made to apply within
territorial waters, these situations would not fail under its
scope.
<P>
At the same time, however, the spread with which threats can develop
in the region is such that most navies are unwilling to accept
restrictions on their actions within their territorial waters.
If a naval ship discovers a small, unidentified ship speeding
through its waters under suspicious circumstances, a threat to
the coastline can develop in a matter of seconds, and the defending
ship does not want to be encumbered with the need to raise INCSEA
signal flags and wait for a reply before responding.
<P>
This problem never arose in the negotiations over the original
INCSEA Agreements. In those cases, the participants were all ''Blue
Water'' navies with Blue Water problems. The Middle East is different
and points the way to difficulties which might be expected in
applying such an Agreement to other regional contexts where the
intended participants are primarily coastal defense navies.
<P>
The regional participants left Antalya promising to engage in
further study and discussion of the question. Suggestions have
ranged from leaving it to Parties to informally exercise the provisions
of the Agreement in territorial waters where circumstances warrant,
to establishing special provisions for use within territorial
waters.
<P>
Finally, some states raised concerns that proposals requiring
surface ships operating with submerged submarines to display certain
signals, might jeopardize the secrecy of submarine operations.
This argument was a constant factor in the original US-USSR INCSEA
negotiations. The US was vehemently opposed to any restrictions
on submarine operations. After discussion, however, it was decided
that this provision is essentially a safety one and is aimed not
at submarines, but at surface ships which might be operating with
them. Within the Middle East discussions, consideration of this
subject continues.
<P>
These are the main issues of consideration. It is important to
note that they comprise a minority of the original Canadian draft
text. Over 70% of that draft has been tentatively accepted as
a valid framework for an eventual Agreement by the regional participants
after in-depth discussion and some modifications. We expect to
continue our examination of the text at another meeting this autumn.
<P>
In the meantime, Canada has been asked to prepare two events this
summer in support of the Middle East SAR and INCSEA discussions.
The first will be a practical demonstration of both SAR and INCSEA
concepts involving Canadian and American warships currently on
station in the Mediterranean. The second will be a Workshop for
senior naval officers From the Middle East, which we hope will
take place at the end of the summer in Canada. Both of these proposals
were endorsed by the most recent ACRSWG Plenary in Doha, Qatar
in April.
<P>
Canada hopes that these events will enable us to make progress
on both INCSEA and SAR at the next working level meetings devoted
to this subject in the autumn. 
</BODY>

