<H2><B>NON-MILITARY COOPERATION IN THE MEDITERRANEAN AND NORTH
AFRICA</B> </H2>

<P>
<B>Professor Salvino BUSUTTIL</B>
<P>
Director-General, Foundation for International Studies
<P>
University of Malta<HR>

<P>
The forms of non-military cooperation in the Mediterranean and
North Africa on which I shall concentrate are basically classical
and conventional, that is they are essentially based on somebody
from the North contributing something to the South. The main area
of concentration concerns the environment especially the marine
environment. In this context, the principal success lies with
the Mediterranean Action Plan which, launched in 1975, was subsequently
given its institutional frame-work through the Barcelona Convention
to which all Mediterranean States plus the European Union are
signatory. That Convention, on the protection and conservation
of the Mediterranean Sea against pollution has had a chequered
history. It operates through five regional centres broadly corresponding
to the Protocols which now enrich the Convention.
<P>
Following the Nicosia Charter in 1990 and the Cairo Declaration
of 1992, the contracting parties to the Convention agreed on the
initiative of the European Union, that it was important Sustainable
Development be pursued, so that environmental and developmental
concerns be brought together. However, apart from official declarations,
there is very little to show so far for this move.
<P>
A further area of co-operation is in fisheries, especially through
FAO's General Fisheries Council of the Mediterranean; and, in
agriculture, through ICAMAS, the International Centre for Advanced
Studies in Mediterranean Agronomy which, inter alia, also promotes
Aquaculture. There is, of course, also Euromar, to the extent
practicable under the Eureka Projects which however is limited
to a few Mediterranean countries which have been able so far to
participate. The latter project, in particular, is considered
to be a model for the creation on a joint basis of research and
development between the North and the South and should be extended
to provide technological co-operation in a number of areas.
<P>
In so far as University co-operation is concerned, Med Campus
and the Community of Mediterranean Universities as well as, lately,
the University of the Mediterranean (UNIMED), foster networks
of co-operation between major universities. However, there is
still a considerable potential to be fulfilled. I think that the
first necessity is technological co-operation especially through
the identification of regional needs to which regional technological
solutions should be found.
<P>
I referred earlier to Eureka as providing a possible model for
this co-operation. It would seem to me, for example, that solar
desalination could be a good candidate for a focus of co-operation
using those sources (i.e. the sea and the sun) which are plentiful
and would of course contribute in an important manner to the solution
of one of the major problems in the Mediterranean, North Africa
and the Middle East: the supply and distribution of water.
<P>
Again, in the sphere of fisheries co-operation so far is very
limited. There are no regional or even bilateral fisheries. Sea
routes are non- existent in the sense that there are no agreed
routes in the Mediterranean. Similarly, for emergencies at sea,
especially for major catastrophies there is no stock-piling of
equipment; and the southern countries, in particular, would in
an emergency, still have to rely on assistance from countries
such as France and Italy and, to a lesser extent, Spain and Greece.
<P>
Moreover, the countries of the South also need important and urgent
assistance for the disposal of liquid and solid wastes, and for
the transport of toxic material which unfortunately, still finds
its way from the North to the South. There should also be a more
responsible attitude towards tourism which, in the manner it is
now being conducted, adds a source of upheaval in the Southern
countries, particularly through the modes and styles of life which
it suggests; and which, for economic as well as cultural and religious
reasons, the South finds it difficult to follow even as its younger
generations seem to want to ape it.
<P>
Increasingly, I find that in the Mediterranean it is important
that an act of courage be taken towards institutional advancement
i.e. to have a mechanism, however simple and however inexpensive,
to bring together the countries of the Mediterranean. Interesting
concepts have been mooted such as the Council of the Mediterranean,
a Mediterranean Agency or a Mediterranean Authority. It would
seem to me that the creation of a Mediterranean Commission for
Sustainable Development, bringing together environmental and development
concerns, could be a major step in this direction. Such a commission
could be created by a protocol to the existing Barcelona Convention
and could, at least during an initial period, be linked to the
administrative and institutional arrangements of the Mediterranean
Action Plan.
<P>
At the same time, the Mediterranean Forum held in Alexandria last
July has now raised the possibility of greater co-operation in
economic, political and cultural affairs. Indeed, the next meeting
is being held in Portugal proceeded by gatherings on economic,
political and cultural issues. It may well lay the ground for
the creation of such a commission as I have just referred to.
Ultimately, however, it is in technological advancement that the
real solutions to regional ills can be found.
<P>
Co-operation between government and universities as well as with
industry, especially in research and development, is essential.
Of course, for the South this may not be an easy matter because
few Southern countries have a tradition of this type of co-operation.
But in a situation where the ratio of GNP devoted to research
funds is now in the ratio of about 3/40 : 1 between North and
South, the need for technological advancement in order to motor
economic growth and development is imperative.
<P>
In this context, Confidence Building Measures (CBMS) are of course
important. But they should not lead to one-way traffic i.e. CBMs
coming from the North to the South. Since they are Confidence
Building Measures, they must be authentic, and they must arise
as much from the South as from the North. Secondly they must not
be so projected as to convey the impression of an &quot;imposition&quot;
of values. Let us not forget that values constitute a very basic
problem and are rooted in ethnic, religious and cultural traditions,
which through their differences, contribute to instability and
insecurity in the Mediterranean.
<P>
Neither must we continue to promote a transfer of technology based
on an import/export mentality from the North vis-&agrave;-vis
the South, respectively, especially where the technology exported
is obsolescent and environmentally &quot;poor&quot;.
<P>
CBM's should be genuinely inspired. They should also involve non-governmental
organisations. After all, it is not only and perhaps not even
primarily Governments, that introduce and instill Confidence Building
Measures. Confidence is a human resource and therefore cannot
be imposed by governments.
<P>
Some conclusions:
<P>
It is evident that Mediterranean countries need to pool their
resources. In this context, the above-mentioned proposal for a
Mediterranean Commission for Sustainable Development might provide
the framework necessary. Confidence Building Measures must be
seen as responding to regional needs or through the needs of a
particular area of the region and must be so conceived, so promoted
and so implemented as to show objectively and without any ambivalence
that they are meant to raise the standard of living of the peoples
of the Mediterranean, of North Africa and the Middle East, in
a setting of durable peace and lasting security, a security which
is not so much military as much as a guarantee against poverty,
injustice and equality. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
