<BODY>

<H2><B>REMOTE SENSING : THE TOOL OF INTEGRATED COASTAL ZONE MANAGEMENT
</B></H2>

<H2><B>Towards Peace in the Mediterranean</B></H2>

<P>
<B>Ms. Anna SPITERI</B>
<P>
Coordinator, Malta Council for Science and Technology
<P>
Remote Sensing Centre, Malta<HR>

<P>
Abstract
<P>
Remote Sensing, GIS and mathematical modelling are emerging as
the new enabling technologies that could be utilised for continuous
environmental sustainability. Such tools together with an integrated
resource management approach developed on a national and regional
scale, and the establishment of a regional data communications
infrastructure will facilitate peaceful regional co-operation
in the long term.
<P>
Space technology in the Mediterranean is still associated with
spy satellities and is not seen as a potential environmentally
friendly technology. Regional iniativites like for example oil
spill monitoring, which is a simple excercise to carry out with
remote sensing have still not happened, in spite of the legal
frameworks already established under the UN Environmental Programme
(UNEP) and the Mediterranean Action Plan (MAP).
<P>
The task to shift the paradigm from a security equals military
balance approach to a security equals peaceful cooperation is
indeed a very daunting one.
<P>
In this paper an attempt is made to present a vision of the Mediterranean,
whereby a regional data communications infrastructure will facilitate
the implementation of an integrated management approach, which
will, in turn, enable a fast and sound decision making. In this
scenario a new and creative business culture will grow and flourish
which will propel the Mediterranean region towards a new type
of prosperity and long-lasting peace.
<H4><B>1. Geographical Characteristics of the Mediterranean</B>
</H4>

<P>
The Mediterranean is described by a particular type of climate,
as well as a complex geology which determine the coastal landscape
characteristics. The Mediterranean coastline itself defines a
virtually enclosed sea, highly saline because of heavy evaporation
which is not balanced by inputs from rain and rivers. An inflow
which passes through the Straits of Gibraltar from the Atlantic
maintains the sea-level. The Mediterranean waters are comparatively
warm and governed by surface currents which change during the
year. The complexity of these currents reflects that of the sea's
structure. In addition, the Mediterranean tides are weak, an extremely
significant feature which facilitates shipping, but at the same
time is detrimental to the problems of pollution along the coast.
<P>
The Mediterranean basin lies at the centre of a very intricate
patchwork formed by tectonic plates of the earth's crust sliding
under one another. This gives rise to strong seismic and volcanic
activity, which many times leads to tragic human upheavals.
<P>
The four major river deltas (Rhone, Ebro, Po and the Nile) are
considered as unstable areas, in the sense that they are very
sensitive to variations in the sea level, with rapidly alternating
periods of erosion and sedimentation, reflected by advancing or
retreating shore-lines.
<P>
The sea-level changes experienced in the Mediterranean also aggravate
the fresh water situation, a scarce resource in most parts of
the region, as saltwater intrusion &quot;pollutes&quot; the aquifers.
<P>
Against this background of a highly fragile physical environment
the Mediterranean countries are facing similar rapid resource
depletion and environmental deterioration due to demographic,
social, cultural, political and economic pressuresThese environmental
scenarios require therefore to be studied in their complexity,
using a holistic approach and within a global framework. To reach
this goal, a regional strategy needs to be devised that could
be acceptable to all countries of the Mediterranean. To reach
this goal, a regional strategy acceptable to all Mediterranean
countries needs to be devised.
<H4><B>2. The Regional Strategy</B></H4>

<P>
The strategy which should be aimed at political, scientific and
business levels should facilitate the introduction and implementation
of an Integrated Resource Management approach at the local, national
and regional level.
<P>
Primarily, the strategy has to define what constitutes an integrated
approach, secondly, what will be the objectives of such an approach
and thirdly, what are the tools to achieve effective results.
<P>
The fundamental approach of Integrated Resource Management is
based on the premise of shared information, that is, an easy flow
of data from one sector to another. The revolutionary aspect of
this approach will be that information passes not only vertically,
i.e. it follows not only the usual hierarchical organizational
structure, but information flows also occur laterally, that is,
from one sector to another. The latter flow is then not necessarily
restricted towards the top of the sector, as it may indeed occur
predominantly at the level where the actual data is required.
The basic idea of IRM is based on open networks, the size and
the number of the points in the network depending on the task
in hand.
<P>
The short-term and long-term benefits of Integrated Resource Management
will be in having all the necessary data available whenever a
need presents itself, thus enabling both prompt and sound decision-making.
<P>
The tools required for IRM are clear: a data communications technology
infrastructure on a regional scale which would also allow for
real-time transmission from satellites and their data input to
strategic GIS nodes. These GIS data centres will collect, store
and have the facilities to utilize instantly information on the
environment, especially on coastal and marine resources as diverse
as water quality, fish stock movement, coastal urbanization impacts,
sea level fluctuations, coastal dynamics and so on.
<P>
Through the use of GIS and mathematical modelling capabilities
it will become possible to establish the carrying capacity of
any coastal resource; as well as to detect and contain natural
and manmade hazards, such as coastal erosion, effluent overflows,
oil spills, etc.
<P>
It is clear that the combined use of remote sensing, GIS and a
modern data communication infrastructure presents a necessary
condition to carry out resource management and coastal zone management
on a national and regional scale. However, for such management
to be effective it will be furthermore required that the above
tools are utilized and understood in a wider political, cultural
and economic context.
<H4><B>3. The Mediterranean Action Plan (MAP)</B></H4>

<P>
The presently existing regional diplomatic infrastructure is offered
through the Mediterranean Action Plan of the United Nations Environment
Programme (UNEP/MAP).
<P>
UNEP/MAP was set up in 1975 by the signatories to the Barcelona
Convention. It operates on a relatively small budget and is currently
concerned mainly with monitoring the Mediterranean environment
through MEDPOL. MEDPOL, with the assistance of about 200 scientific
groups from 83 institutions in 16 countries, gathers data on the
state and trends of pollution in the Mediterranean and carries
out research projects.
<P>
MAP marked the start of an international cooperation to clean
up the Mediterranean Sea. The Barcelona Convention has so far
provided the essential framework for common action and regional
decision-making.
<P>
Another element of MAP, the Blue Plan, looks ahead to the first
25 years of the next century and predicts dramatic demographic
change. According to its findings, the south, which had 32 % of
the Mediterranean countries' population in 1950, will account
for about 60 % in 2025. An estimated 400% increase in population
is predicted over these 75 years. As well as an increased resident
population, the region could experience the arrival of 158 million
tourists by 2000 and 260 million by 2025.
<P>
A newly established Regional Activity Centre(RAC) of MAP deals
with Environmental Remote Sensing(ERS). RAC/ERS is stationed in
Scanzano, Sicily. Amongst its recommendations it mentions the
monitoring of oil spills in the region, with the use of repetitive
satellite coverage. If the financial means and the political will
are found to achieve this particular aim, each coastal state would
benefit from such an early-warning system which could detect oil
spills before reaching the respective coasts and hence prevent
their contamination. Such a remote sensing operation should be
the first exercise of a regional integrated coastal zone management
infrastructure.
<H4><B>4. Some perspectives on integrated coastal zone management
</B> </H4>

<P>
More than 35% of the international trade in crude and refined
petroleum products is crossing the Mediterranean Sea, which is
very vulnerable to pollution, both from the ships carrying such
products as from coastal refineries and loading and unloading
terminals.
<P>
The most recent large-scale tanker disaster in Mediterranean waters
was the Haven explosion on 11 April 1991, when a Cypriot tanker
caught fire and exploded while at anchor, seven miles off Genoa
in Italy. The tanker, which carried 144,000 tonnes of crude oil
at the time, broke into three parts and it is estimated that more
than 10,000 tonnes of fresh and partially burnt oil were spilled
into the sea before the ship sank. Collection of the burnt residue,
which was highly viscous at ambient temperatures, proved very
difficult. The Italian authorities concentrated on deploying booms
to protect beaches but gale force winds soon carried both oil
and booms ashore.
<P>
Within the week following the incident, floating oil affected
beaches to the west of Genoa and strong winds buried oil in sand.
Some oil spread as far as the Hyeres near Toulon in France. The
coast of Monaco was also affected. It took ten days before divers
were able to stop the main leakage from the wreck.
<P>
In the same month about 140 people were killed when the ferry
Moby Prince collided in thick fog with an oil tanker moored in
the Italian port of Livorno.
<P>
The Paris-based Economic and Maritime Research Agency (Economar),
has shown concern that the multiplication of very fast passenger
ships on routes which are plied by large carriers, could result
in the repetition of similar or even worse accidents, and has
suggested that the Mediterranean should impose a system of compulsory
navigation control similar to that existing for aviation.
<P>
A radar system operating from a shore-based control and a monitoring
station would track ships' movements and make radio contact with
their masters to determine the identity of the ships and their
destinations. The shore station staff would then be able to advise
the ships on route-finding to help avert any potential collisions.
However, this plan, which has the support of the United Nations
Environment Programme's Mediterranean office, is being strongly
resisted by tanker owners.
<P>
While major incidents draw attention to the Mediterranean's problems,
the insistent background pollution must be considered equally
serious. Every year about 650,000 tonnes of hydrocarbons are released
in the Sea mostly through deliberate discharge of bilge and ballast
water from ships. New industries and industrial processes mean
that the cargoes are increasingly hazardous. Petroleum products
are not the only problem. Increased sea transport of industrial
chemicals, often carried on roll-on ferries, brings a growing
danger of accidental spills of toxic material.
<P>
The above mentioned cases are just a few examples of not necessarily
connected events and scenarios that could be monitored effectively
if a regional technological infrastructure can be put in place.
<H4><B>5. A Mediterranean Communication Technology Infrastructure
</B> </H4>

<P>
The establishing of a Mediterranean communication technology infrastructure
is a momentous task which cannot be achieved in isolation. The
European Union has already initiated and developed programmes
and projects in the last decade, which if extended to the Mediterranean
region could prove of mutual benefit. The present policy of the
EU for the Mediterranean encompasses programmes that deal with
Euro/Med partnerships such as Avicenne; Life; MedCampus; MedInvest;
MedSpa etc. Such programmes are meant to develop human networks
which would lead to other cooperative projects in the future.
These networks would be enhanced if supported by a regional data
communications infrastructure.
<P>
Moreover, it should also be realized that if the Mediterranean
is kept out of the communication technologies evolving in Europe,
it would create a future imbalance of development and standardization.
<H4><B>6. Telecommunications policy of the European Union</B>
</H4>

<P>
The Maastricht Treaty calls for the establishment of Trans-European
Networks which implies the preparation of guidelines for the introduction
of Broadband Networks in the Community. The Treaty foresees actions
favouring the interconnection and interoperation of the national
networks and the access to these networks, taking into account
the necessity to link the peripheral regions, that is the EFTA
countries, and in the more distant future, the Central and Eastern
European countries, with the central regions of the Community.
It does not consider the Mediterranean region.
<P>
Indeed, a far-sighted approach that should be the immediate concern
of the Mediterranean countries is to already adopt and adapt measures
to ensure the interoperability of data communications networks
and applications. Such a conformity in the overall technological
infrastructure will enable North South and East West communication
and will facilitate the integrated coastal zone management possibilities
in the Mediterranean.
<P>
The measures to be taken to ensure the interoperability of data
communications networks and applications are fourfold: they concern
the needs for common architectures, standardization, information
and training, and provision of data communications bearer services.
<H4><B>7. Architectures</B></H4>

<P>
One of the main difficulties in setting up networks between administrations
is the diversity and incompatibility of the national systems,
each of which has been developed separately but which must now
be interconnected and made interoperable. The definition and introduction
of jointly devised architectures is one way of solving the problem
while at the same time cutting down investment and operating costs.
<P>
The main purpose of a common data communications architecture
for networks between administrations will, therefore, be to create
and optimize the conditions under which the administrations independent
information systems are to intercommunicate over the telecommunications
networks.
<H4><B>8. Standardization</B></H4>

<P>
Since the major objective in the implementation of efficient data
communications networks is interoperability between the various
parts of a particular network and between different networks,
the use of common message formatting and communication standards
is a condition of success.
<H4><B>9. Information and training</B></H4>

<P>
In addition to all these activities, awareness campaigns will
aim to inform and train administrations directly and indirectly
concerned by the issues of trans Mediterranean and international
data communications networks, and to facilitate coordination and
monitoring between administrations at national and regional levels.
<H4><B>10. Bearer services</B></H4>

<P>
Finally, analysis of users' needs in the various areas of administration
involved in data interchange shows that three types of bearer
service will generally be required: electronic mail, file transfer
and access to databases for interrogation or updating.
<H4><B>11. The Potentially Leading Organisation in the Mediterranean:
CEDARE</B></H4>

<P>
The &quot;Centre for Environment and Development for the Arab
Region and Europe&quot; (CEDARE); may well prove to be the organization
to take on the task of leading the region to develop a data communications
infrastructure and to advocate a regional integrated coastal zone
management. At its first focal point meeting which took place
in Cairo in June 1993, a general consensus showed that CEDARE
should play an active role in creating a regional network enabling
multi-lateral cooperation. At an earlier meeting of its Technical
Advisory Committee, members recommended that CEDARE could be instrumental
in the collection, assessment and dissemination of information,
as well as the vehicle for introduction of new ideas, methodologies
and technologies in the region. More recently, CEDARE also decided
to set up an Information Service Unit (ISU), based on a modular
style, which could mean the start of a much larger information
network.
<H4><B>12. The Middle East Peace Accord</B></H4>

<P>
Last year's historic peace accord in the Middle East may well
prove to be the gateway to a new type of cooperation in the region.
It should give rise to new opportunities for economic growth which
will lead to prosperity on the one hand, but could contribute
further to the region's environmental degradation on the other.
However, with the right communication infrastructure and the right
management approaches, local and foreign businesses will be able
to grow and flourish. Set in an integrated management atmosphere,
a different economic culture may develop. These companies will
come to deal with environmental issues as matters of a strategic
concern. This means treating the environment as integral to overall
business planning and decisionmaking, and managing it as such.
<P>
These practices will, in the long-term, create wealth and propel
the Mediterranean towards prosperity and long lasting peace. 
</BODY>

