<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jovan Kurbalija">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H3>Monday, November 27, 1995</H3>
<HR>

<P>
IT-policy and the Use of information and communication technology
in the German Foreign Office
<P>
Mr. Pius Fischer, Head of the Section for IT Policy
<P>
German Foreign Office
<P>
Presentation of IT-projects of Foreign and Commonwealth Office
<P>
Head of Strategy Group
<P>
Foreign and Commonwealth Office, London
<P>
Panel discussion with participation of the representatives of
German and UK Foreign Office
<P>
National experiences in the use of IT in the German and British
Foreign offices were shared through separate presentations by
Mr Fischer, Head of the IT section of the German Foreign Office
and Mr Bradford, Head of Strategy Group of the British Foreign
Office. The experiences were further deliberated upon in the ensuing
panel discussion.
<P>
The salient points of Mr Fischer's presentation on IT were: A)
to make work easier and more effective, to speed up transmission
of information and instant access to information; B) to facilitate
communication between missions and ministries of the German Government;
and, C) cooperative decision making, coordination and participation
in decision making through IT.
<P>
He elaborated upon achievements of the German Foreign Office in
the use of IT tools. It was an impressive expose of the high degree
of computerization in various German offices. He informed the
group that there were seven thousand users in the German Foreign
Service and so far 229 Missions have been connected on a Wide
Area Network. The system was used as a world wide network based
on modern technology and customized according to each user's requirements.
The German Foreign Office has arranged extensive training facilities
at headquarters, as well as, in missions which made easy the task
of utilizing the systems potential to the maximum. The system
ensured adequate confidentiality and security against any unauthorized
use. Participants appreciated the achievements but probed specifically
into areas of security management of the system and the cost factors.
<P>
The British representative's presentation mainly focused on the
dismal performance of the system in the late Eighties and early
Nineties when it was adopted without the thoughtful planning and
assessment of available resources. The British FCO had to incur
a net loss of twenty million pounds due to erroneous planning.
However, the situation was quickly rectified in the light of the
Wilding Report of 1978 and Coopers and Lybrand Report of April
1991.
<P>
He was quite candid in admitting that the in built conservatism
of the FCO in adopting new technologies was also responsible for
problems. He then listed certain contributing factors: lack of
resources, security aspects and personnel reluctance to switch
over to new technologies as key reasons for the comparatively
slow introduction of IT in the FCO. However, at the same time
he briefed the group about benefits which can accrue from the
adoption of IT in Foreign Services in a strategic manner. He also
suggested that IT should not be implemented for the sake of modernization
of office methods but in accordance with the specific requirements
otherwise it can prove counter productive. He also stated that
in order to create a culture for the implementation of IT a mix
of rewards and punishments along with change in organizational
structure and planning methods were a pre requisite. He advocated
a cautious approach in this regard and warned about high costs
both in terms of wastage of financial and human resources if proper
planning was not adopted. He also highlighted the fact that to
secure adequate funds for IT, the FCO had to embark upon a concerted
campaign of redundancy of staff. So far 390 jobs at various levels
had been retrenched and another 150 would be surrendered soon.
<P>
Mr Bradford's pragmatic presentation appealed to participants
who acknowledged the need for proper planning in view of the peculiar
developing structure of their economies and financial constraints.
<P>
The panel discussion was very stimulating in view of the shared
concerns and fears about the future and impact of IT in the foreign
services of developing countries. While Mr. Fischer optimistic
about the implementation of IT in the German Public Service, Mr.
Bradford pleaded for a cautious approach to avoid wastage of human
and financial resources. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
