<HEAD>

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jovan Kurbalija">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
Monday, November 20, 1995
<H3><A HREF="#opening">Official opening</A></H3>

<P>
Twenty one <A HREF="partic.htm">participants</A> from sixteen
Commonweatlh countries were welcomed to the Workshop on the Use
of Information Technology in International Relations in Malta,
by Dr Jovan Kurbalija, Head of Unit for Computer Applications
in Diplomacy, <A HREF="http://www.medac.comnet.mt">Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, </A>University
of Malta , Mr. Henry Alamango, Director of the <A HREF="http://www.comnet.mt">Commonwealth Network in Information Technology for Development (COMNET-IT).</A>as
well as Professor Fred Tanner, Director of the Mediterranean Academy
of Diplomatic Studies.The two institutions, sited in Malta were
co-sponsors of the Workshop in collaboration with the Maltese
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Representatives of the Maltese Ministry
of Foreign Affairs, the Commonwealth Secretariat, and students
from the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies in Malta
were also in attendance at the opening session.
<P>
The Workshop was officially opened by Ambassador Victor Camilleri,
Permanent Secretary in the Maltese Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
In his <A HREF="#framework">address</A> he took note of the fact
that the Workshop was being held within the context of Malta's
Third Country Programme which had recently been launched jointly
with the Commonwealth Secretariat and which, with the involvement
of COMNET-IT, would promote human resource development in Commonwealth
countries to bridge the gap between the developed and developing
countries in the acquisition of new technologies. Ambassador Camilleri
underscored the fact that &quot;... with the media and communication
explosion, diplomacy is being transformed into a new state-of-the-art
technological information network- a global village - where the
management of political, eonomic and social issues can be conducted
through the information superhighways, amongst which was the Internet...making
it possible to bring minds together, in thinking together, in
acting together in meeting the challenges of the new millenium.&quot;
<P>
The reception which followed the official opening provided an
opportunity for the participants to engage in meaningful discussion
with invited guests on a number of related issues..<HR>

<H3><A HREF="#framework">General Framework of the Workshop</A>
</H3>

<H5>Major Objectives of the Workshop</H5>

<UL>
<LI>To introduce the use of Information Technology in International
Relations to small Commonwealth developing and other states with
limited resources.
<LI>To contribute to the overall strengthening of the capacity
of the countries concerned in both conducting their external relations
and participating in a meaningful manner in subregional, regional
and worldwide diplomatic activities.
</UL>

<H5>Conceptual Approach and Methodology</H5>

<P>
The workshop activities were coordinated by Dr. Jovan Kurbalija.
Interaction was based on a conceptual and practical approach which
included the traditional format of lectures/seminars as well as
IT-based slide and multi-media presentations. Each module was
followed up by computer simulation exercises.Participants were
exposed to the varied experiences of other governments and managers
in the acquisition and implementation of information technology
in diplomatic activities by way of presentaions from representatives
of the governments of Malta, the United Kingdon and Germany as
well as representatives of the Malta Systems Unit Ltd. Particular
attention was paid to the efforts of Malta- a developing country
aspiring to membership of the European Union - in the application
of information technology in the conduct of its international
relations.
<P>
An Electronic Embassy, comprising five fully equipped computers
with multi media and Internet facilites, was set up at the workshop
to provide participants with daily practical experience in the
use of computer hardware and software applications, such as word
processing, spread sheets, databases which could be particularly
helpful in offfice automation. It was agreed that as a conclusive
exercise participants would create a Home page for the Workshop
on the Internet.<HR>

<H3>Opening of Electronic Embassy</H3>

<P>
The first session provided participants with an overview of the
various IT facilities which were available in the Electronic Embassy.
These included electronic mail and the Internet which were the
two areas of IT to which participants were hitherto least exposed
within the context of Diplomacy and International Relations. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
