<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Preliminary Programme</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>INTRODUCTION<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Alberto BIN</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>, Deputy Director
&amp; Holder of the Italy Chair of Mediterranean Diplomacy and
Relations, Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, Malta
</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
Today, the Mediterranean region is characterised by a multitude
of problems and challenges. They include wide socio-economic disparities
among the coastal states, migratory pressure, environmental degradation,
political instability and the expansion of various forms of extremism,
in addition to other sources of tension such as ethnic and minority
issues, boundary disputes, conflict over resources and arms proliferation.
<BR>

<P>
On the southern shores of the Mediterranean in particular, the
consequences of economic problems and population explosion contribute
to exacerbate an already difficult socio-political situation.
In part, this is the result of the disequilibrium between the
levels of development on the northern and southern shores of the
Mediterranean. Socio-economic tensions and potentially unstable
political systems affect the domestic situation in many countries
of the southern shore, fuelling migration towards Europe and forming
a fertile ground for the development of religious extremism. In
addition to that, the concentration of military arsenals in the
area remains at alarming levels because of a preoccupation with
declared and potential conflicts.<BR>

<P>
Within this degree of diversity of risks and challenges, there
is a clear interrelation in security terms among the countries
of the region, deriving mainly from their growing interdependence.
This interrelation suggests the need for a cooperative approach
to security. Indeed, only co-operation will make it possible to
tackle and solve the problems of security and latent instability
in the Mediterranean.<BR>

<P>
Actually, attempts at generating a dialogue on issues of direct
interest to the countries in the region have a fairly long history
dating back to the early 1970s. The immediate cause for their
ineffectiveness is to be found in the conditions prevailing at
the time of the East-West confrontation. The end of the Cold War
and the breakthroughs in the Middle East peace process have lifted
many of the constraints on regional co-operation in the Mediterranean.
Indeed, many comprehensive or partial co-operation initiatives
have seen the light of the day since the collapse of the Berlin
Wall. <BR>

<P>
Among the initiatives aimed at establishing a regional co-operation
framework the EU-sponsored Euro-Mediterranean Partnership deserves
special mention. In June 1994, at their meeting in Corfu, the
Heads of Government of the European Union asked the EU Commission
to provide an evaluation of the existing Euro-Mediterranean policy
and to make proposals for strengthening it. The Commission responded
to this request with a document which proposed the creation of
a regional partnership and led to endorsement at the European
Council in Essen in December 1994 of a new approach to relations
with the Mediterranean countries. On 27-28 November 1995, the
fifteen EU member countries and twelve Mediterranean states (Morocco,
Algeria, Tunisia, Egypt, Israel, Palestine, Jordan, Lebanon, Syria,
Turkey, Cyprus and Malta) met in Barcelona and approved a blueprint
for an ambitious Euro-Mediterranean Partnership aimed at fostering
free-trade and closer co-operation in the region. The Partnership
embraces politics and security, economic and financial development,
and social, cultural and human affairs.<BR>

<P>
To examine current security trends and prospects for co-operation
in the Mediterranean in the wake of the Barcelona Conference,
the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, University of
Malta, organized a two-day Colloquium on &quot;Co-operation and
Security in the Mediterranean: Prospects after Barcelona&quot;,
on 22-23 March 1996, in Malta. <BR>

<P>
The Colloquium sought to promote a constructive exchange of views
on issues of security, stability and co-operation in the Mediterranean
following the establishment of the Euro-Mediterranean Partnership.
It brought together over thirty experts from the Mediterranean
region, Europe and the United States, representing governments,
international organizations, foreign policy institutes and the
academic community. A number of these individuals made presentations
at the Colloquium and their papers are included in this volume.
<BR>

<P>
The papers collected in Part One and Part Two discuss the outcome
of the Barcelona Conference as seen from the Northern and Southern
rim of the Mediterranean respectively. Part Three examines various
aspects of Mediterranean security and co-operation. Although contributors'
opinions may diverge on specific political, economic or socio-cultural
issues, a consensus seems to emerge on the importance of the process
started in Barcelona as a milestone in the relations between Europe
and its Mediterranean neighbours. <BR>

<P>
It is hoped that the papers contained in this volume will contribute
to a better informed debate on the multiplicity of issues and
challenges confronting the Mediterranean on the eve of the 21<SUP>st</SUP>
century. <BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
