<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>INTERNATIONAL COLLOQUIUM</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>ECONOMIC SECURITY IN THE MEDITERRANEAN<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Salvino BUSUTTIL</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>, Director-General,
Foundation for International Studies, Valletta</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
<B>I. Introduction<BR>
</B>
<P>
While populations around the shores of the Mediterranean are bound
together by shared historical experience, cultural exchanges and
trade, there are still some striking differences at an economic
level. On the northern shores Italy, France and Spain have a fundamental
role in setting the EU's Mediterranean agenda whilst smaller countries
like Portugal and Greece reflect the challenges and constraints
confronting peripheral but relatively developed regions in southern
Europe. On the southern shores of the Mediterranean, there are
countries which, confronting severe socio-economic problems, experience
the rise of fundamentalism.<BR>

<P>
However, even within the poorer regions of the Mediterranean region,
certain differences subsist. Attempts towards regionalism have
not been markedly successful (a case in point being the Union
of the Arab Maghreb (UMA)) largely due to divergent socio-economic
policies and lack of economic complementarity among the members
as well as political instability. Turkey and Egypt have a combined
population of over 100&nbsp;million, with population growth rising
at around 2.5 per cent per annum. Demographic problems are expected
to create further socio-economic pressures within the region.
On the other hand, Malta, Cyprus and Israel are countries which
have registered exceptional economic growth, compared to the rest
of the Mediterranean non-member countries (MNC) and also to the
northern Mediterranean EU members. <B>II. Priority economic areas
<BR>
</B>
<P>
The main economic areas for the co-operation in the Mediterranean
region in the aftermath of Barcelona (November 1995) may be summarised
s follows :<BR>

<OL>
<LI>Energy, Water, Telecommunications, Transport infrastructure
<LI>Household Food Security, Agriculture and Agro-Industry
<OL>
<LI>Industrial Development, with special reference to micro-enterprises
and small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) and technology creation
<LI>Trade and Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) and the Globalisation
Process 
</OL>

<LI>Environment
<LI>Tourism 
</OL>

<P>
The above list, which is not presented in order of priority, must
be considered in its socio-political context, with particular
reference to the observance of human rights and to the problem
of immigration from the southern to the northern shores. I shall
now comment on each problem area <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. Energy, Telecommunications and Transport Infrastructure
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Investment in infrastructure, especially in water production and
management, in energy and in transport, is a pre-condition for
business investment and a contributor to economic growth, employment
creation and international competitiveness. A large proportion
of the Structural and Cohesion funds in Southern Europe has been
channeled into infrastructural projects. The European Investment
Bank (EIB) has been very active in strengthening the infrastructure
across the Mediterranean countries. Further public investment
is however required in sewage works, waste disposal, telecommunications,
water supplies and energy and road transport.
<P>
Better infrastructure, especially within the rural areas, plays
a crucial role in alleviating poverty. A strengthened road transport
network enables marketing of agricultural products and easy access
to health, education and other services, particularly within peripheral
areas in countries like Algeria, Egypt, and Turkey. There also
needs to be adequate maintenance of road systems, hence necessitating
investments in specialised human resources and equipment. Environmental
infrastructure should also be placed high on the policy agenda
in the Mediterranean region, including measures to achieve better
energy efficiency and promote clean alternative energy sources
(wind or solar).<BR>

<P>
The water crisis is endemic in most southern Mediterranean countries
and islands and is increasingly affecting northern Mediterranean
countries, including France, Spain, Italy and Greece. Demand is
increasing for agricultural, residential and industrial purposes
and thus one of the main challenges confronting all Mediterranean
countries is to design strategies for water reuse and production.
Further investments are required in sewage treatment and desalination
plants. Furthermore there should be sustained efforts towards
monitoring water supply. The need becomes imperative given the
effects of global warming and consequent climatic change.<BR>

<P>
Infrastructure still remains the domain of the public sector and
is expected to remain such in this region. The proposed Mediterranean
Corporation for Industrial Development (see section 3) should
identify other sources of funding to upgrade the infrastructure
in some Mediterranean countries.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. Household Food Security, Agriculture and Agro-Industry
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Agriculture and agro-industry constitute one of the most important
economic areas on both northern and southern shores of the Mediterranean.
Although its share in gross domestic product has fallen in most
countries over the past years, the sector remains one of the main
employers. In several southern Mediterranean countries, a food
subsidy system has been in place to protect household food security,
although budgetary constraints have tended to reduce the coverage
and cost of the subsided products. Malnutrition is not as severe
as in most Sub-Saharan countries but there are vulnerable groups,
especially babies, young children, young mothers and old persons,
who suffer from basic nutritional deficiencies.<BR>

<P>
The priorities in this field are the introduction of appropriate
marketing, pricing, tax and exchange rate policies; investment
in rural infrastructure, health and sanitation and education facilities.
Although these issues fall internationally within the mandate
of the World Bank International Monetary Fund and the Food and
Agriculture Organisation (FAO), yet their economic impact suggests
that there should be more policy-oriented agricultural research
in the region with continuous monitoring of the effects of the
structural adjustment process on household food security, including
the design of measures which need to be introduced at an early
stage to minimise any adverse effects that such a process could
generate.<BR>

<P>
The Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research
(CGIAR) plays an important role within the applied research context,
especially through IFPRI (International Food Policy Research Institute)
based in the United States and ICARDA (Syria). however, there
is scope for a more regionally-focused initiative concerning food
security and nutrition in the Mediterranean region. A Centre could
be set up under the general direction of the specialised research
institute ICAMAS (International Centre for Advanced Mediterranean
Agronomic Studies) based in Paris and with the support of the
EU and FAO, to compile a database which gathers information on
current food demand, forecasts and nutritional status at a micro
level through longitudinal studies using national food and nutrition
surveys. Such studies must be launched at a regional level. The
Centre would liaise with the different National Food and Nutrition
Centres, monitoring the health and diet status of the target populations
and offering recommendations to national and international organisations.
<BR>

<P>
Moreover, the future of agriculture and agro-industry in the southern
Mediterranean countries and of the workers dependent on this industry
lies in the expansion and diversification of trade, upgrading
of product quality, and increasing off-farm employment opportunities.
There is also the need for greater investment in food storage
facilities and new agricultural technologies, in particular drip-irrigation
techniques, and small and medium-scale irrigation schemes. In
the case of some countries/regions, there is the potential to
link agriculture and tourism activities or agriculture and craft
industries. 
<P>
There needs to be a clear commitment by all Governments within
the Mediterranean to liberalise regional trade, especially within
the agriculture and agro-industrial sector, and to support the
creation of new micro-enterprises or small industrial activities
which supply larger units (on a sub-contracting basis or through
the industrial districts concept, which has operated so efficiently
in some regions in Italy). Finally, agricultural co-operatives
at both production and marketing levels should also be supported.
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. Industrial Development, Small and Medium-Sized
Enterprises (SMEs) and Technology Creation<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Industrial development in MNCs is rather unbalanced and of a dualistic
nature. The role of the state has also been traditionally extremely
predominant in the productive activities of the economy in most
southern Mediterranean countries. Thus the main challenges confronting
most countries is a diversification process, away from apredominance
of sectors based on cheap labour costs (textiles and wearing apparels)
and the exploitation of natural resources or agricultural raw
materials to the identification of new market niches and the promotion
of the quality concept in industry. Within this context, it is
important to set in place systems of standards, certification
bodies and testing and calibration laboratories. New export opportunities
depend on the ability to diversify the range of goods offered,
product differentiation and specialisation in high-quality products.
Another priority is to support micro-enterprises and SMEs in their
export marketing strategies through regional trade liberalisation,
stimulating and nurturing entrepreneurs.<BR>

<P>
There also needs to be a socio-economic context conducive to growth,
especially through the encouragement of market mechanisms and
through favouring social factors (education), and political stability
to foster technology creation, rather than traditional and conventional
technology transfer as such. 
<P>
The success of this new technology policy is largely dependent
on how adaptable local factors of production are to changing technological
requirements, the two fundamental pre-requisites being improved
manpower training and the strengthening of the basic infrastructure.
Two areas of potential development in the Mediterranean area are
irrigation schemes and marine industrial technology.<BR>

<P>
Marine technology is an area which indicates a tremendous technological
gap between the northern and southern shores of the Mediterranean.
In this context a Mediterranean Centre for Research and Development
in Marine Industrial Technology would not only reduce such a gap
but could also identify specific needs (for example, water production)
and develop, on the Eureka <I>partenariat </I>model, suitable
technology (for example, solar desalination) to fill those needs.
<BR>

<P>
It is also recommended that a Mediterranean Corporation for Industrial
Development be established, one that could be modelled on the
existing Centre for Industrial Development (CID) between ACP countries
and the EU under the Lom&eacute; Convention and will be mainly
concerned with SME development. The main difference between the
existing CID and the proposed Mediterranean entity is that it
would not only act as a support service but would also be a financial
institution on the same lines as the World Bank's affiliate -
the International Finance Corporation. Thus, the Corporation would
provide finance and investment expertise and raise funds from
international markets, tapping venture capital. A necessary pre-requisite,
of course, would be the development of efficient financial networks,
a strengthened legal and accounting system and the emergence of
a sense of entrepreneurism.<BR>

<P>
The role of the Corporation would encompass all existing programmes
- BC-Net, BRE, Med-Invest and European Community Investment Partners
(ECIP) - and further strengthen the support services component
to development agencies, chambers of commerce, federation of industries
and individual firms within MNCs. this would hence include the
evaluation of initial requests for project proposals, partner
search, feasibility studies, diagnostic studies about structural
changes within different industrial sectors, the design of industrial
strategies, training, export marketing, assistance in technology
creation and promoting deregulation and privatisation initiatives.
<BR>

<P>
These services will be targeted to SMEs and micro-enterprises
since, as the experience of industrialised countries has shown,
they have a vital role to play in resolving the problems of structural
unemployment and weak economic growth. Although micro-enterprises
normally engage less than 10 employees, they operate across various
activities, including agriculture, handicrafts, trading, services
and manufacturing. They are flexible and adaptable and operate
within that informal sector which, especially in the southern
and eastern Mediterranean, has enjoyed a long tradition.<BR>

<P>
The proposed Corporation could support these firms through subsidiaries
or new specialised institutions (modeled, for example, on the
Grameen Bank in Bangladesh) in the areas of easier access to credit
vocational training and training in financial and business management
techniques, which should particularly enable the activation of
agricultural investment in certain remote rural areas. Such forms
of economic activity create new employment opportunities, contribute
to improved, more equitable living standards through broader and
more even income distribution patterns, support women's activities
and strengthen horizontal and vertical linkages throughout the
economy thus engendering a more integrated and resilient economic
base for more balanced economic expansion. The role of non-Governmental
Organisations (NGOs) is also very important in this context. Furthermore
it is imperative to bear in mind that it is not solely the quantum
of the financial support which is relevant but its planning, management
and co-ordination between Government and private organisations
and NGOs.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. Trade, Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) and
the Regionalism-Globalisation Process<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Future Euro-Mediterranean trade relations will culminate in a
free trade area by the year 2010 up new market opportunities to
southern Mediterranean countries. It is still premature to ascertain
the potential magnitude and direction of the trade creation and
trade diversion effects of the proposed Euro-Mediterranean Partnership
but further market liberalisation can be part of the solution
to the bleak economic situation of many MNCs. In 1992, the trade
balance with the EU was only positive for Algeria, Cyprus and
Syria whilst Israel, Turkey, Lebanon, Tunisia and Egypt each registered
a deficit exceeding 1 billion ecus. With further trade liberalisation,
both under the new Partnership and the World Trade Organisation,
the EU is expected to gradually dismantle several of its existing
trade barriers. It is expected that MNCs will benefit from new
opportunities, particularly on the FDI front.<BR>

<P>
The proposed Corporation would also provide a Foreign Investment
Advisory Service to assist governments in the Mediterranean region
to obtain increased flows of FDI and introduce the necessary laws,
policies, regulations and procedures. FDI requires domestic political
stability, sound economic policies and a minimum of restrictions
on commercial and market forces, thus ushering in capital, management
expertise and technology, given the appropriate infrastructure
in terms of policies and institutions. To this effect, it is important
that the effectiveness of various schemes, such as investment
guarantee schemes, incentives, including fiscal ones, for joint
ventures are evaluated on a country-specific basis. The countries
which seem to have the potential to attract important flows of
FDI due to their strategic position, economic and political stability
and market-based laws and regulations are Malta, Cyprus, Turkey
and Israel. Most of the Maghreb-Mashreq region, with the exception
of Tunisia and to a lesser extent Morocco still suffer from political-economic
problems which have to be addressed prior to the constant inflow
of FDI.<BR>

<P>
Although regionalism is constantly, and rightly, advocated empirically
in a pan-Mediterranean context, yet world trade and investment
is increasingly dominated by global strategies and the dominant
role of multinational corporations. Inter-industry trade, reflecting
large differences in relative factor endowments between two groups
of countries (for example northern Mediterranean and southern
Mediterranean) may increase over the coming decades although this
form of international trade would be &quot;crowded out&quot; by
EU-Central and Eastern Europe trade relations. <B><FONT SIZE=2>5.
Environment<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The Mediterranean region has one of the most fragile environments
at a world-wide level. The potential problems are compounded given
the rising population pressures and competing land and water uses
within relatively limited areas. Environmental issues should be
tackled at a regional or international level given that the problems
have a cross-border dimension. Urgent measures are necessary in
the areas of coastal resource management, tourism development,
agriculture, fisheries and aquaculture and protection of natural
and historic sites. Whilst the recently-created Mediterranean
Commission for Sustainable Development through the UN Mediterranean
Action Plan (MAP) (whose juridical framework is the Barcelona
Convention (1976)) is undoubtedly welcome, it is imperative to
set in place the necessary regulatory and economic instruments.
Environmental policy needs to be fully integrated with other policies.
Within this context, for example, it is high time that tourism
and environmental policy are integrated.<BR>

<P>
There needs to be a regulatory body which oversees the implementation
of existing laws and regulations, including economic instruments
like pollution charges, user charges, resource pricing and fines/fees.
The Commission should also operate a Mediterranean Environmental
Facility (similar to the Global Environmental Facility) to protect
biodiversity in the Mediterranean area and the Mediterranean sea.
Eventually, the Mediterranean Commission for Sustainable Development
could also develop a role as a Mediterranean Environmental Authority.
<BR>

<P>
Finally, attempts should be made to quantify any form of environmental
degradation within the region and account for it within the national
accounting framework, strengthening that regional environmental
information system which, for example the Observatoire Mediterraneen
of the Blue Plan (part of the UN Mediterranean Action Plan) is
operating. A pilot exercise should be launched to quantify the
impact of Mediterranean tourism on the economies and natural environments
of all Mediterranean countries and could eventually be extended
to other sectors - agriculture, industry, energy and transport,
thus introducing green accounting within each Mediterranean country.
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>6. Tourism<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Sustainable tourism development in the region is a priority area.
The proposed creation (by Malta) of a Mediterranean Travel Commission,
modelled on the European Travel Commission, is timely given the
recent Agreement by Mediterranean States to expand the scope of
the Barcelona Convention in monitoring littoral development.<BR>

<P>
It is proposed that from an early stage a close working relationship
be established between the Mediterranean Corporation for Industrial
Development and the Mediterranean Commission for Sustainable Development.

<P>
The setting up of the necessary institutional framework to monitor
the effects of further industrial and tourism development in the
coastal areas across the Mediterranean region becomes of major
importance.<BR>

<P>
<B>III. The challenge<BR>
</B>
<P>
The public and private sectors in each of the countries bordering
the Mediterranean have important challenges for the coming years
to introduce the necessary regulatory measures and create the
right business environment for balanced economic growth and the
promotion of private initiative. Protecting the environment and
integrating environmental policy into industrial, energy, agricultural
and tourism policy should also feature as a priority on the policy
agenda. Four main Centres which would promote and monitor sustainable
economic development in the Mediterranean region are: <BR>

<OL>
<LI>an Agriculture, Food and Nutrition Research Centre; 
</OL>

<P>
(2) a Mediterranean Centre for Research and Development in Marine
Industrial Technology;<BR>

<P>
(3) a Mediterranean Corporation for Industrial Development with
special emphasis on micro-enterprises and SMEs;<BR>

<P>
(4) a Mediterranean Travel Commission.<BR>

<P>
The Mediterranean Commission for Sustainable Tourism can already
provide an important catalyst for most of these proposals and
could, through the legal framework of the Barcelona Convention,
offer a basic institutional structure for consolidation and further
expansion. With the mobilisation of the necessary financial and
political support from all countries in the region it is possible
to tap the necessary human and financial resources so that these
institutions are set up by the end of this decade equipping the
Mediterranean region to better meet the challenges of the next
Millenium.<BR>

<P>
The challenge, then, is to avert those seeds of danger which,
taking root in economic soil, can sprout social and political
pressures, their tentacles menacing military security. More importantly,
the 'new' security of the Mediterranean should be one that guarantees
the application of basic human rights, without whose observance
there can be no stability, military or otherwise.<BR>

<P>
Indeed, economic insecurity may unfold in the Mediterranean, in
a neo-colonialist scenario where hegemony is fomented and exercised
through economic and financial instruments.
<P>
The marked reluctance, for example, of the more advanced European
states to support a Mediterranean development bank has less to
do with the avowed abundance of venture capital than with greed
and the creed of favouring bilateral, rather than multilateral
co-operation, the former allowing that master-client relationship
whose raison d'etre is not, now, the supply of armaments but the
channeling of foreign investment; and this, in such a form and
with such design as to perpetuate a vassal dependence more thrilling
and binding than ever offered by arms.<BR>

<P>
Cicero would today declaim <I>cedant arma economiae</I>, not <I>togae</I>!
<BR>

<P>
That form and design is expressed in a number of ways, such as
the terms of loans and grants, the former in crippling national
debts, the latter, more subtly, in conditions that so regulate
the grant as to compel the client-state to engage the master's
consultants, accept their project and buy the required technology
from the master. More nefariously, the relationship is sometimes
one where the client-state is de facto forced to introduce in
its territory relatively obsolescent and polluting processes.
<BR>

<P>
In rather paternalistic overtures, Barcelona (November 1995) encouraged
southern Mediterranean states to seek private investment, eschew
public ownership and generally to promote market economies in
the belief that the great magic wand of prosperity could only
be waved by capitalism, oblivious to the socio-political structure
of many of these states where the private sector, in so far as
it exists, is often the oligarchic preserve of a closed and restraining
nomenclature. <BR>

<P>
It is important that the north concretely help the south to promote
the private sector, not limiting itself to declamatory rhetoric.
Tourism, too, itself a useful source of foreign exchange and employment
generation for the southern Mediterranean , tends to be manipulated
by a handful of major Western tour operators more bent on a culture
of swift returns rather than that of a tourism based on the enjoyment
of that symbolic and natural heritage which the Mediterranean
has so uniquely assembled for the huddling 'northern' masses.
There, too, the hegemony spreads, the southern states being at
the mercy of the north for the direction and quality of a tourism
they have to 'welcome', at a price which has not only ecological
costs but also deep socio-cultural scars.
<P>
For we witness in fact not the adaptation of the tourist to his
vacation land; but the attempt to 'dress' the authentic south
in the fashion of the northern costume, accentuating that social
change which the western mass media already export to an 'entertainment'
hungry south.<BR>

<P>
It is the 'western' style of life of the north, in its tempting
allure to a youth seeking 'liberation' from the perceived fetters
of inhibiting traditions, that, by the implied superiority of
the economic and political regimes in which it flourishes, abets
the new imperialism enforced by socio-political models.<BR>

<P>
In conclusion, then, one must caution against the notion that
cultural tourism is an altogether socially positive value, or
a necessarily economically productive process. It must be planned
and managed in the socio-economic and socio-cultural setting of
the Mediterranean world and adapted to the traditions and styles
of the different receiving countries in the region. The cost-benefit
result of the exercise should ultimately be, in both economic
and social terms, a plus for those countries; but those responsible
for the promotion and direction of the industry must bear in mind
that at stake are human resources whose management must be inspired
beyond Mammon.<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
