<HEAD>

<TITLE>"European Security and the Mediterranean"</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>EUROPEAN SECURITY AND THE MEDITERRANEAN<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Guido LENZI</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>, Director,
Institute for Security Studies, Western European Union, Paris</FONT>
<HR>

<P>
Here in Malta, a few months ago, we heard President Arafat state
that &quot;security is a way of life&quot; : an important recognition
of the new international attitude in the post-Cold War era, where
confrontation and ideological intransigence have given way to
participation, co-operation and compromise. International security
has undergone radical changes, not only in posture but also in
mentality. Deepening and enlargement are the two directions of
the systemic change that is underway in Europe, with the intent
of projecting security eastward in Mitteleuropa, but also southward
in the Mediterranean. The Barcelona conference, which established
the Euro-Mediterranean partnership, mentioned security only in
its preventive aspects, political and diplomatic, assuming that
the relevant co-operative defence mechanisms would follow suit.
They now have to be addressed openly, without the ambiguities
and misunderstandings of the past.<BR>

<P>
The OSCE established European security mechanisms, which evolved
after the fall of the Wall. Are they suitable for the whole Mediterranean?
And if not, what adjustments could be made to satisfy regional
specificities? The first step can only be broader transparency
and dialogue. Barcelona set a similar framework and method, embracing
the whole region, regardless of the obvious local differences
of situations and perceptions. Security as such was kept aside,
on hold, until other practical prerequisites are in place. The
field should be opened before it can be leveld, and multifaceted
interconnections established, as a prerequisite for transparency,
mutual understanding and trust.<BR>

<P>
In Europe and elsewhere, defence is no longer so much a matter
of territorial defence, but rather of co-operative endeavours,
along the lines drawn by the WEU &quot;common concept&quot;, by
the new &quot;enlargement concept&quot; of NATO, and by OSCE behavioural
principles. This requires, in each country, North and South, not
only more specific commitments and training for peace support
operations, but mainly a more extensive information of public
and parliamentary opinions, to ensure the support that is necessary
for consistency, political sustainability and financing purposes.
<BR>

<P>
This presupposes a more coherent multilateral context, in which
national production of and contribution to security is as important
as the consumption of it, from which many benefitted in the fifty
years under the bipolar stalemate. Furthermore, the new multi-dimensional
and transnational challenges produce at the same time a globalisation
and a fragmentation of the responses. The erosion of state authority
under the pressure of the most varied &quot;self-determinations&quot;
can only be restored by international co-operative endeavours,
in many fields that were up to now the preserve of sovereign national
prerogatives.<BR>

<P>
Today, once a crisis has erupted, it is difficult to intervene,
contain and reabsorb. Prevention and mediatory interposition is
the name of the new game, which implies also interventions in
internal affairs. The UN itself, after the experiences of Somalia
and Bosnia, with their mixture of Chapter 6 and Chapter 7 of the
Charter, is not willing to engage directly in peace enforcement
any more, and will increasingly rely on regional arrangements
duly mandated under the provisions of Chapter 8. Sub-regional
aggregation and agreements are therefore indispensable for stability
and security purposes, which external interventions can only supplement,
not substitute. Especially in the many so-called &quot;out-of-area&quot;
contingencies, ad hoc mechanisms by the &quot;willing and able&quot;
are the most adequate to adjust to the shifting and unforeseeable
combinations and variable factors. Variable geometries and hard
cores apply to every country, whether it already belongs or aspires
to European security architectures (which should in itself dispel
any misperception of a Western hegemonic fortress).<BR>

<P>
This is how things stand in continental Europe. The same principles
and mechanisms should apply to the areas contiguous to it, first
and foremost to the Mediterranean. Strategically, the Mediterranean
area is not a coherent system, its problems are not military in
nature, sub-regional diversities are great. But a common mentality
must spread, similar to that which is applicable to Europe.<BR>

<P>
The WEU &quot;Common concept 27&quot; states that &quot;the Mediterranean
basin is a high priority for European security ... (calling for)
guidelines for co-operation (and) permanent dialogue&quot;, recognising
that there is no direct military threat from the South. Barcelona
has indicated the same initial stepping-stones. Soft security
measures, dispelling misperceptions, could consist in exchanges
of information, an inventory of the commitments undertaken, a
comparison of experiences, a review of co-operative models (for
peacekeeping operations, crisis prevention, consultation, assistance
- in particular within OAU; for non-proliferation; for the containment
of new risks). <BR>

<P>
An evolutionary process is underway, rather than a state of affairs,
in each of our countries, in continental Europe as well as in
the Mediterranean. For mutual relations to develop, the rediscovery
of one's own and each others' identities is a prerequisite, that
must involve the participation of all of the strands of our civil
societies.<BR>

<P>
Even the military instrument is nowadays subjected to these multiple
factors, as it adapts to a new preventive role, under conditions
of greater transparency. Prevention is the overriding requirement,
involvement rather than containment the new imperative. Transparency
and exchange of views and experiences are the essential instruments.
Pluralism of contributions constitute at the same time the goal
and the prerequisite for further advances.<BR>

<P>
In the Mediterranean, the North-South relationship must expand,
but it presupposes a South-South two-way street. European states
individually and the Commission must evolve beyond their bilateral
relationships with North African states. The Fifteen cannot however
deal with the North Africans one by one, lest they be accused
of ganging up: Europe, as Kissinger used to remind Europeans,
needs to dial &quot;one telephone number&quot; to reach most usefully
its North African partners.<BR>

<P>
After the Ministerial Council of Petersberg in June 1992, the
Mediterranean Group of the WEU indicated seven principles that
should inspire the Euro-Mediterranean endeavour in the security
field. They are: dialogue, transparency, confidence, conflict
prevention, sufficiency, peaceful settlement of conflicts and
non-proliferation of armaments.<BR>

<P>
Now that a broader concept of security is being accepted also
in the Mediterranean, the opportunity exists of addressing the
relevant military concepts, starting with CSBMs. They should achieve
transparency (through communications, exchanges, common strategic
language), co-operation (in PKOs also within OAU, humanitarian/civil
protection, nonproliferation and the tackling of new risks), working
groups (for bilateral, trilateral co-operative purposes), and
multinational operational endeavours (such as manoeuvres and exercises).
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
With such CSCMs, collective security would develop, as a process,
incrementally, in the Mediterranean as usefully as in continental
Europe, in the context of the partnership established in Barcelona.
<BR>

<P>
Since Barcelona, WEU within EU and the Mediterranean have a clear
road ahead of them. Political will should combine the evolving
events to provide the energy for all parties concerned to proceed
with a converging purpose, even if with different national contributions.
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
