<center><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;7 - <A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6">INTERNATIONAL
CONVENTIONS</A></H1>

<P>
The need to review the International Conventions on Drugs, and
to stimulate debate on drugs policies and the functioning of International
antidrug policies
<H3><A HREF="#aitkins">Andy ATKINS - United Kingdom  </A>- <A HREF="#cabises">Hugo CABIESES - Peru </A></CENTER>
</H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="aitkins">Andy
ATKINS </A>- United Kingdom</H3>

<H3>''International Conventions: the need to stimulate debate
on drug policies and their enforcement''</H3>

<P>
NGOs should analyse the coherence between drugs and development
policies in general. Drugs policies should not only be based on
international conventions but on a profound analysis of the macro-economic
mechanisms to prevent harm caused by large scale production, trafficking
and use of drugs.
<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
There are two major problems:
<P>
a) Drug consumption, production and trafficking, which I shall
call collectively 'the drug phenomenon', appear to be increasing
in both North and South. This is despite the existence of international
conventions aimed at preventing the phenomenon, to which a large
number countries are signatories.
<P>
b) Drug control efforts are themselves producing negative side-effects
in many countries. These include consequences for human rights
and democracy, the environment and national self-determination,
(all important components in 'development).
<P>
This suggests a need to stimulate debate about drug-control conventions,
specific policies, and the functioning of drug-control agencies
which enforce them. In particular, two sets of issues or questions
need debating:
<P>
a) Concerning the failure of the conventions to prevent a global
increase in the drug phenomenon we need to ask whether the phenomenon
is increasing because:
<UL>
<LI>the current conventions are fundamentally flawed (i.e. different
conventions might prove more successful)?
<LI>the current conventions are sound but are inadequately enforced?
<LI>conventions alone - of any kind - are insufficient to control
a phenomenon which has deep societal, cultural and economic roots?
</UL>

<P>

<P>
b) Concerning the existence of negative side-effects we need to
ask whether they are:
<UL>
<LI>an inevitable result of the design of current conventions:
<LI>a product of the manner in which the conventions have been
interpreted in national legislation (i.e. not intrinsically the
fault of the conventions themselves)?
<LI>a result of the manner in which national legislation is enforced
in practice by drug-control agencies?
<LI>a combination of the above?
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The predominant view expressed by major international players
in drug control (US, UN, EU) is that the drug phenomenon persists
because the current conventions are inadequately enforced. While
officials may acknowledge that the phenomenon is linked to other
processes (macro-economic, social, etc.), in practice it is treated
as independent and self-generating. Questioning of the conventions
themselves appears taboo. Few governments seem prepared to acknowledge
that drug control activities present negative side-effects.
<P>
For many NGOs and other commentators, the conventions themselves
are seriously flawed. They are unlikely to succeed while little
attention is given to the other contributory factors which help
generate the drug phenomenon (such as rural poverty in the South
and social alienation in the North). Moreover the side-effects
are painfully obvious and their gravity calls into question the
wisdom and morality of current policies as well as the manner
of their implementation.
<P>
From this writer's point of view, therefore, behind the failures
and dangers of current drug conventions and policies lies a lack
of coherence between drug control policies and other policies
(economic, human rights, environmental, etc.).
<H3>Current policies and conventions</H3>

<P>
Let us look at the conventions, some of their characteristics,
and some features of the policies which derive from them.
<H5>Key global conventions are:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>the UN's Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs (1961) and its
Protocol (1972) [149 signatory states at November 1994]
<LI>the UN's Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs
and Psychotropic Substances (1988), known as the 'Vienna Convention'.
[103 signatory states at November 1994].
</UL>

<H5>Important characteristics of the conventions:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>they are based on judgements about the medical and moral dangers
of consuming certain natural and synthetised substances.
<LI>they seek to control the production, trade and consumption
of substances classified as dangerous.
<LI>they seek to achieve this control through the total legal
prohibition of some substances or the strict regulation and restriction
of others for approved medical purposes only.
<LI>they oblige states to penalise individuals who produce, trade
or use substances in a manner not approved of by the Convention.
</UL>

<H5>Important characteristics of policies</H5>

<UL>
<LI>National policies largely prohibit the substances proscribed
by the conventions, establishing penalties for those who contravene
national drug-control laws.
<LI>But there is great national and even local variation in the
nature and severity of the penalties set by the law.
<LI>There are also great variations, between nations and within
them, in the degree to which the law is actually enforced.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
From the developmental point of view, this gives rise to several
problems:
<H5>Problems with the conventions:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>they focus on the drug phenomenon as an independent primary
problem which causes others; they barely mention the fact that
it is highly interdependent with other variables (societal, cultural,
economic) and is as much a symptom of other factors. For example
in Latin America, economic adjustment packages and free trade
agreements (which typically reduce state expenditure on agricultural
promotion and cut tariff barriers on imported food), severely
disadvantage the peasant sector. This forces farmers into drug-linked
cultivation in order to survive. In both North and South, the
deregulation of financial markets facilitates money laundering.
And in the North, one factor in drug consumption is urban and
rural deprivation, itself caused or permitted by the interaction
of policies on employment, housing, education, etc.
<LI>The drug conventions have no control over these economic and
social processes which are powerful contributors to the drug phenomenon.
Thus the solutions they offer can only be partial, focusing more
on drug production and consumption <I>per se</I>, than on their
causes.
<LI>The conventions are inconsistent.They exclude certain addictive
and potentially lethal substances such as alcohol and tobacco
yet include other substances, such as the coca leaf, which is
harmless and possibly beneficial in its natural state. This inconsistency
encourages a diversion of effort towards reducing the production
and consumption of certain substances because they are illegal,
when the consumption of two legal substances, alcohol and tobacco,
poses a much more serious public health problem in most countries.
<LI>The conventions represent a particular (and not universal)
moral and cultural view-point as well as medical judgements which
are increasingly contested. This invites tension between states
as some attempt to impose their 'norms' and views on others. This
can be seen both within the North (eg France vs Netherlands) and
between the North and South (eg Bolivia vs Peru).
</UL>

<P>

<P>
From these follow several common components of current drug control
policies, which have serious developmental implications.
<H5>Problems with policies:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>the predominant focus on law enforcement: this has diverted
attention from the economic and social causes of the drug phenomenon
and thus must take some of the blame for the failure to produce
viable and attractive economic alternatives for cultivators of
drug-linked crops.
<LI>forced eradication of drug-linked crops: when demand for the
final drug remains constant, eradication tends merely to displace
illegal crop production to other areas. Moreover, eradication
may compound environmental damage: peasant cultivators with viable
alternatives may move further into forested areas, clear more
land, and replant. Fumigating crops from the air with chemicals,
may also damage soil, food crops and water systems.
<LI>strengthening law enforcement: introducing more severe anti-drug
legislation in both North and South has failed to reduce the drug
phenomenon. In many countries, such laws have undermined civil
rights such as the right to a fair trial. Moreover, where they
are enforced by police with little knowledge of or respect for
human rights norms, this leads to serious human rights violations.
Finally, 'getting tough on drugs' typically criminalises large
numbers of predominantly poor people. This tends to produce a
congestion of the legal system which then fails to cope with arguably
more serious crimes, as well as to inhumane prison overcrowding.
<LI>'militarising' drug control: strengthening law enforcement
by involving the military in drug control duties may risk even
more widespread human rights violations. It also jeopardises the
hard-won gains of democratic sectors in many developing countries
to regain control of the state from the armed forces, and to strengthen
civilian control over domestic law enforcement.
<LI>Conditioning foreign aid on 'drug-control performance': the
experience of the US conditioning aid to Bolivia, for example,
suggests that it may force governments to take risky actions of
questionable value merely to please the donor and avoid financial
penalties. The Bolivian government's drive to meet crop reduction
targets by forcibly eradicating coca without providing alternatives
to farmers, has increased human rights violations and provoked
protests which have threatened national stability.
</UL>

<P>

<H3>Alternative policies and practices</H3>

<P>
In the short term there are a range of options which should be
considered, within the framework of current conventions.This requires
attention to three broad areas as follows:
<P>
a) coherence of drug control policies with human rights norms:

<UL>
<LI>possible action:
<LI>ensure that national drug control legislation does not violate
international human and civil rights norms.
<LI>ensure that NGOs and other sectors of society in developing
countries are accorded a role in monitoring the use of foreign
drug-control assistance.
<LI>deny lethal drug-control assistance to forces (police or military)
with a record of human rights abuse.
</UL>

<P>
b) alignment of drug control policies with developed instruments;
<UL>
<LI>possible action:
<LI>Northern trade blocs (US, UE) could widen the scope of trade
preferences which they have offered to certain drug 'producer'
and 'transit' countries
<LI>Northern donors could direct their aid more effectively, to
help peasant farmers currently growing drug-linked crops to gain
better access to domestic and international markets for 'alternative'
products, including those eligible for preferences.
<LI>Northern blocs could give encouragement to fairly traded products.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
c) Coherence of drug control policies with economic and social
policies:
<UL>
<LI>possible action:
<LI>Northern countries which support drug control in developing
and Central / Eastern European countries could instruct the multilateral
financial institutions (IMF, World Bank, etc) to consider the
implications for drug control and poverty reduction of the economic
policies / packages which they promote.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
In the long term, there is a need for a widespread public and
political debate about the costs and benefits of the prohibition
of drugs, which is the foundation of the current conventions.
Getting official backing for such a debate would itself be an
'alternative policy' when governments currently tend to avoid
such discussion themselves, and criticise others who attempt it.
<P>
Central to this debate is a discussion of priorities. It needs
to be made clear that reducing the drug phenomenon will require
changes in other policies  (economic, social) which may go against
the grain of current orthodoxy in these areas. Thus publics and
politicians need to decide which is more important to them - effective
drug control or these other policies. The public must come to
realise that our own desires and attitudes are often contradictory.
For example, the 'average' Northern citizen would typically be
concerned by human rights abuse but demand 'tough action' against
drugs in the South. She or he may be concerned at poverty in the
South but simultaneously demand cheap food, little realising that
low prices in the North for certain imported commodities are a
cause of poverty in the South.
<P>
Secondly, publics and politicians must be made aware that we must
decide priorities even within the sphere of drug-control. Hypothetically,
for example, controlled legislation of drugs could lead to fewer
people dying from contaminated doses, less crime surrounding the
trade, but far greater numbers of people taking drugs. Continued
prohibition on the other hand may inhibit more people from trying
drugs but lead to many more deaths from impure or over-doses.
Which is preferable? When we have a greater societal discussion,
we are more likely to get a reasonable consensus which leads to
policies which are effective in their own terms.
<H3>Strategies to help bring about alternative policies</H3>

<P>
Some general suggestions on strategies:
<UL>
<LI>identify relevant fora: those interested in changing policy
must identify the bodies with authority over policies with implications
for the drug phenomenon, at international, national and local
levels. From the above, it should be clear that this includes
a much wider group than the United Nations Drug Control Programme
(UNDCP), national government and local police. It includes the
IMF, World Bank, World Health Organisation, numerous ministries
in each country, regional and local authorities, etc.
</UL>

<P>
build alliances: we should seek to build coordinated alliances
which together undertake the task of:
<P>
a) informing about and lobbying for the need for certain changes
within the parameters of current conventions;
<P>
b) promoting discussion about priorities in drug control, alternative
conceptions of drug control (non-repressive, non-prohibitionist,
etc.), and the possible need to revise the conventions themselves.
Key partners in this alliance might be institutions who are regarded
as non-party political, whose work touches on the issue of drugs,
and who carry some moral authority with the general public. Obvious
ones are domestic police forces and the Churches.
<UL>
<LI>promote informed debate / defend free speech: a key task is
to make it legitimate for politicians and others to speculate
about drug policy without suffering fierce criticism. This will
require a concerted effort by alliance to publicly defend the
right to freedom of thought and speech on drug issues and to demand
that drug policy should be de-politicised.
<LI>promote genuine North-South dialogue / resist conditionality:
promoting genuine dialogue (i.e. with no risk of punishment attached
to holding a different view) between countries, cultures and sectors
with very differing attitudes to and policies on the drugs phenomena.
</UL>
<HR>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="cabises">Hugo CABIESES </A>- Peru
</H3>

<H3>&quot;North-South relations and amendment of treaties as regards
the coca leaf&quot;</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
In order to tackle the worldwide problem of drug trafficking and
drug abuse, this contribution proposes amending international
treaties.  Circumstances have changed since the adoption, in Vienna
in 1988, of the United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic
in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances.
<P>
Among these amendments, I suggest a change in the status of the
coca plant, which is a natural resource, a cultural asset and
an ancestral &quot;Andean/Amazonian&quot; plant, but which is
regarded as a narcotic drug and is therefore included on the list
of psychotropic substances.  The 1961 Single Convention on Narcotic
Drugs, which prohibits their use for purposes other than scientific
or medical ones, lists not only cocaine but also the coca plant.
 This decision was taken following the report by the Board of
Enquiry which visited Peru and Bolivia in 1949; the merits of
that report have today been called into question.
<P>
Since 1988,  the Peruvian and Bolivian representations to international
bodies, in particular the Commission on Narcotic Drugs of the
United Nations' Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC), have been
urging a review of the status of the coca plant.  Their proposal
has had its supporters and detractors among the various governments,
but coca plant growers in Bolivia, Colombia and Peru support the
proposal.  In 1991 they set up the CAPHC - Consejo Andino de Productores
de Hoja de Coca (Andean Council of Coca Leaf Producers) through
which they defend their belief, with weighty arguments, that coca
is not synonymous with cocaine, that coca plant growers are not
synonymous with drug traffickers and that a coca leaf user is
not synonymous with a drug addict.
<P>
Farming representatives and CAPHC representatives attended the
last three sessions of the Commission on Narcotic Drugs of the
United Nations ECOSOC in Vienna.  They proposed amending the treaties
as far as the coca plant was concerned.  I attended the sessions
in 1993 and 1994 and was able to put forward our views at the
latter meeting.
<P>
In 1995, Mr Evo Morales, the President of the CAPHC presented
our proposal.  I firmly believe that the most effective and peaceful
way of combatting cocaine trafficking is to withdraw the coca
plant from the list of psychotropic substances, and permit its
processing for beneficial ends, such as the rehabilitation of
drug addicts.
<P>
Paragraph 84 of the 1995 report by the Financial Action Task Force
on Money Laundering (FATF) indicates that the matter will be discussed
in Vienna during the session of 14-25 April.  The report adds
that the Task Force has repeatedly drawn the Commission's attention
to the fact that the opinions and practices of the governments
of Argentina, Bolivia and Peru with regard to licit and illicit
coca leaf production do not comply with the agreements under the
1961 Single Convention (paragraph 84).
<H3>Drug trafficking and the North-South context</H3>

<P>
The production, trafficking and consumption of drugs has become
a worldwide phenomenon and, contrary to the claim that could have
been made in the early 1980s, no country can seriously maintain
today that it remains untouched by the problem or that it is only
a consumer, or a supplier or a launderer of the proceeds of drug
trafficking.
<P>
The terrorist violence and institutional corruption caused by
these illicit activities are no longer confined to the cities
or the countryside of the South.  Responsibility is no longer
bilateral but multilateral.
<P>
Where drugs are concerned, we have moved on from a dependent world
to an interdependent world.  Until the 1980s, the international
division of labour, so to speak, in the drug trade was much more
specialised than it is today.  Specifically:
<P>
a) The raw materials of drugs, namely marijuana, opium poppies
and coca leaf, and the chemicals needed to process them were produced
in no more than 20 countries of the South, in the Andes, the Golden
Triangle and the Golden Crescent.  
<P>
b) Drugs produced in the South, mainly hashish, cocaine and heroine
in that order, were consumed in few countries of the North, and
chiefly in the United States and western Europe.  
<P>
c) The proceeds from drug trafficking were laundered in a few
tax havens, principally small Caribbean islands, and in the financial
centres of major cities in the most developed countries of the
South, such as Mexico City, Buenos Aires, Sao Paolo and so on.
<P>
d) Cartels, &quot;high risk entrepreneurs&quot;, had divided up
the drug trade: North Americans and Mexicans dealt in marijuana,
North Americans and Colombians in cocaine and Italo-Americans
and Afghans, Pakistanis and Thais in opium and heroine.  These
were distinct groups.
<P>
e) Most of the profits from these activities remained in the countries
of the North, and in particular in the hands of North American
and European mafias.  The farmers who grew the raw materials were
the worst off and ended up even poorer than before the boom in
the drug business.
<H3>The present situation</H3>

<P>
Now, in the mid-1990s, the situation is the following:
<P>
a) The raw materials and chemical products used to make drugs
are produced in countries of both the South and the North.  The
United States is currently the world's leading producer of marijuana,
while eastern Europe produces large quantities of opium and hashish.
 The opium poppy, which used to be a middle-eastern and south-east
Asian speciality, is now grown in Colombia, Mexico and Guatemala.
 Only the coca plant cannot be grown in any other region than
the eastern Andes.  At present, the chemicals used in drug production
are made in the North and exported to the South.
<P>
b) Consumption is no longer confined to the North.  Increasingly
large quantities of cocaine and opium paste are being consumed
in various countries of the South, particularly the bigger countries
in which poor people from rural areas are moving to the cities.
 Marijuana, however, was already in use in the South.  Drugs from
the South are less pure than those from the North and they are
consumed especially in the poorest urban areas.
<P>
c) Today the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking is very
widespread.  Virtually the entire international financial system
is involved in these illicit activities.  Attempts by Northern
countries to combat laundering conflict with the interests of
the South, but also and especially with bankers in their own countries.
 There is an obvious contradiction between the freedom of capital
markets, which implies bank secrecy, and the need to control money
from questionable sources.  
<P>
d) Cartels have become international and worldwide.  Today more
than ever, as in any other international business activity, the
concepts of ''collaboration'', ''total quality'', ''research''
and ''flexible production'' have become the strongpoints of cartels
which have not only survived but have actually come through a
fruitless ten-year drug war stronger than ever.
<P>
e) The farmers who grow the raw materials for drugs are still
the bigger losers and are still be used as a bargaining tool between
North and South whenever the drugs question arise.  Their situation
has further deteriorated after more than a decade of promises
of ''alternative development''.  Unfortunately this has never
materialised, and the promises have been kept neither by governments
nor by international co-operation bodies.
<H3>Amending the treaties</H3>

<P>
In short, since the early 1990s, &quot;everyone does everything&quot;
in this high-risk business.  In both North and South there is
drug production, consumption and trafficking.  The phenomenon
has become increasingly multilateral.  Part of the basis of multilateralism
is the existence of and compliance with international treaties
which are accepted and respected by the parties.  International
treaties against drugs are characteristic of the United Nations,
and have existed since before 1944 when the United Nations was
founded.  It has become almost traditional for world conferences
on the subject of drugs to be held every ten or fifteen years.
 On these occasions conventions on drugs are amended to bring
them into line with new circumstances.
<P>
The most recent United Nations convention on drugs dates back
to 1988 when the ten year-old boom in cocaine was at its peak,
marijuana production was well established in California and opium
was not yet being produced in Colombia or Guatemala.  The Berlin
Wall had not yet come down, the Cold War was still a reality.
 But seven years on, it is clear that the convention must be amended
to fit with the times.  But it must be amended chiefly because
it is ineffective: all the measures it recommended to combat drug
trafficking and reduce consumption at the international level
have failed.  One of the amendments to be made to the Convention
is the status of the coca leaf as a narcotic drug, for which reason
it has been on the &quot;black list&quot; since the 1961 Single
Convention.
<H3>What am I proposing?</H3>

<P>
a) Coca is not synonymous with cocaine.  The coca plant grower
is not a drug trafficker.  The coca leaf user is not a drug addict.
 These proposals are very closely linked.  The fact is that we
are protecting a natural resource and two types of people, the
coca plant grower and the coca leaf user.  The international stigma
attaches not only to the product itself but also to the people
who grow it and use it.
<P>
b) The coca plant must be destigmatised, which means it must be
removed from United Nations list I.  To talk about decriminalisation
would not be appropriate here since my proposal could be confused
with the proposal to legalise drugs.  Our campaign in favour of
the coca plant is not in any way a first step towards the decriminalisation
of cocaine, marijuana or any other drug.  It is a mistake to equate
coca, opium and marijuana.
<P>
c) This campaign to reinstate the coca plant and to combat drug
trafficking and drug abuse must be waged on all fronts.  Everyone,
except drug traffickers and those who support them, must rally
to this worldwide cause.  This action in favour of the coca plant
must not be separated from action against drug abuse and drug
trafficking.  There are three battles, one for and two against,
battles which could help us to win a war in which we, the people
and governments of North and South, are all allies.  
<P>
d) At international level, action should begin with the Commission
on Narcotic Drugs of the UN ECOSOC, which has proposed that a
working party be set up.  Once the working party has produced
its report, the Commission on Narcotic Drugs will forward its
proposals to the General Assembly of the United Nations and the
Secretary General will order that a binding resolution be drafted.
<P>
e) The main arguments are scientific, and mainly medical and pharmaceutical,
ones.  Such arguments, which may or may not be correct, were behind
the inclusion of the coca plant on list I.  The evidence which
existed prior to the United Nations debates (1947-1953) is not
sufficient since science has made great advances in 50 years.
<P>
f) I am opposed to drug trafficking and drug abuse, just as I
am opposed to the two policies that are supposed to combat them,
namely the &quot;drugs war&quot; and &quot;alternative development&quot;
in producer countries.  Both policies have proved ineffective.
<P>
g) I am not in support of promoting coca, marijuana or opium poppy
production.  As far as coca is concerned, there has been a substantial
production surplus since the boom in cocaine use.  The two other
plants are not Andean crops and moreover, unlike the coca plant,
they destroy the environment.  At present, even if the coca plant
is removed from the list of narcotic drugs, the surplus needs
to be reduced by voluntary substitution.  I have proposed a model
of comprehensive sustainable rural development with the coca plant
(DRIS-C), and I have calculated that we must allocate no more
than 130,000 hectares to coca plant farming in Bolivia, Colombia
and Peru, for various medicinal and industrial purposes.  From
an agronomical and ecological point of view it is neither possible
nor desirable to increase or even maintain present coca farming
levels to meet the need for this beneficial natural resource.
<P>
Finally,  I maintain that the CAPHC, as an umbrella body for coca
plant producers and users has, and must have, priority place in
this action which must proceed at worldwide level, particularly
during this Decade of Indigenous People.
<P>
The farmers, settlers and indigenous peoples of the Andes who
grow the coca plant are the sole guardians of a resource which
is not only natural but also cultural, and which is an important
component of their vision of the world and their ancestral heritage.
<HR>

