<H1>Introductions</H1>

<H3><A NAME="lemmers">Jos Lemmers </A>, Executive Director of
the North-South Centre of the Council of Europe<BR>
</H3>

<P>
Since its creation in Lisbon, in May 1990, the European Centre
for Global Interdependence and Solidarity of the Council of Europe
- the North-South Centre - has been committed to promoting a global
partnership dialogue on key issues of global interdependence reflecting
the many relations and complex inter-linkages of Europe with other
continents.<BR>
In this respect, the Centre organised several international gatherings
such as the International Colloquy on Democracy and Human Rights
in 1992, the International Encounter on the Role of Women in an
Interdependent World in 1993, the International Conference on
Rwanda in its Regional Context: Human Rights, Reconciliation and
Rehabilitation in 1994, and its first Consultative Assembly in
1996 on the theme &quot;Europe's Role for Greater Solidarity in
an Interdependent World&quot;.<BR>
The unique system of quadripartite co-management of the Centre
by parliamentarians, governments, non-governmental organisations
and local and regional authorities - the <I>quadrilogue </I>-
provides the possibility for a permanent dialogue and exchange
of experiences among people and institutions with different points
of view. The role of the Centre is to bring them together and
to create the circumstances which allow them to communicate, listen
and learn from each other, and to benefit from each other's complementarities.
In this framework, the North-South Centre's Executive Council
decided to convene an International Conference on &quot;Drugs:
Dependence and Interdependence&quot; which will take place in
Lisbon from 23 to 25 March 1996.<BR>
The Conference is organised in partnership with the Brussels based
Environment and Development Resource Centre. This important encounter
will bring together representatives from the four quadrilogue
partners of the Centre and will gather participants from all over
the world who are experts on drugs issues in relation to different
fields of global interdependence: development, environment, social
affairs, health, prevention, information and education, among
others. The drug issue reflects a cruel interplay of market forces
and organised crime in our increasingly interdependent world.
It imposes itself as a self-reinforcing spiral on local communities
in North and South where consumption and production, addiction
and &quot;dealing&quot; have become intertwined daily realities.
The problem has even spread to the official economy and spill-over
effects, through bribes and corruption, have been recorded in
those very sectors and institutions which were designed to control
and fight it.<BR>
Today there is growing awareness that no single element of this
multi-dimensional question should be examined in isolation and
that only a comprehensive and multilateral approach, taking into
account its complex and interdependent nature, will enable society
to come to grips with the issue at root level.<BR>
Incoherent, often even contradictory, measures at micro-level
by a multitude of actors and institutions would seem bound to
fail in the face of a powerful maze of organised forces which
reap the benefits of production and marketing in defiance of sovereignty
or the rule of law. In order to stimulate the debate, experts
from different countries have submitted contributions to the Conference
on the different themes which will be discussed in the working
groups.<BR>
For each theme there is, in most cases, one contribution from
Europe and one from the &quot;South&quot;. These papers, submitted
under the sole responsibility of the authors, reflect experts'
points of view on different questions which will be debated during
the Conference. It is hoped that this procedure will contribute
to lively discussions resulting in practical recommendations based
on a multilateral approach in the quest for lasting solutions
to the drugs problem in an interdependent world<HR>

<P>
.<A NAME="kingham"></A> 
<H3>Ron. A. Kingham, Director of the Environment &amp; Development
Resource Centre</H3>

<H3>The role of Citizens' Associations</H3>

<P>
In the search for international strategies to deal even more effectively
with the issue of drugs, attention needs to be given to the potential
role of citizens and citizens' associations in both the debate
in Europe on the global drug phenomenon and in the implementation
of new European strategies. Because of their long-term experience
in the field, citizens' associations in Eastern and Western Europe,
and their partners in the South, possess valuable knowledge of
the root causes and effects of the drug phenomenon and of the
impact of the current drug control strategies in both producer
and consumer countries. European citizens' associations have several
motives for their initiatives in this field. First, there is the
need to respond to requests from our partners in the South, who
are daily confronted with increasing drug related problems including
those resulting from drug control strategies implemented by European
and international authorities. Secondly, citizens' associations
consider it almost impossible to obtain real, sustainable development
without taking into consideration effective measures towards drug
supply and demand issues. Finally, the setting of the drug issue
in its global, North-South and East-West context is an important
tool in development education activities in which European citizens'
association are involved. In short, strategies and policies to
combat drug-related problems will not be effective unless citizens
are directly involved in designing those strategies and policies
and in implementing them. And it is especially in the areas of
public awareness building and formal and informal education that
citizens' associations can be most effective.
<H3>Establishing a European NGO Council on Drugs and Development
<BR>
</H3>

<P>
With this in mind, an initiative was taken in Paris, in April
of 1993, when a small group of mostly development oriented European
NGOs decided to work together toward the creation of a European
NGO Council on Drugs and Development. The work toward the establishment
of the Council has been a concrete expression the wish to create
an instrument for European NGOs to contribute to the debate on
a more effective European policy on the drug issue and seek mechanisms
which will also enable NGOs in developing countries to put forward
their concerns and views to policy makers in Europe. In working
to establish a European NGO Council on Drugs a list of possible
principal themes which the Council could address was developed.
These themes will be the basic elements of the dialogue which
the Council will want to promote - among its own members, with
the wider NGO community and with the concerned international institutions,
including the European Union and the Council of Europe. These
are also the themes of the Lisbon International Conference on
Drugs: Dependence and Interdependence. It is our hope that the
Lisbon conference will make a significant contribution toward
more coherency between drugs and economic policies and that those
policies will embrace broader issues in an integrated approach
involving citizens' organisations, especially indigenous groups
in developing countries, in the formulation and implementation
of relevant programmes and projects. It is also our hope, indeed
our intention, that the Lisbon conference will be an important
step toward the creation of the proposed European NGO Council
on Drugs and Development so that NGOs in this field, North and
South, will be able to work more closely together and more effectively
also in their interaction with official bodies. Such an independent
citizens' body would carry out research, put forward policy options,
exchange expert information, promote educational activities and
work to support projects of our Southern partners. These operational
points should also be discussed at Lisbon.
<H3>Acknowledgements<BR>
</H3>

<P>
The organisers of the Lisbon conference wish to thank the distinguished
group of experts who graciously consented to prepare the background
papers for the Lisbon conference. They have done an extraordinary
job in succinctly putting forward an integrated analysis as well
as extremely valuable recommendations for policy and action options
for the future. Special thanks go to B&eacute;n&eacute;dicte de
Smet for commissioning, co-ordinating and editing the papers,
to the members of the European NGO Committee on Drugs and Development
for their own writing and advisory roles, and to our assistants
at EDRC for their editorial and production work. Finally, we would
also like to acknowledge the role of the members of the conference
preparatory committee, of the staff of the North-South Centre
and Mr Georges Estievenart, Director of the EMCDDA, for their
assistance in making this publication such a solid basis for discussion
at Lisbon. Let us hope that our deliberations will make a difference
which will be felt in the lives of the people of whom we speak.
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="eestivenart"></A>Georges Estievenart, Director of
the European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drugs Addiction</H3>

<H3>The drug problem today<BR>
</H3>

<P>
It is a commonplace to say that drugs are one of the greatest
ills of the end of this century, one of the most complex and most
evil. It is a commonplace, but it is true; or it is a commonplace
because it is true. In comparison, our progress against the problem,
and education about the problem seems very slow, and at times
hesitant. But nothing could be worse than denial or indifference,
both also very great ills of the end of the century. But what
are we faced with on the world drug scene? We see a diversifying
and expanding output; organic products still show staying power,
but the devastating progress of synthetic products such as ecstasy
and amphetamines also faces us.
<P>
The previous ideas, simplistic, though convenient, have made the
issue unclear, ideas which opposed countries producing drugs and
those consuming them, with each country influencing the other
malevolently. Which producing country is today not a consumer,
and which consuming country is not increasingly becoming a producer?
And so, there is the South and the North, often badly affected,
without speaking of Eastern Europe, where drugs, prostitution,
weapons and nuclear trafficking, in an increasingly corrupt climate,
is becoming the powderkeg of tomorrow. For each cause there is
an effect; the fight against drugs itself is a double-edged sword;
in the South, politicians passionate in the fight against drugs
are elected with drug money, and in the North, accommodating politicians
claim to defend the moral and religious values passed down by
tradition. Face with this scourge of humanity, the answers are
organised little by little as the global understanding of the
phenomenon progresses. There too, black and white blend. The diversification
and the complementarity of efforts is developing. The war against
drugs, tried by the United States, having failed, has given way
to a more complete and integrated policy, where the repression
of drug trafficking, of the flow of drug money and of chemical
precursors still remains a high priority, increased even, in recent
years, but also where a more careful and organised attention is
being given to the fate of the drug addict himself, either on
the level of prevention or on the level of the limitation of the
consequences of the addict's addiction (harm reduction).
<P>
The most advanced policies today seem indeed to be those which
fuse in a coherent whole strong measures to repress the serious
crime associated with drug trafficking, with determined measures
within the socio-medical framework on drug addicts both at an
individual level (prevention, treatment, rehabilitation), and
at a collective level, in facing head-on the economic and social
conditions which exist in many weakened conurbations. This is
the orientation which in any case seems to be emerging little
by little in Europe, as was recently brought to light at the Brussels
Conference, held on 7 and 8 December 1995 devoted to the policies
in the fight against drugs in Europe, and which was confirmed
at the European summit in Madrid on 14 and 15 December 1995 when
it adopted by the report by the European Drug Expert Group.
<P>
At the same time, certainly, the ideological debates over the
legalisation versus prohibition of drugs which is taking place
all over the world in public opinion carry on, as well as the
bilateral controversy between States whose basic options, as we
know, often diverge, lending little to arriving at the working
solution which everyone awaits. In this context, the discipline
in reading, measuring and providing information on the global
drug phenomenon must be considerably reinforced. The recent creation
in Lisbon of the European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug
Addiction makes a decisive European contribution in that direction,
based on the principle that reliable information at the level
of the 15 Member States of the European Union is in itself a political
advancement. Indeed, information is not an accessory to policy
but an element of it, and with that in view, the EMCDDA must be
able to progressively identify the common elements of a European
approach to the problem, which naturally will fully take into
account the extent of globalisation of the drug phenomenon.
<P>
It seems to me that in the coming years the highest priority is
what I would call the &quot;reduction of contradictions&quot;
on the subject of drugs; the contradictions between North and
South, between national measures and international measures, between
the repression and reduction of demand, between the repression
of organised crime and petty crime, between demand reduction in
ebb (prevention) and the reduction of risks in flow, between State
entities dealing with the fight against drugs and the decentralised
individuals and non-governmental organisations. You will say that
this is an enormous programme, but an inevitable one, the only
alternative being resignation and defeat. There is no doubt in
this context that the Lisbon Conference, based around the &quot;Dependence
and Interdependence&quot; theme comes under the first category
and in this way contributes to the fight for the dignity and the
rights of man in the twenty first century. <HR>

