<center><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;4 - <B><A NAME="theme2">DEBT AND STRUCTURAL</A></B>
</H1>

<P>
effects of structural adjustment and privatisation policies on
the informal sector of economies in the South and in the East
<H3><A HREF="#chossudovsky">Michel CHOSSUDOVSKY - Canada </A>
</H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="chossudovsky">Michel
CHOSSUDOVSKY </A>- Canada</H3></center>

<H3>''Global Debt and the Criminalisation of Economic Activity''
</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Global debt has favoured the rapid growth of illicit trade and
the criminalisation of economic activity on a world scale. Globalisation
is marked by a parallel process of &quot;internationalisation
of the criminal economy&quot;. The national mafias increasingly
operate as transnational business entities within the global marketplace.
There is ample evidence of expanded levels of &quot;business transactions&quot;
and exchange between the various criminal organisations. Moreover,
a significant part of this criminal economy is fully integrated
into the workings of international banking and finance.
<P>
There are several, and often contradictory, estimates pertaining
to the size of the criminal economy. A recent estimate of the
United Nations suggests that total worldwide revenues of transnational
criminal organisations (TCOs) are of the order of one trillion
dollars representing an amount equivalent to the combined GDP
of the group of low income countries (with a combined population
of 3 billion people). The United Nations estimate includes the
trade in narcotics, arms sales, etc. as well as the earnings derived
from the mafia controlled services economy (eg. prostitution,
hotels, gambling, exchange banks, etc.). What these estimates
do not adequately convey is the magnitude of routine investments
by the criminal mafias in &quot;legal&quot; business ventures.
<H3>The Role of Economic Restructuring</H3>

<P>
The evidence confirms that the macro-economic reforms imposed
by external creditors on developing countries have been conducive
to a weakening of both the export sector and the internal market.
In turn, the crisis affecting the <I>&quot;legal economy&quot;</I>
has created an environment which favours the rapid development
of illicit production and trade.  In other words, the vacuum created
in the legal economy and the consequent collapse in the standard
of living tends to encourage, in many developing countries, the
concurrent development of an <I>&quot;alternative economy&quot;</I>
based on the narcotics trade and a growing number of illicit activities.
In many countries in the Third World and in the former Eastern
bloc, export and domestic markets collapse simultaneously creating
a situation where illicit production becomes the dominant &quot;leading&quot;
sector as well as the main source of foreign exchange.
<H3>The Reforms in International Banking</H3>

<P>
This restructuring of the real economy (at national and world
levels) is also accompanied by profound changes in the global
monetary system. National and global patterns of economic growth
are conditioned by the internationalisation of macro-economic
reform. The latter are not only conducive to the restructuring
of the real economy, they also favour the removal of barriers
to the movement of money within the international banking system.
<P>
The reforms of international currency markets (including the development
of electronic transfers and the deregulation of foreign exchange
markets) tend to facilitate the circulation and recycling of &quot;dirty
money&quot; in the international banking system. Major international
commercial banks not only constitute an outlet for money laundering,
they also provide credit to the agents of illegal trade (often
to the detriment of legal agriculture and manufacturing).
<P>
Offshore banking and the global laundering of dirty money have
become inherent features of the international banking system.
At the global economic level, the evidence suggests that legal
and illegal business activities are increasingly interlocked.
 Illicit trade permeates the fabric of normal financial and business
operations as well as the organs of State power. The evidence
would suggest that the economic mafias also exercise control over
major banking interests.
<P>
Conversely, legal business activities invest in the criminal economy
through the acquisition of banks, commercial companies, etc. which
are involved in the laundering of dirty money and/or have business
linkages to criminal organisations. The process operates in both
directions: criminal organisations (eg. with interests in the
narco-economy) acquire banking and productive assets in the legal
economy; conversely legal economic and financial interests have
a financial stake in the illicit economy.
<P>
The foregoing process also affects the structure of the national
State: prominent political figures and senior officials in national
governments have ties of allegiance to criminal organisations.
There is, in this context, a consequent &quot;distortion&quot;
in political structures and social relations which has a direct
bearing on policy formulation by national governments, including
the articulation of macro-economic and financial reforms. Criminal
organisations involved in illicit trade increasingly constitute
a powerful undercover lobby operating both at the national and
international levels influencing the scope and direction of government
policy.
<H3>Offshore Banking</H3>

<P>
Offshore banking shields corporations from taxation and provides
a safe-haven for the laundering of dirty money 1. The banking
havens are not limited to the many tropical island republics,
offshore facilities are now firmly established within the boundaries
of the European Union: Luxembourg, the Channel Islands, Dublin,
Madeira and Gibraltar. The offshore havens are an appendage of
the Western Banking system.  With deregulation, they have become
an integral part of the workings of the global financial marketplace
2. The magnitude of offshore banking is overwhelming. The Cayman
Islands constitutes the fifth largest banking centre in the world
with more banks and registered trust companies than the number
of its inhabitants 3.
<P>
Vast amounts of <I>&quot;black money&quot;</I> (namely money which
has escaped taxation) can be moved rapidly through electronic
transfer from one offshore safe haven to the next.  Corporations
can also use the banking havens to <I>&quot;recycle their profits&quot;</I>
towards a variety of business activities including speculative
investments and <I>&quot;hot money deposits&quot;</I> in the &quot;emerging
financial markets&quot; of south-east Asia and Eastern Europe.
 Large amounts of dirty and black money are channelled towards
the purchase of State assets in the so-called &quot;countries
in transition&quot;. The purchase of large amounts of government
debt in the form of bonds and securities is also transacted directly
from the island havens. The island safe havens have also been
extensively used by criminal organisations to launder <I>&quot;dirty
money&quot;</I> including the proceeds of the drug trade. <I>&quot;Dirty
money&quot;</I> - which routinely transits through the island
havens - is in turn converted into <I>&quot;clean money&quot;</I>
enabling the criminal mafias to acquire control over banking and
productive assets in the &quot;legal economy&quot;. Conversely,
the billions of dollars of <I>&quot;dirty money&quot;</I> deposited
in bank accounts (by these criminal organisations) enable the
&quot;legal&quot; banking system to considerably expand its lending
activities including the purchase of government bonds, which signifies
that the public debt is also financed by the proceeds of illegal
trade...
<P>
Moreover, with electronic transfers, the nature of money has changed.
Money becomes an intangible which moves at high speed within the
system. The rapid circulation and internationalisation of money
movements is an essential feature of the evolving World monetary
system. These innovations in banking also contribute to enlarging
the activities of money laundering. The convenience and speed
at which dirty money transactions can be undertaken tend to facilitate
the development of illicit trade and the narcotics economy.
<H3>The Role of Macro-Economic Reform</H3>

<P>
The restructuring of the real economy is paramount to an understanding
of the growth of illicit trade. Since the early 1980s, the <I>&quot;macro-economic
stabilisation&quot;</I> and <I>&quot;structural adjustment&quot;</I>
programmes imposed by the IMF and the World Bank on developing
countries (as a condition for the renegotiation of their external
debt) have led to the impoverishment of hundreds of millions of
people. Contrary to the spirit of the Bretton Woods agreement
which was predicated on &quot;economic reconstruction&quot; and
stability of major exchange rates, the structural adjustment programme
has largely contributed to destabilising national currencies and
ruining the economies of developing countries.  Internal purchasing
power has collapsed, famines have erupted, health clinics and
schools have been closed down, etc. These conditions have in turn
favoured the development of illicit trade and the criminalisation
of economic activity.
<P>
In the case of Peru and Bolivia, for instance, the IMF sponsored
reforms have contributed to undermining the role of legal commodity
exports while providing a boost to the narcotics economy. In Bolivia,
the 1985 IMF-sponsored macro-economic stabilisation programme
was conducive to the collapse of mineral exports and the restructuring
of the mining economy. The reorganisation of the state mining
consortium COMIBOL had a direct impact on the development of the
illegal coca economy: severance payments to redundant miners were
invested in the acquisition of land in the coca producing areas
by workers who had been laid off to the extent that both capital
and labour were redirected towards the coca economy.
<P>
In Peru, the development of the narco-economy under President
Alberto Fujimori also bears an intimate relationship to the conduct
of macro-economic policy: the August 1990 economic shock created
the conditions for the further growth of the drug trade.  First,
the contraction of internal demand coupled with the lifting of
tariffs on imported food staples, contributed to a serious recession
in agricultural production.
<H3>Macro-economic Reform and Illicit Trade in the Eastern Block
Countries</H3>

<P>
Since the late 1980s, the IMF-World Bank &quot;economic medicine&quot;
has been imposed on Eastern Europe, Yugoslavia and the former
Soviet Union with devastating economic and social consequences.
Also of significance is the extent to which the economic measures
in the former Soviet Union contribute to destroying civil society
and distorting fundamental social relations: the criminalisation
of economic activity, the looting of State property, money laundering
and capital flight are bolstered by the reforms. Dirty and black
money from offshore havens are recycled towards the acquisition
of State assets in the former Soviet Union. Luxembourg and the
British Virgin Islands are respectively ranked third and fourth
among &quot;foreign investors&quot; in the Russian Federation...
4
<P>
In other words, the privatisation programme (through the public
auction of State enterprises) favours the transfer of a significant
portion of State property to organised crime. The latter permeates
the State apparatus and constitutes a powerful lobby broadly supportive
of Yeltsin's economic reforms. According to a recent estimate,
half of Russia's commercial banks are under the control of the
local mafias, and half of the commercial real estate in central
Moscow is in the hands of organised crime. 5
<H3>The Real Economy: The Shift from Legal to Illicit Production
</H3>

<P>
While the legal commodity economy declines as a result of the
macro-economic reforms, illegal commodity exports are expected
to play an expanded role in generating the revenues required to
service the external debt. The creditors do not distinguish between
clean and dirty money. The recycling of dirty money towards debt
servicing is a necessary consequence of the weakening of the legal
economy and the incapacity of developing countries to service
their debt from shrinking export revenues.  Various institutional
mechanisms which favour the recycling of dirty and black money
towards debt servicing have been established by national governments.
The repatriation of capital flight to meet debt servicing obligations
is encouraged by the Bretton Wood institutions.
<P>
The application of the IMF economic reforms tends to further depress
world commodity prices because they force individual countries
to simultaneously gear their national economies towards a shrinking
world market thereby creating a situation of oversupply on world
markets. In turn, the dollarisation of input prices, the reforms
in the structures of credit to agriculture and manufacturing further
exacerbates the decline in the real economy.
<P>
World prices collapse for legal primary commodity exports in a
global economy characterised by surplus output. In turn, &quot;alternative&quot;
exports unfold within the spheres of the illicit economy. With
legal commodity prices plummeting, illicit trade and the narco-economy
often become the main source of the country's foreign exchange.
<H3>The Collapse of the Internal Market</H3>

<P>
The collapse of the legal domestic manufacturing and agriculture
(for the internal market) including the informal sector is engineered
through the liberalisation of trade and the lifting of tariff
barriers. Trade liberalisation destabilises internal markets and
undermines domestic production geared towards the internal market.
The dumping of food surpluses in Sub-Saharan Africa, for instance,
has contributed to the demise of food farming and livestock production
for the local market. The latter are replaced by imports from
the European Community and North America. The development of illegal
production results from the displacement of food agriculture.
<P>
Two processes are taking place concurrently: exports collapse
and the internal production for the domestic market is replaced
by imports. In the extreme case, the restructuring process leads
to the collapse of the entire legal economy. Legal exports are
replaced by illicit trade and imported consumer goods replace
goods produced by domestic producers. Namely, the national economy
is reduced to illicit production, in turn, the latter becomes
the main source of foreign exchange which funds debt servicing
and imports. In many developing countries, illicit production
has become the dominant activity overshadowing the legal economy
and replacing legal exports.
<H3>NOTES</H3>

<P>
1. For instance, 30 percent of the top 500 European companies
have subsidiaries in the British Channel islands.
<P>
2. Most of the financial actors in the Channel Islands offshore
centres and the Isle of Man, for instance, are an offshoot of
London High Street banks.
<P>
3. Estimate by Jack A. Blum presented at Jornadas: Drogas, desarrollo
y estado de derecho, Bilbao, October 1994. See also Jack Blum
and Alan Blook, &quot;Le blanchiment de l'argent dans les Antilles&quot;
in Alain Labrousse and Alain Wallon (editors).  La plan&egrave;te
des drogues, Le Seuil, Paris, 1993.
<P>
4. See The Banker (London), April 1995, p. 38.
<P>
5. See Paul Klebnikov, &quot;Stalin's Heirs, Forbes, 27 September
1993, p. 124-134.
</BODY>

