<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;5 - <B><A NAME="theme2">DEVELOPMENT AID </A></B>
</H1>

<P>
The record of development cooperation policies, especially in
substitution and alternative development
<H3><A HREF="#oomen">Joep OOMEN - Netherlands </A> -<A HREF="#lanza">Gregorio LANZA - Bolivia </A>
</CENTER></H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="oomen">Joep
OOMEN </A>- Netherlands</H3>

<H3>''Development aid: the record of development cooperation policies,
especially in substitution and alternative development''</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Illicit drugs production has become an increasingly important
development option in many developing countries. The demand for
drugs has enabled the establishment of an illicit sector; one
which is always searching for and finding places and mechanisms
which guarantee a maximum of benefits against a minimum of risks.
Structural poverty in producing countries is at the root of the
problem. The illegal sector is capable of doing what established
society is less and less capable of doing, that is it can offer
a perspective to those who do not have any, in this case, the
small peasant community. The extension of drug-linked cultivation
together with the growth of the sector involved in the manufacturing
and commercialisation of these drugs in developing countries is
directly linked to the severe socio-economic crisis that affects
these countries. The lack of development opportunities in traditional
rural areas and the destruction of the productive apparatus have
resulted in the migration of population towards the cities or
rural regions where development poles can be found which require
labour. In drug producing countries, these development poles are
based on the cultivation of plants used in the production of drugs.

<P>
Nevertheless, it would be a mistake to suggest that the price
received by a grower of opium in Burma, cannabis in Morocco, or
coca in Peru enables him to live well. In fact, these crops are
often the only profitable ones as the prices received for other
cash crops do not cover the production costs. 
<P>
It is therefore not surprising that the repressive strategy against
the cultivation of these plants, which is financed and implemented
under pressure mainly from the United States, has failed. It has
resulted in the so-called &quot;balloon effect&quot;, that is
the irrational extension of illicit cultivation towards areas
that are even more difficult to control. This, in turn, has brought
about counter-effective and undesirable effects such as the corruption
of institutions in charge of repression, the appearance of armed
movements that benefit from the social conflicts in order to obtain
control over the producing areas and the environmental damage
produced by the methods to eradicate illicit cultivation.
<P>
In comparison, the strategy of alternative development is a much
more positive answer to the problem. This strategy implies providing
concrete measures which favour alternative development options
to those related to drugs. This strategy can be applied both in
producing areas, and in areas where migration takes place. It
consists both of the creation of production lines and the establishment
of the necessary technical and social infrastructure to increase
the living standards of the local population.
<P>
Unfortunately, the results of the alternative development strategy
have, in most cases, been disappointing. More than once, it has
had counter-productive results, leading to an increase in drug-linked
cultivation. Even in the areas where projects have been successful
in reducing drug-linked cultivation, there is no evidence that
they have had any impact on the phenomenon of drugs trafficking
in general.
<P>
There are various reasons for this, both external and internal
in character. What is needed is a profound analysis of these reasons
leading to a series of necessary measures aimed at improving the
impact of alternative development strategy.
<H3>Current policies</H3>

<P>
The alternative development strategy is implemented through programmes
and concrete projects that are financed mainly by the developed
countries in the form of bilateral, multilateral and, to a lesser
degree, NGO assistance. A large part of that aid, especially that
given by the European Union and its Member States is being coordinated
within the framework of a specialised UN Agency, the United Nations
International Drug Control Programme (UNDCP). These programmes
started in the 70's and, since then, have been implemented in
the most important drug producing regions: the Golden Triangle
and Crescent of Asia, the Andean region of Latin America and in
some African countries.
<P>
The difficulties presented by the implementation of these programmes
are above all related to the fact that there is a lack of coherence
between the programme and the judicial and political contexts
they have to be executed in. On one hand, the programmes are implemented
in such as way as to satisfy the requirements established by the
International UN-Conventions on narcotic drugs (those of 1961,
1972 and 1988 respectively). These Conventions clearly mention
the need to eliminate the cultivation of prohibited substances
such as coca leaves, poppy and cannabis for non-medical purposes.
This implies that the target population of the alternative development
programme is considered to be violating the law, which hinders
the relation of mutual trust necessary between the two partners
in a development programme, ie the executors and the beneficiaries.
Without this trust, sustainable development is impossible. On
the other hand, the programme is executed within a context in
which a general rural development policy is virtually absent.
Conversely, many of the countries in question implement economic
measures that seriously affect the already marginalised rural
sector, such as the abolition of state support to the peasants,
the liberalisation of trade in agricultural products, etc. These
measures take place within the framework of a structural adjustment
programme elaborated by institutions that support the restructuring
of the economic policy of countries with an external debt, like
for instance the IMF, World Bank etc.
<P>
Finally, the economic policies implemented by developed countries
provoke an increased marginalisation from the global economy of
the peasant sector concerned, as a result of the low and fluctuating
commodity prices for their products and the unfair competition
caused by the flood of subsidised food imports to the national
peasant produce in developing countries. This phenomenon has gravely
damaged the perspective of the national productive apparatus in
general, and substitution programmes in particular.
<P>
Furthermore, serious criticism has been raised with regard to
the way in which the alternative development strategy has been
implemented by the concerned agencies, among others, the UNDCP.
This criticism refers to the fact that no distinction has been
made between cultivation for traditional use and cultivation for
drug production; that the dimensions of these programmes are often
exaggerated, with a disproportionate amount of funds being spent
on non-productive items and that their approach often fails to
foresee possible negative socio-economic and ecological outcomes.
There is evidence for example that the introduction of cash crops
as a result of alternative development programmes has generated
irreparable damage to the eco-system and to the traditional socio-economic
patterns of the population, which is, in most cases, indigenous.
Other crucial and consistent elements in this criticism of current
alternative development programmes are the lack of participation
by the target population in decision-making processes, as well
as the lack of coherence within a policy that promotes the commercialisation
of the alternative products.
<P>
In short, the alternative development strategy appears to be more
concentrated on the substitution of plants and less on the substitution
of rural poverty.
<H3>Alternative policies and practices</H3>

<P>
There is no doubt that the alternative development strategy, if
applied in an appropriate manner, is a positive answer to the
fundamental problem that lies beneath the massive production of
drugs, i.e. rural poverty. In order to  make the strategy more
effective in this sense, it is indispensable to establish a coherent
alternative development policy, whose main objective is not the
eradication of plants, but the eradication of poverty. This policy
has to aim at substituting the dependency on standard or illicit
mono-cropping, which actually characterises the situation of many
peasants in developing countries. In order to obtain this objective,
the policy should have international, national and local implications.
<P>
In the international sphere, promoting alternative development
requires the countering, in all appropriate fora, of the increasing
marginalisation of the small peasant sector in developing countries.
This can be done by addressing the adverse impact on this sector:
<UL>
<LI>of the low and fluctuating prices that their products are
subject to on the world market;
<LI>of the measures taken in the framework of the structural adjustment
programme, imposed by international financing institutions;
<LI>of the export of subsidised food products by developed countries
to developing countries.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Furthermore, the alternative development strategy should not be
related to the execution of the International Conventions on Drugs,
which prohibit the cultivation of plants that can be used for
the manufacturing of drugs; conversely, the degree should be considered
in which this prohibition impedes the implementation of development
programmes, whose principal protagonists should be the growers
of these plants (at present considered as criminals by the International
Conventions).
<P>
On a national level, alternative development programmes should
be integrated in a rural development plan, that covers all areas
with a potential for agriculture. This plan should seek to obtain
economic progress for all, including credit, extension activities,
investigation and transference of new and adequate technologies,
and at the same time, adapt the model of self-sufficiency and
traditional technology, using it as a foundation of the economic
structure. Obviously, this rural development plan should also
include measures to protect national production, and above all
agricultural production, against competition from abroad.
<P>
On a local level, the approach of an alternative development programme
should be integrated, aiming at an economic model that enables
the target population to assure themselves fair incomes in the
framework of sustainable activities (with commercial perspectives
and respecting the environment). Therefore, the stability of the
peasants and their communities should be a first priority.
<P>
The foundation of the productive strategy should be food security,
with production for the local, national and international markets,
respectively, as its main production lines. On the international
market fair-trade products should be promoted. In the case of
agro-industrial projects, these should be articulated to the above-mentioned
priorities, and designed and implemented on the basis of profound
feasibility and marketing studies.
<P>
Under no circumstances should a production model be applied that
is damaging the local genetic biodiversity. As a consequence,
the cultivation of plants actually submitted for international
prohibition should be included among various possible production
lines, benefitting from the juridical possibilities that the current
Conventions might offer. For this purpose, investigations should
be carried out in order to determine potential beneficial applications
that these plants might have, also within an international context.
<H3>Strategies</H3>

<P>
In order to carry out a policy of alternative development, the
involvement and collaboration of two actors are indispensable:
the target population and the bilateral and multilateral agencies
in charge of financing and implementing the programmes. It is
very unlikely that all the changes suggested in the current alternative
development policy will occur soon. But already, the institutions
that implement it should carry out a critical evaluation of their
approach in close collaboration with the non-governmental organisations
that represent the target population, peasant organisations, and
local development organisations. According to the recommendations
that will result from this evaluation, the current programme should
be reformulated. Furthermore, in every possible degree, damage
caused by programmes that have already been concluded should be
repaired.
<P>
In order to improve the impact of alternative development programmes
in the future, these should be carried out with the agreement
and full participation of the target population in every phase
of the programmes: design, planning, implementation and evaluation.
To make sure that this participation is equitable, the programme's
objectives should be limited to the search for real development
options, and before these are found, no forced eradication of
illicit plants should be considered. In turn, investigations should
be carried out, together with specialised organisations, into
the way in which the commercialisation of beneficial derivatives
of these plants could open possible production lines.
<P>
The economical sustainability of the projects is to be guaranteed
by support to peasant organisations that enables them to maintain
optimum levels of development after the conclusion of the project.
On the other hand, local independent research organisations specialised
in development and environment should be supported in order to
monitor constantly the ecological and economical sustainability
of the development programme as it occurs. When the destination
of the products, prompted by an alternative development programme,
is the export market, international non-governmental organisations
that are in charge of so-called 'fair trade' schemes should be
contacted. This requires that peasant organisations should participate
in the control over the commercialisation and transformation of
their products, thus avoiding the possible undermining effects
of development on the essential food self-sufficiency activities.
<P>
Nevertheless, there is enough reason to doubt the sense that any
alternative development programmes might have if the macro-economic
measures are not taken to offer a market for the products it wants
to promote. These measures fail under the responsibility of the
supranational institutions.
<P>
The World Trade Organisation should eliminate the adverse impact
of the increasing liberalisation of international trade on the
small peasant sector, for instance through the establishment of
minimal and stable prices for the products that might be an option
for alternative development programmes. Financial institutions
like the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund should
give priority to the elaboration of a rural development plan,
whose objective is to reactivate the agricultural sector based,
above all, on the fulfilment of local and national needs.
<P>
It is suggested that an institution like UNDCP, with the experience
and prestige it has obtained as being the UN specialised agency,
be the natural actor to suggest to the international community
the immediate need for adopting these measures. Furthermore, UNDCP
should, together with organisations specialised in the issue,
monitor global economic and financial policies, in order to give
sufficient warning of their possible adverse impact on the increase
of the drugs economy.<HR>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="lanza">Gregorio LANZA </A>- Bolivia
</H3>

<H3>''Features of the production and economic integration of illicit
crops''</H3>

<P>
The production of illicit crops is concentrated in backward or
developing economies.  This is the case with the poppy in Afghanistan,
Pakistan and Burma, the coca leaf in the high forests of the Andean
countries of Bolivia, Peru and Columbia and, more specifically,
within the framework of agricultural subsistence economies in
which other crops are not profitable.  
<P>
These illicit crops constitute the raw materials for the production
of drugs, for example the coca leaf for cocaine.  Although the
peasant producers are improving their living conditions, they
remain impoverished, and the &quot;coca-cocaine&quot; circuit
has a very significant economic impact on the overall economy
of these countries, creating employment and bringing in foreign
currency.
<P>
In many cases, the increase in the production of illicit crops
has coincided with periods of economic crisis and structural adjustment
policies.
<P>
The supply of illicit crops is in response to the pressure of
demand from the international market.  In this fashion, certain
countries are able to reintegrate into the world economy.  The
globalisation of the economy has an adverse impact on raw materials
as such on the economies of the South.
<P>
The imbalances that result from the production and processing
of illicit crops in the economies of countries affected by these
activities will take a long time to overcome. 
<H3>Concept of alternative development</H3>

<P>
The United Nations International Drug Control Programme (UNDCP)
defines alternative development programmes as follows:
<P>
These are programmes created to promote the efforts of developing
countries to eliminate the production or processing of illicit
drugs in their territory.  Such programmes may assist governments
in setting up and designing alternative socio-economic policies
for peasants involved in the production of illicit crops and raw
materials.  They may facilitate and further the transition of
an entire country from economic dependence on production and trafficking
to a development strategy based on products other than narcotic
drugs.
<P>
At the Berlin Conference, a concept was proposed similar to the
one above: alternative development is defined as a process designed
to eliminate and prevent the production of crops intended for
the manufacture of illicit drugs by rural development measures
specifically designed to sustain national economic growth.  It
must include social and economic measures and must also be based
on the gradual reduction of crops in the drug growing regions
through easily accessible technical and financial assistance.
<P>
For its part, the American administration takes the position that:
it is generally possible to gauge success as a function of the
reduction of the production of and trafficking in narcotic drugs.
 However, the alternative development process is a long-term project,
and consequently, it is neither useful nor appropriate to measure
&quot;short-term&quot; success, such as the reduction in production
from one year to the next. 
<P>
The Government of the United States assesses the success of alternative
development on the basis of:
<P>
i. the number of licit jobs compared to the number of jobs in
coca cultivation;
<P>
ii. income from licit activities as against income from coca cultivation;

<P>
iii. total legally-generated foreign currency as opposed  to foreign
currency originating in coca plant production.
<P>
The Bolivian Government declares in its &quot;national strategy
for alternative development&quot; that it proposes to replace
the economy of the coca plant and its derivatives through the
creation of jobs generating income that will be able to make up
for the loss of employment and of revenue from illegal activities.
 Alternative economic development aims to offset with rapid financial
assistance, the social and economic cost of programmes to destroy
illicit coca crops and will also promote the structural change
needed to overcome the external asphyxiation to which the economy
of the country will be exposed as a result.
<P>
It is clear that there is no standard criterion, at any rate in
relation to the three following subjects:
<P>
1. Is only the income generated by crops to be replaced or the
economic activities created by the entire circuit?
<P>
2. Must the results be measured as a function of the surface area
of destroyed crops or on the basis of socio-economic parameters?
<P>
3. Is there a close correlation between the eradication of illicit
crops and drug demand?  Also, what role is played here by the
consumer countries?
<H3>Investments and markets</H3>

<P>
Investments for alternative development (in millions of US dollars,
for 1984-1995)
<P>
<B>     Bolivia  Peru   TOTAL</B>
<P>
<B>Government</B>   28.8   20.4   49.2
<P>
<B>USAID</B>    79.1   29.8   108.9
<P>
<B>UNDCP</B>    42.3   39.1   81.4
<P>
<B>Total</B>     150.2   74.1   239.5
<P>
Estimates based on data from the &quot;Andean Counter-Drug Initiative&quot;,
UNSAID - Bolivia, UNDCP Peru and Bolivia.
<P>
As we can see from this table, investments are low.  In the case
of Bolivia, for example, they amount to an average of 13 million
dollars annually; even if the 50 million dollars spent on destroying
25,000 hectares of coca plants were added, the annual average
would still be only 18 million dollars.  If this is compared with
the income generated by the coca plant and its derivatives, which
for Bolivia is estimated at 500 million dollars and for Peru at
2,000 million dollars annually, it is fair to say that these investments
are negligible.  As to the markets of the countries of the North,
they are blocked by quasi-tariff measures, which prevent any importation
of crops legally grown in the countries of the South.
<H3>Results</H3>

<P>
By and large, the results are limited, whether for job creation,
the generation of foreign currency or crop substitution.
<H3>The case of Bolivia </H3>

<P>
In Bolivia, alternative development has not had an effect for
three reasons:
<P>
i. modular projects that are small in scale and without economic
impact;
<P>
ii. little peasant participation;
<P>
iii. technical mistakes relating to the types of substitution
crops and markets envisaged.
<P>
In the years 1984-1989, attempts were made to resolve these problems,
notably in the agro-industrial units of UNDCP, so as to achieve
better quality and raise peasant participation.  The infrastructure
was improved somewhat.
<H3>The case of Peru</H3>

<P>
In the case of Peru, alternative development has been concentrated
primarily in the region of traditional production.  The violence
in the region of Huallaga has made it impossible to encourage
alternative development in the largest areas. However, in the
past two years, 1994-1995, cocoa and cocaine production has faced
a crisis of overproduction and a collapse in prices, in some cases
exceeding 300%.  This might stimulate the cultivation of alternative
crops - see the example of cocoa and its industrialisation, which
has benefited from the experience of and infrastructure developed
by the UNDCP.
<H3>The case of Colombia</H3>

<P>
The case of Columbia is somewhat unique because of its initial
situation as a country that processed drugs from the raw material
grown in Bolivia and Peru.  In the past two years, however, coca
production in Colombia has increased in surface area, from 30,000
to nearly 80,000 hectares.  In this new context, efforts are being
made to give fresh impetus to alternative development.  In the
past, projects receiving the special support of the UNDCP, and
which have been administered by the Government of Colombia in
the regions of southern Cauca, Piamonte de Putumayo, San Jos&eacute;
de Guavire and in Nari&ntilde;o have accounted for an investment
of 20 million dollars.
<H3>The current situation</H3>

<P>
Despite all the experience accumulated in the area of alternative
development, and notwithstanding the official declarations in
1995 of the Governments of Peru, Columbia and Bolivia, alternative
development policies have given way to the forced eradication
of coca crops.  The resulting situation of violence has created
an obstacle to the smooth functioning of alternative development
projects.
<H3>Problems to be raised</H3>

<P>
1. If long-term policies are involved, the results must be measured
with socio-economic parameters, which are not only meaningful
for over a long period.  If short-term policies are to be employed,
the sole measure would be the reduction of the number of hectares
of illicit crops.
<P>
2. Investment is insufficient.  The markets are limited by protectionist
measures, particularly those of a quasi-tariff nature.  In this
context, how can shared responsibility and the policies of the
North find their expression?
<P>
3. How can the contradiction be resolved between extremely open
economies and the free market, on the one hand, and the participation
of state and international bodies intervening in the alternative
development economy, on the other?
<P>
4. How can a consensus be reached with the coca-producing peasants,
if at the same time a sort of war has been declared against them?
 The forced destruction of their crops by fumigation is a threat
to human lives and to the environment.  
<P>
5. If we are aware that the problem is worldwide, how can demand,
which drives the supply, be reduced?
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
