<center><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;6 - <B><A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6">ENVIRONMENT</A>
</B></H1>

<P>
The environmental impact of the drug economy and of development
alternatives
<H3><A HREF="#rumrill">Roger RUMRILL - Peru </A></CENTER></H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by Roger RUMRILL - Peru
</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Drug trafficking has existed in Andean countries, particularly
in Peru, for a quarter of a century.  From the outset, in the
1970s, the illegal drug economy using the coca leaf as its raw
material, has had a devastating effect on the legal economy, social
and cultural organisation, politics, the environment and ecology.
<P>
In the specific case of Peru, the illegal coca economy has been
and still is linked to guerilla movements such as the Sendero
Luminoso (Shining Path) and the MRTA (Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement).  This illegal activity has also infiltrated the armed
forces and the police, which are supposed to be fighting it.
This considerable economic force, which injects an average of
one billion dollars every year (30% of Peru's exports) into the
Peruvian economy, distorts the economic process in the region.
<P>
The effect on the environment and regional ecology is very negative.
 Peru, the world's leading producer of coca leaves, with roughly
300,000 hectares of plantations, has had to clear more than one
million hectares of rainforest in the tropical region of the Amazon,
where coca plants are grown on natural terraces between 600 and
1500 metres above sea-level.  The damage caused by this deforestation
is not confined to erosion and impoverishment of tropical soil
but includes also a progressive and rapid depletion of biodiversity.
<P>
There is also very extensive contamination of rivers and soil.
 The engineer Buenaventura Marcelo Tadeo calculated that in order
to process the production from 160,000 hectares of coca plants
(yielding an average of 2,400 kilos per hectare per year), in
1987 alone, 57 million litres of kerosene, 32 million litres of
sulphuric acid, 16,000 tonnes of quicklime, 3,200 tonnes of carbide,
16,000 tonnes of toilet paper, 6,400,000 litres of acetone and
a similar amount of toluene were needed.  All these chemical wastes
are dumped into the rivers and lakes of the Amazon valley and
are extremely harmful to wildlife and human health.
<H3>Regional, national and international policies</H3>

<P>
Unfortunately, national and international policies are not working
on a global solution to the problem of drug trafficking.
<P>
United States' government policy, particularly since the Republicans
took control of Congress in December 1994, has concentrated on
a strategy to eradicate coca, marijuana and opium poppy plantations,
and has ignored the economic and social parameters of the problem.
<P>
This pressure to eradicate plantations has tended to militarise
the drugs war, which, in turn, has eroded the democratic foundations
of Andean countries and brought about increased corruption in
state structures and frequent human rights abuses in the region.
<P>
International macro-economic policies, structural adjustment programmes
and the unbridled application of the neo-liberal model have served
to stimulate the illegal economies in Andean countries.  In Peru,
Bolivia and Colombia the expansion of coca, opium poppy and marijuana
cultivation is directly linked to the opening up of the free market,
the decrease in customs tariffs and the protectionism of the North.
 The prices of legal crops such as rice, maize and others have
fallen because of unfair competition from imported produce.  This
has forced farmers into illegal activities.
<P>
Since the second half of 1995, coca leaf prices have fallen in
Peru to their lowest level for a quarter of a century.  The reasons
can be found in the overproduction of raw materials and processed
drugs, the increasing autonomy of national cartels and &quot;businesses&quot;
and the partial dismantling of the production, supply and transport
systems.
<P>
In Peru, the government of President Fujimori has decided to withdraw
the army from the war against drug trafficking giving, as one
of its reasons, the many corruption scandals that have been uncovered.
 The national police have once again been made responsible for
this activity.  However, no effective economic and social policy
has been implemented to deal with the crisis among coca plant
producers and help the country reach a structural solution to
the problem.
<H3>Alternatives</H3>

<P>
A quarter of a century after the beginning of the drug trafficking
era, particularly cocaine trafficking, policies to control and
reduce both demand and supply have proved ineffective.  Drug trafficking
today is pandemic.
<P>
All these policies and their underlying philosophical concepts
should now be reviewed, at international, national and regional
level.
<P>
In the case of Andean countries, United States' policy (&quot;Andean
drugs war&quot;) should be the first to be reviewed.  After more
than a decade of implementation of this policy, the problem of
coca leaf, opium poppy and marijuana production and their export
to the United States and Europe has not been resolved;  in fact,
quite the reverse, the problem has worsened.
<P>
One example is the expansion of land used for coca plant crops
in the Peruvian valley of Huallaga, which is the biggest coca
leaf production area in the world.  In 1970 at the beginning of
the drugs era, there were only 7,000 hectares of coca plants in
this valley, whereas today there are more than 200,000.  It is
important also not to forget the frequent human rights abuses
and corruption scandals that occur.
<P>
The concepts of shared responsibility and globality should also
be reviewed.  The debate should be approached from an economic
angle with a view to resolving the problem of rural poverty in
Andean countries and in all countries which grow illegal crops
as raw materials for natural drugs.  Mostly these are Third World
countries, except in the case of the United States, which is the
world's leading producer of marijuana.
<H3>Strategies</H3>

<P>
Given the wide range of interests at stake, most countries, particularly
those in the North which are the biggest consumers of drugs, refuse
to review or change their drugs policies.  National and regional
bodies are not sufficiently powerful to urge them to take the
necessary decisions.
<P>
The countries concerned could have an opportunity to negotiate
radical changes in their policies at the World Drugs Summit to
be held in 1997.  Consensus on the need for this Summit exists
among all the countries except the United States.
<P>
Structural adjustment policies, the unrestricted opening up of
our borders and protectionism among the rich nations of the North
have all contributed to the spread of poverty and consequently
to the expansion of illegal crops just as the recession has contributed
to expansion in the demand for drugs in industrialised countries.
 The only option is to redefine these policies and try to establish
a balanced relationship with developing countries.
<P>
As far as the Andean countries are concerned, a programme or strategy
for the whole region is needed urgently to enable them to negotiate
with the United States.  It is only in consensus that the Andean
countries will be able to resist the pressure for eradication
and militarisation from the United States.
<P>
Another step, particularly for Peru and Bolivia, would be to secure
the decriminalisation of the coca leaf and its withdrawal from
the list of narcotics drawn up by the 1961 Single Convention in
Vienna.
<P>
For the tropical regions of the Andes where the coca plant is
grown, it is essential to start a process of crop conversion.
 The damage caused to the environment by the production and processing
of coca plants is a threat to the greatest biodiversity of our
planet.
<H3>Lima, 15 January 1996.</H3>

</BODY>

</HTML>
