<BODY>

<center><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;8 - <B><A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6"></A><A NAME="theme8">NEW
PRODUCERS AND TRADERS</A></B></H1>

<P>
The emergence of new producers and of new criminal organisations,
particularly in Africa and in Central and Eastern Europe
<H3><A HREF="#labrousse">Alain LABROUSSE - France </A> - <A HREF="#levai">Miklos LEVAI - Hungary </A></CENTER>
</H3>

<H2><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="labrousse">Alain
LABROUSSE </A>- France</H2>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
On the illicit drugs front, the 1990s have been marked by two
phenomena: an explosion of production and trafficking in their
&quot;traditional&quot; areas and resultant contamination of new
regions, chiefly the territories of the former Communist countries
in Eastern Europe and the African countries south of the Sahara.
In both regions, these phenomena occur against a background of
political and economic upheaval whose salient feature is the establishment
of democratisation processes and ultra-liberal policies. While
action at the political level is difficult, at the economic level
a number of adjustments would avert the undesirable effects of
liberal policies on drug production and dealing.
<H3>The former Communist countries' role in the trade</H3>

<P>
The former communist countries, whose respective yields were once
intended for local consumption, have a tendency to be caught up
in international dealing: Kazakhstan for cannabis derivatives,
Tajikistan, Uzbekistan or Ukraine for opium poppy derivatives.
These two types of production, though expanding extremely rapidly,
have not yet attained significance on the world drug market. The
main changes in the trading processes in fact stem from the break-up
of the Soviet-dominated Eastern Bloc. The first effect is that
the confined space of the bloc, ruled by its own internal logic,
has been restored to a wide-open state both for the previous marketing
traditions and the new polarities of international commerce. Secondly,
tendencies towards completely unregulated trade practice have
been strongly accentuated by this sudden opening-up and by the
infirmity of economies and societies abruptly subjected to the
elementary laws of predation and survival. Furthermore, drug trafficking
as a quick source of capital gain and the interpenetrating arms
traffic which it finances revolve around the markets created by
war in the former Yugoslavia and conflict in the Caucasus and
Central Asia.
<P>
The Turkish organisations are present on the terminal portions
of these drug pipelines. Albanians from Kosovo and the Former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia are also active on the route through
the Balkans and the Italian Adriatic ports. Bulgaria and Romania
are transit points for the Turkish, Russian and Caucasian connections.
Turkish narcotics dealers are present not only along the older
Mediterranean routes dominated by the Italian Mafia, but also
the more independent new Balkan routes, the preserve of the Russians
and Caucasians. The Balkan trade has overland and seaborne variants
which are endlessly multiplied by the involvement of Lebanese
and Kurds to the South and Serbs and Croats to the North.
<H3>African drug growing and distribution</H3>

<P>
Cannabis, introduced into East and Central Africa as from the
14th century, did not reach most West African countries until
after World War II. In all parts its use was of a folk nature.
Deterioration of national economic situations in the 1970s and
remedial application of structural adjustment programmes in the
1980s brought rapid expansion of the crops. In many African countries
today, they represent the sole expedient enabling farmers to weather
the recession, especially as the local authorities turn a blind
eye or are implicated in the traffic. Certain countries - Nigeria,
Ghana, Ivory Coast, Senegal and others - supply the regional markets
and export increasing quantities of their production to Europe.
<P>
Since the early 1980s, Africa has also become a major transit
route (air and sea) for heroin being delivered from Southwest
and Southeast Asia to the USA and Europe, as well as cocaine from
America bound for Europe. The initial leadership of the Nigerian
rings has given way to a trend towards multinational structuring
of networks: Kenyans, Tanzanians, Zairians, Senegalese, etc. Although
the traffickers long preferred East African ports for transhipping
consignments, particularly hashish originating from Southeast
Asia, growing use of West African ports where customs officials
are very readily bribed is observed. It has also been noted that
the Moroccan traffickers use the coasts of the Cape Verde Islands
and Senegal, handy to the Spanish and North African coasts.
<H3>Alternative policies</H3>

<P>
Both regions of the world, though very different in many respects,
are affected by situations with a number of points in common which
account for the development of illicit activities.
<P>
1. Conflict situations in a number of countries: [Tajikistan,
Azerbaijan, Armenia, Chechnya, former Yugoslavia; Somalia, Rwanda,
Chad, Liberia, Sierra Leone, Senegal]. (See text on conflicts).
<P>
2. Elsewhere, it is the democratisation process which gives rise
to the illicit tradings. Indeed, the new democratic parties are
looking for alternative resources whether legal or illegal to
counter the old single parties which usually retain part of the
resources monopolised by the state structures [Russia, Georgia,
Ukraine, Romania, etc.; Mozambique, Guinea, Chad, Ivory Coast,
etc.].
<P>
3. All these countries are nevertheless alike in being under constraint
from the international financial organisations to accept economic
liberalisation policies: privatisation, application of structural
adjustment plans, etc. This is the level where it may well be
possible to act by making alterations in these policies which
would remedy their ill-effects:
<P>
a) privatisation: ensure that it is not carried out through laundering
of mafia money [East Germany, Russia, Bulgaria, Romania, etc].
<P>
b) ensure that branches of European banks in these countries do
not take advantage of their location to engage in practices forbidden
them in the West [Hungary].
<P>
c) possible proposals for agricultural policy:
<P>
giving poor farmers access to production resources subsidised
by means of inexpensive loans;
<P>
maintaining arable acreage and safeguarding land tenure;
<P>
hedging the prices of local produce against imports;
<P>
guarding against fluctuations in world rates for exported agricultural
products;
<P>
diversifying revenue sources by diversifying agricultural and
non-agricultural activities;
<P>
founding agricultural organisations which are not empty shells
that merely act as political relays but can form real countervailing
powers which give farmers a firmer footing on which to negotiate.
<P>
Needless to say, all these proposals run counter to the policy
laid down by the World Bank and the international finance bodies.
<HR>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="levai">Miklos LEVAI </A>- Hungary
</H3>

<H3>''New Producers and Traders: The Emergence of New Criminal
Organisations, particularly in Central and Eastern Europe''</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
One of the more remarkable aspects of the expansion of the drug
trade has been the spread of addiction and the drug economy to
the Third World and to the former socialist countries in Central
and Eastern Europe. In my paper, I am going to concentrate on
the latter region.
<P>
Drug abuse has been a fact of life in Eastern and Central Europe
since the late 1960's, but although illegal drug abuse is far
from uncommon, illegal trafficking and organised crime have yet
to take hold.
<P>
Before speaking about the new producers, traders and consumers,
let me take a brief look at the old ones, I mean, the drug-scene
during the socialist period.
<P>
In that time, the main features of the drug problem were the following:
owing to the nature of the economy (planned economy run by the
state), the political system (one-party state) and the strict
social control of every day life, the drug trade to fulfil the
demand of the market had not been formed. Drug trafficking was
small, the 'real drugs' (such as opium, heroin, cocaine, and cannabis
derivatives) were missing and the drug problem was not linked
to criminality. (For example, in Hungary, the wide- spread form
of drug abuse was 'glue-sniffing'). We could say the drug problem,
particularly the demand for drugs, had already started in Central
and Eastern Europe during the socialist period. I think the most
important finding of that time is that drug abuse in a society
can come to exist without the supply of 'real' drugs.
<P>
The above-mentioned features of the drug scene in the region have
changed since the collapse of the former regime. Today, all elements
of the drug problem in the Western countries are present in the
countries in question. Thus, for example, illicit trafficking
to meet the domestic demand has started and there has been an
attempt to produce home-made drugs. There is an extremely wide
variety of illegal drugs available, and money-laundering actions
related to the illegal drug business have appeared in Central
and Eastern Europe. However, I must add that 'Central and Eastern
Europe' is just a geographical and political common name for a
territory. In this territory, there are many countries with the
same social difficulties, but with many differences from the point
of view of culture, development, and the facts of social life,
like the drug problem, Let us examine a few examples of the common
features and differences in the field of the drug problem, which
in addition, illustrate the new producers and the new criminal
organisations.
<P>
According to the official figures, the number of drug consumers
is 1.5 million in Russia. In Moscow, you can get all kinds of
drugs. The narcotics Mafia of organised drug sellers and buyers
have controlled over-trafficking in the country. The estimated
income of the Mafia was more than 0.5 billion dollars in 1995.
''Cannabis sativa'' has grown to roughly 1 million hectares, for
producing marijuana (about 1 million tons per year). For Colombian
cocaine cartels, the target country, or at least the distributive
country, is Russia. The law enforcement agencies have discovered
two university laboratories which manufactured synthetic drugs
for the Mafia. 
<P>
In Hungary, we have had another kind of problem. Although the
number of consumers has been increasing (their number is about
25-30,000), our country is mainly a way station for the movement
of drugs, given that its borders are no longer secure. The other
reason: the so-called Balkan-route, that is, the route of smuggling
heroin from South-Eastern Asia to Western Europe, has been transferred
to Northern countries so that Hungary (and the Czech and the Slovak
Republics) have become the predominant transit countries for drug
trafficking. (In Hungary, less than 4 kg heroin, 2.5 kg hashish
were seized in 1990, while in 1995 more than 500 kg heroin and
also more than 500 kg hashish were seized). The territorial monopoly
of the Balkan-route belongs to the Mafia's in Turkey, and the
Albanian Mafia's are also quite involved in the illicit drug smuggling
that is crossing Hungary. Further new features of the drug trafficking
and producing in Hungary: the production of amphetamines in illegal
laboratories, or in an illicit way, to transport to the Netherlands
and Sweden, ''cannabis tours'' to the Netherlands, domestic production
of cannabis, cocaine trafficking headed by a Nigerian network,
and newer drugs on the market are amphetamine derivatives (i.e.
metaphetamin: Ecstasy-pill).
<P>
By the mid-nineties, illicit drug trafficking, which is a part
of international organised crime, had reached Hungary. Hungarian
citizens are involved in this business. So far, national organised
crime has appeared in different territories mainly in the field
of tourism, trafficking in foreign currencies, prostitution, theft
of cars, and smuggling people. Hungarian and foreign dealers sell
drugs on the domestic market. Distribution of drugs ordinarily
takes place indoors, particularly in restaurants; very few sales
occur on the street.
<P>
The situation is basically the same in the Czech and Slovak Republics
and Poland as in Hungary, with the difference that, in the latter,
synthetic drugs (mainly amphetamines), are produced in large quantities
to be smuggled in Scandinavia.
<H3>Drug policy issues</H3>

<P>
Central and Eastern European countries have joined the UN Conventions
on the drug issue (1961, 1974) and have ratified the UN Covenant
of 1988 Against Illicit Traffic on Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic
Substances. In addition to the mentioned international conventions,
these countries have taken into account the documents of the Council
of Europe, when forming their drug policy. For example, when Hungary
modified the articles on the Criminal Code concerning the drug
problem in 1993, the experts who prepared the Bill took into consideration
Recommendation n&#186;1085 of the 40th Plenary Session of the
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe. Based upon the
mentioned international and regional documents, the goal of the
drug policies of these countries is ''harm reduction'', and they
implement the ''double strategy'' in criminal law. It means there
are huge differences between the severity of punishment of the
consumer and the trafficker.
<P>
What is the impact of this policy in the region? First of all,
the drug problem is treated as a legal issue, which could be controlled
mainly by means of criminal law. Because of this feature, the
law enforcement agencies have had the central role in the drug
policy in Central and Eastern Europe. Among the total number of
criminals, are an increasing number of drug offenders, particularly
traffickers. (For example, in Hungary, the number of registered
offenders was 37 in 1990, and 324 in 1994). In spite of the fact
that, on the one side, most of the consumers belong to disadvantaged
social groups, and on the other side, drug trafficking is good
business, the drug policy of these countries has neglected the
social policy and economic aspects of the drug problem.
<H3>Alternative policies and practices</H3>

<P>
If we are looking for alternative policies, we should take into
consideration the actual social and economic process in the region,
namely the privatisations of the economy and the social consequences
of this process. These countries do not have enough financial
resources and capital for privatising the economy. The governments
make efforts to cut the social policy budget in order to obtain
resources to revitalise the economy.
<P>
Certain groups of individuals, who do not have the necessary financial
resources either to become legal participants in the business
life, join in the ''black economy'', of which drug trafficking
is a very fruitful field. Both efforts have influence on the drug
problem. If we take into consideration the above-mentioned processes
and the results of the latest general elections in these countries,
we have to understand: these countries need financial sources
to revitalise the legal economy and to ensure money for social
policy and welfare is available, because one of the most important
values for their citizens is the right to social security.
<P>
Alternative policy should mean an alternative international finance
policy which should respect the above-mentioned situation and
value of the given region. 
<H3>Recommendations </H3>

<P>
Today, we do not have a comprehensive and real picture of the
drug problem in Central and Eastern Europe. For this reason, the
fundamental recommendation is that we should carry out a comparative
epidemiological, criminological, and legal research on this issue.
<P>
International NGOs should monitor and evaluate the loan and credit
policy of the international organisations.
<P>
Local NGOs should monitor the features of the ''black market''
organised crime, and the relationship between these social facts
and the tendency of the drug problem, as well as the legal regulations
in relation to these issues.
</BODY>

