<CENTER><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;10 - <B><A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6"></A><A NAME="theme8"></A><A NAME="theme9"></A><A NAME="theme10">CONTROL
MEASURES</A></B></H1>

<P>
The consequence of repressive anti-drug measures, the need for
non-repressive measures and the connection between drugs and human
rights
<H3><A HREF="#cesoni">Maria Luisa CESONI - Switzerland </A> -
<A HREF="#soberon">Ricardo SOBER&Oacute;N GARRIDO - Peru </A>
- <A HREF="#vargas">Ricardo VARGAS - Colombia </A></CENTER></H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="cesoni">Maria
Luisa Cesoni </A>- Switzerland</H3>

<H3>Regulations governing drugs and psychotropic substances</H3>

<P>
Legislation on drugs, which serves as a framework for policies
aimed at controlling the production, distribution and use of certain
natural and also synthetic substances, legally defined as &quot;drugs&quot;
and medically defined as &quot;psychotropic substances&quot;,
has gradually taken form during this century, partly due to a
number of international conventions.  These international conventions
(firstly on opium, then other drugs and, later, psychotropic substances)
aimed to restrict the trade in such products to solely medical
purposes.  They represent a trend moving from administrative control
to control through criminal law measures and from the prohibition
of the products to the &quot;indirect&quot; prohibition of their
use.
<P>
Without going into the details of international regulations, it
can be said that prohibition has been gradually configured around
three main axes:
<UL>
<LI><I>the prohibition of the production and distribution extraneous
to the qualities authorised for therapeutic purposes</I>, enshrined
little by little in the first international conventions (from
the Shanghai Conference on Opium in 1909 to the Single Convention
on Narcotic Drugs and the Convention on Psychotropic Substances,
both of 1971);
<LI><I>enforcement measures against trafficking</I>, enshrined
in the single Convention and firmly reinforced by the Vienna Convention
on illicit trafficking in drugs and psychotropic substances of
1988;
<LI>enforcement measures against purchase, possession and growing
for personal use, introduced by the Vienna Convention of 1988.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
National legislation has evolved in parallel to and sometimes
ahead of international law.  In Western countries, particularly
in Europe, the different national legislations form a relatively
coherent whole, which can be outlined as follows:
<UL>
<LI><I>enforcement measures against consumption</I>, either directly
or indirectly, through the punishment of possession, eased by
various forms of alternative treatment;
<LI>increasing enforcement efforts against trafficking;
<LI><I>extension of control through criminal law</I>, through
the definition of new offences.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
This means that prohibition of the production of natural base
substances is shaped by international conventions and the individual
legislation of the producer countries.  Prohibition of the transformation,
distribution and consumption of substances is conditioned by international
conventions (including European treaties) and the individual legislation
of both producer and consumer countries.
<H3>The application of international and national law</H3>

<P>
Paradoxically, despite the failures of enforcement policies aimed
at curbing production, trafficking and consumption, there was
an all-out offensive of enforcement measures in the 1980s.  Declarations
of war on drugs abounded.
<P>
Every war has its victims.  In this case, it is the farmer-producers,
small-time smugglers, user-suppliers and users, and in particular
the intravenous users of &quot;hard drugs&quot;, known as drug
addicts: in a nutshell, the weak links of the chain.  Other victims
have been certain principles of international and domestic law,
together with certain human rights which were trampled upon or,
in any case, not taken into account in this war, in which, increasingly,
any means serving the end of eliminating drugs is permissible.
<P>
Other documents will focus on the negative effects generated in
producer countries by limiting crop production to medical purposes,
eradication programmes and measures against trafficking.  To give
just a few examples, we could mention the development of a kind
of right of interference by the countries of the North (there
are the interventions by the United States in Latin America but
also the conditions sometimes attached to European development
aid policies), the militarisation of anti-production and -trafficking
measures, entailing a generalised restriction of freedoms (eg
in Colombia in the 1990s) and, more recently, the substitution
of heroine consumption for traditional opium consumption, giving
rise to eradication programmes in some Asian countries.
<P>
In Europe, and Western Europe in particular, measures to combat
trafficking have failed to curb this phenomenon, according to
national and also international police forces, which link the
increased number of confiscations to the increased flow of substances.
 The demands of this combat have produced three kinds of negative
or even harmful effects, however:
<P>
a) exceptions made to the general principles of law and human
rights violations arising from the introduction of national emergency
legislation;
<P>
b) the assertion of the need to punish consumers as a means of
persecuting traffickers;
<P>
c) the deterioration of health and socio-economic circumstances
of users, particularly addicts.
<P>
We can illustrate this with a few examples:
<P>
a) laws aimed at combatting drug trafficking seem to be evolving
towards an ever greater number of exceptions to the principles
of national legislation and violations of international and national
human rights norms.
<P>
For example, certain extensions of police powers (custody, night-time
house-searches, delivery surveillance etc) common to the legislation
of most European countries, introduce differential treatment between
drugs offenders and other offenders, violating the <I>principle
of equality before the law</I>;  the shift in the burden of proof,
provided for in the area of money laundering for example, limits
the <I>rights of the defence</I> and cancels the <I>presumption
of innocence</I>.  This constitutes a violation of three fundamental
principles of criminal law established by both national legislation
and human rights conventions.
<P>
b) national policies on drug use have alternated in the past between
an approach focusing on law enforcement and an approach with greater
emphasis on medical aspects.  Since the Vienna Convention, there
seems to have been a trend towards stronger law enforcement in
different countries: in Italy and Sweden, which introduced new
criminal legislation against drug users (later repealed in Italy);
in Spain, which introduced an administrative penalty for consumption
in public; and even in the Netherlands which, while maintaining
the most liberal policy of all European countries, are showing
less tolerance towards foreign drug users.
<P>
Only AIDS seems capable of reversing this trend, as it obliges
countries to develop policies of risk reduction.  Such policies
are operated in parallel with criminal measures against users
however, and in particular there seems to be an increasing divergence
between the users benefiting from substitution programmes and
those who do not, exacerbating the situation of the latter.  While
the Vienna Convention advocated the punishment of users as a means
of combating trafficking, the most recent European meetings have
revealed a consensus that punishment is a useful means of making
users seek treatment.  Thought should be given to the real reasons
for this attitude, as it contrasts so starkly with the consensus
established in medical circles that access to socio-therapeutic
programmes which are not freely decided is ineffective.
<P>
c) In all European countries, drug users are subject to criminal
proceedings and imprisonment, either for actual use or for minor
trafficking or other such offences.  In France, 66 to 76% of drugs
arrests between 1972 and 1994 concerned users and 13 to 24% user-suppliers.
 In Italy, in the first half of 1994, drug addicts accounted for
32.6% of the prison population.
<P>
The penal environment has a definite repressive impact on the
living conditions of these subjects, particularly those dependent
on heroine.  Furthermore, it hampers the monitoring of socio-therapeutic
projects.  Drug consumption develops above all in underprivileged
environments and when users encounter penal measures, they fall
into a downward spiral of increasing marginalisation and worsened
socio-economic circumstances, job prospects and health conditions.
 On this latter point, it must be stressed that the countries
which clamp down most firmly on users seem to be those which are
the last to introduce policies to prevent the risk of HIV contamination.
 The proportion of intravenous drug users among known HIV-positives
and AIDS sufferers and the high percentage of users contaminated
with HIV and AIDS are indicative of the perverse effects of strong
enforcement policies.  The high and known risks of overdose following
forced severances in prison are also worth underlining.
<P>
Nowhere, except perhaps in the Netherlands, are drug users considered
as citizens.  Being a community with reduced rights, often before
they begin consuming, they are crushed by repressive policies,
instead of receiving support through policies fostering their
access to fundamental rights.  Yet rights to the free development
of one's personality, social life, work, housing, freedom and
health are recognised both at national level (in certain constitutions
or domestic laws) and international level (Universal Declaration
of Human Rights of the United Nations, European Convention for
the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, European
Social Charter etc).
<H3>For an alternative policy</H3>

<P>
In both North and South, the drugs issue masks complex and often
serious situations.  Although the phenomena linked to it differ,
they all seem to be symptomatic of unsuitable social and economic
models and a lack of equality where the enjoyment of fundamental
rights by individuals and peoples are concerned.
<P>
An alternative policy ought therefore to take a global approach,
striking at the causes as well as the symptoms.  In which case,
it seems obvious that policies aimed at reducing unemployment,
cleaning up and integrating suburbs, general education and youth-oriented
policies would be far more effective than specific anti-drug policies.
<P>
However, these specific policies are <I>a priori</I> not without
their uses: the problem is to make them effective and ensure that
they respect the rights of those targeted.  Nevertheless a new
model is needed, and we must think in terms of alternative policies.
 A change of pattern in Western countries means a) attaching priority
to health, regarded as both a medical and social condition, and
b) considering drug users as citizens with full rights.  This
would engender a necessary diversification of policies geared
to the different substances, user populations and modes of use,
and a generalisation of risk reduction policies, extended to cover
the social and economic risks run by users.
<P>
It is not just a matter, therefore, of intensifying prevention
programmes to combat consumption as a health risk and providing
a range of socio-therapeutic support mechanisms but also of devising
policies to provide users with concrete assistance and support
for resolving problems in their everyday lives and finding their
place in society and working life.  Finally, it is necessary to
foster a positive image of users which, by replacing the negative
image of drug addicts, encourages firstly the users to think that
they can &quot;kick the habit&quot; and secondly the public not
to resist integration policies.
<P>
But these policies are not enough to ensure that the new model
will be effective, if the users are still forced underground,
partly by the need to supply their habit from illegal markets
and partly by the necessity of raising money for these extremely
expensive supplies through crime.
<P>
Various options are open to us, and they do not necessarily require
the legalisation of the products.  All the legal rules in force
are aimed at restricting the movement and consumption of drugs
and psychotropic substances to medical use.  If it is accepted
that the mental and physical health of drug-using citizens must
be protected and is as much under threat from the spells of detention
which are bound to befall an &quot;addict&quot; as the consumption
of substances in illegal circumstances, the provision of substances
within a medically-controlled circuit to users who cannot do without
them is compatible with the existing rules.
<P>
The examples set by Switzerland and England show that it is possible,
not only to develop substitution programmes (eg with methadone)
but also to dispense heroine which, if monitored for quality,
used with uncontaminated instruments and followed by more general
socio-therapeutic supervision, can help users gradually regain
their place in society (as demonstrated by the initial assessment
of the experimental heroine distribution programmes in Switzerland)
and, perhaps, even halt their consumption.
<P>
The reinsertion of users into a context of legality does not only
entail their reinstatement as persons recognised in law but would
also reduce risks to society; it is society, after all, which
suffers from offences related to the use of certain substances
and from the cost of law enforcement policies which, in many countries,
is considerably higher (and substantially linked to the punishment
of users) than the cost of prevention and care.
<P>
It may be assumed that the reduction of drug-related delinquency,
the redirecting of expenditure and also the gradual disappearance
of users from the context of illegality would change public opinion
in the long term and, consequently, generate more respect for
the rights of drug-using citizens.
<P>
Within such a policy framework, it would be a good idea to distribute
drugs and not just substitution products for two reasons: a) gaining
the loyalty of users, so that they do not return to the illegal
drugs market (it is known that users on methadone programmes often
continue to consume heroine on a more or less occasional basis)
and, consequently, b) gradually reducing the room available for
illegal drugs selling, making it less and less attractive for
trafficking networks.
<P>
Finally, it must not be forgotten to review the transgressions
perpetrated by anti-trafficking (and also anti-demand) policies
against the fundamental principles of criminal law.  Even if we
were obliged to admit (which is not the case) that the end justifies
the means, it must be pointed out that the value of such transgressions
is far from proven.  Nevertheless, they continue to spread into
new areas, calling into question one of the base institutions
of democracy, namely justice.
<H3>Paving the way for effective strategies</H3>

<P>
Current political conditions, both nationally and internationally,
suggest that the adoption of a new model will not be easy.  It
requires a change of mentalities and a change of tune, but also
more knowledge and less mystery as regards common ground.  This
seems to require working links between at least four sectors:
the NGOs on the ground (focusing on drugs, poverty, suburbs etc),
human rights NGOs (rarely dealing with drug-related problems),
academic circles and local administrations committed to alternative
policies within their catchment areas.
<P>
One of the obstacles to policy changes is the opportunistic use
of false truths in order to justify current policies and conceal
the real issues.  An effort to rationalise, pass on and possibly
expand upon existing verifiable knowledge is a prerequisite for
any action.  This knowledge exists but is fragmented at present.
 A comparison of alternative practices existing in various countries
at local and national level is also essential, to gauge the feasibility,
effectiveness and reproducibility required to form a basis for
a shift to other policy models.  We believe that grassroots operatives
and theoreticians must join forces in:
<P>
a) analysing the <I>real issues</I> of existing policies;
<P>
b) analysing and evaluating the <I>effects</I> of these policies;
<P>
c) devising and proposing <I>alternative</I> policies:
<P>
at institutional level, through lobbying
<P>
at public opinion level, by involving and enlisting the media
<P>
The first step is therefore to create a forum where these protagonists
can meet, work together and gradually extend their network, free
from institutional constraints.  This would pave the way for concerted
and co-ordinated activities and could provide a collecting point
for data gathered at grassroots level, which might supplement
information collected by institutional bodies and shed more light
on it.  This will give such a body the legitimacy it needs to
become a real partner for national and international decision-makers
and thus influence the framing of policies themselves.<HR>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="soberon">Ricardo SOBER&Oacute;N GARRIDO
</A>- Peru</H3>

<H3>Role of the United Nations</H3>

<P>
Since its creation in 1945, the UN (the United Nations Organisation),
has developed actions aimed at promoting the respect of human
rights in the world.  The negotiation of international treaties,
the approval of numerous political declarations and the recent
initiatives to avoid or stop wars and other armed conflicts which
are affecting world peace all bear witness to the enormous efforts
made by this international organisation throughout the world.
<P>
Furthermore, the UN has established an entire structure of agencies
and bodies responsible for human rights and other objectives contained
in the San Francisco Charter.  Among the six committees which
comprise it, there is one concerned with human rights and one
concerned with drugs.  In addition, organisations like UNESCO
(United Nations Organisation for Education, Science and Culture),
UNDP (United Nations Development Programme), WHO (World Health
Organisation) and HCR (Office of the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees) have certain responsibilities for trying to solve
various specific types of problem facing humanity.
<P>
Nevertheless, in 1945, the UN also inherited a further task from
its predecessor, the League of Nations: control of the growing,
trafficking and consumption of illicit drugs.  For this purpose,
it has created the Commission on Narcotic Drugs, the Financial
Action Task Force on Money Laundering (GAFI), while the WHO takes
action in the fields of prevention and prohibition on the world
scale.
<P>
Thus, the UN drew up a list of 107 psychotropic substances (among
them the coca leaf, from which human industry extracts the alkaloid
of cocaine).  UNO also ratified three treaties of universal scope
(1961, 1971 and 1988) establishing a world legal structure for
the fight against drug trafficking.  Lastly, UNO has various mechanisms
which should now be evaluated from the standpoint of rationality
and effectiveness in relation to the principles which govern a
state under the rule of law and the international system of human
rights, at least as regards actual practice.
<P>
I refer here to the application of extradition, (in Bolivia, there
have been examples of simple kidnappings), surveillance of deliveries,
aerial spraying with herbicides of dubious quality, the detention
of consumers, the creation of many offences, special and emergency
laws and procedures (this was the case in Peru between 1978 and
1991, and is still the case in Bolivia with the unconstitutional
law 1008, and the Statute against drugs in Colombia).
<H3>Conflicts between human rights and the fight against drug
trafficking</H3>

<P>
The prisons are full, in both rich and poor countries, of not
yet sentenced and hence formally innocent people arrested for
drug-related offences (but, despite this, these prisons have become
supply centres for legal and illegal drugs).  A single example
suffices: in the United States in 1994, of the 82,127 prisoners
held for federal offences, 50,394 (or 59,4%) were in prison for
offences connected with drug trafficking or consumption.
<P>
However, the big drug barons who have colossal fortunes have several
alternatives when faced with prison: repentance, submission, collaboration
with the police.  Lastly, the very widespread corruption among
the police, the judiciary and the prisons constitutes a final
way - and frequently indeed the first - to obtain illegal release
and freedom.
<P>
Democracy in the countries in which drugs are produced or through
which they transit has been, and still is being, weakened.  The
military in my country are in political and military control -
under a state of emergency - of the majority of the producer regions
where some 200.000 hectares are under coca.  It is here that there
are the most serious cases of corruption and the management of
dirty money to permit drugs to be exported.  To combat this situation,
Fujimori's democratic government has decided that all drug trafficking
offences committed by the military should be judged by military
law and not by the judiciary.
<P>
Elsewhere, corruption and the infiltration of the money and influence
of traffickers' organisations have ended up corrupting various
civil authorities, at the highest levels, and affecting electoral
processes at all levels.  Mexico and Colombia are clear examples
of this.
<P>
Curiously enough, other processes at work in this &quot;global
village&quot; of ours are having a negative effect on anti-drug
efforts.  The globalisation of economic relations, the financial
stabilisation of certain countries of the South and the opening
of world markets constitute the three biggest successes of the
world economic community in recent years.  However, these successes
have brought about a situation in which the production of drugs
has become the only means of economic survival for millions of
small farmers on the Rif, in the mountains of Thailand and in
the Andes.  In this connection, we draw attention to the fundamental
contradictions between the policy of openness in the South, the
maintenance of strict protectionist measures in the OECD economies,
and the subordination to drug trafficking of broad social, economic
and financial sectors.
<P>
Subordination (others call it addiction) to the consumption of
drugs has not changed one iota.  The producers of coca and poppies
in the Andes are increasing at the same rate as the queues of
unemployed and redundant workers.  This situation is the consequence
of the structural adjustment programmes and reforms of the State,
notably in Peru and Bolivia.
<P>
On the other hand, the bands of traffickers find their illegal
trade facilitated by the opening of international markets, the
consolidation of trading blocs between drug producing countries
(Andean group), transit countries (MERCOSUR) and consumer countries
(NAFTA and the European Union), and by the increased flows of
goods and persons.  Lastly, young consumers find no answer to
the serious disintegration of the family, and seek escape in drugs
as their only response, despite the enormous amounts of money
involved.
<P>
The anti-drug actions frequently carried out in many countries
end up directly affecting the human rights situation in the countries
concerned: frequent arbitrary imprisonment, essentially of mere
consumers who are classified as traffickers; compulsory uprooting
of plants with no micro- or macro-economic alternative available;
indiscriminate spraying which has a serious impact on biodiversity
in Amazonia and on legal crops (Guaviare, in Colombia); violent
police raids as in Bolivia (Chapare, in the Cochabamba region).
 All this to be able to achieve the objectives set in agreement
with the United States and to go on receiving the &quot;collaboration&quot;
of this country and its support for any request for credits from
the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and the World Bank.
<P>
The theory according to which there is only one way to approach
the problem of the supply, trafficking and consumption of illegal
drugs - formal prohibition and rhetoric - has proved a resounding
failure over recent decades.
<P>
At the same time, such efforts have seriously affected democratic
processes in certain countries of the South, and have restricted
in them the possibilities for the effective enforcement of human
rights as recognised in the Charter of the United Nations itself
and in the Universal Conventions.
<P>
At the individual level, i.e. concerning civil and political rights,
various obstacles have arisen, such as the states of emergency
declared in regions where coca and poppies are cultivated (Huallaga,
Guaviare and Chapare valleys).
<P>
Second, there are problems resulting from the application of arbitrary
and unjust legislation, such as the special laws in Colombia and
Bolivia: carte blanche, trials which violate the basic principles
of the rule of law, and harsh if not arbitrary sentences such
as life imprisonment in Peru or the death penalty in Asian countries.
<P>
As regards the implementation of economic, social and cultural
rights, anti-drugs policies not only constitute an obstacle -
together with structural adjustment, stabilisation and financial
rehabilitation policies - but also work against the possibilities
for sustainable development as proposed by the international community
at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, and at the meeting
on Social Development in Copenhagen in 1994.
<P>
Collective rights are also weakened by the application of the
anti-drug actions, because the illegal drugs economy becomes a
way of escaping from poverty.  The results of these actions hit
the weakest links in the drug chain; the law is applied against
producers, and the economic losses shift towards the centres of
production and consumption.
<P>
For these reasons it is essential to redefine world objectives
and policies in such a way that the standpoint of the South is
given more weight than it has received in the past.  It is essential
not to dissociate the problem of drugs and trafficking from the
problems of poverty, North-South international trade in agricultural
products and the protection of the Andean and Amazonian environments.
<HR>

<H3>Contribution by Ricardo VARGAS - Colombia</H3>

<H3>Consequences of repressive anti-drug policies and relationship
between drugs and human rights</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
The strengthening of the prohibition as a basis for approaches
and decisions in the battle against drugs is directly and indirectly
affecting human rights in those countries with illegal drug economies.
This situation is experienced differently at the three levels
of the drug economy: production, distribution and consumption
of narcotics.
<P>
At the production level the effects are closely related to the
presence of illegal crops, grown in a context of crisis-ridden
rural economies, of occupation of farm land belonging to the indian
communities, and generally in those areas of the farming sector
worst hit by the globalisation of the economy. Illegal crops have
become the primary alternative solution for defending the jobs
and incomes of peasant families, and the principal means of access
to goods and services such as health care and education, as well
as non-essential consumer items.
<P>
Government decisions to destroy the crops, and the producers'
response to such decisions are resulting in a tendency towards
the militarisation of the zones concerned, under the control of
armed guerillas, with little state presence. The result is a complex
conflict in which producers are caught up in a war, in the name
of the battle against drugs and subversive activities, that is
having unforeseen effects in terms of human rights and the violation
of international humanitarian law.
<P>
Furthermore, in its fight against drug trafficking, the Colombian
Government has decreed a series of measures under cover of the
State of Emergency, legislative measures that affect many aspects
of everyday life and make for a &quot;faceless&quot; justice system
that undermines legal guarantees and citizens' right to due process.
The state is also guilty of serious human rights violations that
it conceals by laying the blame on drug trafficking, thereby prolonging
its time-old impunity in such matters.
<P>
Finally, in connection with the consumption of illegal substances,
the Government is attempting, through legislative reform, to undo
the progress made by the Constitutional Court when it declared
certain provisions in the Narcotics Bill unconstitutional because
they denied rights to people who chose to consume drugs. The reform
would criminalise drug consumption again, which would only further
marginalise groups with problems of drug addiction.
<H3>Institutional policies and agreements at the national, regional
and international level and their impact in Colombia</H3>

<P>
While Colombia's anti-drug policy is based on prohibition, it
is strongly influenced by the pressure periodically brought to
bear by the Unites States. The imposition of a bilateral agenda
demanding anti-drug actions to keep Washington happy actually
results in a total lack of co-operation between the two countries,
with Washington trying to call the cards unilaterally.
<P>
This is a violation of Colombia's national sovereignty, preventing
it from handling the problem in its own way. It is apparent in
the lack of participation of civil society in decisions on drug
issues. The state has monopolised the decision-making process,
and any attempts at independent action have been in vain.
<P>
At the production level, overtures were made by the communities
concerned, but their offer to phase the crops out gradually were
ignored in favour of the total crop destruction policy imposed
by the United States, turning production areas virtually into
war zones. 
<P>
At the distribution level, Colombia has suggested subjecting dealers
to Colombian law, but this offer lacked credibility in the eyes
of Washington, and the threat that extradition or other means
of detaining and trying drug bosses in the United States will
be reintroduced is taken very seriously.
<P>
Finally, at the drug consumption level, a decision of the Constitutional
Court decriminalised possession of small doses of narcotics for
personal consumption, but Washington rejected this decision, leading
to pressure in Colombia to return to the old prohibitionist regime
under which consumption was considered as a criminal offence.
<P>
Colombia, therefore, has lost its sovereignty in the field of
anti-drug policy; decisions are taken on the basis of international
pressure, which is all the heavier today as the President's credibility
wanes in the light of his alleged dealings with the drug barons.
<P>
This state of affairs is affecting criminal law policy with regard
to traffickers, with legislation bowing to the whims of external
pressure for the sake of an international image in keeping with
the prohibitionist approach. It is also obstructing Alternative
Development policies, since repression prevails over consultation
with the communities concerned, and drug users' rights are violated
by exposing them to criminal prosecution.
<H3>Recommendations on alternative policies and actions</H3>

<P>
1. The Colombian Government must stop treating producers (peasants,
settlers, indians) as criminals. It must help them strengthen
their organisations, and make room for dialogue, so that environment-friendly
regional development solutions may be proposed and further violence
avoided.
<P>
2. The Colombian Government must not confuse the armed conflict
in the country with the drug problem. It must develop separate
policies on these two issues, while bearing in mind that certain
problems are common to both, and that dialogue and negotiations
should also be encouraged to produce a peaceful solution to the
internal conflict.
<P>
3. The U.S. Government must accept that there are socio-economic,
cultural and political problems in the production zones which
are incompatible with the pressure it is exerting on Colombia
to destroy all the illegal crops indiscriminately. Solutions must
be found to the basic problems facing populations in the production
areas, and to the environmental aspects of the question.
<P>
4. The international community must strengthen the Alternative
Development solutions and urge the Colombian Government to make
room for participation by the local communities through their
organisations, and to assume its responsibilities concerning the
protection of the environment.
<P>
5. The U.S. Government must respect Colombia's sovereignty and
stop interfering in its internal affairs by pressing for the militarisation
of the battle against drugs and for the reintroduction of extradition,
which will merely prolong the violence. The legal economy in Colombia
is already under threat from the certification system, and this
further jeopardises the chances of promoting viable alternatives
to illegal crop production.
<P>
6. The international community must strive to strengthen the Colombian
justice system in respect of fundamental rights, due process and
the elimination of all extra-judicial measures that constitute
a threat to human life or personal freedom.
<P>
7. The international community must encourage serious and impartial
analysis of the drug issue, in order to propose solutions other
than prohibition and the resulting repression among citizens caught
up in the drug problem in one way or another.
<P>
8. The Colombian Government must respect the decision of the Constitutional
Court concerning the decriminalisation of personal consumption,
and develop and strengthen its drug abuse prevention and treatment
policies.
<P>
Alternatives and proposals concerning the impact of the anti-drug
measures
<P>
The alternatives are directly related to social factors at each
level of the illegal economy. At the production level, more value
should be attached to the role of the local peasant and indian
communities, with machinery for consultation with the Government
in the context of a regional development dynamic.
<P>
At the distribution level, solutions may lie in legalisation and
in the country's own, sovereign criminal law system, developed
to cater for the nation's interests in a context of joint responsibility,
reciprocity and interdependence at the international level. A
special regime should consequently be developed for this type
of offence, based on respect for each country's internal decisions
and independently of other, unrelated issues on the international
agenda.
<P>
At the consumption level, what Colombia needs is the decriminalisation
of personal consumption, a liberal victory that would encourage
preventive measures and treatments based on individual self-determination,
and above all an alternative to the present atmosphere of criminality
and social stigma that merely exacerbates the social exclusion
of drug users.
<P>
All these proposals mean making provision for full participation
by the communities concerned, who have thus far been excluded
from the decision-making process, which has been monopolised by
the Government, under considerable pressure from external influences
and in particular from U.S. interference in Colombia's domestic
affairs.
<P>
Hence the need for international fora where the social aspects
of the drug issue can be discussed impartially, without interference
from political interests in the countries concerned. This would
help Colombia to improve its public image at home.
<P>
Furthermore, there is a serious lack of information in Colombia
concerning alternatives to prohibition currently being developed
and tested at the international level, and exchanges of experiences
at various levels, a lack of information that merely serves to
strengthen the position of those who deny the need for serious
reflection on the subject.<HR>

<H3>Contribution by Ricardo SOBER&Oacute;N GARRIDO - Peru</H3>

<H3>Role of the United Nations</H3>

<P>
Since its creation in 1945, the UN (the United Nations Organisation),
has developed actions aimed at promoting the respect of human
rights in the world.  The negotiation of international treaties,
the approval of numerous political declarations and the recent
initiatives to avoid or stop wars and other armed conflicts which
are affecting world peace all bear witness to the enormous efforts
made by this international organisation throughout the world.
<P>
Furthermore, the UN has established an entire structure of agencies
and bodies responsible for human rights and other objectives contained
in the San Francisco Charter.  Among the six committees which
comprise it, there is one concerned with human rights and one
concerned with drugs.  In addition, organisations like UNESCO
(United Nations Organisation for Education, Science and Culture),
UNDP (United Nations Development Programme), WHO (World Health
Organisation) and HCR (Office of the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees) have certain responsibilities for trying to solve
various specific types of problem facing humanity.
<P>
Nevertheless, in 1945, the UN also inherited a further task from
its predecessor, the League of Nations: control of the growing,
trafficking and consumption of illicit drugs.  For this purpose,
it has created the Commission on Narcotic Drugs, the Financial
Action Task Force on Money Laundering (GAFI), while the WHO takes
action in the fields of prevention and prohibition on the world
scale.
<P>
Thus, the UN drew up a list of 107 psychotropic substances (among
them the coca leaf, from which human industry extracts the alkaloid
of cocaine).  UNO also ratified three treaties of universal scope
(1961, 1971 and 1988) establishing a world legal structure for
the fight against drug trafficking.  Lastly, UNO has various mechanisms
which should now be evaluated from the standpoint of rationality
and effectiveness in relation to the principles which govern a
state under the rule of law and the international system of human
rights, at least as regards actual practice.
<P>
I refer here to the application of extradition, (in Bolivia, there
have been examples of simple kidnappings), surveillance of deliveries,
aerial spraying with herbicides of dubious quality, the detention
of consumers, the creation of many offences, special and emergency
laws and procedures (this was the case in Peru between 1978 and
1991, and is still the case in Bolivia with the unconstitutional
law 1008, and the Statute against drugs in Colombia).
<H3>Conflicts between human rights and the fight against drug
trafficking</H3>

<P>
The prisons are full, in both rich and poor countries, of not
yet sentenced and hence formally innocent people arrested for
drug-related offences (but, despite this, these prisons have become
supply centres for legal and illegal drugs).  A single example
suffices: in the United States in 1994, of the 82,127 prisoners
held for federal offences, 50,394 (or 59,4%) were in prison for
offences connected with drug trafficking or consumption.
<P>
However, the big drug barons who have colossal fortunes have several
alternatives when faced with prison: repentance, submission, collaboration
with the police.  Lastly, the very widespread corruption among
the police, the judiciary and the prisons constitutes a final
way - and frequently indeed the first - to obtain illegal release
and freedom.
<P>
Democracy in the countries in which drugs are produced or through
which they transit has been, and still is being, weakened.  The
military in my country are in political and military control -
under a state of emergency - of the majority of the producer regions
where some 200.000 hectares are under coca.  It is here that there
are the most serious cases of corruption and the management of
dirty money to permit drugs to be exported.  To combat this situation,
Fujimori's democratic government has decided that all drug trafficking
offences committed by the military should be judged by military
law and not by the judiciary.
<P>
Elsewhere, corruption and the infiltration of the money and influence
of traffickers' organisations have ended up corrupting various
civil authorities, at the highest levels, and affecting electoral
processes at all levels.  Mexico and Colombia are clear examples
of this.
<P>
Curiously enough, other processes at work in this &quot;global
village&quot; of ours are having a negative effect on anti-drug
efforts.  The globalisation of economic relations, the financial
stabilisation of certain countries of the South and the opening
of world markets constitute the three biggest successes of the
world economic community in recent years.  However, these successes
have brought about a situation in which the production of drugs
has become the only means of economic survival for millions of
small farmers on the Rif, in the mountains of Thailand and in
the Andes.  In this connection, we draw attention to the fundamental
contradictions between the policy of openness in the South, the
maintenance of strict protectionist measures in the OECD economies,
and the subordination to drug trafficking of broad social, economic
and financial sectors.
<P>
Subordination (others call it addiction) to the consumption of
drugs has not changed one iota.  The producers of coca and poppies
in the Andes are increasing at the same rate as the queues of
unemployed and redundant workers.  This situation is the consequence
of the structural adjustment programmes and reforms of the State,
notably in Peru and Bolivia.
<P>
On the other hand, the bands of traffickers find their illegal
trade facilitated by the opening of international markets, the
consolidation of trading blocs between drug producing countries
(Andean group), transit countries (MERCOSUR) and consumer countries
(NAFTA and the European Union), and by the increased flows of
goods and persons.  Lastly, young consumers find no answer to
the serious disintegration of the family, and seek escape in drugs
as their only response, despite the enormous amounts of money
involved.
<P>
The anti-drug actions frequently carried out in many countries
end up directly affecting the human rights situation in the countries
concerned: frequent arbitrary imprisonment, essentially of mere
consumers who are classified as traffickers; compulsory uprooting
of plants with no micro- or macro-economic alternative available;
indiscriminate spraying which has a serious impact on biodiversity
in Amazonia and on legal crops (Guaviare, in Colombia); violent
police raids as in Bolivia (Chapare, in the Cochabamba region).
 All this to be able to achieve the objectives set in agreement
with the United States and to go on receiving the &quot;collaboration&quot;
of this country and its support for any request for credits from
the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and the World Bank.
<P>
The theory according to which there is only one way to approach
the problem of the supply, trafficking and consumption of illegal
drugs - formal prohibition and rhetoric - has proved a resounding
failure over recent decades.
<P>
At the same time, such efforts have seriously affected democratic
processes in certain countries of the South, and have restricted
in them the possibilities for the effective enforcement of human
rights as recognised in the Charter of the United Nations itself
and in the Universal Conventions.
<P>
At the individual level, i.e. concerning civil and political rights,
various obstacles have arisen, such as the states of emergency
declared in regions where coca and poppies are cultivated (Huallaga,
Guaviare and Chapare valleys).
<P>
Second, there are problems resulting from the application of arbitrary
and unjust legislation, such as the special laws in Colombia and
Bolivia: carte blanche, trials which violate the basic principles
of the rule of law, and harsh if not arbitrary sentences such
as life imprisonment in Peru or the death penalty in Asian countries.
<P>
As regards the implementation of economic, social and cultural
rights, anti-drugs policies not only constitute an obstacle -
together with structural adjustment, stabilisation and financial
rehabilitation policies - but also work against the possibilities
for sustainable development as proposed by the international community
at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, and at the meeting
on Social Development in Copenhagen in 1994.
<P>
Collective rights are also weakened by the application of the
anti-drug actions, because the illegal drugs economy becomes a
way of escaping from poverty.  The results of these actions hit
the weakest links in the drug chain; the law is applied against
producers, and the economic losses shift towards the centres of
production and consumption.
<P>
For these reasons it is essential to redefine world objectives
and policies in such a way that the standpoint of the South is
given more weight than it has received in the past.  It is essential
not to dissociate the problem of drugs and trafficking from the
problems of poverty, North-South international trade in agricultural
products and the protection of the Andean and Amazonian environments.
<HR>

